<head><title> Pacific Journalism Review 1995</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#70DBDB"> 
<A HREF="../../back.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/PJRmast.gif" width=150 depth=200 ALT="Pacific Journalism Review masthead"></A>
<HR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475>
<TR>
<TD width=200 align=left>http://acij.uts.edu.au/PJR/issues/back95/95contents.html
</TABLE>
<HR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475>
<h2>Vol 2 No 1, November 1995<P>
CONTENTS</h2>
<A HREF="../back.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/PJR2.gif" width=200 ALT="Cover of PJR issue"></A>
<A HREF="95editorial.html"><h3>Editorial</A><P>
Articles</H3>
<UL><LI><B><A HREF="95times.html">THE TIMES OF PAPUA NEW GUINEA: AN <BR>INVESTIGATIVE TRADITION</A></B><BR>
<I>By Harlyne Joku</I><BR>
In May 1995, one of the Pacific's best known newspapers closed. A regional magazine summed up <I>The Times of Papua New Guinea</I>   thus: <I>Strength:</I>   the diversity of views and efforts to cover national life full. <I>Weakness:</I>   Loss of skilled journalists that it develops to organisations like the <I>Post-Courier.</I>

<P>
<LI><B>SELF-CENSORSHIP: THE MOST INSIDIOUS GAG</B><BR>
<I>By Peter Cronau</I><BR>
Journalists feel the pressures to conform to the accepted values of their workplace. But those pressures come not just from editors and producers above them, but significantly from the journalist's peers -- their fellow journalists.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="95invest.html"><B>INVESTIGATIVE JOURNALISM IN MELANESIA: IS IT NEEDED?</B></A><BR>
<I>By Walter Nalangu</I><BR>
Some argue there is no place for investigative journalism in Melanesia, particularly in Papua New Guinea. Such critics believe that for investigations to be effective then politicians must make changes. A media panel at a UNESCO-funded seminar at the University of Papua New Guinea debates these issues.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="95sbs.html"><B>PNG: UNDER THE SPELL</B></A><BR>
<I>By Helen Vatsikopoulis</I><BR>
Corruption and law and order problems beset Papua New Guinea in its 20th year of independence. Says the former Governor of the Central Bank, Sir Mekere Morauta: 'This nation is under the spell of the statement that we are rich. So our riches will deliver us from the evils, from our own evils. They didn't. Where are we now?'
<P>
<LI><B>OPEN SEASON FOR SNIPES</B><BR>
<I>By James Pinder</I><BR>
'For 365 days a year, the media cop it from our pollies. But the overseas press are employed to report on the country and its goings on -- not the whims of our politicians, who, whenever they make a boo-boo, claim they are misreported.'
<P>
<LI><B>ATTACKS ON THE PRESS</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
A record 173 journalists were held in prison at the end of 1994 and 72 journalists were killed in the line of duty -- eight more than the previous year. Pacific cases have been cited in monitoring of news media abuses.
<P>
<LI><B>TIME TO LIGHT UP THE NBC AIRWAVES</B><BR>
<I>By Ian Boden</I><BR>
'The [Papua New Guinea] National Broadcasting Commission is a shadow of its former self. The provincial Kundu service, following years of neglect, has become an unproductive shambles. The flagship Karai service has a weak signal. And the cash cow Kalang has contributed little.'
<P>
<LI><B>INTERNATIONAL NEWS FLOW COOPERATIVE STUDY</B><BR>
<I>By Sorariba Nash</I><BR>
A media cooperative study of foreign news and international news flow in the 1990s is under way. The objective is to define a New World (Dis)order geography of news gathering. Papua New Guinea and other Pacific nations are involved.
<P>
<LI><B><A HREF="95copyright.html">THE COPYRIGHT LAW AND PNG</A></B><BR>
<I>By Professor John Nonggorr</I><BR>
'Papua New Guineans would not be impressed by fancy arguments advanced elsewhere -- that it is immoral to copy somebody else's work and that a country should adopt copyright laws to enhance its international standing.'
<P>
<LI><B>THE DEATH PENALTY: A FLAWED DEBATE</B><BR>
<I>By William Ferea</I><BR>
Media debate on the controversy over capital punishment in Papua New Guinea has been emotional. But the arguments have been flawed and distorted.
<P>
<LI><B>DILEMMA FOR  FIJI MEDIA AND THE CONSTITUTION</B><BR>
<I>By Philip Cass</I><BR>
Fiji prides itself on being at the crossroads of the Pacific and yet the rest of the great ocean remains almost invisible to the Fijian press, to whom the world consists of floods in India, stock prices in Australia and OJ in the US.
<P>
<LI><B>BLEAK MEDIA SCENARIOS CONFRONT VANUATU</B><BR>
<I>By Kiery Manassah</I><BR>
Lack of qualified and experienced journalists, a tendency to allow censorship and disregard for the notion of publicly funded broadcasting services belonging to the public hamper freedom of information.
<P>
PINA 1995 CONVENTION IN PNG:<BR>
<LI><B>1 SERVING TRUTH WITH DEVELOPMENT NEWS</B><BR>
<I>By Sir Julius Chan</I><BR>
Flawed journalism has sullied Papua New Guinea's good name and built up an unfortunate but valid distrust of the media. The country and its problems have been the victim of shallow journalists unable to look past the bad.
<P>
<LI><B>2 <A HREF="95maino.html">PEOPLE, NEWS AND GOVERNMENT</A></B><BR>
<I>By Sir Charles Maino</I><BR>
Like all rights and freedoms, freedom of the press sometimes gets a rough handling by various authorities and governments throughout the world. In the Pacific, the right must be preserved for the interest of the people.
<P>
<LI><B>3 A BLURRED AND DISTORTED VIEW OF PNG</B><BR>
<I>By Gabriel Dusava</I><BR>
Some 'mischievous' news media do not present a full portrait based on real life in Papua New Guinea but a caricature -- without the humour of a cartoon -- which too often misses the point.
<P>
<LI><B>4 <A HREF="95vision.html">SHARE THE WHOLE VISION, GOOD NEWS AND BAD</A></B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
Image-massagers sprucing up Pacific government images aren't enough. While issues such as the raskol problem, land disputes and Bougainville remain unresolved, there will continue to be a 'bad press'.
<P>
<LI><B>5 REGIONAL CONFLICTS: GETTING BOTH SIDES</B><BR>
<I>By Sorariba Nash</I><BR>
How well has the mass media in the South Pacific fared covering military, social and political conflicts in the region -- such as Bougainville? What are the problems encountered by journalists covering such disputes?
<P>
<LI><B>6 PACIFIC MEDIA AWARDS</B><BR>
PINA Pacific Media Award winners at the 1995 convention.
<P>
<LI><B>7 NOW THE NEGATIVE NEWS FROM PARADISE</B><BR>
<I>By Kunda Dixit</I><BR>
Pacific countries are increasingly sensitive about media coverage. Singled out for special scrutiny and criticism are the Australian and New Zealand media, which specialise in the region. An Asian perspective.
<P>
PROFILES IN MEDIA<BR>
<LI><B>Wendy Bacon: A BULLET AND AN ORCHID</B><BR>
<I>By Sophie Kuasi</I><BR>
Wendy Bacon, a winner of the Walkley Award, exposed corrupt activities by some New South Wales police officers and also foreigners implicated in the Fiji coups. Now an academic, Associate Professor Bacon assisted University of PNG's new investigative journalism course.
<P>
<LI><B>Neville Togarewa: A SCOOP IN THE JUNGLE</B><BR>
<I>By Nimo Kama</I><BR>
From his observation and association with the three newspaper companies, Neville Togarewa believes in investigative journalism is mostly lacking in Papua New Guinea. However, it is demanding. It involves courages as well as resources.
<P>
<LI><B>Abby Yadi: FROM FISH TO BUSINESS</B><BR>
<I>By Sophie Kuasi</I><BR>
Abby Yadi once had his name written on a bullet after taking an inside photograph of a Defence Force helicopter which was published on the front page of the <I>Post-Courier</I>.   His family was also threatened during the Bougainville crisis.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="95rainbow.html"><B>A PHOTOGRAPHER'S DATE WITH A NUCLEAR DEATH</A> *Photos</B><BR>
<I>By David Robie</I><BR>
President Jacques Chirac's controversial final round of nuclear tests at Moruroa and Fangataufa atolls in 1995 unleashed an unprecedented storm of international protest. And dilemmas for journalists covering the riots in Papeete and the junkets by French authorities. The Vanuatu government banned news reports on protests. A journalist on board the original environmental campaign ship <I>Rainbow Warrior</I>   -- bombed by French secret agents a decade ago -- recalls the events. He was later arrested by the French military.
<P>
<LI><B>CAT-AND-MOUSE OVER THE FRENCH NUKES</B><BR>
<I>By Ekonia Peni</I><BR>
French nuclear tests and the controversial draft Pacific logging code of practice drew most of the media coverage at the Madang South Pacific Forum meeting. But logging was almost brushed aside by the host country.</UL>
<P>
<h3>Forum</H3>
<P><UL>
<LI><B>Give 'new kid on the lock' a fair chance</B><BR>
<I>Henry Chang, Editor-in-Chief, The National</I><BR>
<LI><B>Tabloid transition</B><BR>
<I>Peter Cronau, Director, Australian Centre for Independent Journalism</I><BR>
<LI><B>Ancient Remingtons</B><BR>
<I>David Ingram, National Training Manager, SBS Radio</I><BR>
<LI><B>World-class education</B><BR>
<I>Dr Suzanna Layton, Lecturer, Departent of Journalism, University of Queensland</I><P></UL>

<h3>Reviews</H3>
