<head><title>Cafe Pacific: Nius Country Profiles: Cook Islands</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FF6EC7">
<A HREF="../david_prof.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/cooksflag.gif" ALT="Flag of Cook Islands" WIDTH=100></A>
<HR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=450><tr>
<TD width 200><TD align=left>http://acij.uts.edu.au/cafepacific/resources/profiles/cooks.html
</table>
<HR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=100%><tr>
<TD width 100%><TD align=left><P>
<Font size=6><A HREF="../david_prof.html"><B>Cook Islands</A></B></Font size=6>
<P>
<H4><IMG SRC="../../images/bullet.gif"> Go to <A HREF="#News media">News media</A></H4>
<P>
<Font size=3><B>Head of State:</B> Queen Elizabeth II (represented by a Governor-General).
<BR>
<B>Head of Government:</B> Prime Minister Sir Geoffrey Henry. 
<BR><B>Capital:</B> Avarua (Rarotonga).
<BR><B>Official languages:</B> Cook Islands Maori, English. 
<BR><B>Currency:</B> NZ dollar = 100 cents. 
<BR><B>Area:</B>  234 sq km (15 islands); Rarotonga (67 sq km); Mangaia (51).
<BR><B>Population:</B> 19 100 (1994 est.). 
<BR><B>Time: </B> -- 1030 hours GMT.
<BR><B>Adult literacy: </B> 75 per cent (1990).
<BR><B>GDP per capita:</B> $3800 (1992).
<P>
<IMG SRC="../../images/cooksmap.gif" ALT="Map of Cook Islands" WIDTH=250>
<BR>
<Font size=1>Map: Gemini News Service</Font size=1>
<P>
<P><B>Political system: </B>The Cook Islands is self-governing in free association with New Zealand. It has a 25-member Parliament (one member representing Cook Islanders abroad) elected for a five-year term by universal adult suffrage, an elected prime minister and a cabinet of ministers.
<P>
The upper legislative house of 21 hereditary chiefs, the House of Ariki, has advisory functions only. Local affairs are handled by island councils and village committees in the outer islands. More Cook Islanders live in New Zealand than inhabit the islands themselves. The Queen's Representative in the Cook Islands represents the British sovereign who is head of state.
<P>
<B>Political parties:</B> Cook Islands Party (ruling party since 1989 elections) and Democratic Alliance Party (opposition). 
<P>
<H3><A NAME="News media">News media:</A></H3>
<B>Press:</B>
<UL><LI><B>Cook Islands News: </B>Daily; 2500; English; Cook Islands-owned, Cook Islands News Ltd; Editor: Alex Sword. PO Box 15, Rarotonga. Tel: (682) 22999; Fax: (682) 25303. Email: <A HREF="MAILTO:cinews@gatepoly.co.ck">cinews@gatepoly.co.ck</A>
<P>
<LI><B>Cook Islands Press:</B> Weekly; 1500; English; Pubisher: Jason Brown; Editor: Barbara Dreaver. Email: <A HREF="MAILTO:cipress@gatepoly.co.ck">cipress@gatepoly.co.ck</A><BR>
<I>Other publication:</I><BR>
<B>Sports Weekly</B></UL>
<P>
<B>Radio:</B>
<P>
<UL><LI><B>Radio Cook Islands:</B> Broadcasts in English and Maori, including bulletins from Australian and NZ national stations. Cook Islands Broadcasting Service (CIBS). Formerly Cook Islands Broadcasting Corporation; privatised in September 1996 with staff and other shareholders taking a stake. PO Box 126, Rarotonga. Tel: (682) 29460. Fax: (682) 21907.
<P>
<LI><B>Radio Kia Orana Country FM103:</B> Broadcasts general programs 18 hrs/day, seven days/week in English and Maori.</UL>
<P>
<B>Television:</B>
<UL><LI><B>Television Cook Islands (CITV):</B> The station broadcasts daily showing footage on local sports, news and cultural programs, as well as New Zealand and world news from Television New Zealand. Broadcasting hours are from 1700-2300 (Mon-Fri). Cook Islands Broadcasting Service (CIBS). Formerly Cook Islands Broadcasting Corporation; privatised in September 1996 with staff and other shareholders taking a stake. PO Box 126, Rarotonga. Tel: (682) 29460. Fax: (682) 21907.
</UL>
<P>
<Font size=1> Copyright © 1995 David Robie and South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information in Development (SPCenCIID). <IMG SRC="../../images/updated.gif"> 28 October 1996</Font size=1>
<HR>
<A HREF="../david_prof.html"><IMG SRC="../../images/Nius.gif" height=27> Return to Nius country profiles index</A>
</P></TABLE>
</body>
