<HEAD>
<TITLE>Do Asian news values deny freedom of expression?</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Do Asian news values deny<BR>
 freedom of expression?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Two</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Ironically, the notion of Asian values may have sprung from an American academic idea that love of freedom is time-bound and place-bound. It argues that, despite more Asians, Africans and Latin Americans devoting their lives and giving them up for freedom, it is yet something they do not really understand and cannot therefore truly want. Not in their ethnic heart of heart.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Who came up with this idea? I don't know; maybe an American academic or journalist invited by a Third World dictatorship to paint a pretty picture of the country under its heel. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But the idea of special values suddenly became very attractive when the communist threat to democracy - as the justification for suppressing democracy - evaporated with the Cold War. For the old dictators, the situation became even more alarming with the peaceful People Power revolution in the Philippines.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
As President Aquino told the US Congress, she led the mass of Filipinos in a revolution, not for bread though they were hungry; nor for money, though they were poor, because they gave what little they had to her campaign. But for good old American freedom. And she was the daughter of one of the richest families in the country, surrounded by bankers and businessmen all intent on two things: the restoration of freedom and the impartial rule of law. It was possible, in fact, it could not be denied, that a people can rise up really for freedom, without awaiting instructions from Moscow.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Without the bogey of communism and the threat to business, Third World dictators were at a loss how to defend their continued suppression of freedom.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
That was when we started to hear in earnest that freedom got in the way of progress and clashed with the native values of countries that came to birth in freedom struggles. Struggles that resonated with the phrases and feelings of the Declarations of Independence and of the Rights of Man: freedom of speech, freedom of conscience, freedom of assembly and the right to petition the government for redress of grievances or throw it out in the next election.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Against these values for which so many Asians fought and died, the authoritarians opposed a set of elusive excuses with a pedigree only in their sense of distress.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
A Philippine colleague attempted the following reconciliation of journalism with so-called Asian values: "Authoritarian governments limit journalistic activity to those values that observe the primacy of the state administration." Citing Siebert, Peterson and Schramm - people I never heard of in law school - instead of Chafee and Learned Hand - she maintained that "one classical theory of journalism ranks government as a higher force than the individual in the scale of social values." 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Nonsense. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In theory, journalism can never rank the force of government higher than its constitutional right. There is a guarantee of press freedom, while government is mentioned in constitutions only as a force to be curtailed.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In fact, governments try to limit journalistic activity, not to values upholding state administration, but away from acts of maladministration and malfeasance of which governments should be ashamed. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
When the country is in a real crisis, Asians would do better to consult Oliver Wendell Holmes on when to restrain journalism in the face of clear and present danger, such as German submarines off the Atlantic coast, than the Analects of Confucius on how to curry the favour of your master.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
My colleague would oblige journalism to justify its work in terms of the values that keep the people in power in their places. But journalism need explain itself no more than the truth it serves.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
There are no two theories of journalism - one for liberal societies in the West and another for authoritarian dispensations in the East or wherever. There is only one kind of journalism - that which seeks the truth and tells it plain. The rest is propaganda.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
