<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: One</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: One</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Teodoro L. Locsin. Section Two</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 3</B><BR>
Mr Locsin I appreciate your textbook and simplistic view of press freedom in Asia, and I have a question as an Asian as well as a journalist. When you talk about there's no such thing as Asian values in journalism, because you say 'find the facts, tell it straight.' How about 'find the facts, and give it meaning'? Then where does Asian values, or any form of values, fit in this?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR> 
Well, in my experience as a journalist, I find the facts, and I give it meaning in light of the criminal court. For example —  maybe I'm just a working journalist and not a theoretician — my idea is to find the facts, say in a financial transaction which the government is involved. My duty of interpretation is to know the Securities and Exchange Commission Act, the penal code, the law on fraud, the law on bribery, and see if I interpret these facts and the case, a plausible case, for favouritism arises. That's the kind of interpretation I do. I can never think of finding of finding myself in a situation where, as an Asian, I say 'oh, he's taking a kickback here' or 'It looks like he's taking a kickback': 'well, I'm an Asian and we do it, and that's fine'. I just never come across that. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Problems of interpretation are like this. Let me give you a concrete example since we're ... The Philippine National Bank just sold its principal asset in a bidding. They sold it to the highest bidder. The bidder had no money (it was for 1.3 billion). So the president of the bank lent him 1.3 billion [laughter]. And then he said — when I attacked it — he said, 'Well the other bid was 200 million'. I said of course it's 200 million, that's his money. 1.3 billion is your million. This is yours but there's nothing . . . the Securities and Exchange Commission or the Central Banking that says that I have violated the Single borrowers Limit. That’s the kind of interpretation I would confine myself to, but certainly not to broad cultural things that say 'Well it’s OK in the Philippines because we're Asian to extend these loans as long as they're within the Single Borrowers' Limit.' I thought it was improper, and I continued to attack it for that. A bid is a bid. The guy has to bring the money to the table, I'm not supposed to put the money on. So I'm just not, I just can't understand any vaguer values that should determine what kind of news you print or how you write it.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 4. John Tebbutt, Monash University</B><BR> 
Mr Locsin, I'm wondering if you could comment on the role of might be called 'public journalism' or 'public broadcasting.' Maybe given some experiences in the Philippines, but also just generally within the Asian region (and also maybe if you know about the Australian situation). 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR> 
I’m not familiar with public journalism in the rest of the region. I hope we're referring to the same things — James Fowler wrote the book Public Journalism . . .
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 4. John Tebbutt</B><BR>
Maybe if I clarify it?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR> 
Yes, maybe you should, because that's the only familiarity I have with public journalism. And he said that there has been an ongoing debate in the United States whether  public journalism was 'proper' journalism, and the New york Times took a position against it, the Washington Post I think took a position against it. In other words people who go out investigate issues like the environment and make it a special concern and hammer on it. I don't see anything wrong with that. I tell you I have an ongoing quarrel with some public journalists in the Philippines. They are in fact some of the best journalists we have: they're young, they're enterprising and energetic and they keep going after the same illegal logger — well, he's no longer an illegal logger, he's now a respected businessman. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
They keep doing this, all the time, they keep going, and I say 'With all your talent, with all your resources, I won't print your stories on the environment any more because I've asked you also to please investigate what this cabinet official has been doing stealing so much, and that other official has been stealing so much. Why is it that  we keep going after environmental polluters, and we don't go after these guys. These guys are picking the national treasury. These guys are affecting posterity. I think this is a more immediate danger. I'm not saying I won't print your story, but I wish you'd expand to more dangerous subjects, for example politicians in the North. Those guys tend to pack guns.' Public journalists in the Philippines do not touch them, but they certainly touch businessmen who pollute rivers. So let's just be even handed about this. If we're going to be brave, let's be brave across the board.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 4. John Tebbutt</B><BR>
Just a quick supplementary. Maybe something else though about independence and state-funded broadcasting which is one of the questions I was trying to get to too. Do you see a role for public broadcasting organisations that are state-funded that maintain some sort of independence from the state?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin </B><BR>
Oh yes. That is the first thing I tried to do. When we won the revolution the government ended up with four television stations, all but one in fact. They were owned by Marcos cronies, so they were under me [?]. And we wanted to turn one of them into a BBC type — we have no idea what the BBC type is in the details — but we have the idea that this is going to be a TV station that would broadcast intelligent, in depth stories about things that are not commercially viable. It never flew. The Congress said that as a reaction against the Marcos years when he was subsidising so much they refused to pay a cent. One station remains government but it supports itself by having basketball on from morning to night [laughter]. I think that's really wrong because Great Britain has shown that it can be done. I like watching BBC.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
