<!--Website produced by Future Thinkers 1996-->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Training Journalists for the Newpaper Business</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Training Journalists for the Newpaper Business</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Section Two</B></FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In serving these two demanding sometimes merciless masters, the Singapore journalist at the same time has cope with three realities. Reality number one, there are limits to our job, limits to how far we can take a story. The government sets these limits. Mr Li Quan Yu described the situation quite vividly in his 1994 interview on his encounter with Lesley Hoffman. He said, 'So, we settle the OV markers. In the end, the Straits Time had to come back to Singapore and run it on our terms. And that's how it has been, and that's how Singapore progressed.' 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The limits were further enforced on Jan 1, 1975, four years after the demise of the Eastern Sunand the Singapore Herald. This is how they control the press in Singapore. The Newspaper and Printing Presses Act was passed. In this Act, which is our number one reality because it exercised control by requiring newspapers, publishers, printers and chief editors to be licensed. There is an additional reserve power: newspaper companies must issue management shares, but only to those with government positions to hold them. And these management shares are  for 200 times more voting power than ordinary shares. And they decide who to hire and fire in a newspaper. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now we all know that good useful newspapers have three basic obligations: one, to gather and disseminate relevant timely information accurately; two, allow citizens a forum to speak their minds on matters that impact on their lives and future (provided the comment is not defamatory, inflammatory or irrelevant); three, make their own position on these issues clear to readers so that amidst the different voices it is unambiguous. How a newspaper carries out these observations is shaped, I believe, by local conditions. The history, the geography, the culture of the society it serves. In Singapore for readers of the Straits Times the approach that is most familiar to them is the Anglo–American one, because of the language used, English. SO even within the company that I work we are often attacked by our own people for not taking out the cudgels against the government. But Singapore at the end of the day, by universal accounts, has a good government. On most accounts it has done well by the country. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Looking at the wealth and wellbeing of Singapore and Singaporeans I believe the Singapore media has achieved much by not opting to take the path of adversarial journalism. Being anti-establishment is not a newspapers' only path to greatness and glory, especially when the government is not a bad government. Singapore's prosperity could not have been achieved had the media not chosen this path. WE chose the path well travelled by the Japanese, so for us a second reality is we see our first and foremost role as to help build and maintain a national consensus amid the clamour for more democracy and debate. That is to serve the national interest. Sometimes, in the eyes of the westerner, this appears as not telling the truth. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Last night at a dinner to mark the opening of this conference, Mr Michael Mann, Chief Executive of Australian TV and former diplomat, who has travelled and worked extensively in Asia, said he sometimes wonders whether, on reading a Japanese report, he was at the same event as the Japanese journalist. Perhaps what is often not appreciated is that newspapers are information filters also. The world has a wide range of filters. The way the Japanese filters news for its people is best explained by Eamon Fingleton a long time observer by the Japanese. He writes in his book Blindside, on the Japanese press, and I quote: 'Where important national economic strategies are concerned, the work of journalists is not so much to inform as to persuade. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Even to the point sometimes of consciously withholding information. For example after World War ll Japanese journalists withheld from the public for years the fact that the cost of living was much higher in Japan that in other countries. They did not want the national consensus undermined. This restraint was lifted only after Japan surpassed the United States in per capita income in mid 1980s.' This is how a Japanese journalist explained it to Fingleton. I quote: ' We were doing what was in the best interest of Japan. Every society has things it does not tell the public. Even in America during the Vietnam War the Washington Postand the New York Times did not tell all they knew.' End of quote. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
