<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reporting Business in South-East Asia</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+1">Reporting Business in South-East Asia</B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Section Two</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
How the world has changed.  With the collapse of the Soviet Union and the
disrepute into which socialism has fallen, we are all capitalists now.  Daily
newspapers usually carry at least one major business/economic/ financial
story on the front page.  The Wall Street Journal enjoys the biggest
circulation of any daily paper in the U.S.  Business magazines have
international editions and have stepped up their international coverage in
most cases.  Business programs, even business channels, blossom on TV.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Here in Australia, BRW does a superb job covering the local scene. 
Australian Sunday morning TV, for example, used to be all about rehashing
the sporting events of the previous day.  Now there are business programs
all over the place.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Business is the big story of the day.  "It's the economy stupid," was
President Bill Clinton's successful rallying cry in 1992.  And it is the
economic stability of today, with the stock market and corporate profits at
record highs, that won him re-election, despite the serious questions about
his ethics and flexibility of principle.  It is telling to note that Bob Dole's only
serious competitive offer was also economics-based - a 15% income tax
cut.  In Europe, the European Monetary Union and the coming shakeout of
the social security blankets, especially in France and Germany, are the
biggest stories of the day - and tomorrow.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Yet perhaps the biggest of these business stories is Asia.  And it is likely to
remain so.  A born and bred New York friend recently returned from a trip to
Asia and reported: "I think I've seen the future."  This was a telling remark
because New Yorkers, for those of you who don't know the breed, are quite
as firmly convinced as the French or the Chinese that they occupy the
center of the universe. Now and forever. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Asia's economic boom has a sense of permanence to it.  That is not to say
there won't be busts. Of course, there will.  But over the long haul, Asia
seems likely to continue to attract an enormous amount of foreign
investment and equally large amounts of technology and skills transfers. 
Non-Asian companies will come to depend upon this region for more and
more of their sales and income.  Australia, as you well know, already is
inextricably linked to Asia - whether she likes it or not. To my mind, the
sooner she embraces that reality the better. The world is dividing into
economic blocs and Australia is far too lightly populated to stand alone as
the tyranny of distance, to employ Geoffrey Blainey's felicitous phrase,
continues to crumble.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Since journalism's job is to report such changes, its practitioners will go
where the action is. And the business action increasingly will be in Asia.  So,
too, will the political and social action but that is someone else's talk.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
To date, the Asian business story has been largely one of boom - of
expanding economies, massive infrastructure projects, emerging middle
classes, strong exports, and the like.  In short, a positive story.  But, as I
said earlier, all booms bust and the bigger the boom the bigger the bust. 
Mexico and Japan are two recent examples on the Pacific Rim.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Journalists enjoy both booms and busts are more interesting to cover - here,
of course, I'm referring to the business version.  I should admit right here
that the dirty little secret of journalism is that it is a lot more fun to practise
than most professions, especially when you are young and a touch anti-
establishment.  Besides, disaster stories sell more newspapers, magazines,
TV shows and advertising. The fall of the mighty, especially if they have
been up to chicanery, is the crux of great drama..  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Historically, most of this drama played to a restricted audience, the home
market.  That meant it was either easier for the establishment involved to
control.  If it did play to foreign audiences, they usually weren't really all that
interested or involved. And, in any case, that had little impact on the
domestic audience. But journalism, like so much else, is going global. And
that changes everything. The facts increasingly are out there for all the world
to see. If the Emperor has not clothes it is going to be hard for him to hide
that fact.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
That brings me to two major developments that will dramatically affect
coverage of the Asian business story - and the story itself.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
