<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Two</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Two</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Siva Arasu, Hugh D. Menzies, Brian Toohey. Section Two</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question 2 Paddy McGuiness</B><BR>
Paddy McGuiness, Sydney Morning Herald and Age. I'd just like to pose a question to the panel. What was the difference in principal between the Nike corporation exploiting cheap labour for manufacturing purposes in Indonesia, and the Straits Times exploiting cheap labour for journalistic purposes in Sydney. Might it not be possible that both groups want the job?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Hugh Menzies</B><BR> 
How old are the Australian journalists?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Siva Arasu </B><BR>
Do I need to say anything to that [laughter]
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 2 Paddy McGuiness </B><BR>
I'd like a comment.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Siva Arasu </B><BR>
I think when you produce a magazine as a publisher you go where the supply is and basically supply right now is in Australia. Technology has allowed us to produce a paper of a certain quality within certain financial constraints using the best people we have. ... to limit ourselves to Singapore that's a narrow point of view. If tomorrow we can find good journalists who can do the job in India or in America or in Japan we will do it, because at the end of the day a good paper is useless if it is dead. So to achieve absolute quality you cannot ignore the fact that we give that quality at a cost that allows us to live the next day, the next year and after that.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Panel</B><BR>
Do you pay your workers $2 a day, army stationed outside their office or factory like Nike do? Perhaps you could put that to Paddy. [laughter]
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paddy McGuiness</B><BR> 
I'm aware of that famous saying that there's only one thing worse than being exploited in a third world country and that's not being exploited. [laughter] Against that I think the campaign to draw attention to these things given what the people in the west are paying for the shoes is not astray, or given that a black basketballer might get paid more for one ad than the entire 30 000 strong Indonesian workforce is something well worth reporting.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Chair </B><BR>
We're running out of time, can we make those two the last questions please.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question 3</B><BR> 
Just a question for Ms Arasu. You mentioned in your talk that - well, the feeling I got was that you were saying - that restrictions on press freedom in your country had not stood in the way of economic prosperity. Would you concede that restrictions on press freedom in other parts of South East Asia may in fact be standing in the way of a national consensus and the development goals of those countries. Indonesia I think would be an example.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Siva Arasu</B><BR> 
I think when we talk about press freedom, the word itself has different meaning for different people. And what is considered free in Australia or America or in Japan is not necessarily the way Singapore or Indonesia or Malaysia sees it. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Living next door to Indonesia and having visited it several times, I think that Indonesia today is much better than it was 20 years ago when I first visited it. The same with my neighbour Malaysia. And the speed or the methods America, Australian or British journalists want us to apply at a ... in our own country. My response to that is merely, in my country, in my society, the speed is fine and the speed that you want us to do things by may not work if there is complete upheaval of things. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So, at the same time you know I hate giving examples of countries that are  not my own because, if you look at - this is a favourite quote of the leaders of my country, and I do not like using it. But one of their favourite quotes is: look at India, it has very free press; look at the Philippines, it has very free press: but how well are these people doing? So there are two sides to it. Yes, sometimes a free press can help, sometimes a free press can be a big obstacle. Well, I think each country has to make its choice.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
