<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsagency Reporting</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER>
<B><FONT SIZE="+2">Newsagency Reporting</FONT></B>
</CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Two</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
When I first joined AP in Asia, in Manila to be exact, we were still getting copy from Indonesia by morse code.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
We used radio to transmit AP news and photos from Tokyo to other points in Asia which were not then linked by cable. Satellites were still some way off.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Communications were the single most important aspect of a reporter's job, apart from getting the story. If you could not find a way to get your story out you may as well not have been there.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
At the Tokyo Olympics in 1964 I was amazed to see Japanese photographers carry baskets of carrier pigeons into the press room at Enoshima where I was covering the yachting.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
They used them to fly film back to Tokyo 50 miles away. It was quicker than road or rail and more reliable than any other communications available.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Over the two weeks I was there I often wished I had brought some myself, so often did the communications collapse. But carrier pigeons don't always work either.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
At the D-Day landing at Normandy in 1944 an AP photographer figured pigeons would be the best way to get his film back across the English channel.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
However the pigeons got lost and were captured by the Germans who processed the film and published the photos in their own newspapers - with the AP photographers by-line.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It was always a credo among wire service reporters that you were only as good as your communications. And that was true.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
When I first went to Laos there was no phone connection to the outside world. You had to take a taxi to the wharf on the Mekong river, take a boat across, clear Thai immigration, then find a phone that worked and an operator who could get a line to Bangkok. Not an easy job. It could day a whole day to dictate one story.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Often reporters would write a story, drive to the airport and try to find a willing passenger to hand carry copy and photos to the nearest city where there was a AP bureau.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Appropriately, these messengers were called pigeons in the trade.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Communications remained slow and unreliable during the 60s and 70s, most of the time I was in Asia I am sorry to say. Often it seemed the fastest way to file a story would be to put it in a bottle and toss it in the South China Sea and hope for the best.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Sunspots would wipe out radio teletype communications for days.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
