<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Three</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Three</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Peter O'Loughlin, Zainoor Sulaiman. Section Two</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 2 John Tebbutt.</B><BR>
A similar question maybe - John Tebbutt from Monash University - but maybe from a different angle. I'm wondering if you could talk about . . . with the very important aspects of speed in journalism and delivery of news, we're also getting an incredible volume of news and an incredible volume of words and pictures. I'm wondering if you could talk about the economic of that on your industry. Is that an advantage, is it a stage of overload and that it's too much. If you could maybe just comment on the situation of the increased volume of information and use that we're getting.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin</B><BR> 
Well, there's no doubt about it, the volume is much greater and will get much greater. But it's not like the old days where you had a photo-machine running and you came in the morning and you found there were 100 photos lying in a basket. Now they're electronically captured and if you want to look at them you call them up on the screen 16 at a time and choose the ones you want. So basically what this information flow's giving you is a greater range of options. Instead of AP choosing out of 100 photos ten to send you, we'll send you the whole lot and you can choose the ones you want. And it's the same with words. I mean you can keyword search your own database to pick what stories you're interested in. I think it's harder for us to gather all this, it costs more to gather it, but it doesn't cost any more to transmit it. So it just provides you with more choices at the other end.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 3. Syd Aspery</B><BR> 
Syd Aspery from DPA. Like very many people I'm an ex-employee of UPI. UPI is a private company. AP is a co-operate. Zainoa you've told us that Bnahma is to be privatised.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Zainoa Sulaiman</B><BR> 
Corporatised.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 3. Syd Aspery </B><BR>
Corporatised rather, in preparation for full privatisation. Could you tell us how the structure as a co-operative has affected you in terms of business? Has this enabled you to finance your movement into digital and away from conventional print media? Is it a question when you're a co-operative that you've been able to pass on the cost of this to your customers because in effect your customers are also your shareholders. Is this the business structure that has favoured  AP against UPI. Also perhaps if you look at Reuters, which is your arch rival, they're a private company and no a co-operative, could you just explore these things for us. Thanks.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin </B><BR>
That's pretty difficult. Well I'm not privy to the secrets to the secrets and the decision making of the AP Board. But they are elected by the newspapers who are members of the cooperative. Now, they don't like spending money, I can assure you of that. So any proposal that we put up has to be brilliantly costed, and it has to show it's going to save them money. And most of the way we've been able to expand is that we've been able to get off terrestrial communications, for instance, which were costing us a fortune, and get into satellites. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now, the capital for that had to be found somewhere, so it was found and approved by the Board. Similarly television. The Board decided we had to get into television. Reuters were already in it, and the Chairman of the Board was out here a while ago, and he's from North Carolina, and he believes that we all have to be in the internet and multimedia, and he's got a big operation on internet. And he said, 'Look, you've, if you're not in multimedia online services - even though we can't make a buck out of it yet - sooner or later down the . . . we're going to finish up as road kill on the Information Super highway.' So that had to be funded somewhere. So we've got an attitude with the Chairman of the Board like that: the funding does come. Hopefully it's going to pay us back some money too (I don't think it ever made Reuters any dough, but we're hoping it'll make us some money). 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now, for UPI. UPI in my experiences over the years, was always under capitalised, and they couldn't keep up, they couldn't get the funding for computers. That's what set them over the hill I thought. They brought a  set of computers from RCA or somebody who weren't in the computer business really and were a complete flop. And they just simply had a cash flow problem. But AP is a widely-based and diversified in the news business organisation internationally; Reuters' emphasis (Michael Perry, you can speak for Reuters, I won't), but from my experience Reuters is much more widely into the financial markets than we are. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The AP is more a traditional news and photo agency and we have joint venture with Dow-Jones (which is called AP-Dow-Jones) which provides services that compete with Reuters. But Reuters has got very large investment in the financial market reporting, which we don't. Apart from that they're listed on the stock exchange at various places and have got sources to that sort of revenue.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
