<!--Website produced by Future Thinkers 1996-->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Un-Western Perspectives on News</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Un-Western Perspectives on News </FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B><FONT SIZE="+1">Section Two</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"The United States' global industrial pre-eminence may be slipping, but the domestic output and international sale of one of its manufactures is booming--packaged consciousness, the one- dimesnional smooth-edged cultural product, is made by the ever- expanding goliaths of the message and image business. Gigantic entertainment-information complexes exercise near-seamless and unified private corporate control over what we think, and think about," writes Herbert I. Schiller, author of Information Inequality: The Deepening Social Crisis in America. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
No wonder the news menu is shrinking, the same news line-up is constantly repeated to fill the air time with "news on the hour every hour". Slabs of news come off the assembly lines of the Perpetual News Machines--processed, sugar-coated and packaged for the lowest common denominator in audience surveys. The worrying thing is that this Niagara of information does not bring more understanding, it hardly allows you to grasp reality, and it does not bring you closer to the truth. This is the trend: the more television people watch, the less they tend to know. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It is the same with the technology-driven dissemination of news through the wire services. We heard from an earlier speaker about gigabytes per second of news can now be sent up to satellites and bounced back to earth at the speed of light. Speed, capacity, quantity of information is all we seem to be concerned about. do we ever stop to ask ourselves what it is that we are communicating? Is it worthwhile information, does it solve any problems, does it bring the world closer? What is the quality of the information? Why do we need to know that Bob Dole fell off the stage the instant it happens, why can't it wait till the evening news?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In a recent cover story on the internatioal media, The New Internationalist magazine asks: "Do you really need to have the news as it is breaking? What are you going to do with it? How often are you left with a feeling that you don't understand what's going on? How often has the story been left hanging because it's not seen as 'news' anymore?" 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Many of us find it hard to remember, or believe, the euphoria we felt when the Cold War officially came to a close. We know now that history did not end then. Fair play and justice did not return to international relations. The Cold War may have ended but Third World wars became more virulent than ever. The two superpowers which had used warlords, guerrilla groups and freedom fighters as pawns to fight fratricidal proxy wars in Afghanistan, Cambodia, Somalia or Angola abandoned them with enough guns and ammunition to keep them fighting for decades more. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Today, looking back at 1989, we have to wonder whether the reason for that misguided euphoria was the breathless media coverage of the dramatic events in Europe which may have raised our expectations too high. During the Cold War, the media had an easy job labelling saints and villains. It reflected the interests of superpowers and multinationals and there was little done to explain events in developing countries in their proper context. The needs and suffering of the poorer two-thirds of the world was important only if they were somehow related to the strategic interests of politicians and businessmen in northern capitals. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now that the Cold War bad guys are good guys, the international media are confused, and seems to have given up trying to make head or tail of the mess that is left. They yearn for the good old days when things were black and white, or more precisely, red or not-red.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The Cold War's lessons for the media are clear: their most important role is not just to react to events but to cover the precursors to conflict. Media must fulfil the role of conditioning the public not to think that conflict is the norm. After the cruise missiles leave their silos and the heavy guns are unsheathed, the momentum of war muzzles media. And as Bosnia showed, even the saddest stories of human misery and sufferings of the innocent in the heart of Europe covered close-up and incessantly by the media is not enough to stop war once it has begun.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Satellite television has made war a spectator sport. Global networks pride themselves in being there first for the live coverage of mass death: "The Famine in Utopia" journalism. It can be Korem, Mogadishu, Kigali, Goma ... But what good is reporting if the carnage is already over? Isn't there a higher calling than to just "report"?
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="dixit03.html">Next section</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="dixit01.html">Previous section</A> ] 
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
