<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsagencies in Transition</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Newsagencies in Transition</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Two</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
To us, in many cases, the question of who is right and who is wrong is secondary. Our readers will decide that. Our priority is to ensure that both sides of an ideological or political conflict have
equal chances to defend their causes.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
The challenge for us in wake of the liberalized environment that comes with greater democracy and the communications revolution is not the search for so-called Asian journalistic values. We believe that all over the world, such values should be the same. They should allow all people at all levels to share information equally and enjoy freedom of expression.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
We believe that the quest for so called Asian values as advocated by some Asian leaders is too self-centered and has a grain of anticivil liberty because the state still has too much control over the people.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Our newspaper's stand on human rights most of the times pits us
against Asean governments. Last year the Indonesian embassy pulled out supplementary advertisement with The Nation. This year one of our reporters received a visa to attend an Asean meeting in Indonesia only at the last minute.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	 	
The official Asean version of human rights on the other hand is at odds with the western version. Asean governments argue that human rights principles in the region must be based on its culture and history as well. We at the Nation newspaper disagree.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Maybe our newspaper's attitude and policy have much to do with a characteristic of the Thai people. Thais are very cynical about their government. There is no state-controlled paper in Thailand and there can never be. The only government newspaper that I remember was published some 20 years ago, and it lasted only a few weeks.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Even during a clampdown in the 1970's, Thai newspapers defy the government in their own ways. Siam Rath, which was owned by the late Kukrit Pramoj, a well-known writer and former Prime Minister, stopped doing political reports and opted for absolutely absurd stories. People woke up in the morning and saw these frontpage headlines:  "Birds sing beautifully at Government House"; or "We have counted for you: there are 300 trees around the Defence Ministry".
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This conference has heard that bad media can undermine a nation. I can't agree more. But I think the bottom line is that it is the people, not government, who are in the best position to teach the media to be responsible. Bad press can never get people's long-term supoort. Sooner or later, people will become smarter and they will find out. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Media should have its own responsibility. A decision to publish or not to publish a story should be made in the news room and based on public interest.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Having talked about all this, it would be unfair not to mention restrictions we face in Thailand. Thai newspapers cannot criticise the monarchy, the country's most respected institution. Some of you may think we have a double-standard, for being aggressive when it comes to security or sensitive matters of other countries while being silent to similar issues at home.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
