<!--Website produced by Future Thinkers 1996-->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Four</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Four</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Kunda Dixit, Tulsathit Taptim. Section Two.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 3.</B> <BR>
Syd Asprey from DPA. A couple of weeks ago the editorials in Thai English-language newspapers caused some controversy in Australia. One comment that was made was that the government didn't need to worry about these editorials because the English-language press in South East Asia was very small and not at all influential. That it was the vernacular press that was the premier [?] informer. Could I have your views on the role of the English-language press in, say, Thailand and Indonesia - non English-language speaking countries - and how you see that developing. Are you in decline, or are you growing: how do you see yourselves in say five or ten years. Thank you.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Taptin</B> <BR>
Before I came here, people in the office were joking that I could be arrested at the airport [laughter]. Now I wish I had been [laughter]. The whole thing about this Hansen debate, what we did is we just felt the need to make our opinions known. WE believed that we need some clear guidance, we need some clear directions from big country life Australia. And they upset last night [?] with us Asian people, they look at Australia, they feel like Australia is their big brother. And when the big brother one day say, when someone in the big brother's house says 'Hey you cannot come and play here anymore' [laughter]. So we need clarification. And when what we do to seek that clarification could be in an emotional way but we were sincere. WE just want to hear what the leader, the Prime Minister, the leader of a country as big as Australia, has to say about this growing trend. Somebody said that what she said, what Ms Hansen said, was the words of a person. There can be no denial that this kind of trend is rising in Australia and we just want to know what he leader of the country feels about it. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
And I think we are growing up - responding to your question . . .
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
[brief consultation off mark and indistinguishable]
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
. . . you asked about the Thai language media. Compared with English language media in Thailand they are re much more sensational. There are good newspapers but there are really really bad ones. You can see headlines like 'Government bite the opposition yesterday,' biting the legs [laughter]. And the government . . . I still remember my former Prime Minister Shun, his election [?] was that there are two things I know that bite: [?] and dogs [laughter]. And since [?] doesn't bite in the legs, I'm quite sure what the intention of the newspaper is.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So it was a sort of mutual cynicism, the Thai politicians and journalists. They're both - it is a [?] situation. It's like a 'we agree to disagree' situation. But not the situation at the moment.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 4</B>  <BR>
What sort of readership do you have, with Thai language newspapers?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Taptin</B><BR>
The readership is very small. The English language press has a really limited audience in Thailand. WE have about 50 000 copies, circulation. Our biggest rival, the Bangkok Postalso has the same circulation. So the leadership is really limited to expatriates, to well-educated people. But the influence of the English language newspapers is strong. You can have Thai newspaper making a lot of page one comments and nothing happens. But when we do a page one comment it has an impact.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 5</B><BR>
[?? from Hong Kong] According to the Hansen debate case, I want to ask both the panellist: is that the nationalism really have some role to play in affecting the objectivity of reports?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Taptin</B><BR>
I think reporting is one thing and commentary is another. When we make report, when we do our report we try to be as objective as we can. But when we make commentary we pull no punches.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>[interjection from floor, off mike. A woman following up her earlier question]</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
You talk about Thai language media: no objectivity! [laughter] Not at all, there are some good newspapers, but most of them are quite sensational, very very sensational. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>[clarification from floor, about nationalism]</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
There is no nationalism in Thailand. Thais are so cynical. They attack everything. They attack their own government, they gossip about high press people, they . . . So . . . They are the people who have prejudice or bias in the media community, but it's not because of nationalism. There's no righties or lefties at the moment, just pure [?] problems [laugh]. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kunda Dixit</B><BR>
Can I just say something. I think that on racism there's very little chance that someone can be objective. I think what the Australian politicians have to realise is that whenever they're playing to a domestic gallery it will have repercussions internationally. Because they might think they're only talking for political reasons back home, but there's almost immediate reaction abroad.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 6</B><BR>
Richard Phillips from the University of Western Sydney, Nepean. Just ask whether you have a few of the question earlier in the afternoon about whether journalists should become more multiskilled. What you find in your organisation. Do you think that journalists are changing that way to become expert in also photography and so on, or what?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kunda Dixit</B> <BR>
Well, within our own organisation, in IPS, we'd rather make them multi-skilled in the software, you know, not in the hardware, so that they understand the subject and understand the multidisciplinary nature of the subject. That when they report on the WTO meeting in Singapore that they understand issues, they understand the various, the whole spectrum of concerns, of both developing countries and developed, not just from one side. so it's to expand your own mind before you approach the subject, and not just camera, or a video camera, or whether you can shoot it on your satellite from your suitcase. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 7</B> <BR>
[?] from Charles Sturt University. First of all I'd really like to compliment you because they were both very inspiring talks, and I think that if you like - from an Australian point of view - we had professionals this morning who really have done wonderful work and they are really inspired idealist people (I won't embarrass them by mentioning their names), but the impression that came across was one of great cynicism. And although you say that the Thai media's cynical, I think that your idealism shone through. And all I can say is that idealism is very important for young people who want to become journalists. They don't merely chase the buck. It isn't the bottom line for them. It might be for the proprietors. You'll never get a journalist, a young one at any rate, purely interested in money.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now I'm getting to a really technical question. And this is to  Kunda Dixit. What I couldn't understand is, you told us how you can use the internet to spread out your material quickly and cheaply. And then you said - it seemed to me - that you had an encryption problem. People could raid you. Well I don't understand that. I subscribe .  . . 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>. . . [part way through question. mike rattle]</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kunda Dixit</B><BR>  
Yeah, I can tell you tricks about getting IPS for free. [laughter] Maybe I shouldn't. But there are tricks.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question cont. </B><BR>
But can you still get money from honest people?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kunda Dixit </B><BR>
Well we don't really mind if journalism schools rip us off, because it's all for a good cause, but if media does it we try to - yeah, there have been instances where we've talked to them and threatened to sue them. But as you know, this whole information thing, once it's out there, there's so many ways you can get it for free. You have customised passwords which one of your subscribers has, but can be 'subcontracting' it to someone else, you know. There are ways where they can get stuff from your website and read everything for free because they get your password from someone else. There are contracts we have with Nexus for example in the States, which is only for North American distribution but you can access it anywhere in the world. So they have this bulk rate for Nexus but they can also get IPS, and anyone else that Nexus carries. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
What I meant about the cost of delivery being zero was: just to send our service to some specialised client. So on the homepage side it's different. And I think, we're now working on it to raise revenue that way. In the States our US subsidiary is making a lot of money. We just have to internationalise it.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
