<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Two</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Draconian Laws in Place</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>The refusal of the government to press ahead with an omnibus broadcasting law will not in itself threaten press freedom. But this is not the case with the government's refusal to bring forward meaningful changes to security related laws.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>First there is the Emergency Regulations Ordinance. Its subsidiary legislation was scrapped, but this is not of great significance because the main ordinance continues to confer wide-ranging and ill-defined powers on the Governor and his closest advisers in the Executive Council to declare an emergency and subsequently to make regulations which provide, inter alia, for censorship and the control and suppression of publications. The law allows the declaration of an emergency "on any occasion which the Governor in Council may consider to be an occasion of emergency or public danger," and then empowers the Executive Council to make "any regulations whatsoever which he may consider desirable in the public interest."
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>This ordinance is, in the view of the HKJA, excessive. If it survives the 1997 handover unchanged, it will represent an open invitation to abuse. We therefore call on the British and Hong Kong governments to amend the ordinance in such a way that it makes explicit reference to the limits placed on a declaration of emergency by section 5 of the Hong Kong Bill of Rights Ordinance, which mirrors article 4 of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights. We also want the Legislative Council to be given the power to approve or disapprove a state of emergency once it has been declared.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>There has also been little progress by the government in talks with China about changes to the Official Secrets Act and the Crimes Ordinance, as it relates to treason and sedition. Draft bills have been submitted to the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group - the diplomatic body charged with overseeing the handover. Officials are refusing to give any details of the proposals, citing the group's confidentiality rules.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>However, sources close to the administration have indicated that much-needed liberalisation is not on the agenda. Indeed, the draft changes to the Crimes Ordinance have incorporated new offences - subversion and secession - which have to be incorporated into Hong Kong law under a provision in the territory's post-1997 constitution.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Other changes involve provisions with a colonial flavour. These include clauses in treason provisions relating to the British monarch and the British armed forces. Such provisions will lapse on July 1, 1997. Of particular concern to the HKJA is the excessively wide-ranging, often obsolete nature of the treason and sedition offences under the law. We believe that reform must, in particular, take into account more liberal thinking on the concepts of treasonable and seditious intention.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>It is debatable whether China wishes to reach agreement with Britain on these issues, given that they are highly sensitive and matters close to Beijing's heart. There is a feeling that China is likely to take unilateral action, possibly by pushing them through a hand-picked provisional legislature to be set up next year. It should also be noted that China's understanding of such offences as treason and sedition is far more stringent than Britain's. Further, the concepts of subversion and secession do not even exist in the British common law system.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>There are other items on our agenda, including the introduction of an omnibus broadcasting bill to replace the Television, Telecommunication and Broadcasting Authority ordinances, amendments to the Telecommunication and Post Office ordinances, as they relate to the interception of messages and mail, and the deletion of the outstanding criminal libel provision in the Defamation Ordinance.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
