<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Six</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Wendy Bacon, Jon Casimir, David Wilson. Section Two</B></FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Unidentified questioner</B><BR>
This is not a question so much as a comment to Jon, who sees in the future the development in communication, net communication, the dominant centre with a lot of satellites. It's already here. The US  is the only email address is the only address where you do not have to identify the country.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Jon Casimir </B><BR>
I know what you're talking about but I actually think that's just historical administrative accident more than anything else. It is also due to the fact that Americans see themselves as the centre of the universe by and large [laughter], and the thing has developed from there. But when I said a dominant centre in terms of satellite, what you seem to get in all forms of digital media is very large monolithic core groups and very small ones. What I'd be predicting in terms of media is that there'd be a few global media services - whether it's CNN or whoever - and a whole lot of very localised things.  I think that middle tier of media - your nationals or your regionals - won't really work in the commercial sense. You can actually apply that to almost any digital industry you can see it happening in. The thing about the net, the thing about digital technology, is it just wants to cut out the middleman.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Unidentified questioner </B><BR>
I'd like to ask Jon about the difference between an on-line editor and - I mean, what is your actual day-to-day job and how does it differ from being an editor of a print outlet.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Jon Casimir </B><BR>
Well right at the moment the main difference is that I'm - as I frequently bitch to people about - 'birthing'  that entire end of the company. An editor of a section of the paper now has a whole production set up: we know how to make newspapers, we know what a press is, we know all that kind of stuff. I spend an extraordinary, and frankly appalling, amount of my time in meetings I don't want to be in discussing hardware, software, advertising policies, administrative polices, how we're actually going to build the railroad and build the train before we can deliver the stuff. So at the moment that's the basic way it differs. I have an extraordinary large percentage of my day with stuff that as an editor and journalist I'd rather not be doing.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Karen Glahn.</B><BR>
Karen Glahn, Danish newspaper This one's for David. I just want to know - it's probably ignorance on my behalf - but the Reuters news service, does it give what you have got and what you came here today, was that he sales pitch or information? [laughter] I mean, very charmingly done . . .
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>David Wilson</B><BR>
Thank you! Do they have it? to a certain extent sure. And Mike himself has identified Reuters as our competition worldwide. I mean that organisation. That said, you're talking about an organisation where Mr Reuter is dead - what? - 100 and some odd years, where Dow and Jones have long since passed, and Knight and Ridder and all these people. We're doing it in our time, like [...] is still going around the world giving speeches. It's something where we're trying to take the technology that exists today, and start from scratch. Literally an entire global organisation from scratch, and I was in on the ground floor back in 1990. If we had times I could show you things on this terminal you won't get on the Reuters news because literally the e-links [?] do not exist. [laughter] It's fact! Now you can laugh it off if you want, but the fact is, for example bond markets, blew [...] because you can say OK, either bond's cheap or bond's expensive, we've given people tools they don't have before. 
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Part of . . . is how to take those tools and turn them into pros. I mean Nat Winkle who's my boss and runs the organisation likes to say, that we're in the news business long before there was text. It was information in a different form: numbers, graphs, charts, tables etc. When the journalists came along, we brought in text, we brought in context and all the rest. I think what you were saying earlier it seems to me, kind of fits our model as much as it did the earlier example: the idea that you look at the posting from Sarajevo and then you read the international reporting and it gives you a different perspective than you'd have if you had one or the other only. And the same is true of perspective when it comes to the screens I showed you. There isn't a doggone thing I showed you that's going to tell you why . That's where the journalists come in, and that's how it all fits together for us. You know, sure, we're out there doing the same thing others have done. People in our organisation would be the first to tell you we didn't reinvent the wheel. I'd like to say we tried to work out a different way to make it roll. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
