<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Intersections with Asia: Where the Media stands</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Intersections with Asia:<BR>
 Where the Media stands</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Two</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It's very important in Australia that our coverage be genuinely international and genuinely global but with, I believe, a particular emphasis on the Asia-Pacific, because that's increasingly the part of the world in which our destiny as a country will be determined and shaped. But having made these points I'm concerned, first of all, about the extent to which we are covering the world properly. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
To what extent do you read much in the papers about the crisis of identity going on in the United Kingdom at the moment? And it's a genuine crisis of identity. Is Britain to remain an island off the coast of Europe forever? Is Britain to surrender its national sovereignty and join Europe in a comprehensive way so that the powers of Westminster parliament are subsumed eventually into a European federation, and Britain joins a European monetary union and the identity of its own currency the pound is folded into a new European currency? Britain at the moment is completely racked with the debate about national identity, national sovereignty and its own future: to what extent is this being sufficiently covered in Australia, to what extent is it being appreciated that this is a really fundamental debate judged by any measure.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
On the other hand, looking closer to home, to what extent is there sufficient appreciation in Australia of the enormous magnitude of political liberalisation going on in the Asia-Pacific and of economic changes going on in the Asia-Pacific? Again, I think these are enormously important issues, and I think too much of the coverage in this country is skating across the surface. WE must get beneath the surface. This brings us to the question of means. How do we do this? If I can just focus here on Australian newspapers, essentially there are two ways we do it. We do it by taking, by buying syndicated services or by putting out own correspondents into the region. They're essentially the two methods. Both are very expensive; neither is being handled terribly well. If I could just take first of all the cost of services. I think that Australian newspapers are not using their syndicated services - for which they are paying very substantial amounts of money on an annual basis - they're not using these services well at all and this goes to the question of how the newspapers are organised, their capacity to identify the copy that's on line and to get that worthwhile copy into a newspaper. That's not being handled well. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Secondly, when it comes to employment of their own correspondents, I think that far greater effort could be made here. It's very important that Australia sees the region through its own eyes. Absolutely fundamental. Now we are expanding, newspapers are expanding their number of foreign correspondents in the region, and the ABC has a very substantial network of foreign correspondents in the region. One of the difficulties of course is that the cost of a foreign post is conservatively a quarter of a million dollars, and if you're talking about some posts such as Japan it's an awful lot more. So it's a high cost exercise to put foreign correspondents into the region. However it's an exercise which must be tackled, an issue which must be confronted. It is very very important for Australia to cover the region with its own eyes. It's one thing for us to take American services - very important for us to take American services - but we cannot interpret and cover the Asia-Pacific just through American eyes. Frankly what we ought to be trying to do is to expand and build up our own coverage of the Asia-Pacific and then sell this coverage as a syndicated service to northern-hemisphere papers. That's what we ought to be doing.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I think that to a certain extent a lot of our foreign correspondents have great difficulty in trying to interpret the job of a foreign correspondent in the 1990s. There is so much material available in most capitals. What do you report on? what do you cover? And I think the answer to that question is that he job of the foreign correspondent is not just to duplicate what syndicated services might do out of a particular capital. It's to provide a value-added service. That's why the foreign correspondent's there. The foreign correspondent's got to be good enough to provide that value added service; the foreign correspondent has got to have expertise in the country and in the region - but expertise is not good enough, the foreign correspondent's got to be a good journalist in his or her own right. So I think you need experienced people as foreign correspondents, and you need people who've got a degree of expertise so that they can genuinely provide added value. We need a much greater emphasis in the Australian media on the need for genuine expertise in the region. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I think you need to be aware of the fact, frankly, that an Australian correspondent in Washington carries no clout whatsoever. An Australian correspondent in Jakarta does carry clout. Now what this means is we need to appreciate that there will be different types of foreign correspondents and there'll be different ways of operating. I was quite pleased earlier on this year - not long after the change of government - when you'll recollect that there was a lot of difficulty in our bilateral relations with a number of countries in the region, in particular with Indonesia. And I might just say something about the Australian's coverage of this as a newspaper. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
We as a paper do have considerable expertise when it comes to Indonesia, and I think frankly the Australian government - and senior people in the Australian government - were quite surprised at the fact that as a paper we were able to deal with the Indonesian government, with senior figures in the Indonesian government, on a one-to-one basis, and we were able to write in our paper what was going on in Indonesia and what was the feeling in the Indonesian government towards the Australian government. And were able to do that simply because we have very good contacts in Indonesia just as we have very good contacts in Canberra. And it's very important that Australian newspapers and Australian news outlets get to the stage where we have such contacts that we can deal with senior bureaucrats and senior ministers and heads of government through the Asia-Pacific. And it's when we can do that in terms of our newspaper operations that we'll know that we as a country and we as a media, enmeshing with the Asia-Pacific, meeting our responsibilities as a media in this part of the world. That means having sufficient contacts and access that we can break stories and we know what's going on, and often we know what's going on before the Australian government does. I think that in some countries we are now getting to this stage, and that's particularly important. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="kelly03.html">Next section</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="kelly01.html">Previous section</A> ] 
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
