<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Seven</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Paul Kelly. Section Two.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 3.</B><BR>
Geoff Lee Paul, first of all I'd like to say that I think that the correspondents in the field from the Australian - particularly Patrick Walters on Indonesia - do tend to be very good journalists in what they do. I'm just taking this opportunity to raise a beef that I have with the Australian, so if it appears a bit parochial I apologise to some of the other people in the room. It would seem to me that the Australian is trying to do two things. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
One, it's trying to make a profit, and part of making that profit is the supplements that you run regularly on Asian countries - the individual countries in the region and on the region as a whole - and the information which goes into that supplement is largely geared around corporations and businesses and government departments who have interests and investments in those counties in the region and vice versa. Second thing your newspaper purports to do is to be a national leader and national flagship for this country in representing Australia's views to the region. But I think there is a problem with that in that we're really talking about two Australias and we're really talking about two Malaysias and two Indonesias. That is, the government-to-government level of cultural communications and the people-to-people level. More specifically, my beefs would be with such things as your newspaper sending correspondents out to cover major events such as the twentieth anniversary of Indonesia's de jure recognition or incorporation of East Timor as the 27th province, to a picket outside the Malaysian consulate last July 17th, having a journalist do extensive interviews, having a photographer there, and not running one word. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now that's one of many many examples when the East Timor issues has been totally - if I'd use the word censored it may be little too strong because it has competing priorities. On the Bougainville issue, a freelance journalist who was paid by your newspaper for 12 articles he wrote before the embargo was lifted on the Bougainville story when the new Liberal government got in and changed policy on that. His name is Max Watts. He was paid for twelve stories he wrote on that conflict between 1991 and 93 and all of them were spiked. My final example is, following the Sherman Report being released a number of people rang your features editor's desk and said they'd be prepared to submit an article in response to the death of the Australian journalists at Balibo. They were rudely told by your features editor, 'we will get our own person to do that' and in the end it finished up being [????] Sebrand  who was known to be - as you are through the Australia Indonesia Institute - more closely aligned to the establishment view on relations with Indonesia and hostile to the East Timorese independence lobby.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kelly</B><BR>
Look, I'll just respond to that very very briefly. We require from our journalists the highest decree of professionalism. I appreciate the point you made at the start about Patrick Walters. I regard Patrick Walters as one of the best foreign correspondents in Indonesia, across the board, from any country. And I think that he's a very experienced and a very competent journalist. Now you've raised some individual matters - I'm not aware of those individual matters - I'll just say this. That we take editorial decisions about who will contribute to the paper. No outsider has a right to contribute to our paper. Ultimately my editors will take that decision and I'm responsible for it. And it's quite wrong for any outsider to think that if they call our newspaper . . . 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
[answer cut off, end of tape]
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
 . . . that's a particularly important point to make, and often in discussions - such as some of the comments you've just made - one tends to blur them. Finally, when it comes to our coverage of various countries, I do insist on a balanced coverage. Therefore, when it comes to Indonesia, I would expect our correspondent to cover all events and developments in Indonesia. I don't want our correspondent to focus unduly on East Timor. I recognise that East Timor is an important issue, and therefore in our coverage I would expect East Timor to figure prominently. But I would not expect East Timor to dominate our coverage out of Jakarta. Again, it's a question of balance and judgment. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20>
<br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
