<B></B><HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER AND CIVIL SOCIETY</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=475 SRC="/../images/online.gif" ALT="The Online Journalist"></A>
<IMG VSPACE=10 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
<td width=20><BR></td><td ALIGN=center>
<H1>THE PUBLIC  BROADCASTER<BR>
AND CIVIL SOCIETY</H1>
</td><td width=10><BR></td></tr></table>

<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<B>Submission sections:</B>

<BR><IMG VSPACE=3 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> [Radio National (RN)]<BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430><FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>Radio National (RN)</B>
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
RN has to be seen as the core of the radio networks, the spine that gives not only the rest of the network shape, but also informs the rest of the media by providing the first level of stories. While this is often part of the role of the news and current affairs teams which also service the metros and other networks, the standards set by Radio National affects the way that other networks operate.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The processes legitimated as ABC standards are implicitly set by RN. These involve time taken to check stories, production standards and a broad based acknowledgment that stories presented are complex and views and opinions are varies. The talk components on Radio National, the specialist and more generalist programs assume that items are researched and varied views and voices sought. Producers, researchers and presenters are expected to put to air items and shows which are professionally and ethically defensible. They incorporate aspects of an explicit and implicit charter of responsibilities to diverse communities.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Some stories break on the ABC because there is the time, sometimes, to follow up and investigate stories. Stories are based on material from here and overseas which comes from journals and contacts, rather than what was in the morning papers. There is a focus on conferences and on experts who have something new to say and therefore the content over any time period is both wider and deeper than what is accessible on the metros or on commercial media.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
The view held by some internal managers that this type of activity can be sustained  by 'buying in these types of programs in chunks through Metro strip programming fails to recognise that the loss of the network will have devastating effects. Specialist units without regular programs and time slots become atomised and vulnerable to change and elimination.
<BR><IMG VSPACE=6 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>
Publicly funded national radio is one of the stronger threads in our national fabric. In a diverse and scattered society, a widely available, free-to-air national broadcaster is essential. Tying together city and country, diverse cultural groups, religious, richer and poorer; all the rich tapestry of Australian life cannot be left to the vagaries of the market. The 'shock and schlock jocks' that dominate the USA airwaves indicate the potential influence of radio in creating conflicts, racism and other uncivil phenomena. We need to make sure that there are always countervailing voices on public radio as symbols of more civil societies.
</FONT>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=468 SRC="/../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=475><tr>
<td width=40><BR></td>
<td width=430>
<CENTER><A HREF="#top">[Return to top]</A> <A HREF="cox-05">[Previous section]</A> <A HREF="cox-07.html">[Next section]</A></CENTER>

<CENTER><A HREF="cox-01.html">[Changing Australia]</A> <A HREF="cox-02.html">[Political correctness and balance]</A> <A HREF="cox-03.html">[The agora or forum]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-04.html">[The ABC is not cultural spakfilla]</A> <A HREF="cox-05.html">[The metros]</A> [Radio National (RN)]<BR>
<A HREF="cox-07.html">[Social Capital and the ABC]</A> <A HREF="cox-08.html">[The displeased piper's wanted tunes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-09.html">[The ABC too timid with alternative views?]</A> <A HREF="cox-10.html">[Some proposals for changes]</A><BR>
<A HREF="cox-mr01.html">[Marian Robinson]</A> <A HREF="cox-mr02.html">[A two day listening sample]</A></CENTER>
</td></tr></table>

<IMG VSPACE=4 SRC="/../resources/dot_clear.gif"><BR>

