<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 

 STUDENT PLANS TO SUE POLICE ON CLASH<font size= 3><p>

 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475> <TD width= 275  align =left>

<td align=center><A HREF="UniT_toktok.html"><IMG width=200 SRC="images/teargas.jpeg" ALT="Photo of teargas victim" align=bottom></A><f3><STRONG> <P>Philip Yobale ... injured during teargas incident.</STRONG><BR>
<Font size=1>Photo: DAVID ROBIE<P>
</TABLE></td><tr>

<Font size=3>By LYNNE AMEPOU<P>
A student injured in last month's [June] clash between police and university students plans to sue the police for alleged damages.
<P>
Philip Yobale, 28, a final-year creative arts student, was injured when trying to escape from teargas fired by the police into the crowd. 
<P>
He suffered a deep gash on the right side of his forehead, which needed seven stitches, and bruises on his body. 
<P>
"I was suffocating and couldn't see where I was going," he said. "I was pushed against the iron main gate."  
<P>
<P>
<P>The university doctor, Dr Ninikama Moiya, confirmed he had treated two students for injuries during the protest, including Mr Yobale.
<P>
Mr Yobale also had his four-year-old son, Raymond, with him who also suffered from teargas inhalation and scratches on his body. 
<P>
Mr Yobale said: "I have asked the doctor for a report and will take action in conjunction with the university's Student Representative Council."
<P>
SRC president Leslie Menei and vice-president David Arore could not be reached for comment.
<P>
A student leader, Aula Kobale, who was arrested during the clash alleged he had been beaten up and abused by police when taken to Waigani police station.
<P>  
"No charges were laid against me and I was treated like a criminal," he said.
<P>
He was released after an hour when Mr Menei called the police.
</P>


</td><tr>

</table>
