 STUDENTS CAMPAIGN TO ABOLISH USER-PAY<font size= 3><p>

 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475> <TD width= 475  align =left>

By MADLYN AREK
<P>
Student leaders from both universities -- University of Papua New Guinea and the University of Technology -- are looking at every possible avenue to change the PNG government's controversial "user-pay" policy -- even if it means pursuing the matter in court.
<P>
Two conferences have been planned to be held in September and October at the UPNG campus and Unitech.
<P>
The students, general public, non-government organisation and prominent leaders will be invited to aur their views on the user-pay policy.
<P>
Awareness campaigns against the user-pay policy have been scheduled for tertiary students during the Christmas break.
<P>
The chairman of the awareness campaign, Sandis Tsaka, said: "The small Papua New Guinean will be the one whop is going to be severely affected by the policy, experiencing an increase in the costs of basic services."
<P>
The Governor of Manus, Stephen Pokawin, informed the students and members of the public at the sit-in protest at Parliament that fees would increase by 10 per cent next year and if the government stayed in power by 1997 then parents would need to be prepared to pay 50 per cent by the year 2000.
<P>
A student leader criticised the government for "mismanaging" the country's resources and blaming it on the economic crisis.
<P>
The Education Minister, Dr John Waiko, told the students that government introduced the new merit scholarships in 1997 for tertiary, technical and secondary students with proven academic excellence.
<P>
"Two hundred of these scholarships would be offered to tertiary students while the secondary and technical institutions would receive 100 each," Dr Waiko said.
<P>
The students who could not pay their way through their studies would borrow from the government, then repay their loan later.<BR>
ends
<P>
</P>
</table>

