PIPELINE TO LINK PNG GAS FOR QLD MARKETS<font size= 3><p>

 
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475> <TD width= 475  align =left>

By JOSEPH MOROKANA
<P>
A Canadian company, International Petroleum Corporation (IPC), is embarking on plans to build a pipeline linking Pandora offshore gas field in the Gulf Province and the Kutubu gas fields in the Southern Highlands province, to deliver Papua New Guinea gas to Queensland. 
<P>
The agreement signed by IPC and Chevron Niugini in March this year will carry out a feasibility study to deliver one trillion cubic feet of PNG gas to Queensland markets for industrial demands. 
<P>
IPC manager Ted Webb has met with Chevron Niugini for discussions and construction of the pipeline will commence once the study has been completed.
<P>
Mr Webb said: "We have always thought that the Pandora project could be vital in making substantial changes to the Queensland energy market. It could bring large gas resources in PNG to the Queensland market. 
<P>
"By combining the gas resources in PNG, we may also consider linking North Queensland to Central Queensland. This could lead to long-term competitive energy prices permitting faster economic development in PNG and Queensland."
<P>
He said that developing offshore and onshore gas resources in PNG would bring significant benefits to the country. 
<P>
The feasibility study of linking Pandora and Kutubu gas fields was initiated in December 1995. It includes: 
<P><UL>
<LI>IPC 48.19 per cent.

<LI>Command Petroleum Gulf Pty Ltd 16.36 per cent. 

<LI>Ampolex (Pandora Reef) Pty Ltd 12.73 per cent. 

<LI>Pacarc (PNG) Pty Ltd 6.36 per cent.

<LI>Claremont (PNG) Pty Ltd 6.36 per cent. 

<LI>Secab Niugini Pty Ltd 5 per cent.

<LI>Oil Search Ltd 5 per cent.
</UL><P>
Mr Webb said IPC will negotiate with the parties concerned and ensure that contact and discussion with villages along the pipeline route, regarding environmental impacts and other issues relating to the proposed development will continue regularly.
<P>
Mr Webb said the PNG government was instrumental in initiating this approach to investigate the possibility of linking PNG's onshore and offshore gas to service the Queensland markets. 
<P>
Chevron's government and cmmunity affairs manager, Epoa Lalatute, said it would take time and effort to carry out the study to see whether the project would be economically viable for the country. 
<P>
He said it was important to reach a resolution with the parties concerned to enable the project to get underway.
<P>
"There has to be a continuity in discussions and resolutions with the landowners in the Torres Straits, Kikori and Kutubu areas where the pipeline is going to run," he said.
<P>
Meanwhile, earlier this year two Southern Highlands landowner groups threatened to shut down the Kutubu oil field and the pipeline carrying the key export commodity to the coast.
<P>
Mining and Petroleum Minister John Giheno when answering their demands said: "The law clearly states all forms of mineral wealth are owned by the state. It does not belong to one person, a group or a tribe where those resources are found."
<P>
Mr Giheno welcomed the negotiations, and promised to pay outstanding dividends to the landowners. However, he rebuked the landowners over their high demands.
<P>
IPC, the operator of the joint venture, is exclusively engaged in international oil and gas exploration and production.
<P>
</P>
</table>
