<hr>

<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
FOCUS : Toothless Tiger? No. This watchdog knows how to bite.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Raphael Semel </strong><p>


<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475> <TD width= 475  align =left>

If you're a politician, it wouldn't be surprising if you're nervous about a dog snapping at your heels. A dog? Well, a watchdog. <P>

	This watchdog, the Ombudsman Commission, keeps tabs on Government bodies and public figures as it carefully monitors this crucial period of financial crisis and corruption taking place in the country.<P>

	 It is an independent commission which is not subject to direction and control of any person or authority. And it safeguards the rights of citizens by preventing maladministration by Government agencies, abuse of power, bribery, fraud, misappropriation of public funds for personal gain and corruption. <P>

	The Ombudsman Commission is described as a "cleaner" which cleans up the backyard of public leaders and organisations. <P>

	The commission performs two major political functions in investigating "complaints" and "leadership". The complaints division can investigate any misconduct on state service, provincial service and violation of rules in government departments or statutory bodies by people in authority.<P>

	 A brochure says an organic law on the "duties and responsibilities of leadership" gives power and permission to the commission to bring to book all violations of the leadership code by leaders of the nation.<P>

	 The brochure also says public figures like the personal staff of the Governor-General, ministers and opposition leaders would lose their credibility and reputation if injustice casts a shadow over them.<P>


<strong>Malpractices: </strong>The commission is happy to investigate on its own initiative or on a complaint by a person affected by the Government agencies. It is understood that it cannot "bite" or "harm" the Government organs and leaders who get out off hand; it just carries out research and investigates malpractices.<P>

	But the commission has legal power to call upon the head of a department to produce all documents, files and relevant papers regarding the complaint. <P>

	The commission is currently investigating the alleged misappropriation of educational division funds in Oro province.<P>

	 The Provincial Administrator of Oro, Murray Maroroa, says: "The education auditor is under pressure to collate and submit the reports to the Ombudsman soon." The complaints division of the commission will put the jigsaw puzzle together by analysing reports to find the faults. <P>

	"The ombudsman would move a step closer to investigating the reports of each teacher," says Mr Maroroa. This would specifically identify where and what is the root cause of the malpractice and would give the commission an opportunity to make recommendations about the problem.<P>

	 The ombudsman can summon anyone who would give evidence or information in connection with the investigation and can enter any premises occupied by state services to inspect the place in relation to a complaint. It is responsible to instruct and put pressure on leaders if they do not behave according to the law or leadership code.<P>	

</td></tr>
</table>

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475>
<td width =270 align left>

	The commission project officer, Leo Oaeke, says leaders have to know laws on duties and responsibilities. Mr Oaeke adds, "the commission could take action against leaders who violate the regulations."<P>

	 Mr Oaeke worked with the Foreign Affairs Department and Governor-General's Office before going to the Ombudsman Commission.<P>

	 He is a new project officer in the public awareness and training unit of public relations.<P>

	He was attached to Uni Tavur for two weeks in March. And he now plans to do a desktop publishing short course in June, which would be held at UPNG by the South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information in Development <a href = "UniT_SPCenCIID.html">(SPCenCIID).</a><P>

	The commission is free to explore the untouched realm of politicians and can disclose information about malpractice and corruption.<P>
</td>

<td align=center> <IMG  alt= "Mr. Oaeke." SRC= "UT-Oaeke.jpg"></td><tr>
</table>

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475>

	<strong> Privacy: </strong>Individuals who hold on to the public purse and have access to public facilities must be aware that you are not well protected under the Privacy Act. <P>

	The leadership division of the Ombudsman Commission cannot physically touch you but it can make inquiries to take necessary action to enforce compliance by leaders, and also investigate violations and breaches of the leadership code. <P>
	The commission can take tough or easy steps to request leaders to submit vital documents such as annual statements of assets, incomes, business connections, business transactions, gifts and liabilities and accounts of public monies.<P>
	<strong> Legal process: </strong>If there is evidence of violation of the leadership code or misconduct in office by a leader then the matter is referred to the Public Prosecutor for legal process by an appropriate tribunal. <P>
	If the leader is found guilty then recommendation is made to the appropriate state authority to dismiss the person from office or impose other penalty on him or her.<P>
	The Ombudsman would easily identify wrong conduct if it is: 
<UL><LI> Contrary to law.
<LI> Unreasonable, unjust, oppressive and discriminatory - whether or not it complies with the law.
<LI> Based on improper motives and irrelevant grounds and considerations. o Based on mistakes of law or fact.
<LI> Conduct for which reasons should be given but have not been.</ul><P>
	The commission has restrictions which prohibit it from investigating some Government agencies.<P>
	It would not question a decision by a court unless it appears defective in law or administrative practice but would never make an inquiry into the setting up of rules by a local government body.<P>
	<strong>Major role:</strong> The Ombudsman Commission plays a major role in the country but has limited powers to publish its proceedings, reports and recommendations to the general public. Investigations conducted by commission are confidential. <P>
	Last year, The Independent published an edited version of the Auditor-General+s report of its investigation into two lease agreements by the National Housing Corporation with Neisenal No 77 Pty Ltd which was tabled in Parliament on March 28.<P>
	The Auditor-General did not have access to some documents such as board meeting minutes for 1993 and 1994. The secretary of the NHC said the documents were under the custody of the Ombudsman Commission but the Auditor-General was unable to obtain them.<P>
	Once a year the Ombudsman Commission presents a report on the functions and work of the commission with its own recommendation for improvements to Parliament.<P>
	An informed source says the commission is not working at full capacity and is not covering all provinces so that it can carry out its duty. The source says: "This is because the National Government is not fully using the commission by allocating sufficient funds to the Ombudsman to carry out its function." <P>
	Many people say "the commission isn't a toothless tiger nor a creature of the Government in power to whitewash the sins of Government agencies and politicians."<P>
	It is there to perform its constitutional duty, ensuring that Government agencies do the right thing regardless of colour, creed, wealth or poverty.<P>
	 The Ombudsman Commission wants justice to prevail as a flag of the nation rather than abuses of power to overshadow the less powerful people.<P>
</td><tr>

</table>
