<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
VIEWPOINT : An embarrassing bias over aid.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Sorariba Nash </strong><p>


Doesn't 21 years of journalism education expertise in the Pacific count? <P>
	The University of Papua New Guinea has produced more than 150 journalism graduates - many of them in prominent positions in the media around the Pacific today.<P>
	According to one survey, 68 per cent of PNG's journalists have tertiary qualifications. UPNG was the base for UNESCO's Pacjourn (Pacific Journalism) program.<P>
	In return for the expertise it shared with other Pacific countries before the pendulum swing to Fiji, it has become an aid pariah in the region even though we have time after time demonstrated our value.<P>
	 Only one UPNG application under the Pacpress program (US$168,000 for the region) over the last three years - funding for a consultant in our Certificate in Investigative Journalism program launched last year - has been accepted. The other two were not even given the courtesy of an acknowledgment. <P> 
	Fiji-based applications get favourable treatment.<P>
	 The bias is so blatant we'd think twice about applying again to UNESCO. Thanks to organisations like the Post-Courier, Canada Fund through CUSO, the Dutch media aid agency CAF and the NZ High Commission we have had some welcome assistance in recent years.<P>
	Now we hear that AusAID has come up with a five-year aid package called the Pacific Media Initiative to the value of A$3 million. And introducing the scheme, it has put out a project design document. <P>
	This flawed document was supposedly compiled after "wide-ranging consultation" with organisations and individuals within Australia and the Pacific region. <P>
	Although we hear that Papua New Guinea is one of the beneficiaries of this package, none of the individuals or media organisations from this country were consulted. 
UPNG was named as one of five peak journalism training institutions in the report but nobody from this end was consulted. <P>
	The names and organisations are entirely Australian and Fijian apart from regional bodies like the Pacific Islands Broadcasting Association (PIBA), Pacific Islands News Association (PINA), the South Pacific Commission (SPC) Media Centre and the University of the South Pacific - which are all Fiji based!<P>
	This is quite embarrassing. We from this end feel "inadequate" or more so, we don't count anymore. Australians would have been better off calling this package: Australia-Fiji Media Initiatives.<P> 	This is a blatant act of bias and discrimination. If it is a crime to be a member of the Melanesian race and state, I have no regrets at all. <P>
	Maybe I'm just a dumb Papua New Guinean crying "foul" for no good reason. But I think with such persistent attitudes of the outsiders, we have grudgingly fought of such a defeating sense of inferiority complexes over the years. <P>
	However, I am proud of what PNG media has achieved and what it still strives to do.<P>
	On the other hand, I am too embarrassed to attend the coming PINA convention in Tonga later this year and face those "super humans". I'd prefer to stay home and pray that AusAID entertains all our applications under this package. <P>
<BR>
 <strong>Sorariba Nash </strong> is lecturer in broadcast journalism and was one of the founding students in the UPNG journalism program two decades ago.	





