<hr>


<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> Uni Tavur wins best student  paper  prize <font size= 3><p>

<strong> Staff Reporter </strong><p>


	Uni Tavur has won another journalism award  - this time the best newspaper prize in the latest JEA Ossie Awards.<P>
	Announcing the awards this week, judges convenor Roger Patching of Charles Sturt University said Uni Tavur had won the prestigious print prize in the Best Regular Student Publication category of the 1995 Ossie Awards for student journalism.<P>
	The annual awards are competed for by individual students, newspapers, TV and broadcast programs at more than 22 universities in Australia, New Zealand and the Pacific.
	This is the first time an award has gone to a Pacific tertiary institution. The judge, Max Suich, chief executive of the <Emp>Independent Monthly<emp> in Sydney, said Uni Tavur was  "by far the most impressive" of the student publications. 
"It has a level of maturity in its writing and editing and a concern with serious national issues that made it stand head and shoulders above the others," he said.<P>
	Journalism lecturer David Robie welcomed the award, saying it rewarded the paper's "tireless efforts".<p>
	Uni Tavur last year won a Pacific community newspaper award. Students from QUT and Charles Sturt University dominated  most of the individual awards.<P>
	David Robie, lecturer and managing editor of Uni Tavur, said: "We've been on the right track in our editorial approach. This is a credit to our students as we have been up against university journalism departments in Australia and New Zealand with publications produced by far greater resources than we have."<P>
	 The Ossie Awards are sponsored by journalist, educator and author Sally White in memory of her father, the respected  author and journalist Osmar White. <P>
	The Journalism Education Association (JEA) represents lecturers at the 22 professional journalism courses at Australian universities as well as journalism teaching staff at institutions in Papua New Guinea, Fiji and New Zealand.<P>


<HR><table border=0 width=100%>
