<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
The new face of UPNG law and order.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Rapheal Semel </strong><p>



	THE ADMINISTRATION of the University of Papua New Guinea has taken strong steps in the past three months to restore the well-being of the campus and to win back its high reputation and credibility. It has succeeded in drastically reducing the level of lawlessness on campus. <P>
	Vice-Chancellor Dr Rodney Hills gave this message last month at the 41st graduation ceremony to public, staff and students. <P>
	"The 'situation crime report' has successfully indicated that less crimes are committed every two weeks on campus - not like the past, when the crime record was high and committed regularly," he said. <P>
	A positive indication of a reduced law and order problem has boosted university morale. The administration's new direction is to socialise and cooperate with other university body units to "weed out" criminal activities. <P>
	<strong>Public outraged : </strong> Also at the graduation, founding father Sir Michael Somare said the situation on campus had developed to a point where the public was outraged at the number of students and teachers being killed on the campus, and students being intimidated against doing their studies. Sir Michael added that the violations and destruction of property were uncalled. <P>
	He said the campus should be a source of national pride not disgrace. <P>
	Several constructive, preventative measures have been taken to fight crime. <P>
	"Neighborhood watch" groups have been set up to monitor staff houses and other areas within the university community. The management has increased security manpower by employing 20 more temporary staff. <P>
	The registrar, Thoa Iamo, said the Vice-Chancellor had written a letter to Deputy Police Commissioner asking for a stun-gun licence to be granted to the university security unit.<P>
	This is to protect security men dealing with dangerous criminals entering the university premises.<P>
	"The stun-guns would also be beneficial to assist security safeguarding students and staff," said Mr Iamo.<P>
	Temporary security guard dogs are now operating effectively within the main campus, and medical and creative arts faculties.<P> 	Security chief Mark Alu said: "The new security personnel are the right calibre with a better background of education and security techniques." <P>
	The security unit have mace and flare-guns for protection. However, the unit still wants the administration to issue them with bulletproof vests to protect them from rascals using high-powered firearms. <P>
	Mr Alu has asked the Vice-Chancellor to install alarm devices in all academic staff houses and student dormitories.<P>
	The devices would be of great assistance in case of accidents, where they would press the alarm to inform the security about the accidents. He believes there should also be a road built around the university fence which security could patrol at night to keep outsiders from coming in.<P>
<strong> Firm support : </STRONG> The president of the Student Representative Council, Lesley Menei, said the SRC had firmly supported the moves initiated by the Vice-Chancellor to fight crime.<P>
	"The administration has cooperated well with SRC, student services, security advisory committee, security unit, regional groups and provincial groups," Mr Menei said. "The on-going problems which have been demoralising the reputation of the university are now declining."<P>
	Mr Menei said despite the cooperation to weed out crimes there was a list of students who would be facing the student-disciplinary committee for allegedly breaching the bylaws of the university.<P>
	He added that they would face different charges, according to the degree of crimes being committed.<P>
	The "situation crime reports" have indicated the law and order problem on campus has been reduced. However, the student female warden, Rosa Au, criticises the reports saying serious crimes are still being committed. <P>
	Mrs Au backed up her criticisms, saying female students were still reporting cases of harassment and assault by male students.<P> 
	"One female student was assaulted by her outsider boyfriend during the graduation," she said.<P>
	Some factors contributing to the reduction of criminal activities are: 
<UL><LI> The students now pay "user" fees and think about studies.  <LI>No fortnight allowance pay to students. 
<LI> An alcohol ban on campus.
<LI> Closure of the university club.
<LI> A tough stand and cooperation among university administrative units.</UL><P>
	 The accommodation of staff and students on campus are far apart and students do not share ideas or play games with staff. <P>
	There is no peace and harmony among both parties - but isolation and hostility. Perhaps the administration should consider building staff and students accommodation closer together in future. <P>




