<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
Council votes to sack Rali.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Staff reporter </strong><p>


The University Council of the University of Papua New Guinea yesterday decided to dismiss a senior national academic.<P>
	The head of the chemistry department, Dr Topul Rali, is being dismissed by the council for his involvement in the destruction of university property late last year.<P>
	Dr Rali was suspended in January for being allegedly involved in a violent incident in which the office of the Vice-Chancellor and accounts office were ransacked on December 22 - the day after anthropology lecturer Janet Kisau was murdered.<P>
	Dr Rali was protesting over the tragic death. About K10,000 worth of damage was caused by the rampage.<P>
	An investigation was ordered into the incident. It was completed about a week ago and the report handed to the council. <P>
	Sources said the report was considered yesterday and a unanimous decision was reached to dismiss Dr Rali.<p>
	"There was indisputable evidence that Dr Rali was a party to the ransacking of the offices and destruction of property," one source said. <P>
	The sources said the council was taking a tough stand on misbehaviour by both staff and students.<P>
	Earlier this month, Vice-Chancellor Dr Rodney Hills announced a strict new code of conduct for academic and other staff. <P>




