PACIFIC : Papuan flag prisonor's death shock.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Special correspondent in Jayapura </strong><p>


Mystery surrounds the death of West Papuan anthropologist Tom Wainggai, whose body's return to Jayapura this week triggered rioting in the Irian Jaya capital.<P>
	Witnesses said three people were killed, scores injured and 37 arrested as protesters burned vehicles, shops and other buildings.<P>
	 Mr Wanggai was sentenced to 20 years' imprisonment in 1989 for raising a West Papuan flag - the "Morning Star" - in Jayapura seven years ago.<P>
	 He died last week while being driven to a hospital from Cipinang Prison in Jakarta.<P>
	Mr Wainggai was not known to have had any health problems until, a few days before his death, he complained of feeling unwell.<P>	
	 Suspecting that his food had been poisoned, he refused to eat the prison food supplied by the guards, sources said.<P>
His condition rapidly worsened and he asked the prison governor, Mintardjo, for permission to go to a Christian hospital for examination and treatment. But this was refused.<P>
When his condition deteriorated, he was taken from his cell last Thursday for transfer to an Indonesian Government hospital but died on the way.<P>
	 His Japanese-born wife, Teruka, wanted the International Red Cross to conduct an autopsy of her husband's body but the Government said this could only be done at a Government mortuary.<P>
	She first heard of her husband's death from a Jakarta-based NGO. Teruka herself served four years in prison. She was sentenced to eight years in 1989 because she had sewn the flag which her husband unfurled on December 14, 1988. She was released in November 1993.<P>
	Military authorities have said Mr Wanggai died of natural causes.<P>
	 West Papua Movement (OPM) rebels are still holding 11 hostages, including six Europeans, after 75 days in captivity to highlight their struggle for independence from Indonesia. A Madang-based OPM leader, Moses Werror, has appealed to the rebels to free the hostages. <P>
	The European Parliament last week passed a resolution seeking communication with the OPM in a bid to free the captives. The resolution cited the difficult human rights situation, environmental destruction and the pressure on maintaining West Papuan culture and heritage. <i >Tapol </i ><P>




