<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
INSIGHT REPORT : Press freedom at risk.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Raphael Semel </strong><p>

Judges, politicians, academics, civil servants, an archbishop, media executives, journalists and grassroots activists have debated the future of the nation's news media and the freedom of the press at a two-day public seminar in Port Moresby.<P>

Organised by the Papua New Guinea Media Council, the seminar+s theme was "Freedom at the Crossroads - The Media and the Constitution". <P>

Council chairperson Anna Solomon pledged this week that it would help media organisations and the Government to improve the industry. <P>

"The council is now in place. It is now finalising its regulations which will help its media work," she said.<P>

She added that the Australian Press Council, whose chairman, Professor David Flint, was a guest speaker at the seminar, would assist the PNG council. <P>

Freedom of expression as provided in the constitution was a focal point of seminar discussion because of the Constitutional Review Commission (CRC) task to review freedom of the press and media accountability. <P>

Views contrasted sharply, although most speakers strongly defended the principles of freedom of speech and self-regulation by the news media. <P>

One of Papua New Guinea's constitution "fathers", <strong>John Momis, </strong> said section 46 - freedom of expression - was based on the fundamental principle of democracy lying in the rights of individuals.<P>

Different rights gave an opportunity to each person to contribute creatively and constructively to the political, economical, social and cultural life of the country, he said. <P>

<strong>Unjust laws : </strong>"To fulfil this obligation may mean exercising the feedom of speech to criticise unjust and ineffective laws and policies of the government of the day," Mr Momis said.<P>

He believes the media is accountable to the nation's citizens rather than any particular department, group or organisation. Therefore media is an active instrument to promote people's awareness and consciousness about events in the country.<P>

However, <strong> Chief Justice Sir Arnold Amet</strong>, who opened the seminar, highlighted the CRC+s terms of reference "whether changes need to be made to ensure that, while freedom of the press is maintained, owners, editors and journalists of all elements of the media are accountable and that persons aggrieved by the media abuses have accessible redress."<P>

<strong>Fragile subject : </strong> Sir Arnold said freedom of the press was a fragile subject. <P>

"Do not pretend for a moment that a free press is perfect and has no faults and does not produce ill-effects or consequences," he said. <P>

"You all have a powerful influence on that which can be good, so does a free press with hidden political agenda, malicious intent and irresponsibility be a powerful destructive influence in a community." <P>

Media organisations played an important role in society in facilitating freedom of expression and publication of ideas and opinions. <P>

"No individual, private or corporate, has any absolute right to do or say anything that has the potential to harm or denigrate the reputation of another, without justification," Sir Arnold said. <P>

He encouraged media organisations to report events and issues accurately and with balance. Culturally, many Papua New Guineans were far more offended by untrue stories, immorality, explicit sexuality and violence in media than in western countries.<P>

Vital issues discussed at the seminar included: 

<UL><LI> The constitution.
<LI> What is accountability.
<LI>Community expectations.
<LI> The role of media or press councils.
<LI> Public information services.
<LI> Journalism training for the future.
<LI> Experiences from other lands.</UL><P>

The Archbishop of Port Moresby, <strong>Sir Peter Kurongku</strong>, said media must provide information which people had the right to know. <P>

"Things are happening in the country which people need to be informed about," said Bishop Kurongku. He said news media should explain satisfactorily about the happenings because they were responsible and accountable for disseminating information.<P>

<Strong>Code of ethics :</strong> However, he said media must first be accountable to God then to their own conscience to respect others in terms of the code of ethics, integrity and commitment.<P>

The media should not be accountable to one particular organisation like Parliament or the government of the day. But the media must be responsible for inaccurate, incomplete, unbalanced or defamatory information. <P>

The general manager of Word Publishing, <strong>Ian Fry</strong>, outlined the role of mass media to inform the community on current issues and to comment on them; to educate the people in matters affecting human and community; to provide open access for community; to entertain and to provide access to the market for business, goods and services.<P>

Mr Fry said the important issue was the mechanism of accountability and the status of the body to which each group was accountable. <P>

There were formal mechanisms to ensure accountability of leaders. He said an important aspect of the role of the media was to seek the truth, to oppose injustice, inequality, violence and the destruction of environment and to hold a mirror to society and all its institutions. <P>

The Opposition spokesman for finance and planning, <strong>Masket Iangalio</strong>, said freedom of expression was under threat. The country was entering a "dangerous" time for the constitutional democracy.<P>

Mr Iangalio said some unthinking and uncaring leaders who did not want to be exposed to public scrutiny and debate threatened the provision of freedom of expression.<P>

<strong>Bad images : </strong>However, the chairman of the CRC media committee, <Strong>Professor John Waiko</strong>, told seminar participants that the CRC did not intend to abolish "and will not abolish" section 46.<P>

But the CRC would closely reconsider information available through Internet. This was to control or stop the offensive and bad images such as pornography that come through the internet channel.<P>

Prof Waiko challenged the media to analyse and reevaluate its present condition to promote unity in the country.<P>

<strong>Professor David Flint</strong>, chairman of the Australian Press Council and chair of the executive council of the World Association of Press Councils, said the essential role of the news media was to "subject public life to scrutiny". <P>

He cited Justice Black of the US Supreme Court in his ruling denying injunctions sought against the New York Times and Washington Post in the 1969 Pentagon Papers case:<P>

<blockquote>"In the First Amendment the founding fathers gave the press the protection it must have to fulfil its essential role in our democracy. The press was to serve the governed, not the governors.<P>

"The Government's power to censor the press was abolished so that the press would remain forever free to censure the Government. The press was protected so that it could bare the secrets of government and inform the people. <P>

"Only a free and unrestrained press can effectively expose deception in government."</blockquote>

A senior Post-Courier journalist, <strong>Neville Togarewa</strong>, stressed several misconceptions and weaknesses of the government and the media. Media as the fourth estate and watchdog of the country had been misconceived by bureaucracy of being constantly in conflict with government. <P>

"Government is concerned about the selection and placement of stories in the press and electronic media - but this is obviously the job of the editorial committees," he said.<P>

Mr Togarewa blamed successive governments for failing to provide adequate resources to make the National Broadcasting Corporation truly "the voice of the nation". Thus the overnment needed other media avenues to publicise information.<P>

It should not restrict or regulate the media but instead pass a freedom of information act to allow journalists to have access to cabinet records - the official documents which citizens needed to know about. <P>

<strong>Some mistakes :</strong> He admitted that journalists sometimes made mistakes through bias and misreporting and said they must be held responsible. The code of ethics was an essential element of accountability. <P>

Mr Togarewa encouraged the employers to provide on-going training to give reporters necessary skills to confidently do their job. <P>

He said the Government should help the training of journalists by allocating sufficient funds every year to UPNG's South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information in Development and the Divine Word Institute in Madang. <P>

A lecturer in journalism at UPNG, <strong>David Robie</strong>, highlighted the "significant and valuable" training and input the university had provided for students in PNG and the South Pacific in the past two decades. <P>

Mr Robie said research had shown 68 per cent of Papua New Guinean journalists had a tertiary qualification, contrasting with other South Pacific countries such as Fiji which had 16 per cent.<P>

He added that many of UPNG's graduates today held high positions in the media industry and other respective areas. He praised the assistance of the Post-Courier, New Zealand High Commission, UNESCO and CUSO through the Canada Fund in recent years.<P>

The training newspaper Uni Tavur had last year become a commercial tabloid. Last month an electronic newspaper version had been launched on the World Wide Web.<P>

"Students now graduating from UPNG have a level of computer literacy undreamed of three years ago," he said.<P>

<strong>'Hard realities' : </strong>Many graduates could now produce publications with their firsthand experience of the "hard economic realities" of advertising and distribution.<P>

But Mr Robie also appealed for further funding for air conditioning in the newsroom, a major revamp of broadcast facilities and development of resource materials.<P>

Broadcast lecturer <Strong>Sorariba Nash</strong> made a plea for the purchase of vital equipment for training students in radio and television journalism basics. <P>

"Courses in electronic media are divided into two categories - radio and TV," he said.<P>

"There is an old studio with broken down machines. Our TV camera was taken away by another university department which has nothing to do with training media personnel," Mr Sorariba said.<P>

"With the cutback in Government spending on tertiary institutions, this is the time for for the business houses to lend a helping hand." <P>



