<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
FOCUS :  The tragedy of Janet Kisau.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Michael Miise </strong><p>


December 1995 was crisis time. It was the most lawless month on Waigani campus
that senior staff of the University of Papua New Guinea can recall.<P>

Break-ins happened everyday as the atmosphere of crime and fear worsened. Then
four days before Christmas Janet Kisau, a lecturer with the department of
anthropology and sociology, was tragically murdered.<P>

She was shot dead just a day before she was due to fly to Australia to begin a
doctorate at La Trobe University in Melbourne.<P>

A day later a group of drunken academic staff ransacked the accounts offices
and assaulted the acting bursar in protest over the death.<P>

An expatriate professor and his wife were threatened and the academic was
forced to take research leave.<P>

The crisis rounded off a year of unprecedented violent incidents.<P>

Last May, commerce lecturer Oigen Konio was stabbed to death in a gang attack
just meters from his house on campus. Two students were also murdered and there
were scores of break-ins and car thefts.<P>

<strong>Safer place </strong>: New Vice-Chancellor Dr Rodney Hills took office in the second week
of January and quickly pledged to make the sprawling campus a safer place for
more than 2500 staff and students.<P>

"Urgent action has to be taken to improve security for individuals and property
on campus," he said in a "state of the university" address to academics and
university employees.<P>

"Staff, students and property are threatened by unlawful behaviour. The
situation is causing morale to deteriorate.<P>

"Staff are leaving - recruitment is becoming difficult.<P>

"Staff and students are fearful, and female students have found it unsafe to
move around after dark. Evening academic activity has all but stopped."<P>

Some of the problems had stemmed from outside the campus; others had been been
caused by "undisciplined personal behaviour" by staff and students, Dr Hills
said.<P>

Often the behaviour had been associated with drunkenness.<P>

"If the university is to be a credible centre for higher education, these
trends have to be reversed."<P>

He added that "protecting the people" on campus must be his first priority.<P>

Dr Hills quickly followed his promise with the installation of floodlights in
strategic sites around university buildings.<P>

<strong>Strong attack </strong>: But while Dr Hills made a strong attack on "aggressive and
threatening" behaviour from some staff and students, he did not discuss action
or investigations over specific violent incidents such as Ms Kisau's death.<P>

Janet Kisau, in her mid-30s, was a mother of two. From Yakandanda village,
Wabag, in Enga province, she did her grades 11 and 12 at Aiyura National High
School in 1981-82.<P>

She graduated with an honors masters degree at La Trobe University in 1993 and
was to return there to do her doctorate when she was slain.<P>
Ms Kisau was held up outside her home at Fort Banner with two friends after
returning from a Christmas party  about 2.30am on December 21.<P>

The two companions, off-duty policemen, reportedly fled to warn the campus
security office about the hold up when she was shot.<P>

Ms Kisau is survived by her daughters, Eva Nemba,12, and Gloria Nemba, 10, who
were living with her at the time of her death.<P>

Janet Kisau was well known by staff and students and was regarded as a great
loss to her department, the university and the country.<P>

"I'm very saddened by her death", says anthropology lecturer Vincent Warakai, a
lecturer with the anthropology and sociology department.<P>

"She was very friendly to all, speaks to people of all works of life and was an
approachable person. She had academic potential that she was going to pursue
and she would have made a great sociologist."<P>

Campus Review, the Sydney-based newspaper circulating to universities in
Australia, New Zealand and the Pacific, reported that a La Trobe senior
anthropology lecturer, Dr Martha Macintyre, who was to have been Ms Kisau's PhD
supervisor, described her death as a tragedy.<P>

<strong>Graduate  studies </strong> :  Dr Macintyre said Ms Kisau would have been one of the few
PNG women who went on to do graduate studies and was a "very intelligent and
extroverted person who was enthusiastic about anthropology".<P>

The death of Ms Kisau led to the ransacking of the university accounts office,
causing K10,000 damage.<P>

Protesters also assaulted the acting bursar at the time, Everest Mwesigye, and
a security guard. Mr Mwesigye returned to Uganda.<P>

Professor Hal Markowitz, director of the university's Institute of Continuing
Development Education, was threatened and told to leave the country. He left
with his wife in early January for research leave.<P>

Acting dean of arts, Professor Ron Huch, told staff: "As usual, the
perpetrators had been drinking. It is incomprehensible that such actions
should occur on a university campus - especially one in such a state of
distress.<P>

"To say that UPNG and all of us are in peril is an understatement. Please take
as much care as you possibly can over the next two weeks."<P>

Dr Topul Rali, head of the chemistry department and a former UPNG disciplinary
committee chairman, was alleged to be one of the protesters in the rampage and
the university is investigating his case.<P>

On January 3, police raided six staff houses on campus during the investigation
over Ms Kisau's death and charged two academics and a civil servant with
firearms offences.<P>

Anthropology lecturer Jo Mangi was fined K200 by the Boroko District Court for
possessing a rubber bullet and a gas gun bullet said to be of a type used by
police to disperse rioters.<P>

Agriculture and Livestock Secretary Dr John Kola was also fined K200 for
possessing 250 .22 rifle bullets and nine shotgun cartridges.<P>

Dr Rali has been charged with  possession of a high-powered firearm and
pornographic magazines. He has pleaded not guilty and his case has been
adjourned to next Wednesday.<P>

Acting university security chief Mark Alu said the homes of three other
academics  -  current disciplinary committee chairman Dr Paul Mawa, education
lecturer Joe Kerpei and law graduate Gibest Kerekere - were raided but none
were charged.<P>

<strong>'Families fear' </strong>: "Academic staff cannot teach to the best of their ability
because they always think about their families back home and fear that they
might be attacked," Mr Alu said.<P>

Mr Warakai was later assaulted in an attack believed to be linkedwith the
police raid.<P>

City police chief Philip Taku appealed to UPNG residents to immediately
surrender any unlicensed firearms or amunition.<P>

Addressing students on campus earlier this month, Mr Taku said he was also
concerned at the many cases of rape and other crimes on campus and in the
residential areas.<P>

"The university authorities have pledged to support police in weeding out
criminal activities on campus," he said.<P>

Mr Taku appealed for student cooperation with police.<P>

The Vice-Chancellor, Dr Hills, has called for "neighbourhood watch" groups.<P>

"The university has a boundary that is too long to manage effectively with
present resources," he said. "However, we'll introduce guard dog patrols in
sensitive areas." <P>


