<HEAD>
<TITLE>Do Asian news values deny freedom of expression?</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Do Asian news values deny<BR>
 freedom of expression?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Three</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The real conundrum is presented by deeply theocratic societies like Iran today or Afghanistan under the Talibans tomorrow, or intractably primitive communities. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Can there be journalism in a society where the most important truths were revealed once and for all one thousand four hundred years ago? Do you report female genital mutilation as such, or as a Bar Mitzvah? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I don't know the answer, but I do know that if a moral exception or a suspension of judgement is made in such cases, they should not extend to the wives of an Asian dictator's sons who wear not purdah but Chanel.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Communist China occasionally rumbles on about unique values, yet its official philosophy denies such things as Asian values. And China remains hard put to explain why it was wrong for foreigners to kick around Chinese in the past the way Chinese officials kick them around in the present.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I have never heard of an Asian liberation movement that demanded national slavery in place of foreign domination. It was always liberty, fraternity, even equality or at least progress for the majority and not just a select or foreign few. I would be insulted if it was ever suggested that I, as an Asian, ever raised my fist to have it manacled as an assertion of cultural identity.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So far we have yet to stumble upon a single viable Asian value.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Lee Kuan Yew paid lip service to the primacy of the family in the Asian scheme, yet wasn't he reported as having proposed a two-tiered system of rewards to discourage procreation by the less smart and encourage it among the gifted? That's not Asian; that's pre-war German eugenics. In fact, the foundation of Singaporean success is the abolition of the traditional Oriental family and the eradication of its corrosive influence on public administration.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The model for Meiji Japan was not Confucian China on its knees before the European powers but Prussia. On the other hand, the historical parallel of the Philippines under Marcos or Indonesia under Suharto would be England under the Stuarts.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The secret of Asian success, where it has happened, was not Asian values but British-style administration, German-style tactics and the French Civil Code. The story of modern China is the struggle to overcome the anarchy of its Confucian roots for the cleanliness, order and prosperity of the foreign legations - spread nationwide. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Thousands of years of Confucianism, said the Economist in its New Year's issue, coincided with the same number of millennia of famine, crime, weakness, corruption and science going the wrong way. “If Asian values encourage clean living,” said the Economist, “why are so many booming Asian cities bywords for vice and corruption? Until recently, these ancient traditions were blamed for Asia's backwardness. The authoritarian systems they bred stifled individual initiative.”
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
At no time in Asian history has individual freedom conflicted with national survival or economic development. Chinese liberals did not obstruct Chinese progress; Chinese authoritarians ripped the country to shreds in the attempt by each to take all of it for himself. Until the communists took over it all.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It was the communists in the army who attempted to seize power in Indonesia; the power held by the army today. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The idea that journalism in Asia must, as this one writer put it, "respond to the surge of [Asian] value aspiration rising from underdevelopment" is drivel. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
