<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: One</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: One</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Teodoro L. Locsin. Section Three</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 5</B><BR> 
I'm just wondering if you're familiar with the term 'development journalism' in the Philippines and what it in fact means to Filipino journalists. One interpretation is that it is a method by journalists to counter the very negative images that are portrayed of societies and peoples in the developing world. DO you have a particular view on that.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR> 
In the Philippines 'developmental journalism' is known as 'envelopmental journalism'. It's a journalism that's basically fuelled by the envelopes the politicians and the public officials pass out. Just tell it, tell what you see. We don't hesitate, the newspapers don't hesitate to say something that's good about the country — why not? it's our country — if it's there. But if it turns out that there's a kidnapping of a Chinese businessman's son every day, I don;t care what it does to foreign investments I'm going to have to write it and say it.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 5</B><BR>
So did that mean journalism is just a form of — an ideological journalism?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR> 
It's an excuse, an excuse for hiding the truth. I don't think that's ever good. There are exceptions of course, in the case of ethnic conflict, but that's something else.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 1</B><BR> 
I'm sorry, I'm going to ask you another question. It's just that your lecture seemed to give a very positive view about, or a somewhat Utopic view of how journalists should operate, be it in Asia, Africa, Europe whatever, as a continent. While the Philippines is a very free and open press, the same cannot be said about other countries, for example Indonesia where you have so-called private radio and television stations which are forced to re-broadcast the news bulletins from the state owned. Where you have people having their magazines closed and cannot exercise their rights and freedoms. That involves self-censorship, it involves laws that forbid opening of newspapers, of magazines, giving of licenses. How hard do you think it is to operate as an independent, outside of the 'values', just as a plain old following-the-code-of-ethics journalist in Asia?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR> 
You're right. In a previous conference someone put me in my place there. If I have suggested that we Filipino journalists, because we are free, are superior to everyone else: well, that's what think and that's what Americans and they're right to think that, because anyone who exercises full freedoms and expresses his conscience is really better than the man who cannot. But then I do recognise that I can say what I please within the limits of the libel law in the Philippines, but it takes much more courage for an Indonesian to say half of what I would say in total freedom. Because he's going to get shot if he doesn't watch out. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I fully appreciate that some newspapers in some of these countries have to settle with half the truth, and that's not to put them down. I must say that during Martial Law in the Philippines, although we had profound contempt for the only newspaper allowed by Marcos to operate (by his friend), that paper tried at least once in a while to tell a story. When Senator Aquino was assassinated, first they didn't print it, they said it didn't happen, then they put it out small. That's better than nothing. It took courage for that editor to put it out as a small item under 'community news' [laughter]. So, as I say, it's easy for me to talk now, it's harder for him.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 6. Paul Thomas.</B><BR> 
I'm just interested to know your opinion in the growing English press in South East Asia, particularly in countries such as Indonesia and Thailand, and how they're directed at an elite or ex-pat community, and how the issue of Asian values may be implemented slightly different between the press printed in the vernacular and the press printed in English.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR> 
I can't comment, I wouldn't trust my comment, on the use of Bahasa Indonesia in Indonesian newspapers or in Malaysian newspapers. In the Philippines — there was a question last night about whether English language newspapers are just talking to themselves — in fact in the Philippines the English language newspapers dictate the political agenda. There are, the vernacular is used for the tabloids, which basically — I'm not joking — what they deal with is crime, the pin-up girl and vampire visitations [laughter]. It's true. It sells. It's the broadsheet English newspapers that determine the political agenda. They decide what's a truth, what's a fact, even the interpretation of it. So far in the Philippines the English language journalism's what really counts. And of course it reflects libertarian values.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Chair. </B><BR>
Just on that question — and I think it's a very good question — but I refer you to the fact that this afternoon we have in the segment on western perspective on news, there is some comments from Khun Tulsathit Taptin, who's the deputy editor of Bangkok Nation, who's with us this morning. But I think it might be best to invite him to perhaps expand on that very good question this afternoon. Any more questions before we close? I think we have time for one or two more.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin </B><BR>
I'd like to make a comment. Because — the Bangkok Post?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Chair </B><BR>
Bangkok Nation
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin. </B><BR>
Just a peculiar thing. Thailand is a very, almost an insular culture. It's really unique. And the funny thing was that when Mr Aquino was assassinated by the military one of the strongest newspapers to denounce it was the Bangkok Post, and that's where we were getting our news. They were printing both American journalists who covered the assassination and their own feelings of outrage. There was even a student demonstration against the Marcos government in Bangkok, so that says something about Asian values and whether Asians are distinctly Asian as [?word?] are or are not capable of feeling the same outrage towards political crimes and suppressions of individual freedoms.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
