<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Training Journalists for the Newpaper Business</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Training Journalists for the Newpaper Business</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Section Three</B></FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Of course the danger is that working with rather than against the govern-<BR>
ment can become such a habit of mind that we would not recognise the need to break ranks even when it is staring in our face. But let us not forget at the same time that there is no such thing as freedom of the press. The degree of freedom enjoyed is determined by political and commercial considerations. Every newspaper and TV station determines for itself how much freedom it can possibly enjoy. This tradition and practice is universal. both in the east as well as the west. In recent years commercial considerations have become more prominent. Journalism is a business. That is reality three. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
A most dramatic demonstration of this was disclosed recently in a book by Mr Andrew Neil, Full Disclosure, which came out last week. Mr Neil said Mr Rupert Murdoch sacked him as editor of the Sunday Times in 1994 because the paper had alleged that kickbacks were paid for contracts in Malaysia. Mr Neil writes: 'Mr Murdoch had seen the row with Malaysia as a potentially disastrous threat to his business interests.' Mr Neil contends that the articles jeopardise the success of Star TV in Malaysia. Mr Murdoch had paid $US525 mill for Star TV. So naturally he wants a return on that half a billion dollars. He seems to have got it because four weeks ago Star TV finally gained access to the Malaysian market.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now given these realities you might wonder what there is to cheer about. No, we are not disheartened. The media is full of reports on the economic boom in Asia, Singapore's economic success is legendary. WE went form being a basket case in Asia to the second richest country in Asia in 30 years. No government is going to let this hard earned success be jeopardised, especially not now. The end of the Cold War has started a new race. Countries now jockey for competitive positions in trade and business. To keep and improve its position, business and government too would need good timely information. So the pressures to provide such information will grow. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The challenge for journalists is whether they can provide such information to help their country stay ahead in the economic race. For their own good newspapers have to help their countries stay ahead. As their country prospers, so will they. And profitable newspapers are in a better position to provide wider range of services. This is, I believe, a new dimension to the practice of journalism. If newspapers don't or can't rise to this challenge readers will go elsewhere, and technology will make it easier and faster to find alternative sources and to gain access to the information they want. Already in Singapore 150 000 out of 750 000 households are on line. The rest are expected to go on line by 1999. It is going to get harder and harder to control what people see, read and communicate. Ban a publication and people will turn to the internet. It's already happening. Cosmopolitan magazine, banned in Singapore, can be read on the 'net. So the inevitable end result of economic success and the push towards high tech society is a happy one. The OB markers will move, and launch a new age. And age in which there will be a freer flow of information and a freer press. And on that cheerful note ladies and gentlemen I thank you for your attention.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="arasu02.html">Previous section</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="../panels/session-two01.html">Panel questions</A> ]
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
