<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reporting Business in South-East Asia</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+1">Reporting Business in South-East Asia</B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Section Three</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The first is the communications revolution.  Computers, modems, satellites,
and the Internet are combining to eliminate political and geographical
boundaries.  Reaganites would have us believe that the arms build-up
destroyed the Soviet empire.  I'm more inclined to believe it was the inability
of the Soviet leaders to control the flow of information from West to East. . 
Once enough Soviet citizens could compare the end results of communism
to those of capitalism for themselves, the jig was up.  No propaganda in the
world can hide a reality in plain view.  And so the Berlin Wall came down
and the Iron Curtain rusted away.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The Internet is one of the great democratizing forces in the world. Anybody
with a computer and a modem can gain access to it.  And through it can
gain access to the world at large.  What's more, the Net remains largely
untamed.  Governments will attempt to rein it in and no doubt will have
some success - the potential replacement of personal PCs with networking
terminals in offices is seen as one move along this route. But I suspect the
Net is a bit like the AIDS virus.  You can obstruct it for a while, but it
eventually finds a way around the blocker.  I suspect scientists will have
greater luck controlling AIDS than will government in controlling the Internet. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Let me provide an example. The news media is rushing to put its stories on
the Net.  None of them have quite worked out how to make this pay - though
the Wall Street Journal is experimenting with charging - but they feel they
have to be there because it is the future.  (Personally, I would have grave
doubts about starting a print publication as a stand-alone business in this
day and age).  Not long ago, Reuters put a story on Cambodia on the Net.
Not long afterwards, the agency received a furious protest from that
country's government.  The complaint created initial confusion at Reuters
because the story was generally favorable.  Eventually, management
discovered that someone had done some minor but key on-line editing,
turning a generally favorable piece into a critical one.  This sort of thing will
continue to happen. There is no lock created that people don't quickly learn
how to pick.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The other force for change is the steady evolution of the so-called First
World economies from industrial bases to service bases, with a strong focus
on the information/entertainment sector.  When allied to the
communications/information technology revolution and the steady decline of
barriers between nations, this development fosters the creation of global
media giants.  Ted Turner's CNN was a forerunner of this trend.  Rupert
Murdoch's News Ltd. empire is the archetype.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But there is something else. Historically, media empires have been owned
by individuals with an strong interest in news gathering.  Even the owners of
commercially-based TV networks like NBC and CBS in the U.S. took their
greatest pride in their news operations, even though the entertainment side
paid all the bills.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This is no longer the case.  A growing number of today's media empires are
owned by companies whose managements are not all that interested in the
truth-seeking aspect of journalism.   They may not even see it as vital to the
functioning of a true democratic society.  Here, I am talking primarily about
the U.S., where General  Electric owns NBC, Disney controls ABC,  and
Westinghouse calls the shots at CBS.  But we are seeing similar shakeups
and developments elsewhere.  The new owners want their empires to have
a piece of the Asian business action and are not about to let their news
operations, which contribute little or no profits, mess things up by revealing
too many naked emperors. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The full ramifications of this development are yet to play out.  But there has
been at least one straw in the wind.  During the opening ceremonies of the
Atlantic Olympics, NBC commentator Bob Costas make a passing remark
about China's less-than-scintillating human rights record.  Other
commentators subsequently discussed charges of drug-taking by Chinese
swimmers, observing that their performances at the Games fell far below
previous efforts when drug-testing was less strict.   Beijing complained and
NBC subsequently apologized.  In an earlier time, there is no way NBC
would have done any more than accept the complaint and perhaps offered
soothing words.  But now GE runs the show at NBC and GE has a massive
commercial stake in retaining good relations with China.  News coverage
does not contribute much to GE's bottom line.  And, today, bottom lines
matter more than prestige.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Taken together these developments raise intriguing questions for news
coverage of the Asian business story.  The western view of journalism,
especially in nations deriving from the British tradition, is vastly different
from that held in Asia.   Good journalism is essentially adversarial.  It
winkles out the truth from whatever source and publishes it.  More often than
not that truth has to be winkled out of those who hold power and revealed to
those who do not.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This creates the potential for serious cultural clashes.  Everybody here is
familiar with the actions of many Asian power structures when subjected to
serious journalistic scrutiny.  Local reporters are censored at best, jailed and
severely punished at worst.  Foreign correspondents are warned, ejected or,
more recently, sued along with their employers. And come July 1, the one
bastion of free press in Asia - Hong Kong - passes from British to Chinese
rule. Finding a base from which to cover the Asian business story without
will be tricky.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Traditionally, business journalists have not been as adversarial to their
subject as their political and social counterparts.  But that doesn't mean they
have been toothless.  And they are becoming more aggressive as better
minds come into the field and the story moves from the back pages to the
front.  Personally, I'm not into ideological confrontations with my subjects -
and most business journalists I know are much the same - but I do hold with
truth-seeking.  A lawyer/politician member of my family once remarked that
evidence not subject to cross-examination is useless.  I might say the same
about journalism.  It is an adversarial business because its raison d'etre is to
present the truth, insofar as the journalist can unearth it, about a given
subject.  And while there are those who hold that much of the media
diligently separates the wheat from the chaff and publishes the chaff, there
are a those who do attempt to publish the wheat on a regular basis.  
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
