<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Two</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Two</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Siva Arasu, Hugh D. Menzies, Brian Toohey. Section Three</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question 4 Kalinga Seniveraine</B><BR>
I would like to ask Ms Siva about training of journalists to report what I would call an 'Asian perspective' and specifically a Singaporean perspective. And also I would like to add something more before you answer that. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now recently, just last week, we had this experience in Australia where two Thai newspapers have written very strong editorials which I would say were the Asian perspective's about Australia's race problems. And the Prime Minister Howard said in parliament that they misrepresented Australian government's policy. Which sounded really similar to what Le Puan Yu and Dr Mahathir has described Australian media over the years when they have reported about the two countries. Now if you are to train journalists to report with that Asian perspective (I'm not talking about 'Asian values' more Asian perspective), because, the media as it is, the international media ... 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
For example what we are seeing in Asia is rapid urbanisation, which is really often described as 'westernisation'. Now ... building the world's first cyber city Pukhaja ..., and when that city's built I'm sure the western media will say that Islamic Asian nation has become secular and westernised, but you will find any such city anywhere else in the world. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So how do you . . . for example when you look at the western societies, you see an ... of western societies, what is called a new age is really the age old tradition of Asia, for example yoga is being prescribed by doctors here to treat hypertension and heart diseases. And also there's yoga teachers in suits teaching stress management  in big corporations. So also earlier you said there are Singaporeans who go overseas, learn western techniques of news production and all that, when they come back, how do you train a journalist - in other words if I use this unfashionable word in this age of globalisation - how do you colonise their mind [laughter]? To report from a western perspective, but probably using the techniques, the production techniques they use in the west.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Siva Arasu</B><BR>
I think there are some things that are universal, that's not east and west. I think we're all agreed on that. And, how do I decolonise their thinking: I don't try to, because I think living in Singapore - they're smart for one thing. When they go away they come back, they can see the difference. And the way to train a person, not necessarily a journalist, is to train their mind to think. I do not want them to think the way I do, but they way that they think for the good of their own community. And at the same time that they can live with themselves, that is what I think is the other objective of my training program. Not to make them think the way we all do. If they think the way I do and I am very much older than them, what's going to happen is Singapore is not going to progress very far. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The way I think is determined by the circumstances and the history during which I grew up. They are going to grow up in a different era, different time, and they'll have their own history. So they cannot think the way I do. So the way to do it is I think for them to apply the universals of searching like all of us for what it best for our own community, the truth for our own community. And at the same time on an individual level to live with our conscience. I think that's all I can do as a trainer. There's no special method I use.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question 5 Annmarie Anton</B><BR> 
I'm Annmarie again, freelance journalist. I'd be very interested to hear more on the side of Ms Arasu in terms of the Pauline Hansen debate. I'm giving an overrun again, but I'd really like to hear it from you, working for a company like Singapore Press Holdings. How was the Pauline Hansen debate covered in Singapore, and how has it filtered in a company like yours, and if you could also mention other companies, and whether there is truth in the statements that it's actually effecting badly the business relationships between Australia and Asia. And how that's filtered in your training as well: did you discuss it on a training level as well?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Siva Arasu </B><BR>
We ran the statements made by Pauline Hansen and a few days later we ran an unfortunate story which happened to our defence personnel in Perth. Three groups of them at three different times were assaulted, pelted with eggs and attacked by various people. And every story that we got from Australia suggested that Pauline Hansen  is to be blamed. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Anyway, what happened is that there was a statement released by both the Perth government as well as Singapore government saying this will not effect relations. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Within the organisation what happened is that we of course - Singaporeans being like any other community - reacted to what they see as a racist attack. And so we got our fare share of letters from people who were emotional, whose points of view were certainly rather hysterical. We did not suppress all those points of view, but we did not run all of the letters we received. What we did was we picked letters that presented the different points of view in what we considered was a non-inflammatory way.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Did we discuss it in our training program? We didn't discuss it in our training program, we did discuss it in our news rooms. And I think our overriding concern is the bigger picture. Most of us have been to Australia at least once. For many Singaporeans they have been to Australia more than once, and I can't say I know of any Singaporeans that did not enjoy their time in Australia holidaying. And many of them also read Australian magazines, they have friends here, they have relatives here. We know that for the vast majority of Australians they are not what they re made out to be, they are not racist. And if you want to be cynical all of us are racist, it's just that it's not politically correct or civilised to talk about it. So for once somebody did bring it out to the surface and it had unpleasant repercussions. But at the end of the day I think the Singapore reader as well as the Singaporean, is sophisticated enough person to be able to differentiate what is and what is perceived to be just a person representing a point of view and not necessarily the Australian point of view.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>End of question session.</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
