<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER>
<B><FONT SIZE="+2">Newsagency Reporting</FONT></B>
</CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Three</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
During the 1971 war in Dacca a magazine reporter who had been on top of the story for weeks filed his story to New York through the local ptt- after paying the operator to ensure it went ahead of everybody else. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
He got a brief message back from New York saying " got take three seven nine and eleven. Can you repeat those missing ?"
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
That proved impossible as the Indian air force had bombed the transmitters so his story remained unpublished. He went back to New York and had a nervous breakdown.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Disasters like that rarely happen any more. Satellites, cellular telephones and lap top computers allow you to transmit from your almost anywhere these days with speed and reliability.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
During the Vietnam war AP's communications out of Saigon depended primarily on what was then called a half speed circuit. Copy moved at about 33 words a minute. It seemed to take all day and often did. Contrast that with what is happening today.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
AP in Asia has just linked up to Asiasat. We are now moving data at 256 kilobytes - that is the equivalent of 256,000 words a minute.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Twenty years ago newspapers in Asia had a Teletype machine that delivered copy to them 66 words a minute. It was connected to the AP bureau by telephone line. Everytime it rained, and that is every day in the monsoon season, the line would die. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
These days newspapers can stick a dish on their roof and suck in the highest quality digital news and photos at mind bending speeds.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The problem of filing from difficult places has almost been overcome.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
If we have to report a war or a famine in a country without first class communications we take our own in the form of a collapsible satellite dish that fits into specially designed suitcase.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The efficiency of communications and the continuing fall in their cost has opened up the world of the news services to a vigorous new form of competition and that is finance and business news.
 It is the fastest growing area of international journalism.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Peter Kahn, the Chairman of Dow Jones, which publishes the Wall Street Journal among other things, was in Australia recently.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I knew him in Asia where has was a Journal reporter and won a Pulitzer prize for his coverage of the India Pakistan war.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"Do you remember when I was the only Dow Jones employee between Delhi and Tokyo?," he asked. " Well now I've 1,000 people working in Asia." 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
That illustrates the huge growth of business journalism.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The AP had two news reporters in Australia in 1975. Now the combined news room of AP, AP-Dow Jones numbers 30 reporters.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
