<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Three</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Three</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Peter O'Loughlin, Zainoor Sulaiman. Section Three</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 4</B><BR>
My question is, is that it seems to me that there's been huge developments in word processing and distribution. Has the word processing and distribution part of journalism outstripped the technology ... and also taken away all the time journalists had for reflection ...
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer 1</B><BR> 
That's one way of putting it, but when I think of the time that it used to take to write - I was going to bring a Letra 22 typewriter in here for people who hadn't seen one. When you used to travel you'd take a Letra 22 typewriter, about 8 kg of paper, carbon paper, ribbons. you'd write your story on the paper, and then what do you do with it? You spend the next half day trying to find a way to file it, because the TTP was closed, or the communications group wasn't working. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So, I think I wasted more time of my life buggerising around with that sort of end of the business, than I would these days. I mean, you don't waste any time these days. You write your story, press the button, and it's gone. And you should have plenty of time to reflect . The only thing is that in the speed side of the business - and we're all still in it, in fact it is more brutally competitive now, particularly on the financial markets reporting. I mean the competition between Dow-jones and Reuters is something to behold. I mean they count it in seconds. we used to think we were pretty good if we got a beat of five minutes. If I beat Richard by five minutes, I'd ring him up! But these days I mean, Reuters and AP and Dow-jones are hard at it there, and the times are all measured, because they're all logged on to a screen there at the Hong Kong Shanghai Bank Foreign Exchange Dealing Room. And that's how your business survives. You've got to be able to prove to these people that you're giving them the information very slickly. But that doesn't - on the news side - doesn't mean to say that you (because basically all you're doing is telling something that's going to affect the price, and you get that right and that's a one line delivery). But if you're going to sit down and craft a story it's the same old business. I mean you've still got to sit down. Some people are quicker at it than others, and I don't think it takes away any creativity at all.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer 2</B><BR> 
I think I'm getting the drift of the questions, which is whether the technology the newsagencies has means that we can move news instantaneously almost as it happens. And will this not affect us as journalists, and will this not affect the production. now I have to say that yes, journalists must be extremely careful. They can move things in nanoseconds. They can press a button and it's irreversible, un-reversible, and it's out straight away. Before, you could tear the band out of the telex machine, you could phone people up and say 'Ah, forget it, spike it!'. Now it's gone. And this puts an even greater responsibility on journalism. But journalism remains and will remain, whether you're transmitting it by mice, pigeons, satellites, a product that's crafted by humans. By people. And therefore all the qualities that human beings have and as journalists you must just apply the same standard of truth and credibility. The fact you can file it faster to me makes absolutely no difference to the profession at all.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer 3 </B><BR>
... newspapers have the deadlines, and maybe in the evening. But for us in Reuters you know we have to be very very fast. So if you were  ... that you know ... when the editor realises that it could be better presented in such a way that you can find a new story ... That might be a better answer for your question in terms of the quality or the standard you're putting in the copies.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 5. Kim Greggs</B><BR>
My name's Kim Greggs, I used to work for Nightrider for ten years so I've done a lot of business journalism, but my question is: I think it's today that Microsoft's Australian editor starts work after having been in Redmond [??] for some months, and I just wonder: I think Australia's the first place Microsoft has put its own bureau aside from Redmond and I'm wondering how you see that affecting what the newsagencies do if you can get online information just as quick as we've been doing it for years, how that's going to change the scope for wire services? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin</B><BR> 
I can't make any reflections on Microsoft, but I would say that newsagencies such as are represented in this room here, including Reuters over in the corner, have been in business for 160 years and are the best brand names around. Of course we're always interested in watching what the competition's going to do, but I think newsagencies are well positioned to put out an excellent product which has a very high reputation and this information rich age, it's the brand names that are going to count.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>[Indistinguishable question from the floor, possibly a follow up from Kim Greggs.]</B><BR>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer</B><BR>
[Gates is?] a niche player, and it's not anywhere as diversified as Reuters or AFP or AP and I don't think it ever will be. I don't think it'd trying to be. And if you dive into the internet you'll see there are lots of new services coming up there, but the one thing we keep stressing here - all of us, I'm sure - is that you're talking about credibility here. I'm not saying that Microsoft is not going to be credible, but I think it's going to be a long time before it's as credible as AP or Reuters or AFP. And it'll be even longer for the other news services that are cropping up on the internet.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
