<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Un-Western Perspectives on News</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Un-Western Perspectives on News </FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B><FONT SIZE="+1">Section Three</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
If the international media do not show much interest in the precursors to conflict, they seem even less inclined to cover the the "soft" topics that concern human well-being: people's health, education, shelter and nutrition. Nearly 50,000 children die every day all over the world in a "silent emergency": most of them from preventable causes like undernourishment, dehydration, measles or respiratory infections. In his desperate plea to get journalists interested in the story, the head of the United Nation's Children's Fund (UNICEF), James Grant, often asked them if a thousand jumbo jets full of children crashed every day, whether it would make a "story".
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
There are two reasons why the media agenda in the New World Order must change. Firstly, the most powerful nation is worse informed than ever before. A people that is scantily informed about the rest of the world, and therefore cares less and less about it, today commands our collective destinies. It is this under- informed electorate that will choose its future presidents and commanders-in-chief.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Secondly, even though editors who determine the news agenda and the companies that own the media are both predominantly U.S.- based, but also to not just clients in North America and Europe but also to the rest of the world. Ted Turner of CNN recently called Americans "some of the dumbest people in the world", and admitted that this was the case because complex foreign stories got the lowest ratings. At least he knows, but when is he going to do anything about it?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
International media schools have for long propagated a model of reporting that magnifies attention grabbing details: this is the Headless-Body-Found-In-Topless-Bar school of journalism named after an actual headline in the New York Daily News. The three cardinal rules are: news is NEW, news is NEAR, news is NEUTRAL. And to this we may add: news is NORTH.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
An event is deemed important enough to file only if it concerns the rich and famous, the movers and the shakers or is important to them. What happens to the poor, the underdogs, the silent majority is news only if they die by the thousands, commit a gruesome crime, migrate by the millions, provide a market for free traders or threaten the lifestyles of the privileged with their sheer numbers. <B>[WIND VANE DRAWING WITH N-E-W-S]</B> 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This prevalent news formula is inadequate to confront the challenges of equity, justice and global survival. The crisis of the planet is caused in part because the poor and the voiceless have never counted, and they have not counted because the media mostly ignores them. Even as the world becomes more and more interdependent, most mass media still reduce racism, migration, terrorism or recession to discrete isolated factoids and fail to link them to complex global conditions. Journalists are also required to show superhuman aloofness and not be moved by injustice and greed. And even if they are moved, they are not supposed to let their feelings show.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Proponents of this media school claim that such "balanced" and "neutral" reporting is a time-tested model of journalism and the only one that works. But status-quo journalism is also biased because it cannot take sides against wrongs. And by denying their bias, they are actually showing partiality. Observers change reality by the very act of observing, so reporters are a part of the story they are reporting. And yet, "objective" stories appear everyday in the papers and on television: reporting that is scrupulously accurate on facts but misses the nuances of the larger truth because it does not analyse events and come to a conclusion.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
There is a way to write stories by not blaming anyone: by just recording what happened. Counting the bodies after a flashflood without looking at the causes, adding up the statistics on dwindling fish stocks without asking why. This is the sterile one-dimensional reporting of the kind we see everyday in newspapers and on television in our countries. And if there is a feeble attempt to look at causes, the stories invariably blame the slash-and-burn farmer and not the logger, blame the squatter and not the rapacious real-estate developer, blame the fisherfolk who dynamite corals and not the foreign trawlers that sweep offshore seas. That is "neutral" and "balanced" reporting-- blaming the poor.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
