<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Newsagencies in Transition</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Newsagencies in Transition</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Three</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But journalism is not only about what we write and publish. It's also about our ideology and attitude. There are bad journalists in fully democratic countries and there are good journalists in repressive nations. My point is we can acknowledge each other's constraints, and support each other.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
The communications technology revolution should serve this purpose. Laborious cross-border cooperation between journalists of different countries have been made much easier. Governments are finding it harder to halt the flow of information. When barricades were up and down around her house recently, Aung San Suu Kyi made her feelings known all over the world in an article she sent to a Japanese newspaper and The Nation. "Ridiculous" was what she said.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
But let me share with you our feeling toward the information technology revolution. We are optimistic, but only cautiously.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Eliminating or reducing the distance between information and its audience is always welcome. With the advent of satellite television and the birth of cyberspace, information is flowing much faster
 and the growing audience has more sources of news to compare and judge for their accuracy.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
The ability of the media to relay events as they are happening is making policy-makers work harder to respond or react to swiftly unfolding events. Decision-makers are under pressure to act more, and they have less to hide.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
But in this fast-paced development of digitalised journalism, two forces might prevail. They are consumerism and commercialism.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
Along with the liberalization of the media sector comes the capitalist influence. And, as we have always experienced, competition often brings with it the herd-instinct and make reporting to serve minorities in society difficult.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>	
The obsession to serve the middle class, the group that can afford to consume more information, may lead the media to overlook the interests of the mass of people who live in rural areas. News about the latest computer model, for example, may gain priority over a three-day power blackout in a small village.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
