<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Four</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Four</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Kunda Dixit, Tulsathit Taptim. Section Three.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question [?] from Monash.</B><BR>
 Taptim you mentioned that the English language press was very influential in Thailand. I was wondering if there's any risk at all of the growing English press taking in resources - I think it was Brian Toohey earlier this morning who said how expensive good journalism is - I was wondering if there was any risk of the English language press in Thailand drawing the resources that may have gone to Thai language press. And secondly that political debate, or serious political debate, was seen as being put into the English language press as the appropriate realm, and therefore it being isolated from the greater majority of Thais who don't speak English.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Khun Tulsathit Taptim </B><BR>
There's no obvious risk of drawing resources from the Thai language media because, for one thing, Thai people have very limited English education at the moment. One of the first qualifications for joining English media in Thailand is you have to know English. Of course we have some reporters who cover a story and send their report to us in Thai language and we have translators to translate into English. But there has been no problem of brain-drain from the Thai media into English language media. It's the other way around, actually.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
And yes, on the second question, I believe that political debate in the English press somehow is more - if you like to say - intellectual, because we've got academics, we've got a lot of educated people contributing to us. We've got articles from foreign governments. We've got replies we've got questions we've got letters, from everywhere in the world. So the debate is like, in a higher level if you want to say so. But is not totally isolated. If there is an issue that the English language press want to pursue and if you want cooperation from the Thai media, then it is easy to mobilise support. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner</B><BR>
Yes, my question is also to the speaker from the Bangkok Nation. In comparison between your style of reporting and that of the Australian press - because I noticed with interest, your senior editor was covering the Asia–Pacific conference on East Timor in Kuala Lumpar over the weekend and was one of the people detained - I'd be interested in the comparison between how you would cover the issue of the editor or one of your journalists being detained, and how the Sydney Daily Telegraph  depicts a senior ABC correspondent in the region in the middle of a group of Filipinos with clenched fists being released from gaol. And the caption reads: 'Catherine McGrath, centre, with Timor activists outside prison yesterday,' to give the Australian media the impression that the people with clenched fists are from East Timor for a start, and that they are somehow militant for another thing, when all they were doing was celebrating their release from prison, and that she is in the centre of the picture more-or-less depicted as their ringleader rather than as a professional journalist doing her work, prejudicially put under a heading 'You broke the rules PM tells detainees.' 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So it's got a negative heading then it's got the senior Australian correspondent in the region, depicted somehow as being a professional agitator rather than a professional reporter trying to do a job. And I may add to that the Channel 9 news update coverage at the end of their news last night did a similar thing by showing the Ulnar youth, government sponsored group of 200 thugs who broke up a prayer session that was starting this conference where people were peacefully sitting around, the Ulnar youth group who burst in smashing up glasses and chairs and all that - that was, it was cut on Channel 9 news last night, you'd get the impression that these were the conference delegates rather than the people breaking up the conference. So I mean, the overall point I'm trying to make is the Australian media, whatever happens out there in Malaysia, Thailand or whatever, has a stereotyped view that if any Australian is over there at an event offering solidarity with East Timor or whatever, they must be an agitator. Even if they're a professional journalist covering the issue. Is this how you depicted Suny Abraham in your coverage of the issue over the weekend?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Khun Tulsathit Taptim </B><BR>
You really scooped me. I haven't contacted the office over the weekend, I haven't heard it, but I can bet that this is going to be a very very big thing back home. I can't imagine the presentation of this story in the Nation  newspaper. As I told you, our stand is to ensure that both side of either political or ideological conflict have equal chances to defend their causes. It's like a - it's not the question of who is right and who is wrong. It's like two men were having a shouting match. One side is having a microphone, a big loudspeaker, a perfect sound system. The other side is just bare mouth. What we do is just patrol in the microphone for them, let the opinions be heard, and our readers will make a decision on that. Thank you.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question off mike, from the floor and indistinct.</B><BR>
Perhaps the other speaker could reflect on use of prejudicial graphics and captions and headlines. Does the IPS have any qualms about whether its material is used in a prejudicial way with captions added and photos in a certain way?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kunda Dixit </B><BR>
We have it all the time. Newspapers use it, with - we used to have a Libyan subscriber, and every time Reagan was mentioned in our copy, said 'childkiller Reagan'. [laughter] We didn't say 'childkiller', but they put it in, so wire services have very little say over headlines, captions, even the copy of the story. I mean, where do they cut it? They might splice it, they might cut it after the second paragraph, all your context is gone. So it is more difficult for wire services.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
