<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Three</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>China Steps In</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>We may believe that the efforts by the Hong Kong government to reform media-related laws are insufficient. But China believes the government has gone too far.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>In October 1995, the legal sub-group of the China appointed Preliminary Working Committee recommended that three sections of the Hong Kong Bill of Rights Ordinance should be repealed, including a provision enabling the ordinance to override other laws. It also recommended that provisions in six security-related and broadcasting laws should be reinstated. They had been deleted to bring the laws into line with the Bill of Rights. The deleted provisions include the following:
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>1) Sections in the Television Ordinance allowing the authorities, inter alia, to pre-censor and prohibit programs, revoke television licenses for security reasons and stipulate approved sources for news programs.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>2) Sections in the Telecommunication Ordinance allowing the authorities to prohibit radio programs.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>3) Sections in the Broadcasting Authority Ordinance granting powers to the Broadcasting Authority to vet and prohibit television programs.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>4) Sections in subsidiary legislation under the Emergency Regulations Ordinance, allowing the executive authorities, inter alia, to censor and suppress publications.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>5) Sections in the Public Order Ordinance allowing the authorities to license public rallies and marches.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>6) Sections in the Societies Ordinance allowing the authorities to prohibit links between Hong Kong and overseas organisations.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>The exact reasons for these recommendations have never been made clear. The Preliminary Working Committee stated that "the British-Hong Kong Government, by introducing without consulting the Government of the People's Republic of China a series of amendments to the pre-existing laws of Hong Kong in light of the Hong Kong Bill of Rights Ordinance, has violated the principle under the Joint Declaration and the Basic Law that the laws previously in force in Hong Kong shall remain basically unchanged. Some of these major amendments will hamper the administration of Hong Kong and are not conducive to the maintenance of stability in Hong Kong."
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>This statement raises many questions. Did the amendments really breach the Basic Law, which should be the sole criterion for amending pre-1997 laws? If they breached the provisions in the Joint Declaration that Hong Kong's laws shall remain unchanged, then why not target the many other laws that had been changed? It leaves us wondering whether China actually wants the post-1997 government to have, for example, draconian powers of control over the electronic media.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>These recommendations are now being considered by China's Preparatory Committee, which is tasked to prepare for the handover. We hope that the Preparatory Committee will think twice about endorsing these proposals. However, present indications suggest that many if not all the proposals will be adopted in the coming months.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>They could be adopted by the provisional legislature, which will replace the existing Legislative Council on July 1, 1997. The provisional legislature will be elected by a 400-member Selection Committee in late December. However, legal experts have questioned the legality of the provisional legislature, since there is no provision for it in Hong Kong's post-1997 constitution, the Basic Law.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Another consideration is the composition of the Selection Committee, which was chosen by the Preparatory Committee earlier this month. The 400-member selection committee is dominated by pro-Beijing individuals. About three-quarters of the committee members are Hong Kong delegates to the National People's Congress, the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference or the Preparatory Committee, or have been appointed by China as Hong Kong affairs or district affairs advisers.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>With such a predominance of its own supporters, it is that much easier for China to exert its influence on the composition and agenda of the provisional legislature. This in turn would make it easier to ensure that its legislative plans can be implemented. A further possibility is that the National People's Congress could declare the Bill of Rights invalid on the ground that it contravenes the Basic Law.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
