<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Six</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Six</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Wendy Bacon, Jon Casimir, David Wilson. Section Three</B></FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Stephen Quinn.</B><BR>
Stephen Quinn. I teach on-line journalism. This is a question to Jon but I'd welcome the comments from the other people. There's a man called Bill Gates in America - richest man in America - he's starting a web-based non-paper news service. He's got a lot of money behind him. Should some of the news agencies be worried? Should some of the current off-line agencies be worried? What's your take on Bill Gates and the internet.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Jon Casimir </B><BR>
I've got a lot of mixed feelings about Citizen Gates. There's different views you can have on this. One is that Microsoft is a computer company and that really content is a foreign word to them, and to be honest from their experiments on the web, I'd say content is still a foreign word to them. But as you rightly point out, Bill Gates sidelined 1.5 billion dollars from his slush fund this year, and said to his company 'I want you to build web projects and I don't expect a return.' And there really aren't many [laughter] companies in the world that are doing that right now. And I know for a fact that Microsoft in Sydney - we basically know what plan Microsoft's building around the world, it's building a plan called City Scapes, and we know that because we developed it at Fairfax last year and gave it up, and Microsoft had bought it up. So we actually have a pretty good insight into what they're doing. We also know it because they're poaching people. AS a web editor myself I'm looking at a situation where really I've got a competitor who probably has fifty times the budget coming into the next year that I have. Does that worry me? yeah, to an extent.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question from the floor</B><BR>
 Have they tried to poach you?
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Jon Casimir </B><BR>
No, the stupid, stupid people! [laughter] I'm waiting, cause they're paying really terrific salaries to people!  [various interjections]. . . It is putting us in a position where we have to consider a whole lot of things where, as David says, I'm not a great believer that multimedia is some kind of god, but I do concede that we're going into a different place. I do concede that even as a newspaper we'd be looking in the next year, on the Sydney Morning Herald site of going into more audio and video directions. We'll be doing other things. Certainly the video technology of the web is not there yet. They can set up MS NBC as much as they want. But one of the strange things about going to MS NBC, this joint venture between Microsoft and the NBC network, is that unless you're American it makes no sense. You don't even know what NBC is. And they're doing all these things that relate to NBC programs and if you go the site now you're like scratching your head thinking, 'well, what does that mean?' It's a very strange site that they've built. They've got a long way to go and they've got a lot of money to get there.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Unidentified questioner</B><BR>
Just a very quick one to Wendy. given the reticence of the majority of academics including social science academics to stick their neck out into the third world environments, social action fields, apart from  - it seems to be that with the cutbacks in tertiary sectors there seems to be a lack of social and political commitment from within universities. I mean, maybe this is a superficial thing. Obviously the Signposts is designed to overcome that to some extent, but do you see any limitations being imposed from the institutions apart form lack of funds to sort of do it? Is the thing, once it's established, off and running under its own steam, or are there any political or censoring limitations that may develop if it . . . I mean, to the extent that because of the interactive nature of it, if some overseas government complains that it's presenting a tool for some NGO to. . . I mean, it seems to me you're saying if you got to the point where it was instantaneously interactive, where there's hundreds of different NGOs putting stuff in so that it's a news database up to date for the moment, where people can take political action emanating from the screen in front of them - you know, if we saw something coming up in front of us now that said: 'There's been another Aboriginal death in custody down at Long Bay. There's a demonstration in 10 minutes time outside the State Parliament House,' would that sort of information flow lead to some sort of constraint imposed institutionally upon the operation?
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Wendy Bacon</B><BR>
You're assuming there that there'd be a press release from the Aboriginal Deaths In Custody or some other organisation saying, making a statement about it and saying they were going to have a demonstration. If we had the resources to put it on Signposts, it actually automatically downloads every night, so it wouldn't come up that quickly, but I'm sure we would be prepared to put it there. But rather than just stating that I would say that the university is an incredibly politically sensitive environment to work in at the minute, and I'm very concerned about the impact on the way changes to the way research is being funded, of the pressures on the university to go into user-pays in almost every aspect of its activities. And as someone who was in universities earlier and went back into universities later in my career, I'm somewhat disappointed by the lack of vigorous intellectual debate within the university sector. 
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now I think like any other institution, I think that within the university there is a huge range of different views and approaches to this. I have been so far, I can only say that within my own institution, UTS, we published for example a report on Mt Lyall mine which had been suppressed effectively by the University of Tasmania, and that was broadcast on Channel 9, SBS, and the university welcomed that move. I think perhaps some universities - I mean, everyone is going to have to have their market - and some universities are hopefully going to have to go for a defence of intellectual freedom, equity and access. 
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now I also think that what we're looking for is to develop relationships with our colleagues around the country and around the globe who think like we do and for example, David Robie over here who teaches journalism in Port Moresby, UPNG, we've developed a relationship we value a lot with the university journalism department up there where we publish their newspaper which won a prize last year. SO I guess I think it's like journalism. In journalism it's always a question of negotiating the environment in which you live to the best of your ability, and we'll have to do the same in universities. But I guess being a bit of a - I mean, I can't imagine the situation. I can imagine the technology I suppose conceivably being removed, but there's no hint of that. I think the biggest problem - this is the only way I can see anyone managing to stop us, and I can't see any hint of this being likely to happen. 
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But the biggest challenge for us will be to get the fairly small funds that we need to keep this project viable on an ongoing basis. To maintain a pretty big virtual library at ANU they only need one research fellow half time to do that, to process the amount of work. Now that's not a large amount of money. Now we have to set about working out for our project a funding an ongoing arrangement which will see it continue on and there's someone there to receive the messages, put the information on, do the links. I think it's got a healthy future but I agree that we work in a politically sensitive environment.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Stephen Quinn </B><BR>
Stephen Quinn. A little story about postage stamps. Did you know that there is no 'England' on the British postage stamp, because they invented it so they didn't need to, like America doesn't need the US tag. I've got to come back to Bill Gates, because if you've got 1.5 billion dollars, you' can buy an awful lot of content. I think that should be a worry to a lot of media organisations. 
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>David Wilson </B><BR>
If I could just spend a moment on that one because I like to tell people that competition in that sense is really good, right? If I can get my information from Bill Gates or I can get it from Mike Bloomberg or I can get it from Reuters or I can get it from AP or CNN, what's gonna make me choose one site as opposed to another? The answer is simply the quality of the information that you get there. I don't see how that can be a bad thing. I don't see how more competition can be a bad thing, in the sense of raising the level of the competition and making us more focussed on how factual are we, how much information are we providing to people. Who is it that's talking in our stories? Are they real people or someone that is understood, right? The confidential source that the journalist has, he or she won't tell the reader about. To me, having Microsoft or anybody else in the game is a good thing not a bad thing, because it forces us all to take a look at what we're doing every day and say 'how can we make it better?' And that's got to be to the benefit of readers everywhere.
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>End of session</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
