<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Intersections with Asia: Where the Media stands</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Intersections with Asia:<BR>
 Where the Media stands</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Three</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I'd like to say something about the tone of our coverage. The question of cultural differences is quite important here. I know there's a big discussion about Asian values. My view on that's quite simple. My view on that is that at the end of the day there's very little difference between core Asian values and core western values, and I don't accept a lot of the debate that takes place on this particular issue. I do however believe that it's very important for Australian journalists in approaching coverage of Asia to be sensitive to cultural issues and to be sensitive to cultural differences. And I think frankly it's unprofessional if we're not. That doesn't mean that we compromise our coverage. What it simply means is that we are sensitive in terms of the tone of our coverage. I don't want my journalists reporting out of Asia and South-East Asia the way - in the oldfashioned days of Sydney journalism - you would have had a correspondent from the Sydney Daily Mirror reporting on the police round in Sydney. And I think that this cultural sensitivity is being addressed in journalism. I think more and more the journalists who do cover foreign affairs and cover the region are alive to this particular issue. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I'd note the fact that one of the phenomenons in the region has been a very dramatic political liberalisation over the decade in a number of countries. It's important that we don't forget that. What it means is that it is becoming easier for the Australian media to do its job properly in the region. And if you compare the extent of political liberalisation in the region today as opposed to ten years ago or twenty years ago then the differences have been  very significant. And I think that it's noteworthy  to observe that historical perspective. I think that it indicates there's a lot of change going on in the region. And one of the interesting features is the extent of professional development in journalism and in the media right through the Asia-Pacific. And what the Australian media industry must do is it must develop relations with our colleagues right through the Asia-Pacific. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I'm on the board of the Australia-Indonesian Institute, and one of the initiatives that we've introduced in recent years has been meetings of Australian and Indonesian newspaper editors. We've had two such meetings so far, one in Sydney a couple of years ago, and one more recently in Jakarta. These meetings have been I think very beneficial. They've been extremely frank meetings. At the first meeting in Sydney it was very interesting for Australian editors listening to the Indonesian editors describe the way they see the Indonesian media operating; the extent to which they feel that they have discretion, and the extent to which they feel they're operating within a framework composed by the government. And I think this sort of exchange between editors is enormously beneficial and that there should be more journalistic and editorial exchanges.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
However, I would like to close simply by reiterating the point that I've made that within the Australian media I think we've got a lot more to do in terms of coming to grips with the South East Asia, North East Asia, with Southern Asia and with the Asia-Pacific generally. I think that we still find it difficult in as much as our cultural predilections are to the United States and to the UK, and we must continue to cover those part of the world because they're important in their own right and their certainly very much the areas of interest for a lot of our readers. But by the same token it's enormously important for us to expand and improve our coverage of Asia far more than what we've been able to do. I think this is going to be an ongoing and difficult challenge for the Australian media. 
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Thankyou.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
[ <A HREF="#top">Return to top</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="kelly02.html">Previous section</A> ] 
[ <A HREF="../panels/session-seven01.html">Go to questions</A> ]
</CENTER></B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
