<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Seven</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Paul Kelly. Section Three.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question. Paul Thomas.</B><BR>
Paul Thomas from Monash.  To what extent are correspondents improving in their ability to gather news from non-English language sources, including contacts that they make as well as reference to the printed media?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly</B><BR> 
Well, that's really a function of language skills. Some journalists have them, others don't. Frankly, more should have them. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>[interjection from the floor, incomprehensible]</B> 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly</B><BR>
Our Jakarta correspondent has them. Very relevant point: Greg Sheridan, is our Foreign Editor, he travels widely throughout the region. But the answer to your question is: more correspondents should have them. But having made that point, I would also say that sometimes one can exaggerate the value of language skills. Is suppose my experience increasingly is that it's very important for the foreign correspondent to be a good journalist , that is to have a high degree of general journalistic skills. That's enormously important because essentially I think it's more difficult being a foreign correspondent operating in an overseas city than it is being a journalist operating at home in Australia. you simply need a higher degree of skills to do the job properly. I must say that this is a conclusion I've come to over a period of time and therefore I put a very high premium on those general journalistic skills, but I agree with you on language - we should do better, we should do more. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question. Karen Glahn.</B><BR>
Karen Glahn, correspondent for a Danish newspaper You're talking about dealing with your subjects in a sensitive manner. Terry Watson was talking about how you didn't take kindly to him when he was writing about weapons dealings in Singapore. Some matters you can't deal with sensitively, can you? Maybe that's why you've still got good contacts in Indonesia and on the highest level, because maybe you skirt some of the more sensitive - the things you can't deal with sensitively.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly</B><BR> 
Well, I think that's a very good question. There's absolutely no question that the standards which apply to the media in a number of Asian capitals are different to the standards that apply to the media in this country. There's absolutely no question about that. I mean, we are very very well aware of what those standards are, simply because we have our own dealings with Indonesia editors. We are quite familiar with them. I think that is a particularly good point. There are some issues which at the end of the day - whether one's talking about issues in Singapore or issues in Indonesia or in other countries - which are going to defy that sort of approach, I think that's right.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>[follow up from the floor, a bit indistinct: Which means you can't have it all from an Australian perspective, can you?]</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly</B><BR>
Well, I've already said that it's quite clear the framework in which the media operates in a number of countries in Asia is different to the Australian framework. I think we all know that. That's simply a given. I mean, the entire situation is quite different.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>[follow up: You said we had to have the news from the Australian perspective. Obviously that can't happen all the time then.]</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly</B><BR>
No, what I was saying there was, I think it's very important for the Australian media to have its own foreign correspondents in the Asia–Pacific, so we're not just relying on an international news services or other syndicated services, if we have our own correspondents on the spot to provide an Australian perspective. That was the point I was making.
</TD></TR>
