<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Do Asian news values deny freedom of expression?</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Do Asian news values deny<BR>
 freedom of expression?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Four</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Tan Bri (Dr.) A. Samad Ismail attempted a more down-to-earth case for special values that limit what we know better as inalienable rights like freedom of speech and the press. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In his 1994 Ramon Magsaysay Lecture, he linked values to geography and experience. Only areas colonised by democracies will tend to respect democratic practices, like a free press. Yet, all the colonial powers were democracies - England, Holland, France and the United States. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Perhaps he meant only what Ian Buruma observed, that colonial powers did not practice their democracy in the colonies. The autocracy of colonial administration spoiled the native soil for democracy. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But how do you explain the democratic exuberance of Japan, formerly ruled by military cliques under a system of emperor worship? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Or Taiwan, a former military garrison? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Or Korea, more than half a century under the heel of the Japanese Army?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Dr. Ismail tried next to link values to stages of economic development and social organisation, and proposed a certain respect by journalism for the values pertinent to each stage. For example, the poor may as well have no rights like free speech since they cannot assert them effectively or at all. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But doesn't that try to make a value out of necessity? It does not prove the weak don't need rights. Quite the contrary. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In fact, it is not the weak who must stand up for their rights but the government. The ineffectiveness of certain rights shows, not their irrelevance to the individual, but the weakness or indifference of governments.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It turns out, however, that this Asian pundit did not have the rights of the people in mind but those of countries and governments. He quoted approvingly a certain Dr. Chandra Muzaffar who said that poor countries are in no position to exercise their right of free expression at international forums, especially if they are in debt to foreign banks. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This is incredible. Freedom of speech and of the press pertains to individuals against the state and not to a state in the community of nations. Any first year law student knows that.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The issue is not whether poor countries with big debts stolen by dictators have a right to complain to creditor banks for extending the loans, but whether people should enjoy the protected right to speak out against the profligacy of a bad government, and make its officials return their ill-gotten wealth.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The Philippines could complain anytime, anywhere, about bad loans to their crooked government, but the banks would only reply: So why didn't you stop it?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
And the answer to that yields the one indisputable Asian value that explains a great deal of Asian behaviour. That value is life and the fear of losing it, and the unwillingness to risk it by being picked up, roughed up or put against a wall by government agents.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
President Aquino said in a speech at Johns Hopkins: "I worry about the argument that democracy is responsible for instability in free societies. Instability in a democracy is caused by the refusal of elements in the military to tolerate the freedom that the people want. Nowhere in my part of the world did people ever reject democracy. Only the military did."
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
About Asian values, she remarked: "This notion that democracy must be culture - compatible paints a sorry picture of races of men allergic to freedom and uncomfortable with the dignity that liberty alone can confer."
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"Asians love freedom as much as Americans. And while the last time Americans defended their freedom was in 1865, Asians have been doing it more recently - in the Philippines, in Korea and Burma. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"I worry when the burden is on democracy to prove its stability and conduciveness to progress. The burden should be on authoritarianism which was responsible for the collapse of the debt - ridden countries of Latin America, the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"Democracy is stable by nature. It is its critics who are unstable - desiring more power by shorter means than the people will freely allow.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"It is dictatorships that are chaotic. Democracies hold elections, dictatorships wage wars on their own people."
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
