<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: One</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Teodoro L. Locsin. Section Three</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 7. Annmarie Anton.</B><BR>
My name's Annmarie Anton, I'm a freelance journalist. Two years ago there was a Filipino journalist I heard .. from the Philippines. She wrote for Manilla Times and Chronicle at one stage, and the Enquirer. My question first, the comments she made, that since Ramos came into power apparently business is booming like nothing in the Philippines, and newspapers as well as magazines and new radio stations, are coming out in big numbers. Apparently it's as easy to print out your own newspapers for your own advertising (and there's a lot of editorial sacrifices made because of that). How true are these comments from her.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR>
I think you're speaking about Amanda Donilla [?].
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 7 Annmarie Anton.</B><BR>
That's one of them, yes.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin </B><BR>
You're saying that there's been more and more newspapers. No in fact that's not true. The number of newspapers from the time when Mrs Aquino came to power with the restoration of democracy was 22. And we're down to nine. A lot of them have gone out of business. The number of TV stations remains the same. One of them was captured about 80% of the market, that's the Lopez owned group, it's a private group, as against the government run stations which will be privatised next year.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 7 Annmarie Anton.</B><BR>
She was making comments along the lines of that it's easier to set up and release your own newspaper for advertising purposes.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin </B><BR>
No, that's impossible. We all depend on advertising from real businesses.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 7 Annmarie Anton.</B><BR>
What I'm saying is, companies themselves, businesses themselves, find it easier to just print out their own newspapers and put in their own advertising in it.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR>
No, they don't. You have to be specific. John Gocumway [??] now owns the Manila Times. He's not the original owner. The original owner was a publishing family of 100 years. This man came from making basically corn curls and chicken and became very successful (some real estate, some department stores) and bought the Manila Times. He hardly ever advertises in his own paper. And what would he gain from that?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 7 Annmarie Anton</B><BR>
Just very quickly . . .
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR>
Because his newspaper's circulation is very tiny.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 7 Annmarie Anton</B><BR>
Just very quickly one other question. And he was saying on the same breath that — you mentioned earlier (I came late in the talk), you said that you were actually pushing your journalists to cover more corruption cases or corruption issues in government. He's saying that it's quite dangerous for investigative journalists to go that way now in the Philippines, and he quoted the death of about 42 journalists who were doing business investigative journalism, especially in the regional areas and rural areas. How true are his comments? [pause] That journalists tend to actually move away from investigative journalism?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin </B><BR>
I don't have any sympathy with — there's a certain movement in the Philippines about the safety of journalists. There was one journalist who claims he was being followed and some journalists have the cheek to actually organise a rally for his safety. So that's what journalists do is take risks, but actually I did not see any risks to that journalist. In fact most of the journalists shot in the Philippines were shot because they were playing around with somebody else's wife [laughter]: no, I'm serious about that, because if we sensationalise these cases of these journalists getting shot in private, either for gambling debts or refusing to pay or playing around with somebody else's wife, if you sensationalise that and make it common, one day they're going to shoot someone who is a real crusading journalist. And the police and the public will just throw up there hands and say 'oh, here's another one of them.' That's a very dangerous thing, so they should take their causes.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Chair </B><BR>
Can we have one last question? I think Paddy McGuiness wants to.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 8. Paddy McGuiness</B><BR> 
Thanks. Well of course I think most people would agree with you that when we're talking about liberty and freedom of expression 'Asian values' don't exist or are less important than universal human values. Nevertheless, did you occasionally find the continual reproaches and berating of Asian government by people who live in democratic societies where it's easy to be critical, sometimes rather patronising and racist?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Locsin</B><BR> 
I'll tell you. I was in the government and as you know our government came to power basically with the help of the American media. They attacked Marcos like anything and we were happy about it and the attacks were so bad that even after Mrs Aquino technically lost the election, the count, the Spanish parliament, basing itself on the very favourable reports we got from the western press, proclaimed her the President of the Philippines. By the act of the Spanish [??}. It served that purpose. When we were in power the western journalists, I  thought wrongly, became disenchanted with her government, saying that she should have instituted radical land reform etc, things for which frankly we weren't fighting. We were fighting  for pure English freedom. But they insisted no! we were fighting for equitable distribution of wealth and from three months after the revolution we were attacked by the western media. I couldn't find it in my heart to criticise them for what they were doing for us before, now they were doing it to us, it would just be hypocritical. From there point of view this is how they see it. We took advantage of it then because we believed in freedom; we'd have to suffer the consequences now that we're in power. I had no problems with that. We really took a beating from the western press. I don't think she's recovered from it either.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Chair</B><BR>
Well, thank you once again Mr Locsin.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
