<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reporting Business in South-East Asia</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+1">Reporting Business in South-East Asia</B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Section Four</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The business of business journalism is largely to follow the money trail. 
Who has the money, where did they get it, what are they spending it on and
why, where are they spending it , and how great a return is being made and
who is getting it.  The questions remain the same whether those involved
are governments, corporations, the military of family companies. Business at
bottom is about power, money, and counting coup.  If money is the mother's
milk of politics, as an American politician named Tip O'Neill remarked, how
much truer is this of business.  What happens to that money and how it is
used affect the nation and its people as a whole.  Not to mention foreign
investors.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In Asia, where government, the military, and secretive families play so large
a part in the economy such questions are often perceived as rude and
intrusive, let alone impertinent.  But these controllers of money and power
are going to be opened to scrutiny as never before as the world is linked
very more closely together by global trade, investment, and technology.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Social and political questions also will come into greater play in the business
equation.  As we have seen, those with business agendas invariably attach
them to pocket-book issues that matter.  When Nike started making
sneakers in Indonesia to take advantage of that nation's cheap labor,
American workers grumbled about the export of jobs.  That led to press
stories about Nike, especially in regard to the use of child labor.  And that
led to pressure on Nike to do something about it.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Two other examples of business deals prompting scrutiny by the broader
press and carrying political implications. . McDonnell Douglas Corp.'s $1.6
billion deal to make planes for China is now front page news because of
alleged Chinese efforts to shift some of the high-tech equipment into military
production.  The blatant ignoring of copyright in India and China, in
particular, continues to be a regular feature of news coverage.  As the
business story broadens into a more general story, the heavy hitters of the
media get involved.  And that being to affect the broad strategic policies of
nations.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Such stories will multiply as the world's business press follows its national
business sector to Asia.  For journalism, despite what many of its critics, and
even some of its proponents, charge, is more a mirror of society than an
arbiter of change.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Nobody can know how these culture clashes will play out.  Beijing's recent
severe punishment of Wang Dan, who though not a strictly a journalist was
performing a similar function, highlights the potential for collision.  Wang's
treatment is widely regarded as a warning to those who would threaten the
establishment with democracy and a message to the West that things are
done differently in Asia.  But the old order is changing and its replacement
will live in a very different world.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
For as the IT revolution links Asia more tightly with the rest of the world, it
challenges mores and traditional behavior.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
If successful Asian businessmen  continue to send their children off to be
educated in the U.S., Canada and Australia, notably at business schools,
can they expect them to come back home and run the outfit as in the old
days.  Or will they push for more modern management methods and
perhaps even contemplate, heaven forbid, taking the family empire public.  
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
As middle classes expand will they be content to focus on making and
spending money and not challenge the establishment for a greater say in
the running of society?  Nowhere else in the world where a strong middle
class has emerged have they not demanded a great say in the fate of the
nation. I doubt Asia will be much different.  Witness recent developments in
Japan, South Korea and Taiwan.   From those middle classes sprout,
among other activists, crusading journalists and editors.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
