<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Three</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Three</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Peter O'Loughlin, Zainoor Sulaiman. Section Four</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 6</B><BR>
 Can I just ask you to cast your minds forward about ten years or so - you've given us a great background on where we've come from with these services - but where you see us being in ten years in terms of the role of wire services vis a viz local newspapers, the sorts of products you see being offered. There's a lot of experimenting going on at the moment. Do you have a sense for which of those products might succeed. Just a bit of crystal ball gazing . . .
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin </B><BR>
I don't really. I just think we're going to get an exponential growth of what we've already got. I mean, you'll get more online services, but until people can find out how to pay for it I'm not quite sure that it's got any value. We've gone into it in a big way, as I was telling you about the Presidential visit, and the way we do it is different to others. You can only get our online multimedia services through the website of one of our member newspapers. So I think the way it will develop will be the way those newspapers develop their sites. And they will then tell us what they'd like to provide for it, because we are after all just a provider. AP is, unlike some other agency, we're not out trying to develop new products and repackage things to sell individually, and go down the foodchain to smaller organisations and customers. What about you, do you have a feel for the future?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Zainoa Sulaiman </B><BR>
We try to bring . . . as daily as possible to the people, instead of just relying on the newspapers and TV and radio stations. For example we have started what we call the VBI service. You can on the PC, you can get . . . television signal for example. Of course you need a decoder for that to receive our service. There is a limited service, especially you know, the small man playing the stock market for example, they get the ... information there at the same time they get what's related on the news. So I think we have to be read to follow through. Even for example one Malaysian newspaper, the vernacular newspapers, have on the website, six languages. They have the main copy in English, they also have it in Spanish, in French, in German and some other languages. They do it everyday. They are not getting any revenue yet, they have over a million people you know, so we also are on the internet, but we have to see how much then it will effect our business.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer </B><BR>
Yes, I'd like to say that yes the internet poses a lot of problems to newsagencies. Particularly in the control of the information. What's happening is that people scrounge around the internet and pick up information that comes from the newsagency that has been legitimately put ton the internet, then reproduce it and sell it for profit. Well obviously as it is newspapers are not paying, or traditional media clients, do not really pay what it costs to gather information, so internet does pose some problems in that regard. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
We have to ... be very carefully used. But one thing that I do think we're getting towards, and it would be helpful for a lot of people, in smaller countries and in smaller media, is that they will be able to download material that specifically interests them. They don't have to get 80 000 words a day and extract from that 10 000 words that they're interested in. For example in the Pacific countries there are very small media outlets and they may wish and prefer to have just regional Pacific news, and we hope to provide that, so they can dial in and pick it up.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 7 </B><BR>
I'm from a small operator newsagency, it's a domestic newsagency of Portugal, and I'd like to ask the same question to both from the big player perspective and from a national newsagency. As the speed gathers pace in terms of delivering the news and even if a domestic newsagency like myself has tried to put itself on the internet with an English service and a French service and even a Mandarin service and so forth, that as the speed gathers pace, particularly in terms of information about business news and so forth, that what the newsagency is doing is making correspondents like myself doing more in depth work and more analysis rather than giving news per such. Let's call it more current affairs. Do you think that small operators will move more towards that way, more specialised analytical work as opposed to fast - because it's impossible for me as an operator here to beat a ... although I've done it in very small minute details - when Agence France can send it much faster. How do you see both from a big player perspective and from a small agent.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Sulaiman </B><BR>
It's very small beer ... We look at areas of say in our own interests. For example you look at certain - as a Malaysian national agency - we look at something which is of direct interest to Malaysia. So, that would be our focus. And of course the media in Malaysia, and even the other ..., we're more keen to see those stories that effect Malaysia. So I think there's no conflict here. Whereas the wires will be more on general terms, maybe regional or international angle, where we still have I think quite an important role to play to feed the ...stories more pertinent to the country.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin </B><BR>
I'd agree with you. But I also think there's probably going to be a role for your smaller agencies, because the big newspapers aren't doing as much as they used to. When I started on newspapers here in Sydney part of the job for young journalists was to report the local councils. I don't think the newspapers bother with those any more. I think the Sydney Morning Herald has two people who do courts, whereas in London there's an agency that does nothing but courts and sells the reportage to the national dailies. There's one agencies that does Heathrow Airport only, cause the newspapers can't be bothered sending anybody out there if they can buy coverage from these guys at the airport. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
So, I think there's going to be quite a lot more opportunities will come out of this, and the big organisations will concentrate on the things they do best, and that's deploying a lot of people to big events and doing it very fast with a lot of good background. But I think there's also probably room for well-backgrounded pieces that are timeless, there's good opportunity there. Although, you know, we're all doing that, we all do analysis and background on almost every event that's of significance. But I do think yeah, there are opportunities.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer </B><BR>
Yes, that makes three of us in agreement here. But yes I do think that the smaller newsagencies would be better off if they concentrated on the particular angles that their client newspapers are interested in. Because the newsagencies are now definitely moving general stories much faster, and so therefore I think a great deal of emphasis is given to covering the major stories. I think there is room for angles, and I think journalists should go abroad with that in mind and try to set up their own small agencies to supply their newspapers back home.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
