<!--Website produced by Future Thinkers 1996-->
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Un-Western Perspectives on News</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Un-Western Perspectives on News </FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B><FONT SIZE="+1">Section Four</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Today's journalists have to see the links between northern over- consumption and southern deprivation and report on these twin threats to the planet's viability. The beef that hamburger multinationals buy could come from cattle that graze on land cleared of Venezuelan rainforests. Exotic aquarium fish in Singapore's shops may have been caught by a ten-year-old Filipino boy diving down to the corals to squirt cyanide on the reefs. The elegant carpets for sale in shops in Hamburg are woven by overworked and underpaid women and children in Nepal, where the dyes and chemicals needed to treat the rugs have blackened rivers and poisoned ground water.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Poverty, population growth, climate change and the loss of cultural and biological diversity are such serious challenges to future life on the planet that reporting them calls for a new breed of journalists--journalists without mental borders who have the energy and vision to move beyond the traditional classroom concepts of reporting and writing. Reporters who do not just report, but look behind the headlines to examine cause and effect. They must be reporters with wider horizons who constantly explore regional or international linkages to national problems. Journalists shouldn't just hold a mirror to society, but be a part of its reflection. And most importantly, journalists must feel part of the societies and the planet that they write about and care for it.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Today, traditional economic thinking is being revised to take into account ecological realities, social justice and equity. Like economists, journalists also need new parameters. Present rules dictate that stories on the rich and powerful are hard news for page one and articles on landless peasants and the reasons for their plight are for the weekend section. Old fashioned journalism that reduced everything to event-oriented spots needs to be replaced by contextualised coverage that looks at the linkages and true nature of change.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The question of how far journalists should go in taking a point of view without hurting their credibility is something that every reporter has to take very seriously. The squabble between subjectivity and objectivity is the oldest debate in the world's second-oldest profession. Journalism schools today preach the gospel of balanced reporting: a concept inherited mainly from the Anglo-Saxon media schools which during the darkest days of apartheid, for example, behaved in an impeccably balanced manner to report on South Africa by treating institutionalised state racism as if it was a minor corruption scandal. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In a report on a global conference of spiritual leaders and parliamentarians in Moscow in 1988, Anuradha Vittachi wrote: "With each gulp of news, our "objective" reporters chew down the complexity they receive, simplify it to the level of their prejuidices, and them amplify their prejuidices in print. Their loyal readers buy whichever prejuidices correspond with their own, denoucning the other versions as written by liars." 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Narrative neutrality in print and broadcast media has been elevated to a journalistic credo, neutering reporters and making them incapable of distinguishing right from wrong. "Balanced reporting" treats a reporter like a robot, with no power of analysis and comprehension and capable of only a monochrome view of the world. Reporters should concentrate on shovelling facts, it is said, and let the experts handle the more intellectually demanding op-ed stuff. This is not reporting, it is stenography. And as one American journalist put it, "it is relentless factuality, stories without conclusions and journalism without a point of view which is biased in favour of the status quo, relying on its substance on the facts and opinions supplied by the prominent and powerful".
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Objectivity makes journalists only responsible for the method, not the content. It exposes them to manipulation by the elite, who already have greater access to mainstream media. The role of the media is not to serve as a megaphone for those in power: its job is to "place responsibility for the failures of our society on the people and institutions that control society". The biggest problem with the doctrine of narrative neutrality is that it favours the institutions that control society. 
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
