<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Four</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Four</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Kunda Dixit, Tulsathit Taptim. Section Four.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question, David Robie </B><BR>
This is a question for Kunda Dixit that's really a marketing question. In the South Pacific the news media generally speaking and particularly the print media has very limited range of news services. Basically all the daily news services have largely relied on Australian Associated Press feed, which as included limited coverage from Reuters and AP and so on, and also includes some from Agence France press. That changed three years ago when Malaysian-owned National was launched, and they brought in an Agence France Press news service and the coverage changed quite dramatically in Papua New Guinea, where there was a lot more extensive coverage of Asia–Pacific Region and the had an effect on the competitive Murdoch-owned Post. It seems to me that IPS has a very good service that would be very well suited to news media in the South Pacific. I just wondered if IPS has approached that possibility, and are there any papers that might be likely to take their service?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Kunda Dixit </B><BR>
Well, when I was in Port Moresby, David, when I met you, I did go to see the National and the other papers there, and they are very sympathetic to what I said, that we had a different perspective on world events, but I also heard the same old story: that we have information overload, we have so much, we cannot even in the course of a day read all the wire services that we subscribe to, we don't really have space. And I said what I always say, which is that there's a qualitative difference, that what you're getting from us is different, it's not competing with them but it's supplementary. Yeah, I put them on a three month trial and never heard from them again. And also the problem is that our stories are longer. They're more in depth. And I suppose they have limited space. That National is a tabloid, they have very little space, they have a lot of ads. But yeah, I think there is a lot of possibility for having a partner agency in the South Pacific which would do the distribution for us, which already has a network, and we just feed into that. With not our whole service, but perhaps a selection of stories that would be interesting to South Pacific clients. For this I would say stories on global warming for example, or negotiations of the IPCC in Geneva, what happened to govern the outside emissions (it really effects all the island countries); what's happening to other island counties in the Indian Ocean or the Caribbean. These sort of stories are the sort of stories we can offer that would be different, and, well, let's talk.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question [a bit crackly and occasional word missed]</B><BR>
 I would like to get comment from both of you - you mentioned something about journalists having to be a part of society and then also have a representative of these quality papers, the English papers in Bangkok, also that you are independent news source - when we look at the popularity of the tabloid or the sort of popularity of the nationalist kind of news media, you sometimes wonder there is a dilemma being part of the society and representative of most of the population, and the sort of integrity of the media. As you mentioned, many of the quality kind of documentary or the good TV program does not seem to reach the area while the nationalist kind of thing seems to have a much popularity. I would like to get some of the comment from both of you about this dilemma between being part of society and the integrity of the journalism.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer </B><BR>
In Thailand people, like everywhere else, they love to read sensational stories. But they treat those stories like entertainment, like everywhere. There's freedom still fracturing(?) in Thailand, but I think the process should go on. Today some people might believe in some nonsense story if you see it in a sensational newspaper. But sooner or later the people will become smarter and will be more selective about believing in news stories. Of course they will never stop reading tabloids, they like stories about movie stars and other gossip, political allegations and false political allegations, stories like that. But they will get smarter and they will know what to believe. It will take some time but I think that's a process. We have to start somewhere.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer </B><BR>
With us, we really don't do tabloid journalism so much. Maybe we should be doing it. But I'm reminded of the famous headline in the New york Daily News that boosted their circulation, double of what their daily circulation was. The headline was 'Headless body found in topless bar'. [laugh] So that kind of journalism gets you circulation, so it's a dilemma as you mentioned for journalists and media groups. I mean, how populist can you be, and how can you do responsible intelligent coverage. I think the way for media groups who have difficult making intelligent newspaper ends' meet, is to have both. SO you have a tabloid where you make all your money and you subsidise the other one. And I think some newspaper groups are doing that. Others do it by having large circulation vernacular press which is sensational, make money from it, and then subsidise the  English.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>End of question session.</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
