<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Four</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>China Sets the Parameters for Press Freedom</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Despite provisions in the Basic Law guaranteeing press freedom after 1997, there may be other ways to restrict what media organisations can write and say after 1997. Recently, Chinese officials have spelled out restrictive ground rules for journalists.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>The most recent statement was made by China's Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister, Qian Qichen, during the closing session of the sixth plenary session of the Preparatory Committee early this month. He stated that press freedom should be protected by Hong Kong laws. But he said rumours and personal attacks should not be regarded as press freedom. He further explained that there were objective criteria in judging right and wrong, and different professions should be governed by professional ethics recognised by society.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>However, the explanation did not square with criticism sounded by legal scholars in Hong Kong. According to these scholars, the law cannot deal with personal attacks, and there is a grey area between criticism and personal attack.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Mr Qian's line was similar to remarks he made in an interview with the Asian Wall Street Journal. In the interview, the vice-premier said that "(t)hey can put forward criticism, but not rumours or lies. Nor can they put forward personal attacks on the Chinese leaders. For that would not live up to the morality of the occupation. And that is not compatible with personal moral ethics as well." Mr Qian was also quoted as saying that "Hong Kong should not hold those political activities which directly interfere in the affairs of the mainland of China." This has been taken to mean that activities marking the anniversary of the 1989 suppression of the pro-democracy movement in China would not be allowed in Hong Kong.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Similar ground rules were spelt out in May by the Director of China's Hong Kong and Macau Affairs Office, Lu Ping, who asserted in an interview with America's Cable News Network that the Hong Kong media would not be permitted to advocate "two Chinas" or to write about Hong Kong or Taiwan independence. It would seem that from China's perspective, any call for independence for a part of the country would be going against the principle of "one country".
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Mr Lu reiterated his views in August, during a meeting with a delegation of Hong Kong journalists. He said: "I don't want to create any illusions for you. After 1997, it will not be possible for you to advocate two Chinas, or one China and one Taiwan, or Hong Kong independence, or Taiwan independence, or Tibet independence. The press will not be allowed to do so. It is a
 different issue from press freedom." He also stressed that the post-1997 government had to legislate against seditious or subversive acts, and there had to be a differentiation between advocacy and objective reporting.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>During the same visit by the Hong Kong delegation, a senior Chinese official in charge of media policy said that China would of course like the Hong Kong media to consider his country's point of view, but that China would not achieve this goal by implementing a high-handed policy.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>It has become obvious that China will try to set some parameters within which the relatively free Hong Kong media will have to operate after the handover. However, it is essential for the people to stand up for their rights, because China has promised Hong Kong a high degree of autonomy under the one-country two-systems concept, with Hong Kong people ruling Hong Kong.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>We should let the Chinese government know about the contribution that a free press has made in ensuring Hong Kong's success, and about the adverse effects if restrictions are imposed on the media. We should also let Beijing know that the expression of ideas, however unrepresentative, will not harm Hong Kong. I remember that in the early 1980s, some people called for Hong Kong's independence. The suggestion faded away following a thorough discussion in the media. Hong Kong did not suffer as a result. Rather, it continued to prosper.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>I should add here that the HKJA has recently compiled a 10 point agenda for action on freedom of expression. Among other things, the paper calls on the chief executive-designate and the post-1997 government to uphold the right of the public and the media to advocate opinions and ideas, so long as this is implemented peacefully and does not constitute a real and immediate threat to public order or safety. It also calls on the future chief executive to uphold the right to criticise the government and individuals, subject only to the law of libel.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
