<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Seven</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Paul Kelly. Section Four.</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question. Kate Fry</B><BR>
Kate Fry from UTS You talked about the trend to insularity that you pick out in Australia at the moment in our own coverage, and you gave some examples from the UK elections - sorry, the US elections and the UK crisis of identity, and talked about our cultural predilections being in those areas. You haven't actually said whether you think this is occurring, this sort of insularity, with regard to Asia and our Australian coverage. And if you think it is, what do you think are some of the issues we should be looking at in more depth, and perhaps bringing it back to the introduction of this conference, some of the issues to do with changing social structures in Asia, as you're obviously wanting us to deal with them in the US and the UK. What sort of things do you think should be getting more depth and more attention in the Australian media?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly </B><BR>
Well I think the issues are the underlying issues. And this gets back to the point I've been making that the foreign correspondents have got to be very good journalists. They've got to be experienced journalists and they've got to be able to handle things conceptually. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Now in answer to your question, I think that they've got to be able to look at the trends that are going on in Asia. And by the trends I'm now talking about: economic changes; social changes; political changes; technology; telecommunications. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
If you want to be a little bit more specific I mean - the magnitude of Japan's financial crisis over the last several years, and the extent of demoralisation this has fed into Japan's corporate sector is one very very big issues. The nature of Japanese democracy, the genuine nature of Japanese democracy, following the initial loss of the LDP you know, what is the real nature of the decision making process there? It's very different. I mean while Japan has a process of democracy, at the heart the decision making process there, it's a very different sort of democracy to what we understand. How the bilateral relationship between Australia and Japan is being transformed as the old resource-based relationship surrenders to a more complicated relationship, and Australia does not have the clout we once had in Japan and we don't have the personal associations we once had in Japan, and how we handle that as a country. So there are three examples in relation to Japan.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In relation to Indonesia: we've got to try to come to grips with this transition that's going to occur, which will be a unique event for the New Order government, a unique event for Indonesian society. And the fact that institutions in Indonesia are pressing for change - I think there's a very strong feeling in Indonesia that things have got to be done in a different way. There's a real - I believe - feeling of dissatisfaction about the President and about the status quo, outlook, approach and policies of the President. A feeling not just at some levels of Indonesian society for change. Well, there's feelings within the armed forces, feelings within the commercial sector, feelings within the educated people (among students, among academics). 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
We've got to try to come to grips with this and it's a very difficult thing to do, because there are so many different views within Indonesia society about what's going to happen. The increase in religious tensions. Now, these are some examples in relation to Indonesia. Again, these are complicated issues. They're very complicated issues, they need to identified, they need to be written about, they need to be addressed. I think it needs to be done in a sensitive way but it needs to be done. You really need competent reporters to do it. These are very serious journalistic challenges. So in relation to Japan and Indonesia they are some examples.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question</B><BR>
[Name unclear], President of the Foreign Correspondents' Association. You mentioned that you thought it would be a good idea to syndicate stories about South East Asia, particularly Indonesia, to the rest of the English speaking world, which I think is a very good idea. (Often frustrating, for example, my newspaper sending people from Paris here and there in the region who lack in-depth knowledge about what they're writing about). So why isn't that done, or do you know anybody who would be prepared to launch something like that?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Paul Kelly</B><BR>
Well, I think it's something that needs to be addressed, something that needs to be done. It's very important. It's an area of priority I think for Australian media organisations. This is an issue we have under consideration at the moment.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>End of Session</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20>
<br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
