<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Do Asian news values deny freedom of expression?</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Do Asian news values deny<BR>
 freedom of expression?</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Five</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Let me just wrap this up by addressing some specific issues suggested by the organisers. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Does technological change threaten notions of national cultural integrity?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In my view, no; exposure to outside trends by advanced technology strengthens strong cultural aspects, and distils them to their finer parts. Arts, crafts, and systems of thought. The most technologically advanced society today may be Japan, which retains a uniquely impenetrable culture.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Are there such things as Asian news values? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Not specifically Asian, but I think that some conservative Asians worry about the same things that the Christian right worries about in the United States: the influence on the rising generation of too much sex and violence on TV and outrageous hairstyles and clothes. The young everywhere ignore these concerns until they are as old as those who hold them now.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In Bangalore, however, we have again another of those intractable problems raised by the universalist claims of ethics. A group of traditionalist feminist women have threatened to set fire to themselves if India will persist in hosting a beauty pageant. They find these events demeaning to womanhood. Here we have a Western and modern concern - feminism - espoused by a traditional group - Indian women - who would articulate their protest in what was widely regarded as a uniquely Asian fashion - self-immolation - until Norman B. Morrisson set himself on fire on the steps of the Pentagon to protest the Vietnam war.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Will growing affluence lead to more freedom of speech in the region? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Singaporeans tell me they are every year more tightly controlled as the man fades away whose indisputable intelligence held everyone in a stronger thrall than the police could exercise.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
What role should journalists play in the economic and social development of the Asia-Pacific region in the late 20th century? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Dr. A. Samad Ismail, in that lecture of his, proposed that a journalist has a special role. I said no. There is no special mission for a journalist to build his nation separate from his duty to find the truth about it, and tell it as it is. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
There is no such thing as an Asian truth distinct from another kind. Standards for determining what is true and what is a lie do not change from climate to climate. Truth is the only foundation of a valid value system. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
That truth must, in a time of crisis, be protected by a bodyguard of lies is a proposition I find difficult to accept, when there is a more honourable alternative: Hold the story until the crisis passes.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Truth is one. The police club striking the head of a Chinese protester stings as much as the club landing squarely on the head of an American black.  And stealing by the daughter-in-law of an Asian president is stealing plain and simple, and not a form of governance traditional to Asia. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
In no country is there an authentic need to reshape journalistic standards to fit national developmental requirements because journalism's best contribution to nation-building is to be true to its calling - find the facts and tell them straight.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
And, finally, is it possible to predict the future of journalism in the region?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Only if you can predict the price of newsprint until the end of the century, and keep it steady or make it less. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I was invited to answer the question: 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Do Asian values tend to deny freedom of expression? I hope I have shown that the question begged another: Are there Asian values?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
There are things uniquely Asian, distinctive ways of living and coping. But rather than being opposed to such values as free speech, open assembly and democratic elections, these things find purer expression under such values.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I want to know what my Indonesian brother and Malaysian sister really think about his country, my country, the rest of the world. I do not care to know what the President's daughter-in-law, stepping out of a Paris boutique, says the people of her country believe. How would she know? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
I concede that there are, not Asian values, but realities - Asian, African, Balkan - that call for some qualification of free speech. Such as real ethnic or religious divisions that can spill out in blood, as in Bosnia. I will not defend the right to cast a racist slur in a room where somebody has a gun. But with slurs, the press should have little to do, unless it is against politicians, in which case they are to be warmly encouraged.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
But the President's son and daughter-in-law grabbing yet another national resource is not one of those realities that call for any measure of understanding. That reality should invite only attack. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
A century of Asian striving for universal values like individual autonomy, dignity, freedom suggests that the real issue is not between distinct sets of values, but between clashing values within the same set: such as national security versus speech, order versus provocation, art versus conventional morals. Do some of these values tend to deny freedom of the press? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
From time to time yes, as in times of genuine crisis - America in the Great War, Germany in the Depression, and again America in the time of Joseph McCarthy. But, lately, they have tended rather to make freedom strong.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
<TD>
<B><CENTER>
