<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reporting Business in South-East Asia</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+1">Reporting Business in South-East Asia</B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Section Five</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Of course, not all business journalism is adversarial.  While investigative
stories are the most fun and brings the prizes, reputation, and advertising, 
they take huge amounts of work and cannot meet the appetite of TV shows
or publications that must be produced on a regular basis. Besides,
audiences demand useful information even more than a good or insightful
read. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
They want up-to-date market information that is accurate, has been
organized and intelligently distilled for them, and provides a point of view
driven by the facts rather than philosophy or ideology. (In this context,
someone recently remarked that already we are moving from the
Information Age to the Intelligence Age. That suggests a bit of job security
for the editors among you). 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
What other intelligence does the business press audiences desire. They
want to know everything from broad economic outlooks through exchange
rate prospects to, whether to use distributors or agents in a given country. 
They want to know who to do business with and who to avoid.  One of the
more useful pieces I have seen in recent times appeared in WorldBusiness,
a magazine put out by the accounting/consulting firm of Peat Marwick
(speaking of new-style media owners) that bluntly and precisely told readers
who to do business with in Vietnam if they expected to get anywhere.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
That brings me to the question of who will practise this journalism. The
current wave of cost-cutting and downsizing in the developed nations has
prompted many news-gathering organizations to cut back on their foreign
bureaus and even their foreign coverage.  (It is one of today's ironies that
traditional U.S. media, for example, is trimming foreign coverage at a time
when, economically-speaking, the nation is more intricately involved with the
rest of the world than ever before.  In the 1960s, for example, U.S. foreign
trade equated to only 4% of GDP. today it is more than 15%.  And small
companies that never dreamed of exports or foreign investments are
pushing abroad by the thousands.  The contemporary wisdom is that the
end of the Cold War and the triumph of capitalism, along with tougher
economic times, has turned the American focus inward).
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
These cutbacks suggest non-Asian news organizations will rely more on
their own expatriates and locals to provide stories for them.  This may well
impact the quality of those stories for the worse, not least because such
reporters are susceptible to the establishment pressures mentioned earlier. 
Still, that is by no means certain.  An editor of Global Finance, a New York-
based magazine whose title is self-explanatory, recently assigned a
sensitive financial story to a new Japanese stringer.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"I can't ask these important Japanese executives these questions,"
complained the stringer to her New York editor.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"Oh yes you can and you will, if you want to the story to run and to get paid,"
came the reply.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
She did and got her answers.  Most came from the very people she feared. 
Foreigners based in Tokyo filled in the blanks.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The story ran.  She got kudos, her money and a byline.  That did it. Today,
she is one of the magazine's more aggressive and informative writers.  Now,
Japan is not, say, China.  But it wasn't all that long ago, the Japanese were
as quite as anti any sort of unfettered journalism as anybody else in Asia.
They still aren't crazy about it but they have limited choice in the matter if
they want to operate in the larger world and to keep building an economy
that is ever more intricately tied to that world.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It is worth noting that the journalist in that story speaks both her own
language and English.  Command of more than one language is, in fact,
becoming more important than ever for journalists.  Diplomats increasingly
have to speak the language of the country to which they are posted, and are
rewarded financially for doing so.  Why not journalists, even if English is
increasingly the lingua franca of world business.  The China reporting of
Sheryl WuDunn and Nick Kristoff for The New York Times and their
resulting book, China Wakes, demonstrates the immense advantage of
being able to discuss complex manners with interviewees in their own
language rather than through the strainer of an interviewer with an agenda.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
