<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Panel Sessions: Three</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../papers/paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Panel Sessions: Three</FONT></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Peter O'Loughlin, Zainoor Sulaiman. Section Five</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 8 Michael Perry </B><BR>
Michael Perry, Chief Correspondent, Reuters Australia. I'd like to ask a human question here. The discussions have been about the technology, the explosion of news that we're all now providing and now we're providing in a multimedia format. But what of the journalist? What do you see is the future. There's talk of the 'multimedia journalist': is that a myth? is that a reality? Is the journalist of the future going to be expected to supply text, photos, television product, audio. Or is this a technology myth and really we're going to have to have specialists in those areas still?
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer 1</B><BR> 
yes, I do think there's going to be specialists. I don't think people, journalists, will be required to file the multimedia products. And anyway, one of the problems as far as I'm concerned, is very little training is given at all in newsagency journalism. People are taught to be newspaper correspondents and so on but when it comes to training people to work in newsagencies it's virtually non-existent. And I think that there is definitely going to be very specialist people, particularly in the photographic area alone.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin </B><BR>
I dunno, I think we've all had a look at this multimedia person. When I was in Indochina, I mean we didn't have enough staff to send a reporter and a photographer on every assignment, so the reporter would be trained up to use a camera in a basic way, and a tape recorder, and then go out and report, take a picture, get back to the office. Somebody would look after the pictures. He'd write a caption, write a story, and then feed the audio to AP radio in Washington. So the multimedia person has been a round a bit. But when we started AP television, it was an absolute that we would not ask existing photographers or news people to file for AP TV. And with the exceptional case here and there where AP TV was off base or we were off base and they were the only there, that's been held to. I think it's just too difficult to ask a photographer to carry a still camera and a video camera. It's just not possible. And the photographers I know wouldn't do it anyway. I think reporters could be convinced to carry a video in extremis, but by and large it wouldn't be part of the routine job. I think it still has to be a specialist event.
<B>Answer</B><BR>
I'd just like to say that in my experience that journalists never been properly trained in photos. Journalism's a very strong branch of the business, and I think every writing journalist should be really up to speed on what happens on the photo side, and should be able to take a photo and get rid of it back to the office. And I don't mean by pigeoning it with some passenger on Qantas. Should be able to put it in Photoshop and send it. And it may not become compulsory but I think it'd be useful  if journalists were taught to do it.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Questioner 1 </B><BR>
May I ask our Malaysian guest whether or not the technological change has influenced the news values/ Asian values debate in terms of everybody using technology now: does that mean everybody using English language for example as a common currency. I'd like to ask the other speakers whether or not technological change has meant that the public relations expert entering the media and government public relations experts, now will have the upper hand over their critics because they have greater access to the technology.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Sulaiman </B><BR>
No, I don't think there should be any change, because you can go on any language you know. Because in Malaysia [you can be on] the internet in Arabic or Mandarin. In fact we are moving one step ahead by even maybe start submitting our news copy in Mandarin, within the country. Because we have a lot of Chinese newspapers and we have resources say from China and even from Taiwan and Hong Kong. So because ... foreign news into the country, so we must allow this ... to make some money out of this. So, I think the question of English or what level language I think is just - the language is not a problem here. I don't believe English even ... , the technologies or the language you develop accordingly. Of course English has been the second language all the time in Malaysia.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer </B><BR>
I'm sorry, I wasn't sure of the thrust of the second part of that question.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Question 1</B><BR>
The thrust of my question is basically (and I'll raise it because a former employee of mine is in the room here today). When BHP are up against the environmentalists over Ok Tedi, they have the technology and resources to go out and shoot their own propaganda films, put it on the internet, get it out on the wire services, far more effectively than say the Australian Conservation Foundation,  operating on a much smaller budget. What I'm saying is: does the changes in technology allow the powerful to squeeze the meek more, or do we take the other view, that the increase in technology allow everybody to become their own editor and publisher whether they're online or offline? I'm looking at it in terms of the shift in power relations. Particularly with the public relations industry. It sort of seems to - well, in my experience as someone who works on an issue such as East Timor, I find that there's a lot of black propaganda from the Indonesian government which gets on the internet ... , and people who want to counter that can spend their whole time trying to discount it as black propaganda, you know, which is coming out from government sources.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>O'Loughlin </B><BR>
Well, that's one of the problems with internet: you can't control what's on it and who puts what on it. But whether a big company like BHP and Ok Tedi, whatever they put out it still gets  down to the same question in the end. It's going to come to an editor of Reuters or AP or the Sydney Morning Herald and they're going to say 'This sounds like a lot of BHP propaganda to me,' and throw it in the bin. Which is where it should go. They've got the ability to take it anywhere else they like except to buy it into a newspaper, or into a reputable news service. And I don't think they've got any more power than they ever had.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Answer</B><BR> 
I want to back Peter on that because I know what you're talking about. We do get an awful lot of stuff coming over faxes and various forms, through the internet and so on, but nevertheless the same old journalistic skills and qualities are used. You just sift it through and then you try to put out the balanced story: this is what we're looking at. The fact we get more in actual fact, more from a personal level, tends to turn me off a bit. An awful lot of the stuff that is pumped out by these PR companies does end up in the bin. There's just too much of it. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>End of question session.</B>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
