<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Un-Western Perspectives on News</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Un-Western Perspectives on News </FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B><FONT SIZE="+1">Section Five</FONT></B>
<br><IMG vspace=8 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Balanced reporting gives those who have power and wealth an unfair advantage, it is biased against change and ignores the fact that impartiality can also mean taking sides. To sum it all up, objectivity is highly subjective.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
This debate has relevance in Asia, since it is here that nearly half the world's population lives. How Asians live, how they prosper, the numbers of them that will remain poor will determine global environmental trends in the next century. And how is media going to cover environment and development in this region so that it can have an impact on lifestyle and policy? 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Asia is not one continent, it is at least three. A fluke of history led early empire builders in Europe to classify Asia ("everything east of the Ottomans") as one monolithic mass. Marking Asia off as one continent has become even more absurd with the phenomenal growth of East Asia's tiger economies in the past decades, the oil-fed affluence of the Gulf states, Australia's economic and cultural integration with Pacific Asia and the impoverishment of the South Asian subcontinent. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Africa may get more publicity for its famines and grinding poverty and pictures of babies with bloated bellies, but South Asia has three times more truly destitute people: 600 million of them. A shocking half of all under-five children in South Asia are underweight. In comparison, only one in every three in sub- Saharan African children are underweight, according to a 1996 UNICEF survey. The disparities within Asia now resemble the gaps between sub-Saharan Africa and Europe.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It is clear that environmental threats in the Asia-Pacific stem from both poverty and prosperity. More than half the world's population lives here, and they are forced to burn forests or blast corals just to survive from day to day. In the dynamic Asia of the NICs, per capita incomes are now approaching First World levels. But this affluence has often been attained at a high environmental cost to themselves and to poorer neighbours. If China's Guangdong province with its population of 70 million [CHECK] was a separate country, it would be the fastest growing national economy on earth. Rising affluence in the coastal regions of southern China is creating new demands on natural resources and consumer goods. Tigers and rhinos in sanctuaries of the South Asian sub-continent are threatened by demands of traditional medicine, swallows nests from caves in Borneo are ending up in Guangzhou's restaurants, while sharks in the Bay of Bengal are hunted for their precious fins. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Environmental awareness has grown in Japan, Taiwan and Hong Kong but it is not spreading fast enough to keep pace with Asia's rising affluence. The growth model of East Asia is fashioned by the same wasteful extravagance that the West has now learnt is not sustainable. As its huge population gets richer and consumes more, Asia today has become the locomotive for global growth. It would be much cheaper for Asian countries in the long term to learn from the North's mistakes and invest now on sustainable policies and new environment-friendly technologies. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Maurice Strong, who sheperded the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992 on behalf of the United Nations, says: "The battle to save our planet through sustainable development will be won or lost in Asia. It is inconceivable that there could be an effective global transition to sustainable development unless Asia develops sustainably.Asians make up more than half the world's population. How Asians live, how they prosper, how many of them will remain poor, will determine global environmental trends in the next century. The challenge for the Asian media is to cover environment and development with intelligence and integrity so that coverage makes an impact on lifestyle and policy.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
It is possible, for Western journalists or for Asian journalists trained in Western news values, to strike the cultural balance and to find the proper niche in society. And they do not need a label to describe themselves: eastern or western, "Asian values" or Anglo-Saxon ones. In the end it is just a question of professionalism, commitment and a conscience.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Note: Parts of the talk are adapted from the speaker's forthcoming book 'Dateline Earth: Journalism As If the Planet Mattered'
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Kunda Dixit can be contacted at:<br>
Inter Press Service Asia-Pacific<br>
ipsasia@webquest.com<br>
http://www.ips.org<br>
Tel. (632) 635-3421<br>
Fax. (632) 635-3660<br>
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
