<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+2">Freedom of Expression and the End of Colonialism</FONT></B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=2 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<FONT SIZE="+1">Section Five</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<B>Self-Censorship in the Media</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>To reiterate, it is time for us to uphold press freedom. However, there are problems within the media industry itself.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>According to a survey co-sponsored by the HKJA and conducted among journalists in early 1995, 90 percent of respondents believed there was self-censorship in the industry, and one third admitted that they themselves had exercised self-censorship.
 They also indicated that greater "care" would be taken in dealing with criticism about China, than that directed against the Hong Kong government.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>While the clandestine nature of self-censorship means that it is difficult to pin down actual examples, there has at the same time been little evidence to suggest that the situation has improved. Television documentaries vilified by the Chinese government have been bought and then never broadcast, popular but critical TV programs have been axed, and critical newspaper columns and cartoons suddenly dropped.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>There are many reasons for self-censorship. Proprietors might wish to maintain good relations with the Chinese government to ensure post-1997 survival and a stake in the huge China market. Front-line journalists may exercise self-censorship to maintain a harmonious relationship with their contacts.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br><B>The Future</B>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>The future of press freedom depends on proprietors, news executives and of course front-line journalists. I hope we can all treasure the freedoms we now enjoy and fight for those freedoms after the handover. However, there are some factors which are beyond our control. The most significant factor is the political situation in China. Given the close relations between China and Hong Kong, Beijing is unlikely to allow Hong Kong a free hand if the political situation on the mainland becomes more tense. The media tends to become the first casualty in any such situation.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Despite this gloomy picture, there are some rays of light. One is China's open-door policy. When China opens up, and there is no sign that this will change, it has to consider international reaction to its policies. The other is the way the Chinese media is changing. After much interaction with the Hong Kong media, journalists in China have become more energetic about seeking news. We hope these changes will help ease the minds of Chinese leaders.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Another factor is how Hong Kong politicians, and in particular the chief executive, strike a balance between maintaining good relations with the Chinese government and upholding Hong Kong's autonomy and its way of life.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>Support from Hong Kong people and international circles is also important.
 Overall, prospects for press freedom in Hong Kong are not totally gloomy. The most important thing is not to give up. I do not want to see Hong Kong change from a colony under British rule to a Chinese colony. We deserve better than that. We wish to have our promised autonomy - which includes media autonomy - while remaining part of China.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
