<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reporting Business in South-East Asia</TITLE>
<X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=40 BOTTOM=454 LEFT=12 RIGHT=546>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#04043C" LINK="#090883" VLINK="#090883" ALINK="#090883"
BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif">

<!--Begin Level 1 Table-->
<P><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=510>
<TR>
<!--Begin Index Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=100>
<br><IMG vspace=74 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<P ALIGN=RIGHT>
<B><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="#FFB21E">
<A HREF="../index.html">Homepage</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../intro.html">Introduction</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../program.html">Program</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="paperindex.html">Papers</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../panels/panelindex.html">Panels</A><br><IMG vspace=1 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../bios/biosindex.html">Speakers</A><br><IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../IMC/about.html">The International<BR>
Media Centre</A><BR>
<IMG vspace=10 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<A HREF="../credit.html">Credits</A></B><BR></FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=10><P></TD>
<!--End Index Table-->

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TD VALIGN=top WIDTH=370>

<!--Begin Heading Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=360 HEIGHT=162>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><A NAME="top"><IMG WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=90 SRC="../images/interbw75.gif"></A></TD>
<TD WIDTH=15></TD>
<TD><IMG WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=145  SRC="../images/logo75.gif"></TD>
<TD></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<!--End Heading Table-->

<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
<IMG height=2 width=365 SRC="../resources/dot_peri.gif"><br>
<IMG vspace=5 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>

<!--Begin Body Table-->
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=1 WIDTH=360>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><P></TD>
<TD>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE="+1">Reporting Business in South-East Asia</B></CENTER>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Section Six</FONT>
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Be they locals or expatriates, journalists who cover business successfully
will need to call on the usual accoutrements of the trade - innate curiosity,
street smarts, a large supply of chutzpah or gall, and a continuing
willingness to be the eternal outsider.  If you want to join the establishment,
you probably should seek out another career.  But they will need something
else - a sound basis of economics, knowledge of how business works and
some financial training.  I'm always surprised by how many business
journalists can't read a balance sheet or don't realize that it's cash flow that 
tells the tale not profits.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
The necessity of this knowledge is reflected in a story told me by an
acquaintance took a quite senior communications job with a large American
retailer only to discover - to her dismay - that the company was in serious
business trouble.  She expressed her unhappiness in a conversation with
her former boss. 
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"Oh yeah, I know," he replied.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"How do you know," she asked. "Even the analysts haven't caught on yet.
Have you been golfing with the CEO."
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"No," came the reply. "I don't even know the man.  But it's clear from the
financial. They're doing it all with smoke and mirrors."
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"Why didn't you warn me," wailed my friend.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
"It wasn't our business and we assumed you could tell."
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
For business journalists, above all, it is important to see through the
financial smoke and not be fooled by false reflections in the mirrors. 
Because no one is going to tell you.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
Another vital requirement of a business audience is a sense of context.  Too
often, we journalists write only about how companies or entrepreneurs from
our own country are doing abroad.  But that may distort the picture.  If
Australian or American companies are doing poorly in the Chinese widget
market, for example, but their Japanese and Europeans counterparts are
making out like gangbusters, then the latter information should be included
in the story. Why? Because those competitors must be doing something
right. If so, it is vital or the Australian or American readers or viewers to
know what and how and why.  Parochialism is a dead end.
<br><IMG vspace=3 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br>
One final remark on the emerging globalism of journalism of all types. Just
before leaving New York, I caught an item on the Bloomberg television
channel.  The reporter, who possessed a distinct Australian accent, was
reporting on the visit of Queen Elizabeth II to Thailand.  Film rolled of the
British queen talking to the Thai king.  The reporter observed that it is illegal
to criticize the monarch in Thailand and remarked that Queen Elizabeth
surely must wish she enjoyed the same protection.   My immediate reaction
was to wonder how long the Thai king would escape such protection as the
outside world invaded his sanctum. Not for much longer, I guessed, not for
much longer.
</TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD WIDTH=20><br><IMG vspace=15 hspace=0 SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><br></TD>
