<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - History</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<CENTER>
<IMG WIDTH=350 ALIGN=CENTRE HEIGHT=218 SRC="../images/mm.title.jpg">
<BR>
<IMG WIDTH=450 ALIGN=CENTRE HEIGHT=50 SRC="../images/banner.history.jpg">
</CENTER>
<BR><BR>

<I>Media Magazine</I> programs have been produced continually since 1980.  One of 2SER's first programs (the station began broadcasting in 1979) it was also the only specialist media program in Australia at that time.  ABC TV's <I>Media Watch</I> and ABC Radio National's <I>Media Report</I> are Johnny-come-lately's to the scene. 
<BR><BR>
Some things have changed significantly from those days.  For its first five and a half yearsthe program was two hours long and one of a number of magazine style programs - for example there was also a Politics Magazine program.  The program was produced by volunteers and was only broadcast in Sydney.  Due to requests from other stations in the sector, in 1986 <I>Media Magazine</I> switched to a one hour all talk format with programs distributed to community radio stations around Australia.  While <I>Media Magazine</I> started distributing the program on cassette to sixteen stations this quickly became a najor drain on resources.  In mid 1987 the distribution was taken over by the National Program Service (NPS) of the then Public Broadcasting Association of Australia.
<BR><BR>
Since then the program has slimmed down to just under half an hour and is now distributed through the Community Radio Satellite service.  The satellite service replaced the cassette distribution system of the NPS in 1993.
<BR><BR>
<I>Media Magazine</I> has from its early days been recognised as a quality, independent program providing much needed analysis of media and communications issues in a form relevant to specialists yet still accessible to the general listener.  <I>Media Magazine</I> has won several awards for its programming, including awards from the PBAA Golden Reel Awards and the Australian HI-FI Awards.  
<BR><BR>
Many producers have been involved in the program - both as volunteers and as paid staff.  Some of these people are still working in community radio while others have gone on to other parts of the media and some to academia.  Some of the early producers include:
<BR><BR>
<UL>
<LI><B>Trevor Thompson</B>
<BR><BR>
Now employed at the ABC, Trevor has been involved in a range of community radio and ABC radio projects and programs.
<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Christina Spurgeon</B>
<BR><BR>
One of the original volunteers, Christina currently lectures and is completing a PhD at the University of Technology, Sydney.  She has worked for a variety of media policy organisations including the Australian Broadcasting Tribunal and the Communications Law Centre.
<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Michelle Brown</B>
<BR><BR>
Another UTS graduate, Michelle worked at 2SER as Talks producer before freelancing for a range of commercial radio staions and the Sydney Morning Herald.  She has worked at the ABC since 1987.
<BR><BR><BR>
</UL>
Other producers over the years have included:
<BR><BR><BR>
<UL>
<LI><B>Wendy Carlisle</B><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.mcs.mq.edu.au/"><B>Rebecca Coyle</B></a> now a lecturer at Macquarie University<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Tim McNamara</B>  now technical producer with SBS Radio<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Louise Spencer</B><BR><BR>
<LI><B>Simon Nicholas</B> now Program Manager at 2SER<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Abby Duruz</B>  now freelance producer, and technical producer at SBS Radio<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Elisia Yeo</B> now Evening Producer at 2SER<BR><BR>
<LI><B>Michael Dwyer</B> current Producer<BR><BR>
</UL>

<BR><BR><BR>





