<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - PGM 15/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 15/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 9/5/96</H2>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td>theme</td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td>theme</td><tr>
<td>Last Words At</td><td>26:46</td><tr>
<td>Total Duration</td><td>28:10</td>
</table>

<BR><BR>
FEATURE PROGRAM ON MEDIA REPORTING OF THE PORT ARTHUR MASSACRE
<BR><BR>


<B>Item One		Overview</B>
<BR><BR>

Given the scale of reporting of the massacre, can comparisons be made between media coverage of this tragedy and other events?  Associate Professor of Media and Communications Studies at Macquarie University - Phillip Bell - argues that media reporting of the massacre shares much in common with reporting of natural disasters…
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well the style of reporting...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...problems of people."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>6:46</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Associate Professor of Media and Communications Studies at Macquarie University - Phillip Bell</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two		The Community Radio Perspective</B>	
<BR><BR>
Community radio is supposed to present an alternative viewpoint to that put by the mainstream media.  This is particularly the case in news and current affairs reporting where the mainstream media is often criticised for taking a narrow or sensationalist approach.  So how did community radio's national news and current affairs service Public Radio News, deal with the massacre? I spoke to Undercurrents Presenter, Glen Bartholomew…

<table>
<td>in</td><td>"I think what a...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...stay right away from."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>4:04</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Undercurrents Presenter/Producer, Glen Bartholomew</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>


<B>Item Three		The Mental Health Angle</B>
<BR><BR>

Early reports from Port Arthur suggested that the alleged killer suffered from a mental health problem.  These reports were misleading and some mental health professionals are worried about the consequences of the negative media reporting in this case.  Bronwyn Scanlan spoke to President NSW Association for Mental Health - Professor Ian Webster....


<table>
<td>in</td><td>"I think that's probably...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...deems people should work."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>1:48</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>President NSW Association for Mental Health - Professor Ian Webster</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>


<B>Item Four		The Australian and Digital Manipulation of Photographs</B>
<BR><BR>

The Australian has admitted to altering a picture of the alleged killer that appeared on its front page on the Wednesday following the massacre.  Michael Dwyer spoke to Editor of The Australian, Malcolm Schmidtke ....

<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Er, what I'd say...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...was an accident."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>2:47</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Director of the Australian Centre for Independent Journalism, Peter Cronau</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR>

<B>Item Five		The Largest Massacre?</B>


As the body count rose, the media was able to call the massacre the largest in Australia and then the world.  But while it was the largest massacre by a lone gunman, Director of the Australian Centre for Independent Journalism, Peter Cronau explains that this was not always the message that came across...

<table>
<td>in</td><td>"The initial report...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...clear reference to it."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>1:26</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Director of the Australian Centre for Independent Journalism, Peter Cronau</td>
 </table>
