<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 22/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 22/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 27/6/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:18</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:28</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<H3>A Program on Journalism and Indonesia ...</H3>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One		Dr George Aditjondro - Exiled Journalist and Academic</B>
<BR><BR>
A conference on the future of East Timor held recently in Sydney brought together many people including activists, academics and journalists.  While many issues were discussed, the media was high on the agenda.  Speakers at the conference included Alan Nairn - an American journalist whose skull was fractured by Indonesian soldiers during the 1991 massacre at the Santa Cruz Cemetery in Dili - and several Indonesian journalists now working in Australia.  One of those is Dr George Aditjondro - an exiled journalist and academic now working at the University of Newcastle.  While in Indonesia he worked for many years as an environmental reporter for the now banned magazine - Tempo.  Dr Aditjondro spoke to Michael Dwyer about his experiences as a journalist in Indonesia ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"When I was a journalist with Tempo ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... is to join Indonesia." </td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>8:28</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Exiled Indonesian journalist and academic - Dr George Aditjondro</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Two		Australian Journalists and Reporting of East Timor</B>
<BR><BR>
Some people - particularly those who support an independent East Timor - have been critical of the Australian media’s coverage of the Indonesian invasion.  Exiled Indonesian journalist and academic Dr George Aditjondro is critical of Australian media coverage from 1975 to this day.  Despite the deaths of Australian journalists in East Timor he says the Australian media has not been sufficiently active  ...
<BR><BR>
NOTE FOR STATIONS REPLAYING PROGRAM IN PARTS - ITEM TWO IS REALLY A BRIDGE BETWEEN ITEMS ONE AND THREE AND MAY NOT BE SUITABLE FOR INDEPENDENT USE.
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Balibo, that notorious town in East Timor  ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... what they were told was the facts by Indonesia." </td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>(including link)  4:52</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>	Exiled Indonesian journalist and academic - Dr George Aditjondro<BR>
		Widow of Greg Shackleton, one of the six journalists killed in East Timor - Shirley Shackleton</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Three		Shirley Shackleton on The Sherman Report </B>
<BR><BR>
Last Thursday the Sherman Report into the deaths of six Australian based journalists was tabled in Federal Parliament.  The report was set up to consider evidence that the journalists were deliberately killed by soldiers under Indonesian command.  Activists including Shirley Shackleton - widow of Greg Shackleton - have long argued that significant evidence has been ignored by successive Australian and Indonesian governments who have been engaged in a cover up.  Shirley Shackleton spoke to Michael Dwyer shortly before the release of the report ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"My first question to him when I took ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... all records should be put out for us to see."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>3:31</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Widow of Greg Shackleton, one of the six journalists killed in East Timor - Shirley Shackleton</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Four	The Alliance of Independent Journalists</B>
<BR><BR>

The Alliance of Independent Journalists was one of many organisations represented at a recent conference on the future  of East Timor.  A representative of the Alliance  - a Indonesian journalist now working in Melbourne - spoke about the alliance and its work in supporting journalists who choose not to work for media controlled or heavily influenced by the government.  He talked to Michael Dwyer about the formation of the alliance and the current situation for independent journalists in Indonesia...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Independent Journalists Alliance was formed ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... what Soeharto said is just lipstick."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>5:58</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>	An anonymous representative of the Indonesian Alliance of Independent Journalist</td>
 </table>

