<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 48/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 48/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 19/12/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>music</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>25:44</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>music</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>30:02</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR><BR>
<Center>
<H3>Documentary
<BR><BR>
Media and Aboriginal Deaths in Custody</H3>
</Center>
<BR><BR>
In 1991 the Royal Commission into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody presented more than 300 recommendations.  Four of those were directed at the media.  In making these four recommendations, the Royal Commission recognised that media representation of indigenous people helps to shape the cultural world in which they live and shape opinions of indigenous and non-indigenous people alike.
<BR><BR>
In summary, the recommendations proposed:

<UL>
<LI>increased training and job opportunities for indigenous people in the media<BR><BR>
<LI>increased funding on indigenous media outlets<BR><BR>
<LI>that journalism schools to incorporate training in regard to indigenous people and issues<BR><BR>
<LI>that codes of practice be developed for covering indigenous affairs<BR><BR>
<LI>a prize or award for indigenous journalism
</UL>
<BR>
Some five years after the Royal Commission handed down its report, the number of indigenous people dying in custody has not significantly changed.  Some have called for a second Royal Commission while others have questioned where the money dedicated to implementing the recommendations has gone.
<BR><BR>
This documentary considers some different approaches which have been used to meet the recommendations about the media.  The program does not set out to judge the relative merits of different organisations - but to explore the strategies used.  Some organisations have created guidelines - others have placed more emphasis on personal contact including cross-cultural awareness camps for journalists.  Some have provided specific indigenous programs, others look to employ indigenous people in every or any role in general programming.  Indigenous media outlets have their own strategies and goals.
<BR><BR>
While many strategies have used, the continuing level of aboriginal deaths in custody is forcing us to ask any of the measures taken so far have been sufficient.  
<BR><BR>
Some of the speakers include:
<BR><BR>
<UL>
<LI>John Harding - a producer with ICAM on SBS TV<BR><BR>
<LI>Anne Babeliuk - news editor with the Daily Telegraph in Sydney<BR><BR>
<LI>Majorie Anderson - ABC<BR><BR>
<LI>Wal Saunders - Manager, Indigenous Branch, Australian Film Commission<BR><BR>
<LI>Dr Michael Meadows - Lecturer in Journalism at Giffith University
</UL>
<BR>
This documentary was produced by Tanja Dreher and Michael Dwyer.
<BR><BR><BR>
<B>Some Links Related to the Program This Week</B>
<BR><BR><BR>
<UL>
<LI><a href="http://www.austlii.edu.au/car/car_rc_deaths.html">Royal Commission on Aboriginal Deaths in Custody</a><BR><BR>Includes the national and state reports, underlying issues reports, and individual death reports.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.austlii.edu.au/car/index.html">Council for Aboriginal Reconcilliation</a><BR><BR>Includes information on the Council plus the Reconcilliation and Social Justice Library.<BR><BR>
