<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<CENTER>
<IMG WIDTH=350 ALIGN=CENTRE HEIGHT=218 SRC="../images/mm.title.jpg">
<BR>
<IMG WIDTH=450 ALIGN=CENTRE HEIGHT=50 SRC="../images/banner.ausmedia.jpg">

<BR>
<BR>
<H3>
LINKS TO OTHER SITES ON MEDIA AND COMMUNICATIONS IN AUSTRALIA</H3>
</CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>

This is by no means a complete listing - if there is a site which you think we should list here - or if any of the links die  - please send <a href=mailto:radio.2ser-fm@uts.edu.au>email</a>.<BR><BR> <BR>
<H3>Government</H3><BR>
<UL>
<LI><a href="http://www.dca.gov.au/">Department of Communications and the Arts</a><BR><BR>
A source of information on current government policy and future development.  Also has a very good listing of media,communications and arts web sites.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.dca.gov.au/whatwedo.html">Department of Communications and the Arts - Media Releases, Reviews, Publications </a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.dca.gov.au/commslab.html">Department of Communications and the Arts - Communications Laboratory</a><BR><BR>
The Communications Laboratory used to have a much broader brief to study new broadcast technologies and to help develop standards. It's role now is primarily an advisory one to the Department of Communications and the Arts on technical issues.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.dot.gov.au/programs/btce/btcehome.htm">Bureau of Transport and Communications Economics</a><BR><BR>
The Bureau of Transport and Communications Economics undertakes
applied economics research relevant to the Australian Government
portfolios of the Department of Transport and Regional Development,
and the Department of Communications and the Arts. <BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.ipac.gov.au/about/info.htm">Information Policy Advisory Committee</a><BR><BR>
IPAC is a primary government advisory body on online information and communications services and technologies.  Unfortunately it is stacked with telecommunications and media industry representatives and has very few members from community, educational or arts organisations.  
<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.agps.gov.au/customer/agd/clrc/homepage.html">Copyright Law Review Committee</a><BR><BR>
Which is, surprsingly enough, conducting a review into the Copyright Act 1968 (Cth).

</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<H3>Government Agencies and Authorities</H3><BR>
<UL>
<LI><a href="http://www.afc.gov.au/">Australian Film Commission</a><BR><BR>
The AFC is a federal statutory authority charged with supporting the Australian film industry through a variety of means including: film funding and development support, marketing, developing film culture, providing advice to the Federal Government.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.sma.gov.au/">Spectrum Management Authority</a><BR><BR>
The SMA is a federal statutory authority responsible for the management of radiocommunications in Australia.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.dca.gov.au/aba/hpcov.htm">Australian Broadcasting Authority</a> <BR><BR>
The ABA is a federal statutory authority responsible for the regulation of the broadcasting industry in Australia.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.austel.gov.au/">Austel</a><BR><BR>
The Australian Telecommunications Authority was
established in July 1989 to supervise the introduction of
competition in the Australian telecommunications industry.
<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.dca.gov.au/nta.html">National Transmission Agency</a><BR><BR>The NTA is responsible for planning, constructing, operating and maintaining the Federal Government's network of broadcasting transmission facilities<BR><BR>
</UL>
<BR>
<H3>Broadcasting</H3><BR>
<UL>
<LI><a href="http://www.dca.gov.au/aba/hpcov.htm">Australian Broadcasting Authority</a> <BR><BR>
The ABA is an independent federal statutory authority responsible for the regulation of the broadcasting industry in Australia.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.dca.gov.au/"nta.html">National Transmission Agency</a><BR><BR>
The NTA is responsible for planning, constructing, operating and maintaining the Federal Government's network of broadcasting transmission facilities<BR><BR><BR>
</UL>
<H3>Non-government research and policy </H3><BR>
<UL>
<LI><a href="http://teloz.latrobe.edu.au/clc/">
Communications Law Centre</a><BR><BR>The CLC is a public interest advocacy centre representing public and community perspectives are in debates about communications law and policy.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://teloz.latrobe.edu.au/circit/">CIRCIT</a><BR><BR>
Centre for International Research on Communications and Information Technologies<BR><BR>
</UL>
<BR>
<H3>Telecommunications</H3><BR>
<UL>
<LI><a href="http://teloz.latrobe.edu.au/">La Trobe Online Media Program Teloz Site</a><BR><BR>Australian social and policy research in the area of telecommunications.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.austel.gov.au/">Austel</a><BR>
<BR>
The Australian Telecommunications Authority was
established in July 1989 to supervise the introduction of
competition in the Australian telecommunications industry.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.sofcom.com.au/TIO/index.html">Telecommunications Industry Ombudsman</a><BR><BR>
The last resort you'll reach all too often when dealing with the telecommunications industry.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.merlin.com.au/ctn/">Consumers Telecommunications Network</a><BR><BR>The Consumers Telecommunications Network (CTN) is an Australian national
coalition of consumer and community organisations concerned with
telecommunications issues.<BR><BR><BR>
</UL>
<H3>Film and Television</H3><BR>
<UL>
<LI><a href="http://www.afc.gov.au/">Australian Film Commission</a><BR><BR>
The AFC is a federal statutory authority charged with supporting the Australian film industry through a variety of means including: film funding and development support, marketing, developing film culture, providing advice to the Federal Government.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.cinemedia.net/AFI">Australian Film Institute</a><BR><BR>The AFI is Australia's national film culture
organisation, promoting knowledge, appreciation and enjoyment of the art of Australian film in particular.<BR><BR>
<LI><a href="http://www.ozemail.com.au/~sinsite/">Sydney Intermedia Network</a><BR><BR>...providing services and advocacy for the creative use of film, video, sound and all electronic media.<BR><BR>
