<TITLE>Media Magazine - Community Media in Australia</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<CENTER>
<IMG WIDTH=350 ALIGN=CENTRE HEIGHT=218 SRC="../images/mm.title.jpg">
<BR>
<IMG WIDTH=450 ALIGN=CENTRE HEIGHT=50 SRC="../images/banner.commedia.jpg">
</CENTER>

<BR>
<BR>
<H3>The place to look for Australian community media links, discussions, and perspectives.   This is a growing and changing page - make it a bookmark.</H3>
<BR><BR>
<H3>Go to links for</H3>
<BR><UL>
<LI><a href="#cbaa">Community Broadcasting Association of Australia</a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="#cbf">Community Broadcasting Foundation</a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="#gov">Current Inquiries and Government Policy</a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="#ctv">Community Television in Australia</a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="#cr">Community Radio in Australia</a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="#history">Other online accounts of the history of the sector</a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="#online">Online discussion about community broadcasting in Australia</a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="#global">Global Community Media Resources</a><BR><BR>
<LI><a href="#books">Books and articles on community media</a>
</UL>
<BR><BR>

<H3>A Brief Introduction to Community Broadcasting in Australia...</H3>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=3>(Sources used in compiling this introduction are listed below).</FONT></B>
<BR>
<BR>
The development of community media in Australia began in the early 1970's with the emergence of public radio.   While radio has been the dominant form of community media in Australia, the 1990's has seen the development of trial community television services and some forays into online services.
<BR>
<BR>
While aspects of the early history of the sector is contested ground, it is generally held to have begun in the early-mid 1970's with 5UV recognised as the first station.  5UV began 'broadcasting' in 1972 although its frequency was just off the AM band.  The station was in fact licensed under the Wireless and Telegraphy Act and not the then Television and Radio Act.  Although 5UV is held to be the first such station it is in fact predated by 2UV - a similarly licensed station at the University of New South Wales which had first operated in 1961.  
<BR>
<BR>
The emergence of community broadcasting had been hamstrung by the acceptance of the frequency scarcity mantra.  At this stage Australia only had AM broadcasting and FM was seeing strong resistance from governments, existing broadcasters, and the Australian Broadcasting Control Board.  At one stage it seemed FM would be introduced, but on the UHF band rather than the VHF band as it is evrywhere else in the world.  This view did not prevail in the end.  The MacLean Report cut through most of the trumped up resistance to FM and paved the way for its introduction into Australia.

 In 1974 a conference sponsored by the Commonwealth Department of Media brought together interested parties in the development of the sector and a meeting following the conference established the Public Broadcasting Association of Australia.  The dominant interested parties were educational institutions and potential fine music broadcasters.  Out of the conference came a recommendation to start community broadcasting in Australia - although at this stage it was quite a conservative bunch of people and organisations involved.   This conservatism later led several stations including 4ZZZ and 3CR to withdraw from the PBAA to start up the Alternative Radio Federation.  Most of these stations have now returned to the current version of the PBAA.
<BR>
<BR>
Following the decision to introduce FM broadcasting in Australia and community stations were the first to gain FM licenses.  This occured in 1975 when licenses were issued to 2MBS in Sydney and an AM license awarded to 5UV.  A major problem was that there was no official way to license community broadcasters under existing legislation.  Between 1975 and 1976 Australian federal politics was in turmoil -  the Whitlam Labour Government was dismissed by the Governor General and a caretaker Liberal  Government led by Malcom Fraser was given power.  The licensing of community broadcasters got caught up in this turmoil and a number of different stations were licensed by different Ministers in different ways.  The Minister for the Media for most of the Whitlam Government was McLelland who while  reasonably supportive of community broadcasting was not very active in making it happen.  In the dying days of the Whitlam Government a new Minister was appointed - Dr Moss Cass.  Toward the very end of the government he organised a licensing procedure for the the co-called 'Cass Dozen' of stations to be owned by educational organisations.  Around the same time two stations - one in Sydney(2CT) and one in Melbourne (3CR) were licensed as commercial stations not allowed to run advertising.  All in all it seems to have been a confusing period.  An interesting account of these times can be found in an article written by <a href="#thornley">Phoebe Thornley.</a>
<BR>
<BR>
In any case community broadcasting survived and even flourished under the Fraser Government due in no small part to the support received from Tony Staley - the Minister for Communications in the latter years of the Government.  The sector continued to grow through the 1980's  - a relative period of calm before a stormy period at the turn of the decade.  It was revealed that the PBAA - the sector peak body - was bankrupt.  Out of the wreckage was born a new organisation - to become known as the Community Broadcasting Association of Australia.
<BR>
<BR>
That organisation is still the peak body for the sector.  While most radio and television stations fall under the umbrella of the CBAA, several smaller organisations exist to represent stations of particular kinds.  These include the National Indigenous Media Association of Australia (NIMAA), the National Ethnic and Multicultural Broadcasting Council (NEMBC), the Australian Council of Radio for the Print Handicapped (ACRPH), and the Australian Christian Broadcasters (ACB).  Other organsations and forums of importance include the Community Broadcasting Foundation (CBF) - a body charged with policy discussion and distribution of government funding to the sector, and the National Community Media Council (NCMC) - a forum attended by the different community representative bodies including those mentioned above.
<BR>
<BR>
Stations within the sector are now licensed through the Broadcasting Services Act (1992) - an act administered by the Australian Broadcasting Authority.  As part of the requirements of the BSA the sector has developed codes of practice which form part of the license conditions of all community stations.  The radio sector has grown in several phases and is now made up of more than 130 licensed stations and around 80 aspirant stations hoping to gain licenses.  The Broadcasting Services Act brought several other changes - including a name change from public broadcasting to community broadcasting and the opportunity to develop community television.  

Community Television has been operating in Australia on a test basis since 1992.  Across Australia there is one television channel which has not (in most cases) been allocated to a commercial or national service.  This channel - the so called 'sixth channel' - has been allocated to community television trials through section 215 of the Broadcasting Services Act.  The Act will allow this to continue until mid 1997 when the channel will be awarded to a permanent user.  This still could be community television although there are competitors for the channel.  <a href="#ctv">The Australian Broadcasting Authority is conducting a review</a> of the best permanent use of the channel and will report to the government by late February.  In the meantime test licenses (actually open narrowcast licenses) have been awarded in the following areas: Adelaide, Perth/Mandurah, Sydney, Brisbane, Melbourne, Hobart, Lismore and Bendigo.  
<BR>
<BR>
The sector is also becoming involved in online services.  Twelve radio stations from the sector were involved in the recent Community Information Network project.  In the 1996 Federal Budget the government provided funding for two projects involving the sector in online services: the Community Access Network (CAN) and the Community Broadcasting Database.  You can read more about these projects <a href="#cbf">here.</a>
There has also been a move afoot to change the name of the Community Broadcasting Association of Australia to the Community Media Association of Australia.  At the same times moves are also being made to change membership critieria for the sector to allow television members full rights.  In the longer term these changes may see the CMAA also representing some non-broadcast community media organisations.  However both of these measures are very controversial.  
<BR><BR>
So that's where we are in 1996.   This has been a very barebones outline of the development of the sector - resources for further reading are included within this page.<BR><BR><BR>
