<head><title>Freelancers' efforts win recognition</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Freelancers' efforts win recognition</H1>
<p>
<B>Freelance journalists often live life hard - trying to guess the interests of
different media outlets and needing to satisfy the whim of demanding editors,
usually for slim payments not reflecting the effort involved. But a special
award for freelancers helps give some recognition to those efforts. Peter
Cronau reports.</B>
<hr>
<p>
For the first time, the George Munster Award for Freelance Journalism has been
won by two journalists. The 1994 award has been shared by John Birmingham andMatthew Ricketson.<p>
John Birmingham's article, titled "Exit Wounds", appeared in Juice magazine in
November 1993. It described the lives of young Vietnamese in Cabramatta in
Sydney, and asked whether youth gangs really exist or are the product of media
hype.<p>
Matthew Ricketson's article, titled "A Lone Wolf", appeared in the December 11,
1993 issue of The Australian Magazine. The story provided a profile of
controversial right-wing Professor Geoffrey Blainey.<p>
The 1994 awards were announced to a gathering of journalists, friends and
colleagues of the late George Munster in December at the University of
Technology, Sydney. Media writer and winner of the inaugural Munster Award, Liz Fell, presented the $1,000 award which will be shared.<p>
The annual award, administered by the Australian Centre for Independent
Journalism, is open to journalists in either radio or print. It is awarded for
journalism which in the opinion of the judges is characterised by liveliness,
accuracy, independence, integrity and elegance of expression.<p>
The call for nominations for the award is advertised nationally after July each
year, and interested freelancers can get details and entry forms from the ACIJ
at that time. Entries can be either for a series of articles or radio programs,
or for a single outstanding article or program. "People involved in critical
investigative journalism should apply for this award," says a spokesperson for
the trustees of the award.<p>
The award came about 10 years ago when a group of George Munster's friends
decided to commemorate both his life and the outstanding contribution he made
to journalism by instituting an annual award for freelance journalism.<p>
George helped found the independent fortnightly magazine Nation in 1958, which
later merged into the Nation Review in 1972. In its time, Nation had set the
standard for a new generation of journalists to attempt to achieve.<p>
George later became an editor with publishers Angus and Robertson, where he
commissioned some of what have been described as "the most interesting
political books to be published in this country".<p>
In 1981 George reverted to writing, not within the structures of a big
publication but as a freelancer, working as a journalist and writer in both
print and radio. George Munster died in 1984 and his book, Rupert Murdoch: A
Paper Prince was published in 1986 by Viking Penguin Australia.<p>
After his death a tribute in the National Times stated, "George's contribution
to journalism in Australia, his life-long pursuit of the truth, his rejection
of cant in all its forms, his encouragement of other writers, his championing
of civil liberties, and his mastery of the art of intelligent gossip, will
leave a great gap in Australian life and letters."<p>
The award seems a fitting tribute to the man and his work.<p>
<hr>
<p>
<B><CENTER>Previous winners of the</CENTER> 
<CENTER>George Munster Award for Freelance Journalism</CENTER></B>
<PRE></PRE>
