<head><title>Framing the forests debate</title></head>
<H1>Framing the forests debate</H1>
<p>
<b>The battle for the forests of Australia is not only taking place in the logging camps and conservation zones. The press release and the media conference are also battle grounds. Sarah Ford reports.</b><p>
<p>
<FONT SIZE=5>W</FONT>hen seasoned environment reporter, Alan Tate, put a news story to air last August on ABC TV, he was prepared for the repercussions. It came as no surprise to him when the Forest Products Association (FPA) issued a press release stating that he was trying to destroy the timber industry.
<P>
His story on the release of internal documents that showed intensive logging practices had caused severe soil erosion in NSW's south-east forests would inevitably fuel the "forest war" between conservationist and industry groups.
<p>
What his report couldn't reveal was the behind-the-scenes battle that occurred while Tate was researching the story. He was pursued by both sides of the logging debate. One south-east conservation group even threatened him over the phone to treat the story the way they wanted it treated or they would spill the story to other media.
<p>
This may be one of the more extreme examples of how serious the situation has become in the fight for the forests. However, it is not an isolated case. Both sides are battling to win the hearts and minds of the media. Their number one target, the environment reporter, has become skilful in identifying and assessing their strategies.
<p>
While conservationists accuse the forest industry of emotionalism and vice versa, neither deny their use of emotions to gain coverage. The more emotive the issue, the better.
<p>
NSW Campaign Co-ordinator for The Wilderness Society, Tom McLoughlin, believes that a good story requires "emotional buttons pushed, like an Aboriginal or koala angle, which are very powerful symbols in their own right but also have a fashion about them".
<p>
What McLoughlin calls images of "terrible looking destruction shots" or "totem symbols" such as endangered koalas, seem to be central to the conservationists' campaign. The Daily Telegraph Mirror's environment reporter, Simon Benson,
believes this has given the conservationists the edge in the media war.<p>
In October the National Association of Forest Industries (NAFI) launched a $2
million advertising campaign to "confirm people's traditional love of wood
products". Of course, on the same day conservation groups announced that their
united forest campaign would intensify.<p>
NAFI is not shy about its motives. Its press release heralded, "The new
advertisements are highly emotive and feature a little girl's ultimate joy at
seeing her grandfather restore an old wooden rocking horse". According to
NAFI's media manager, Peter Russell, they intend to pursue this tactic that he
believes has guaranteed the conservationists "a good run with the media".<p>
Their previous campaign consisted of a classroom scene where children were
informed by their teacher about "forest facts". Russell thinks that using
children increases the emotional value.<p>
The Sydney Morning Herald's science and environment editor, Bob Beale, detests
the classroom scenario which he claims exploits two concepts; the child's
innocence, and parental concern for their children's future. <p>
He is equally critical of conservationists' exploitation of the rainforest
logging issue due to its emotive appeal. Meanwhile the not-so-lush forests west
of the Great Dividing Range are being cleared "without a squeak from the
greens".<p>
The recent battle over the logging of Wild Cattle Creek in north-east NSW
highlights this point. It received wide media coverage and is identified by the
North-East Forest Alliance as the largest stand of tall, wet, old growth forest
in the Dorrigo Plateau.<p>
NAFI's attempts to present the "forest facts" in their classroom commercials
have failed to impress Peter Jacklyn of Radio National's Earth Beat program. He
says the commercial grossly oversimplifies the situation with black and white
answers which are not true.<p>
"NAFI set themselves up as saying, `Look, it's all very complicated but this is
what's going on'."<p>
So, what indeed is going on in the forests? According to Jacklyn the impact of
logging on the environment is still a "massive unknown" that requires further
scientific research before the facts are determined. Ever since the logging of
native forests became an issue, both sides of the debate have espoused their
own interpretation of the "facts".<p>
When dealing with the media the scientific complexity of the debate is useful
in more ways than one.<p>
Alan Tate explains one of the industry's tactics to gain favourable media
coverage is to select journalists that are sympathetic or pliable and then use
science to confuse the issues that it presents to the journalist. This
technique may not be effective with the metropolitan media but he claims it is
successful particularly, and importantly, in the rural media where the
communities that are directly effected by the issues live.<p>
Some of the rural press printed the FPA's press release that attacked Tate.
FPA's NSW Executive Director, Colin Dorber, describes his relationship with the
rural media as "excellent". He says they publish almost everything he puts out
and he can depend on at least 12 interviews on country radio if he sends a
press release.<p>
The rural media also prints press releases issued by State Forests, the NSW
government body responsible for the seemingly contradictory tasks of both
supplying timber to the industry and conserving the state's forests.<p>
Their Corporate Affairs Manager, Teresa Mannix, says she uses the scientific
complexity of logging to minimise unfavourable media coverage. She says that
scientific detail is helpful in making a negative story seem as boring as
possible, particularly if it has the potential to receive metropolitan
coverage.<p>
"If you go into a lot of technical detail it just seems too hard. The story
just seems too difficult."<p>
The staff in the State Forests corporate affairs team boasts a list of
impressive credentials. Mannix, herself, won a Walkley award in her 10-year
journalism career. Add to this two other journalists, one a previous chief of
staff at the Daily Telegraph Mirror and the other a news director on commercial
radio with experience in TV production.<p>
Their expertise is matched by NAFI's Peter Russell whose achievements include
news presenter on Canberra's Capital TV, deputy manager of public relations for
the Department of Industrial Relations, and the director of public relations
with the Commonwealth Department of Primary Industries and Energy.<p>
Such is the expertise required to control a thriving PR machine - a machine
thats exponential growth in the past five years has led one conservationist to
despair, "We've bred a monster".<p>
According to the executive officer of the Nature Conservation Council, Sid
Walker, this has been the one real success of the national forest protection
campaign. He believes that this PR phenomena has managed to undermine the
conservationists media campaign.<p>
In the hands of Russell, the forest industry's sophistication in dealing with
the logging issue is set to escalate along with the continuing injection of
millions of dollars. As the combat for coverage intensifies, PR power is
crucial to both sides.<p>
The NSW branch of the Wilderness Society meets regularly with journalists to
discuss their campaign issues. Tom McLoughlin explains that meeting in a social
context imprints in the journalists' mind that if he needs information these
are the people to talk to. "It's in the realm of a PR firm, I guess."<p>
The North-East Forest Alliance is increasingly using its own professional
camera crews to take footage of protests or arrests. Its director, John
Corkill, describes this as "direct market footage" which is supplied to the
media with a vision fee.<p>
Lobbying journalists via personal visits, letters, organised lunches and
offering exclusive stories are mutual tactics. Of these, exclusives top the
list of media-grabbing methods.<p>
The Sydney Morning Herald's Bob Beale describes how they work. If State Forests
knows that conservation groups are particularly concerned about an endangered
species it offers a journalist an exclusive with its top scientist who will
give information favourable to their cause The bonuses are two-fold. Coverage
of that organisation's perspective is guaranteed and the story is given
prominence because it is exclusive to that outlet.<p>
Paying for journalists to "go bush" and inspect a logging site is practised by
both State Forests and NAFI. In May last year State Forests held a "wildlife
school" in south-east NSW to teach loggers about the forests' inhabitants. In a
May 30 article, the Daily Telegraph Mirror's Frank Zeller wrote that he was
invited due to the government agency's eagerness "to dispel the perception that
loggers are environmental vandals".<p>
According to the article, State Forests seems to have accomplished this
mission. "[The loggers] could have passed for a bunch of new age-men bonding in
the wilderness had it not been for the hard hats they were wearing."<p>
Invitations to attend these funded trips don't always succeed. ABC Radio's
environment reporter, Nonee Walsh, sees no value in accepting such an
invitation because she claims it is naturally going to be a display of only
their best logging operations.<p>
Conservation groups lack financial resources to attract the media in a similar
fashion. They attempt to gain free publicity by inundating journalists with
press releases updating them on the latest "logging horrors", protests and
hunger strikes.<p>
Walsh says that protests, the conservationists' trademark tactic, are
considered mundane by the media.<p>
"It's kind of like a joke we have around here about traffic accident police
reporting: Just change the name, place and how many injuries there are. It's a
format where you can just fill in the blanks."<p>
Corkill agrees that protests are alienating to the metropolitan media who see
them as semi-theatrical and predictable. <p>
Equally predictable is the forest industry's presentation of the logging issue
as "jobs versus forests". Walsh says a typical argument is that logging is
vital to the economy of a town, despite it only employing 40 people and all the
profits going to the industry companies. <p>
"Their major fall down is that they try `con jobs' too often," she says. Walsh
claims to have a better relationship with conservation groups because she
trusts them more. She is backed by Peter Jacklyn who claims that when
discussing the complex scientific arguments he considers conservationists'
views to be closer to his appreciation of the situation.<p>
According to Colin Dorber, "It's a cultural problem that by instinct,
journalists are not going to trust anyone in business."<p>
After Alan Tate's experience he's not inclined to trust either side. He avows
that there is no industry group tougher than the FPA in their response to
journalists seeking to cover the logging issue. Nor does he ever again want to
deal with the conservation group that expected him to "parrot" their story. On
this occasion, both sides lost the battle.<p>
<hr>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=460><tr><td>
