<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<head><title>Secretly speaking: The ASIS Inquiry transcripts</title></head>

<H1>Secretly speaking: <BR></H1>
<H2>The ASIS Inquiry transcripts</H2>
<HR>

<B>Reportage has recently had a peek at some documents from the Samuels Commission of Inquiry into ASIS. Not that they were secret documents, mind you, sanitised would be a better word for them.</B><p>
<p>
Although we were told originally that the transcripts of testimony by
representatives of the media were due for release in October, their release was
held up until February so that their contents could be "cleared". <p>

Secretary to the Inquiry, Barbara Belcher, said that consideration had been
given to noting on the transcripts where cuts had been made, the magnitude of
the cut, and by whose insistence the cuts were made, but it was decided not to
do so as it would have been too much work.
<p>
The transcripts represent the only material to be released by the Inquiry other
than the slim public report just issued.
<p>
Much of the Inquiry's questioning of the media representatives was on, as
Commissioner Samuels put it, "how one can achieve a balance, an optimum
balance, between the requirements of national security and the public interest
in the free passage and conveyance of information and opinion".
<p>
One aspect under examination was the government's D Notice system for getting
the voluntary agreement by the media not to publish certain information about
ASIS. The Inquiry requested the attendance of several of the country's top
journalists and media representatives.
<p>
The fat packet of "edited" transcripts of the media people who attended the
Inquiry makes for dedicated reading. So in the interests of public debate we
present the edited highlights for your reading pleasure.<p>
As we go to press, legal sanctions on the media's reporting of the activities
of ASIS seem to be only a matter of time if the recommendations of the Samuels
Commission of Inquiry into ASIS are followed. A recommendation was slipped past
the noses of most in the media when the public version of the Final Report was
handed down in early April. <p>
Samuels recommended that the recommendations of the 1991 Gibbs Report be
implemented. The Gibbs Committee which conducted a review of Commonwealth
Criminal Law had concluded that there is an offence where there is publication
by a third party recipient of information in certain specified circumstances.
This means that not only government officers who leak to the media, but also
the journalists who report the information, would be subject to prison terms of
up to seven years.<p>
In our next issue, we will carry a detailed report of this looming threat to
journalists and free expression in Australia.<p>
<B><CITE>Peter Cronau</CITE></B><p>
<p>
<p>
<HR>

<B>Alan Kohler<BR>
Editor of the Age.<p></B>

On the D Notice system:<p>
"We do recognise the need to protect the activities of ASIS and intelligence
services and to protect currently serving members of ASIS. We recognise the
point of the D Notices and the national interest that's involved in that. We
think that is the way to go. ... Just to put it into context of our philosophy
in general, we would regard all truthful publications in the public interest.
As a newspaper our job and our aim really is to publish everything that we can
that's truthful. However, we are bound by a set of limitations, one of which is
defamation, one of which is contempt, and another I'd say is bad taste, another
is statutory restrictions and another is D Notices."<p>
On whether he would seek advice from someone in the Minister's office or from
the D Notice committee to avoid revealing a current ASIS operation and so break
the D Notice:<p>
"I think we would. ... It would depend on who it was. It would depend on the
status of the person concerned."<p>
On Commissioner Samuels' suggestion of a criminal penalty to prevent
publication of a current ASIS agent's name:<p>
"We have voluntarily agreed, and continue to voluntarily agree, not to identify
ASIS agents. So we'd say the only reason then to put that into law would be
that the Government doesn't trust us to keep our word.<p>
"I would urge the commission to take into account the D Notice system and I
would urge the commission to take into account that [it] really has not been
given a fair go and if the media and the government co-operate and resurrect
the D Notice committee then the chances of publication contrary to the D Notice
would be reduced significantly. Therefore I think before we jump to the
conclusion that we should have any criminal type sanctions, as in the ASIO Act
or the Crimes Act, we really should give the D Notice system in Australia a
fair go."<p>
On what level of checking of a journalist's story is practicable:<p>
"I think there would be problems if we were ringing up people that the reporter
had rung to check on the reporter. I think that there'd be grave difficulties
in that. ...<p>
"I think that we employ journalists because they are trustworthy. Any
journalist that needs to have that kind of checking up on facts shouldn't be on
the paper. Before I instituted a system like that in respect of any particular
journalist, where we had to ring up and check their sources, I'd sack them."<p>
<p>
<P>
<HR>

<B>Michelle Grattan<BR>
Then-editor of the Canberra Times<p></B>
<p>
On whether she considers the possible damage to foreign relations with a
country, which can follow from disclosure that an ASIS operation is going on in
that country:<p>
"It is a matter of argument in many cases whether foreign relations have been
damaged.<p>
"Also governments are, in the normal course of events, quite likely to say,
"All this will damage foreign relations", when really the government that is at
the other end is rather more robust. Or that is a convenient argument for a
government under fire about a particular matter that has come out that is
embarrassing to it to run.<p>
"The final point I would make about this is that the conduct of good foreign
relations is a matter for government. It is not necessarily a matter for the
media which is primarily about pursuing information and interpreting and
analysing information for the public....It may act as a bit of a curb on
Governments."<p>
On whether she sees a public interest in publishing information about ASIS
"paying a stipend" to a foreign politician for information:<p>
"One consideration is how an organisation operates and we, as Australian
citizens, obviously have a general set of values about how Governments and
Government instrumentalities operate. If we found that Telecom was paying a
local politician to get favours for it, we would say this is outlandish and
outrageous and this would be a huge story. ...<p>
"So therefore you have to say, do those same sort of politico-moral
considerations, if you like, apply to the country's foreign spying service? Now
probably most of us would say "No", but all I am saying is that that has to be
a question that has to be asked by people who are making judgement about a spy
service.<p>
"At some point between the paying of a bribe and the murdering of people we say
enough is enough and, no, the end does not justify the means. It is not
acceptable to us to have a spy service that will do anything anywhere."<p>
On whether she would be inhibited from publishing a story because Foreign
Minister Gareth Evans advised her that it  "will endanger people":<p>
"Well, it might or it might not. It would depend on how important the story
was, the extent to which it was running generally, whether I guess, too, the
person putting the argument had a convincing case. ...<p>
"I think you would want to be convinced in your own mind that this was a
genuine argument and that it was not an argument that was just based on the
politics of the situation or whatever. ...<p>
"One could equally from the point of logic say that the failure to print the
truth is continuing to endanger people that are already endangered."<p>
On agreeing she would seek the advice of an ASIS media liaison officer should
one be appointed, expressing a note of caution:<p>
"It seems to me that over many years the people dealing with the media from the
Foreign Affairs Department have had ... a lot of influence in how the media saw
certain aspects of foreign policy because they were very skilled and credible
people."<p>
On why she did not insist that one of her reporters attend the Inquiry after he
declined the Inquiry's request to attend [Several reporters had declined to
attend for fear the Inquiry was attempting to discover their sources for
stories]:<p>
"We have touched a number of times on sources. Obviously sources are a
sensitive matter. There have been some statements that the commission was not
interested in pursuing sources. [But] there had been some questions which
perhaps suggested that some of the discussion was interested in sources."<p>
On what she sees as the effective operation of the present D Notice system:<p>
"It is important for the process of government, the process of good government
and good administration, that there be some public light shed on matters when
they go wrong. Despite the temporary embarrassments to governments - and
governments come and go - despite that, it is better in the long run for good
public administration, for good government and for proper conduct of the
country that the media be able to report relatively freely, that the restraints
that they accept in this area are voluntary restraints."<p>
On the proposal to extend the D Notice system to prevent publishing stories on
the past operations of ASIS:<p>
"If you go to covering the disclosure of past operations ... you are finding a
way to cover up things that often will be in the national interest to
disclose."<p>
<p>
<HR>

<B>Jack Waterford<BR>
Then-deputy editor Canberra Times<p></B>
<p>
On the Inquiry's denial it was looking for journalists' sources, following its
request to see a Canberra Times journalist's original notes of an ASIS story:<p>
"The subpoena to produce documents clearly indicated a search for sources. It
asked for notebooks and other such materials. ...In fact it seemed to me that a
clear focus of the thing was designed to, by asking for original note material
and various things like that, to seek out sources. ... It is a largely
hypothetical question, sir, because there are in fact no notes of original
materials that any longer exist or have existed for any time."<p>
On ASIS briefing editors:<p>
"Normally when people do get appointed to senior positions, it is not at all
unusual for officials from government departments to ring up and offer to have
a chat about this, that, usually to lobby their agency's point of view or
something like that."<p>
<p>
<HR>
<B>Peter Harvey<BR>
News director for the Nine Network's Canberra bureau.<p></B>
<p>
On why his news organisation accepts the voluntary D Notice system:<p>
"Well, first and foremost, I suppose, of course, we are concerned about
national security. Secondly, I believe our philosophy is such that operating on
a voluntary basis is preferable to operating under a system of proscription."<p>
On how he would satisfy himself that disclosure of a past action of ASIS would
not lead to disclosure of current activity, as required by D-Notice 4:<p>
"I would go to Gareth Evans' office and I'd probably go to the
Attorney-General's office. If the issue was of an even graver nature I'd go and
see somebody like Geoff Walsh in Keating's office and say, `We have this
information. This is what we've been told. It's obviously extremely serious.
I'd like to know if it's true, if you can say anything about it'."<p>
On whether he sees any problems in consulting with government on such
stories:<p>
"I can't conceive of how I would have in any given set of circumstances the
knowledge of the issue that the government of the day would have. And of course
all of this assumes that the government is going to tell me the truth, or not
mislead and lie to me, and I accept that by and large that's the case, that I
would not be lied to or misled by ministers on issues of that sort of grave
import that I'm certainly imagining at the moment."<p>
<p>
<HR>

<B>David Hill<BR>
Then-managing director of the ABC<p></B>
<p>
On whether the ABC would consult with the government over programs on security
matters:<p>
"The formal position is, we don't want any further restrictions and we don't
want a mechanism of consultation before programs go to air."<p>
On D Notices versus the public's right to know:<p>
"I think a preference, certainly at the program production level is there are
no D Notices. We've lived with this one and we'd be very cautious and concerned
about any change, because I suspect any change would be wanting to strengthen
the D Notice. ...<p>
"I think the view is that if we had any information of public interest, or
information that the public is interested in, we should publish it unless there
is good reason why not. ...<p>
"I don't think there would be a gratuitous publication if ... we we're
satisfied there was no endangering of life and it was a flow of information I
don't think we'd be broadcasting it for the sake of it. I think that even in
the absence of a D Notice there is some responsibility and some sensitivity.
And it would come down to whether or not it was of news value."<p>
On the UK system of contact points in the security services for the media: <p>
"From my experience the relationship with the BBC and British intelligence
agencies is quite unhealthy, and I would hate to think the ABC ---"<p>
Commissioner Samuels: "You mean it is too close or ---"<p>
Hill: "Too close. Too close. In fact I was intrigued to read in Alastair
Milne's autobiography, called DG for Director General, he said that one of his
achievements was that no longer did as many BBC journalists require security
clearance before being recruited by the BBC."<p>
Samuels: "I do not think that can be said of certain print media?"<p>
Hill: "Or the ABC."<p>
<p>
<HR>

<B>Dennis Grant<BR>
Channel 7 news bureau chief<p></B>
<p>
On the media's relationship with ASIS:<p>
"I suppose the relationship is always going to be prickly between those of us
whose job it is to live in utterly transparent houses and cities, where
everything is open in the outside world, dealing with a culture where
everything is closed to the outside world. <p>
On the D Notice:<p>
"I think this is a very mature voluntary system. Of course there will be
arguments along the way, but to codify it, to draw a legislature, a mandatory
line along what governments believe their citizens should see and hear and
know, I think this is a regressive step."<p>
On checking a sensitive story with the Minister for Foreign Affairs:<p>
"Well I have to say to you that in my 12 years in the Press Gallery, a good way
to kill off a story is to ask the Minister's office for comment. It may be a
benign story, something that is actually in their interest to have out, some
worthy piece of information. But in my experience many of those who work in the
Minister's office are there solely for the preservation of that Minister and
the wider implications and interests of the public are given scant regard."<p>
On media scepticism of intelligence services:<p>
"To be an investigative journalist, by definition, there has got to be
something deep and dark to investigate. I think the culture of Australian
society, but particularly its journalism, in the 70s and 80s, was that of
distrust. I mean I don't think we had a very mature or sensible attitude
towards authority. ... I think we overstated our mistrust and as a consequence
we did a disservice to many of our officials and organisations. I'd like to
think that that is not the case any more. But at the same time, there will
always be a professional suspicion and scepticism that is part of a
journalist's armoury."<p>
<p>
<HR>

<B>Paul Kelly<BR>
Editor-in-chief of the Australian<p></B>
<p>
On the D Notice system possibly being reinvigorated:<p>
"I think it would be correct to say that the media and also the wider community
would think that the national security requirements are less than they used to
be, say, during the period of the Cold War for example, and therefore I think
the media would probably look with more scepticism and more scrutiny at any
reactivation of the D Notice system."<p>
On whether journalists are expected to disclose sources to their editor:<p>
"If I feel I need to know the name of a source from a journalist I will ask.
That's the rule, you know, on which I operate across the board. I mean, if a
story is sufficiently sensitive that I feel I need to know the source, then I
will ask, and I will expect to be told."<p>
On the usefulness of an ASIS Information Officer:<p>
"I guess the question is how credible it would be. I mean, ASIS is a secret
organisation which doesn't want to see anything about its affairs published,
presumably, so the question would be the credibility of such a party in ASIS.
How confident could the media be that such a party in ASIS would be making an
assessment only on the grounds of whether or not publication was going to
damage an ASIS operative or a current operation, as distinct from whether or
not ASIS was going to be embarrassed by such a story being published?<p>
On the possibility of a legislative basis for ASIS, an ASIS Act:<p>
"It seems to me that this is then an invitation to the parliament to meet its
responsibilities in relation to ASIS but the difficulty is that when you look
at the actual operational requirements of ASIS I think a lot of people would
argue that the nature of the organisation is to some extent fundamentally
incompatible with parliament having such a role. So we come back to the central
conundrum again of national security versus the public interest."<p>
<hr>
