<head><title>Chomsky and the fake Age photo</title></head>
<H1>Chomsky and the fake Age photo</H1>
<p>
<p>
<B>The Age faked a photograph of Noam Chomsky to reinforce an article saying he
had been wrong on Cambodia. Peter Cronau reports.</B><p>
<hr>
When Professor Noam Chomsky visited Australia in January he was not surprised
to be criticised by opponents of his world view. But even he was amazed at the
extent to which the Age went in an article published on January 25.<p>
The article by right-wing columnist Robert Manne took a familiar line of attack
on Chomsky, criticising him as a defender of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia in
1977. Chomsky has sent the Age a vigorous response to the article, which has
yet to be published.<p>
Accompanying the article is a photograph of Chomsky ostensibly pondering a
worrisome volume titled Cambodia `77. But the photo is a fake.<p>
The Age had doctored a photo taken more recently of Chomsky reading a totally
different book. That book may well have caused Chomsky some worry - its
original title, "American Public Opinion and US Foreign Policy 1987".<p>
Chomsky says of the Age photo, "It is a fake, constructed to insinuate Manne's
message: that I defended Pol Pot. The integrity of his charges matches that of
the photo."<p>
Comparing it with the original photo, the Age photo has clearly been "computer
enhanced", but it appears with no caption or credit, and to readers the
subterfuge is hidden.<p>
The Age's pictorial editor, Stewart Heddington, doesn't deny that the Age faked
the photo. "The caption was left off by mistake by a sub. There was a
hullaballoo by the photographers. They were up in arms. Because basically it's
lying to the public." <p>
The Age developed a policy on computer manipulation of images late last year to
always include a standard statement acknowledging an image has been altered, he
says. "No picture is being digitally enhanced without going through the editor
or myself. It must have `digitally enhanced'," Heddington says. <p>
Of the omission on the Chomsky photo, he says, "That was just a terrible
mistake. It's the last time it happened."<p>
The question still remains as to whether a caption can satisfy the ethical
questions posed by the alteration of photographs, because clearly, now, photos
can lie.<p>
<hr>
