<html><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<head><title>Reporting on business: A case of market failure</title></head>
<H1>Reporting on business:</H1>
<H2>A case of market failure</H2><p>
<p>
<B>Last year <A HREF="#Brian Toohey">Brian Toohey's</A> new book, Tumbling Dice, received widespread publicity
after its launch. But the one chapter the media ignored was the one on itself.
In this extract, Toohey examines some of the media's claims about our 80s'
entrepreneurs, and finds them wanting.</B>
<hr>
<p>
Cracks have appeared in the dominant approach to business journalism that
prevailed during the 1980s. As the 90s arrived, the media had little option but
to look at some of the wreckage. Although some of the business journalists who
did most to misinform the markets continue to thrive, there is the occasional
introspective piece about the media's role in building up the `aura of
infallibility' surrounding some of the entrepreneurs.<p>
It is by no means clear, however, that the problems of the previous decade
won't recur. In theory, journalists should never find it as highly rewarding as
they did during the 1980s to mislead the markets about the financial strength
of so many of the leading players. <p>
While this was more often the result of gullibility than of any deliberate
policy, profit maximising is supposed to go hand in hand with informing, not
misinforming, markets. But market forces during a boom seem to reward
journalism that only encourages the worst excesses while `underpricing' more
cautionary voices. Customers paying to be told the music will never stop do not
want to hear the voice of scepticism. Editors, with rare exceptions, do not
want to publish `downers' when the market wants `uppers'. <p>
Judged by the criteria of pleasing their proprietors (and attracting the
appropriate financial rewards), business journalists did a good job for much of
the 1980s. But their overall efforts did little by way of contributing to the
goal of fully informed markets which is supposed to lie at the heart of
economic efficiency. <p>
On the contrary, example after example exists of the market for business
journalism failing to perform in a manner even remotely approximating the
neoclassical ideal. As many business journalists were to demonstrate, making
money in media was not the same thing as providing an accurate flow of
information to the wider market place.<p>
It all looked so easy the way the business magazines told it in eighties. There
was none of the nineties' soul searching about the nature of the Australian
identity. The answer was simple. The desirable Australian was the entrepreneur.
Not in the older sense of the entrepreneur as a risk taker developing a new
enterprise  or product, but more as a corporate predator making money from
shuffling paper assets. <p>
There was no limit, it seemed, to what borrowing, brashness and a sycophantic
cover story could achieve. The rewards were something to be savoured in public.
Thorstein Velben's phrase about conspicuous consumption was given new relevance
as millions of dollars of shareholders money were siphoned off by a succession
of deal makers idolised in the media. Lists ranked the winners. They weren't
merely rich like the crusty members of the much derided (and largely illusory)
Melbourne or Adelaide establishments. They were super rich - the symbol of the
new Australia. <p>
The media were not alone in creating these new role models. They were urged on
by Labor leaders such as Bob Hawke, Paul Keating, and Brian Burke, with the
latter displaying a special knack for making friends among the
`four-on-the-floor entrepreneurs'. Auditors, accountants, brokers, and lawyers
broke the rules while the regulatory authorities, even allowing for severe
underfunding, performed poorly. <p>
Perhaps more crucially, the profligacy of the banking sector combined with the
wage restraint exercised by the ACTU to generate the funds needed to fuel the
mad asset boom that eventually triggered the 1990-91 recession.  <p>
But the journalism of the period really set the seal of approval on what was
happening. Nowhere was this more apparent than in the two glossy new magazines
to emerge during the 1980s, BRW (originally Business Review Weekly) and
Australian Business. Their message were reinforced by new personal investment
magazines, new business programmes on television, and the elevation of finance
news to pride of place on the front page of newspapers. <p>
BRW was launched by the Fairfax group in 1981 as a `consumer benefit business
magazine' with the slogan `news you can use'. The underlying marketing
philosophy was to put a favourable gloss on business. In August 1980, Fairfax's
then chief editorial executive, Max Suich, sent a memo to Robert Gottliebsen as
inaugural editor, giving an example of consumer benefit: <p>
When you are doing corporate strategies you should not be an outsider looking
in but an insider telling outsiders how to benefit. On the story on Bond, for
instance, I think it is important to make clear how Bond discovered Santos as a
gold mine and what the nature of his style of finding such corporations is.<p>
There were honourable exceptions, but the overall effect of the business
journalism of the time was to create heroes of some of the most recklessly
incompetent executives ever to control a public company. Often the reporting
style was celebratory, with speculators and paper shufflers being treated as
creators of genuine wealth. <p>
Swindlers and thieves were treated as pop stars in carefully airbrushed photos
on the front covers of the magazines. Nonsensical `corporate strategies' were
reported with reverence while ludicrous claims about long-term debt being the
same as equity were presented as new accounting truths. Corporate crooks were
legitimised, spivs given comfort and respectability, well-dressed drongos
transformed into financial giants. <p>
Time after time, a positive `spin' was put on the outlook for companies on the
verge of collapse. Tributes to the immense guile of various corporate raiders
helped built an decisive aura of invincibility for particular takeover
stratagems.<p>
In short, the media watchdogs did not bark. Shareholders and the public may
have been misled - `Bond: too big to stop now' was a typical headline - but the
magazines were following a marketing strategy that worked at the time in terms
of circulation and advertising revenue. No one, it seemed, wanted to hear about
the hard slog behind designing and manufacturing a better widget. <p>
Instead, the market for new readers lay with stirring tales about tycoons
juggling billions in takeover `plays' featuring greenmailers, white knights,
poison pills, war chests and golden parachutes. The former editorial director
of BRW , Robert Gottliebsen, has acknowledged that, "perhaps more than any
other country in the world, we have personalised business . . . It was the
drama of business, we found, that helped sell magazines" (Independent Monthly,
September, 1989, p 3). He was not unaware of the dangers:<p>
Many (business personalities) have copied the politicians and exploited the
system. The journalists who created the `monster' must be watchful that it
doesn't turn around and bite them. I guess this applies to me more than anyone
else.<p>
When they first appeared at the start of the 1980s, BRW and Australian Business
were more aggressively `pro-business' in their journalistic content than the
rather staid coverage available in the daily papers. While the traditional
business pages could hardly be said to be overly critical, they did not go out
of their way to inject the same aura of glamour, excitement and bullish
euphoria which characterised the new magazines. <p>
As the speculative boom took off, however, the dailies boosted their business
coverage, often shifting the more dramatic stories to the front page. They also
carried their share of reporting which amounted to little more than an
image-building exercise for some of the shakiest entrepreneurs. <p>
A notorious example is the Sydney Morning Herald's front page assurance that
Alan Bond would survive after two of its reporters were flown to Perth on a
Bond jet for a briefing organised by the paper's then editor-in-chief. Shortly
afterwards, Bond went sluicing down the gurgler (Mark Westfield and Peter
Smark, Sydney Morning Herald,  21/10/89). Nevertheless, the SMH , through
journalists such as Colleen Ryan, Anne Lampe and Glen Burge, was usually much
more willing than the new magazines to subject the dominant business figures of
the era to serious scrutiny.<p>
Apart from the new business magazines, a number of personal finance magazines
were launched in the mid-1980s, partly to cater for retirees puzzling over how
to allocate their lump sum superannuation pay-outs among the bewildering array
of new financial products spawned by deregulation. Their tone was also bullish
as editors strove to find some new angle which promised to tell readers how to
extract an extra dollar from their investment portfolio. <p>
Television was not exempt from the excitement generated by the boom. Specialist
new programs were introduced, generally adopting a similarly supportive stance
on their subject matter as the business magazines. Nor was such an approach
confined to the commercial media. Instead of developing its own specialists,
the ABC in 1981 approached Gottliebsen to appear each night on its national TV
news as a paid business commentator. Gottliebsen wrote to Suich urging approval
on the grounds that:<p>
It would be a unique promotion vehicle for the magazine around Australia. . . .
It would be a remarkable opportunity to have BRW known as the source of
business commentary among the very readers who (we) are most likely to find
attractive . . .  The proposed deal stipulates that all promotion carries the
BRW name, plus I would be introduced as the Managing Editor of BRW'.<p>
Not surprisingly, Suich approved the plan. The benefits to ABC viewers were no
so readily apparent. Instead of developing more dispassionate commentators from
among its own staff, the national broadcaster handed over the dominant business
spot in its nightly television news to someone renowned for his breathless
enthusiasm for the paper shuffling entrepreneurs who were to wreck such havoc
on the Australian economy. <p>
Readers of BRW and Australian Business were left with the overwhelming
impression that everything the entrepreneurs touched would turn to gold.
Something of the mood can be gained from the upbeat tone of `write-offs'
introducing many articles. The following examples come from Australian Business
(4/6/1981, 29/5/85, 11/11/87, and 14/3/84) , but similar examples are available
from BRW:<p>
* Bond has cleaned up his image. Gone is the brash aggressive businessman of
the 1970s who nearly lost his company. Instead, there is the cautious, more
thoughtful Bond, a man willing to admit his mistakes and show that he has
learned his financial lessons well.<p>
* He's tough talking, ambitious, ruthless and the eternal optimist. John
Elliott's personal style has moulded a corporate philosophy that has made
Elders IXL a model of success. <p>
* Chris Skase's penchant for baby blue is starting to show up in his groups
balance sheets. All his companies are earners. And he got out of the market
just before it collapsed. <p>
* They're coming rampaging in from the west, and they're scared of no one. A
new breed of hustling entrepreneurs, they grew up in the cut and thrust of WA
but became too big for one state to hold.<p>
One of the strongest themes running through both magazines was that takeovers
were unambiguously good for the nation. Indeed, it was the money made on the
share market from takeover coups (or from `green mail' in aborted raids) that
catapulted many of the raiders onto the Rich Lists. BRW's ebullient approach
was captured by its use of a dinkus proclaiming "The Sport of Takeovers" across
the top of several articles. <p>
Australian Business also ran an annual feature extolling the `Top  Deals of the
Year' in which it praised some of the most wasteful, and ill considered,
transactions of the decade. There was an enthusiastic piece, for example, about
Bond's `sale' of the Sydney Hilton, later exposed as a sham by the ABC's Four
Corners. In 1986 George Herscu received high praise for his disastrous takeover
of Hookers. <p>
Although space was occasionally given to dissenting views, the dominant
attitude was summed up Alan Jury, who managed to combine  stockbroking and
column writing for Australian Business. Jury said that the deployment of
productive resources such as capital and labour must be continually reviewed to
ensure that their efficiency is constantly maximised. "Takeovers do this in a
primal way, with the weak (less efficient) giving way to the strong (more
efficient)."<p>
Jury picked three examples of hot performers from the magazine's annual list of
Top 500 companies that could hardly have been less apposite - all three proving
a disaster for their shareholders as well as detracting from the efficiency
with which capital and capital and labour was employed in Australia (Alan Jury,
Australian Business , 13/5/87):<p>
Bell Resources' rocket ride from outside the top 200 to inside the top 25 in
two years is a graphic illustration . . . Similarly, Bond Corp's acquisition of
Castlemaine Tooheys has provided it with a stable cash flow base from which to
service debt and extract future earnings. Another example is Ariadne's takeover
of Repco Corp. Ariadne's swift dissection of the industrial conglomerate may
appear to have been a classic asset strip, but few would argue that the
combined efficiency of the new parts far exceeds that of the previous whole.<p>
The homage to the new breed of business dynamos reached its peak in the annual
Rich Lists published by both magazines. Genuinely wealthy people such as the
Kings Cross identity, Abe Saffron, never made it to the lists, apparently being
considered a little too lacking in tone to appear in the same company as such
future jail birds as Herscu. <p>
For readers who were interested in buying shares, or in taking advantage of
other opportunities associated with those who made it onto the annual Rich
Lists, the implicit message was that they would be dealing with people of
substance. <p>
Business journalists, of course, were not alone in falling into the trap of
focusing on assets displayed far more prominently than the debts behind them.
Banks made the same mistakes. Nevertheless, some of the errors were quite
spectacular.<p>
Rag merchant Abe Goldberg was said to be worth $600 million, justifying his
place as no. 4 in the Australian Business  Rich List for 1989. According to
bankruptcy proceedings commenced shortly afterwards, he was penniless.
Keating's friend, Warren Anderson, was listed in 1990 as being worth $250
million in Australian Business and $190 million in BRW even though his
creditors were being told at the time that he had no assets in his name and his
total income, as declared to the tax office, was only $30,395. <p>
Australian Business compounded its embarrassment by commenting, "He has been
cautious on gearing and should not hurt too much during a slump". At least BRW
redeemed itself somewhat with a piece a year later pointing to the importance
of political connections in his business style (Ali Cromie, BRW, 27/9/91).<p>
Writing about members of the Rich List who were media proprietors could also
present difficulties. Christopher Skase, as owner of the Channel Seven Network,
started a business program which retained several of the nation's leading
business columnists as well as giving valuable exposure to the publications
they represented. At the time, none commented unfavourably on Skase's business
practices or prospects. <p>
In 1988, Australian Business listed Skase as worth $25 million. The journalist
responsible for the listing, Tony Grant Taylor, says that he came under intense
editorial pressure to bump Skase up the list for the following year. Skase was
duly listed as being worth $70 million in 1989. Apparently, considerable
importance was placed upon the publicity Australian Business gained from its
association with the Skase television network. BRW performed just as poorly,
listing Skase as worth $65 million in 1989. <p>
The problems did not stop with the Rich Lists. Only ten days before Skase went
belly up, exposing his participation in a number of extremely dubious
practices, Australian Business (18/10/89) ran a favourable cover story which
assured readers:<p>
He (Skase) does not do fast rash deals of the kind that ensnared Channel 10 and
Alan Bond in Channel 9. In particular, Skase likes to ensure that he extracts
maximum advantage from the leads and lags in financing his deals.<p>
The Rich Lists did more than merely rank the winners. Accompanying essays
extolled the business strategies and personal qualities that had propelled the
high fliers to the top. BRW's August 1987 Rich List carried an introduction by
Les Carlyon which captured the pervasive ethos of the magazine's approach:<p>
We may have to revise our idea of how wealth is created. We should not always
be looking for `productive investment', for mines in the spinifex or new
factories because, mostly, they are not to be found. Much of the wealth on this
list has come from opportunities and daring, from financial alchemy, from asset
switching and trading, from the rationalisation of existing industry rather
than the creation of new industries. And much of it, it should be noted,  has
come from property development . . . <p>
Once the fortunes in Australia were made from rural acres. Glasshouses have
replaced Clancy's sunlit plains. Now, the fortunes are made from city hotels
and arcades, from suburban shopping centres, from towers which house the
energetic young men of the liberated financial sector . . . <p>
To generalise more than a little, the young entrepreneur is not interested in a
secure weekly salary (windfalls are better and harder to tax). He is not much
interested in manufacturing for its own sake; he would rather make money than
things.<p>
Skase and Bond were two of the newcomers to the list that Carlyon singled out
for praise as having `created their own accretions of substance'. For good
measure, he added that what he called the `fast money' made by the high fliers
showed that `the boast of Australia being an egalitarian society were
justified'. <p>
By the 1993 Rich List (BRW, 21/5/93), however, a note of reproval had crept in
as Carlyon wrote without any hint of self-awareness, "In the 1980s, many of the
hot house men were feted as `business leaders'. They weren't; they were merely
brash and quotable; busy rather than productive, dealers rather than
builders".<p>
In November 1993, Carlyon was named the Graham Perkin Journalist of the Year.
<hr>
<A NAME="Brian Toohey"><B>Brian Toohey</B></A> is a Sydney-based journalist. His book, Tumbling Dice, on economic
policy making, has recently been published by Heinemann (ISBN 0 85561 600 8),
and is priced at $24.50.
<p>
<hr>
