<head><title>Thai press freedoms: a challenge to the region</title></head>
<h1>Thai press freedoms: <br>a challenge to the region</h1><p>
<p>
<b>While Australia's foreign owned news papers cut costs to maximise profits,
Thailand is experiencing a period of openness for its media. Thailand hopes to
secure a profitable future for itself itself as the centre of a quality
Asia-wide English language press. <A HREF="#Alan Knight">Alan Knight</A> reports.</b>
<hr>
<p>
Later this year, the Bangkok-based Manager group will launch Asia Times, an
international daily aimed squarely at ASEAN's rapidly growing educated and
affluent elite. Both Singapore and Hong Kong already have better paid and more
highly educated workforces than Australia, and living standards are rising
rapidly in Malaysia, Thailand and sections of Indonesia.<p>
There are even proposals to sell the Asia Times in Australia; to service a
market considered to be ill served by our local press's perceived ignorance of
and disinterest in Asia.<p>
The Thais hope to replace Hong Kong which with three daily English language
broadsheets, a plethora of glossy magazines, satellite television networks and
600 foreign corespondents, is still unquestionably Asia's international media
centre. <p>
Yet journalists in Hong Kong are becoming increasingly nervous about the 1997
convergence with China, which remains openly hostile to a critical press. China
still defines news as whatever the communist party says it is. <p>
The New China News Agency (the official mainland office in Hong Kong) tracks
the movements of pro-democracy activists, issues its own version of
Beijing-style "news" and protests about unfavourable stories. <p>
The Agency last year even sought to stop the Hong Kong Foreign Correspondents'
Club from showing a BBC documentary on the life of Mao, after pressure had
blocked its open broadcast on Hong Kong television. The documentary offended
Beijing's cultural sensitivities by quoting Mao's former personal physician who
claimed the Great Helmsman had a leaning towards young girls. <p>
Such offences have been taken seriously in the Crown Colony since the Beijing
arrest and trial last year of a Hong Kong journalist who allegedly breached
state secrecy by seeking to report on interest rate movements. (See Reportage
Spring 1994). Hong Kong Journalist Union Executive members who unsuccessfully
campaigned for his release have themselves become targets for a mainland backed
campaign to replace them. <p>
Some Hong Kong publications have already begun seeking an accommodation with
the incoming government. An executive for the Hong Kong Daily Standard, the
flagship of Sally Aw's international media group, told a conference on Asian
news values in December that Hong Kong journalists would have to be much more
careful in the future. Amends would have to be made for past mistakes, he said.
<p>
His group had already struck a deal to distribute papers across the border and
did not want potential advertising revenue disrupted by irresponsible
reporting. <p>
Other publications, such as the prestigious Far Eastern Economic Review, have
pledged in public that they will remain in Hong Kong after 1997. In private,
they have been laying plans to move their operations, if the mainlanders find
themselves unable to shake the habit of censorship.<p>
Meanwhile, Thai journalists are enjoying unprecedented freedoms which they hope
to export to the surrounding region. Thailand translated means "land of the
free".  However, media freedoms have been qualified during swings between
democracy and what have been in effect military dictatorships. The Australian
news camera-man, Neil Davis, died there while recording once such exchange of
government.<p>
Christian missionaries introduced the first printing press in Thailand in 1835.
Throughout the 19th century, publishing was mainly confined to the royal court
and missionaries, advocating either Buddhism or Christianity respectively.
However, the tradition of using the press to allow public debate of contending
ideas was established during this period, with members of the Thai royal family
submitting articles for publication under pseudonyms. <p>
The Royal Gazette, founded in 1858, is still used for official announcements.
Daily newspapers came into their own in the early 20th century under the reign
of King Vajiravudh. During his reign, some 20 dailies (among them one in
Chinese and two in English) were printed.<p>
The first point of the Thai journalists' code of ethics affirmed that the main
task of all journalists was "to promote, preserve and uphold the freedom of the
press". The Thai press was seen to be obliged not only to report news, facts
and opinions as well as help people understand the events of the day but was
also expected to (1) look after social well being, (2) act as a medium for
social organisations and (3) promote and clarify social beliefs values and
views. <p>
However, to perform such duties, the press demanded more freedom. Thai
journalists might say, "The more freedom a newspaper has, the more freedom the
society will get".<p>
Such beliefs have helped create a press which ranged from Thai language "blood,
bodies and scandal" tabloid newspapers to quality English language broadsheets.
Thai journalists were perceived to be more tenacious and less willing to buckle
under to authorities than most other of their Asian counterparts. <p>
Their freewheeling, daredevil approach  made it more difficult for authorities
to bring them to heel. During the 1992 demonstrations which brought down the
military backed government in Bangkok, many news paper journalists simply
ignored threats of a crackdown.<p>
Freedom of expression is no longer a question for Thai journalists, according
to Thepchai Yong, the Editor-in-Chief of the Bangkok-based Nation newspaper.
The right to report the "truth" has already been won in bloody battles on the
streets of the Thai capital, he says. <p>
The Nation, a quality broadsheet with a reputation for covering regional
affairs, is strongly opposed to notions of "Eastern-style journalism", which
Thai reporters and editors saw as a paternalistic rationale for censorship and
oppression.<p>
Yong was the keynote speaker at the Asian Pacific regional conference of the
International Federation of Journalists held in Sydney in February. He says
that while it has always been recognised that Thailand had among the freest
presses in south east Asia, the pace of progress, particularly in the last two
years, had been extraordinary.<p>
"For decades the Thai press was content, probably more by circumstances, with
its role as a watch dog. It exposed corruption, crucified wayward politicians
and bureaucrats, and raised the red flag when certain political or military
(leaders) began showing signs of threat to the democratic system," he says.<p>
"Of course, it was not a perfect role. But in the absence of a more credible
institution, the press was left as one of the few safeguards against abuses and
excesses by the powers that were."<p>
However, the Thai newspapers were to play a leading role in reporting
Thailand's "political uprising" in 1992; toppling a military backed government,
by prompting the intervention of the Thai King. <p>
The incident, one of many in Thailand's long history of coup and counter coup,
was best remembered by many Westerners by the memorable news footage it
generated; the unaccustomed sight of powerful politicians crawling across a
palace floor so that they might be summarily dismissed by a wave of the royal
hand. In apparent irony, it became clear that in Thailand, moves towards modern
democracy were reliant on a benevolent monarchy, itself only recently removed
from a divine autocracy.<p>
Most Thai radio and television stations had in contrast to the press, backed
the discredited politicians, and, by down-playing and misreporting the popular
opposition, had themselves lost credibility with the population. <p>
Yong says that although Thailand boasted more than 400 national and local radio
stations, as well as five television stations, most were owned directly by the
government, the armed forces or state enterprises.<p>
"More often than not, they served as propaganda machinery for those in power,"
he says. "Their whitewash account of the event backfired. And for the first
time, the public resentments of the public broadcasting monopoly have forced
both the government and the military to loosen their grips on the broadcast
media. The result was a sudden emergence of privately operated radio news
stations."<p>
Suddenly, Thais discovered the decidedly mixed blessings of talk-back radio.
Ordinary members of the public were the first time able to openly debate
political issues which had until then, been largely the preserve of the
literate elite. <p>
The overwhelming response shattered the familiar arguments heard from
authoritarians everywhere; that the so called uneducated and underprivileged of
Asia had no interests beyond their own daily survival. <p>
The Nation group, which began its own radio news service was deluged with
listeners' letters. A farmer wrote from a remote province, "For the first  time
in my life, I am listening to a news program which is propaganda free and
uncensored. And for the first time, I can make my voice heard."<p>
Yong says that it was too early to predict that moves towards a full democracy
were irreversible in Thailand.<p>
"But the more active political participation by the more outspoken media, is a
reminder that no unconstitutional change will be accepted without resistance.
<p>
"An informed and politically conscious public, is without question the best
assurance against a slide back into the vicious political cycle. And this is
exactly, the greatest challenge facing the Thai media today".	<p>
<hr>
<p>
<A NAME="Alan Knight">Alan Knight</A> has been a journalist since 1973 working for seven years with the
ABC. He currently teaches journalism at UTS, is the ACIJ's Asia Director and is
researching a PhD on Australian journalism on Asia.
<p>
<hr>
