<html><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<head><title>Asia's new English voice</title></head>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Asia's new English voice</H1>
<B>Peter Limqueco, a Filipino journalist and academic, has been appointed Editor at Large at the Asia Times  a new English language newspaper based in Thailand. He says that his potential audience would be "businessmen, policy makers, opinion makers, graduate students, government bureaucrats, and diplomatic corps members". Alan Knight caught up with him recently on his visit to Australia
recruiting contributors.</B><p>
<i><p>
Is the English language market in Asia big enough to bear another
publication?</i><p>
I think so. The International Herald Tribune is fairly American oriented. There's hardly any Asian news in it. The Asian Wall Street Journal, while it has more stories about Asia in it, it is written from an American point of view. The way they look at events is quite different from the way an Asianwould look at them.<i><p>
Americans and the British have previously dominated international English language media in the region, is this new paper a sign that attitudes are changing?</i><p>
Yes. You can see so many countries now where the domination is not there any more. The best example is the Philippines which was an American colony for so long but where not a single newspaper is owned by the Americans. The area where they still dominate is international broadcasting by television like CNN. But with the economic development of Asia and given the growth in economic wealth, it is about time that Asians take the decision to compete with the American and British monopolies.<i><p>
Yet the region is so diverse. What sort of stories will you be looking for
which might he region wide appeal?</i><p>
Essentially we will be looking at the business of politics and the politics of
business. It is not just reporting news as it evolves. It is also analysing
news after the event has taken place. A lot of the international press is only
interested in getting the scoop and putting out the news as fast as it happens.
<i>There is much more to cover and much needs to be put in perspective.<p>
Are there such things as Asian news values?</i><p>
All news should be judged by international standards; which means objectivity
and accuracy. But it has to go deeper than that and that is where some
governments are sensitive. But in the long run, if you start by telling the
truth you should end up by telling the truth. But if you start with falsehoods,
you will always end up with falsehoods. When you say you can't report things
because of cultural differences, that is essentially concealing the truth.
These are international values whether you are in Asia, Timbuktu or anywhere
else.<i><p>
So you are not a subscriber to what the Indonesians, Malaysians and
Singaporeans call development journalism?</i><p>
No. This type of approach concealing information could mean that governments
have something to hide. If governments have nothing to hide, why should they be
afraid of discussion. It (censorship) is only done by totalitarian regimes and
closed societies. Democratically elected regimes should not be afraid of
transparency. After all the people brought them into power. They should be open
to the people.<i><p>
So why base your newspaper in Thailand?</i><p>
Thailand has the most advanced economy in mainland south-east Asia. The
economic development has reached such a point there now that the capitalisation
has reached that of industrialised countries. The economic growth rate will be
maintained at between nine and 12 percent a year for the next five years.
Because of its economic development, Thailand is able to influence neighbouring
countries in Indochina, southern China and Burma. It is in a strategic
position. We also have a substantial tourism industry in Thailand, about five
million people visit each year. All the airlines going to Europe and the Middle
East, stop in Bangkok. Meanwhile costs are low compared to Hong Kong, Singapore
and Malaysia, in terms of wages and cost of living. Lastly and not the least,
the level of democracy in Thailand is second only to the Philippines in
south-east Asia. We have a much wider latitude for democratic practices than
elsewhere. There is, however, still room for improvement.<i><p>
English is not as widely spoken in Thailand as some other ASEAN countries, why
choose it for Asia Times?</i><p>
English is the common language in Asia; among businesses, at international
conferences, even among tourists. It is much more common than other
languages.<i><p>
Will the pool of English language speakers increase?</i><p>
Yes that is the common trend. Even in countries like Malaysia which wanted to
concentrate on Bahasa Malaysia are trying to correct that situation because
they realise that to be able to compete with the world, they must be able to do
it in English. Nearly all the reading materials, instruction manuals in
advanced technologies are in English. Instructions for machinery imported from abroad are in English, so they will lose that ability to compete if they stick
to that national language.<i><p>
How will Asia Times place itself in the market?</i><p>
The Asian Wall Street Journal is better than many. Yet when I read it, I often
ask myself, "Why was this question not asked?" I will give you an example. At
the last APEC conference in Jakarta, all the newspapers appeared to be the
same: whether you read the Melbourne Age or the Philippine Daily Inquirer. They talked about how everyone was wearing batik, as well as the colours worn by Keating, Soeharto or Mahathir. They reported on what was agreed upon; that
ASEAN would phase out trade restrictions over 20 years. Whereas before the
conference, Mahathir, Philippines, Thailand; they were all saying, "We don't
want a schedule". But when the communique came out, it was reported as a
victory for Clinton and the United States. The interesting questions were: How
did Soeharto, the chairman, persuade the other ASEAN members to support the American position? What did he get from Clinton in exchange? That was never discussed by any of the journalists. Those to me are the interesting questions. Maybe they told him he could do what he liked in East Timor?           

</body></html>
