<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<head><title>Asia-Pacific Challenge: Journalists and Human Rights</title></head>
<H1>Asia-Pacific Challenge: Journalists and Human Rights</H1><p>
<p>
<H3><!-- Anchor Link Tag -->
<A HREF="#Aidan White">By Aidan White</A></H3>
<hr>
<p>
At a time when media exercise more influence than at any time in human history,
when violence against journalists is increasing and when governments, many of
them in the dynamic economies of Asia, resist pressure to recognise universal
principles of freedom in society, the role of media and the rights of
journalists have become issues which define the quality of democracy.<p>
In Singapore foreign media, such as the International Herald Tribune in January
1995, have been routinely prosecuted for activities which, in the settled
democracies of the world, are part of the normal democratic process.<p>
In China, journalists who write honestly, professionally and competently are
imprisoned accused of spying or other anti-social behaviour.<p>
In South Asia, a legacy of colonialism remains in a complex legislative
framework which often binds media professionally and economically to the
institutions of state.<p>
In Indonesia, journalists who wish to represent themselves through an
independent, non-governmental and professional association are victimised and
vilified while independent news media are closed down with the approval of a
government sponsored journalists association.<p>
In many countries of the region a tone of compliance over the emergence of what
is ruefully known as "soft-authoritarianism", should sound an alarm bell
throughout the newsrooms of Asia.<p>
The IFJ, which represents almost 400,000 journalists in 90 countries, believes
strongly in the need for professional solidarity in defence of journalists'
rights. <p>
We reaffirm our commitment after a year in which the scale of violence against
journalists worldwide has reached an unprecedented level.<p>
In 1994 some 115 journalists were killed around the world according to the IFJ
Report published in December. Of these a number were killed in Asia. <p>
In taking up the battle for journalists' rights, the IFJ works closely with the
agencies of the United Nations, particularly UNESCO; the United Nations Human
Rights Commission, World Intellectual Properties Organisation (WIPO) and the
International Labour Organisation (ILO), with the International Committee of
the Red Cross, and with a range of other international trade union and freedom
of expression organisatiens.<p>
The IFJ's mandate covers both professional and industrial interests of
journalists. Our current policy program has been defined by the Manifesto For a
Democratic Media Culture, adopted at the Federation's Congress held in
Montreal, Canada, in June 1992.<p>
That Manifesto is an elaboration of the Sydney Declaration, a statement issued
here five years ago following the first international conference organised by
journalists on the issue of media concentration.<p>
The need for a program of practical work to protect freedom of expression and
opinion and to counter the killing of journalists gets more urgent by the day.
<p>
It is not just the toll of journalists killed which worries us, though that is
tragic enough. <p>
But living and working in conditions of fear, poverty, or employment insecurity
journalists often submit to "self-censorship" the most corrosive and insidious
form of censorship of all.<p>
Thc IFJ believes, therefore, that there must be a national legal framework to
create and enhance the conditions for professional journalism. <p>
Any legal framework must identify the full range of obstacles, formal and
informal, which are an impediment to good reporting. The law must protect
journalists against all forms of censorship.<p>
A set of issues upon which the IFJ believes action should be taken has been set
out in a document available from the IFJ titled, "Legislating for a Democratic
Media Culture", which identifies key areas in which the law can be used in the
service of press freedom.<p>
The IFJ considers that the notion of journalism and human rights must also
embrace the need to examine the conditions in which journalists work and, in
particular, the issue of their physical safety.<p>
While a legal framework can put in place the rules by which the game must be
played, the practice of journalism is increasingly fraught with danger and
requires concrete activity to:<p>
a) monitor violations of human rights and attacks on journalists and media
organisations;<p>
b) establish networks of communication between journalists and media
organisations;<p>
c) provide support, including humanitarian aid and legal defence assistance, to
journalists and media organisations where violations of human rights take
place.<p>
In support of these aims the IFJ has implemented a program of action and set up
a new organisation, the Journalists' Safety Service, which is being developed
in all parts of the world and particularly here in the Asia-Pacific region
through the IFJ's Regional Office.<p>
This regional office was established during 1994 and it offers the basis for
the creation of a network of sub-regional organisations bringing together
journalists' organisation from throughout the region. <p>
In all of its work, the IFJ works closely with other organisations which share
our aims and objectives, from the world of trades unionism to a range of human
rights organisations concerned with freedom of expression and opinion.<p>
However, there is no substitute in the end for professional solidarity. Much
more needs to be done to confront the crises we face in the years ahead. In all
the chatter about "new world orders" precious little is heard about protecting
the fundamental democratic values set out in international treaties governing
civil and political rights.<p>
 What is needed from democratic governments throughout the region is a
practical program:<p>
l To intervene on behalf of freedom of expression organisations and journalists
organisations whenever there are alleged violations of human rights;<p>
l To sponsor activities involving regional governments, collective and
individually, to promote public awareness on the issue of freedom of
expression, human rights, social conditions and the safety of journalists;<p>
l To promote dialogue and joint action among media organisations, journalists
and others working in the field of journalists' safety;<p>
l To assist in the publication and circulation of material and information on
violations of journalists' and media rights.<p>
Such a commitment to change would be a modest start in creating a broad
political and social coalition recognising that good journalism counts in a
democracy, that a confident and inquiring media is nothing to be afraid of and,
above all, that human rights take precedence over the ideological imperatives
of economic or social control.	<p>
<p>
<A NAME="Aidan White"><B>Aidan White</B></A> is General Secretary of the International Federation of
Journalists, based in Brussells. He was in Australia in February for the
IFJ/MEAA conference, Asia Pacific Media.
<p>
<hr>
