</DOCHDR>
<html>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<head><title>Under pressure: Media freedom</title></head>
<H1>Under pressure: Media freedom in the Asia-Pacific region</H1><p>

<B>Despite rapid industrialisation and a rise in wealth, the Asia-Pacific region
hasn't experienced a similar growth in media freedom or individual rights.
These <A HREF="#compiled">country reports</A> are from the 
<A HREF="R5IFJ_Safety.html">International Federation of Journalists</A>.</B><p>
<HR WIDTH=100%>
The Asia-Pacific region is shaping up to become the workshop of the world in
the 21st Century. With this economic expansion comes the hope of greater
freedoms for the people who live there. But does economic development
necessarily mean that the people of the Asia-Pacific will enjoy such
fundamental freedoms as those of expression and opinion?<p>
It is the achievement of these freedoms which will define the role the media
plays in the region and determine the future prospects for journalists and
media organisations.<p>
It is important not to make sweeping generalisations, or to set the principle
of universality of human rights in the context of an "outside or foreign"
intervention.<p>
The debate ranges from those countries that favour an "Asian concept of human
rights" to those which favour an interpretation of human rights which is in
line with universal principles which transcend national boundaries.As this
report reveals, there is no evidence to suggest that economic growth by itself
is a guarantee of human rights protection, either for journalists or for other
people in a society. And yet it could be argued that repressive measures
against citizens' rights to free information, for example, actually, damages
the process of economic development and growth.<p>
Indeed, the strongest evidence points towards the need for continued outside
pressure on governments which abuse the rights of media and of citizens to
free, uncensored and professional sources of information. The major question
facing journalists' unions is how such pressure can be applied.<p>
Across the Asia and Pacific region journalists are under pressure. What follows
is a current rundown of the situation in countries in the region.<p>
<p>
<B>BURMA</B><p>
In Burma Aung San Su Kyi, the leader of the democratic opposition, is still
under house arrest on the orders of the State Law and Order Restoration Society
(SLORC), a military body established as a temporary government in 1988.<p>
The authorities continue to deny freedom of expression, freedom of association
and freedom of assembly. There have been a number of specific incidents in the
past year highlighting the control on expression in particular. In July seven
people were arrested for distributing pamphlets calling for the release of Aung
San Su Kyi.<p>
In September Khin Zaw Win and four members of the National League for Democracy
were arrested for passing "fabricated news" to foreign media. In October Khin
was sentenced to 15 years imprisonment and San San Nwe, a writer and member of
the National League for Democracy, was sentenced to 10 years. All the other
defendants were sent to prison for eight years. <p>
These incidents were just part of a range of violations of human rights which
have concerned the international community. Meanwhile, the United States and
Thailand maintain the strongest trading links with Burma.<p>
<p>
<B>CAMBODIA</B><p>
Cambodian journalists have been in the frontline of efforts to maintain a
democracy movement following the first year of a democratically-elected
government in the country. The independent press has been the target of
official attacks following the public exposure in Cambodia and abroad of
military atrocities. <p>
The power of the media to influence public opinion has led to government
retaliation and the deaths of three journalists. In addition Noun Nonn, editor
of Morning News was arrested in July following a coup attempt for publishing an
article which suggested high officials in the ministry of the interior were
responsible for the coup.<p>
The Khmer Journalists Association, an IFJ member, has been in the forefront of
efforts to restrain the authorities from attacks on the press and the
Association led a concerted international campaign against a new press law
which would have further restricted the media. <p>
In September foreign journalists were threatened with expulsion by the prime
minister if they "exaggerated" reports about Cambodia. The IFJ Regional Office
in Kuala Lumpur has been monitoring the situation in Cambodia where the
presence of a number of non-government organisations, including the Australian
Journalists Association, provide civic education and training.<p>
<p>
<B>CHINA</B><p>
The human rights crisis is most apparent in China where the government
expresses continual disregard for the rights of journalists and media
organisations. Curbs on freedom of the press have tightened in the past year.
In a case designed to be a clear warning to dissident journalists, particularly
in Hong Kong, the Chinese authorities arrested and sentenced Xi Yang, a
reporter for the Hong Kong newspaper Ming Bao, to 12 years' jail.<p>
The offence was writing an article on central bank gold strategies and
interests rates when official information on the matter had not yet been
released. The reporters' source, Tian Ye, a clerk at the People's Bank was
jailed for 15 years.<p>
In another case Gao Yu, formerly deputy chief editor of the banned newspaper
Economics Weekly was tried in secret in April and sentenced later in the year.
This case was particularly worrying for it violated China's own legal
procedures.<p>
China takes strong action against dissidents who try to talk to the foreign
press. In April five journalists were held for questioning over contacts with
the wife of veteran dissident Xu Wenli. The action against media was
particularly harsh up to the fifth anniversary of the June 4 crackdown in
Beijing.<p>
Information flows in Tibet are routinely restricted. Satellite television is
strictly controlled. Travel agencies have been forbidden to permit journalists
to take journeys into the region. Of particular concern was the decision by
Star Television, a part of News Corporation based in Hong Kong, to dismiss the
BBC Television World Service from its broadcasts to China. It was an action
specifically taken to ensure that no news service unacceptable to the Chinese
authorities would be broadcast through the company's cable network.<p>
The United States Government renewed China's "Most Favoured Nation" trading
status during the year despite considerable concern expressed by all major
human rights agencies that little or no progress had been made in obtaining the
regime's commitment to respect human rights. During 1994 governments in Asia
and Europe took steps to reinforce and expand commercial relations with China.
The effect of this has been to downgrade the importance of human rights.<p>
<p>
<B>HONG KONG</B><p>
The intransigence of the Chinese government on questions of human rights and
the expansion of trading links with China by the major industrialised countries
of the world are bad omens for the defence of civil and political rights in
Hong Kong. The journalists of Hong Kong, led by the Hong Kong Journalists'
Association, have resolutely campaigned for laws to protect freedom of
information and freedom of expression for the post-1997 era.<p>
During the year journalists held demonstrations over the imprisonment of Xi
Yang (See China, above), but some news media have encouraged self-censorship
and, according to Human Rights Watch, some publications warned journalists not
to sign petitions on Xi Yang's behalf. On May 10 journalists from Hong Kong who
had signed the petition of protest were banned from entering China.<p>
<p>
<B>INDONESIA</B><p>
Attacks on Indonesian journalism in the past year are clear evidence of
Indonesia's abandonment of "openness" and any policy encouraging freedom of the
press. Three well-known publications - Tempo, Editor and Detik - were closed as
the country returned to a familiar pattern of abuse of human rights.<p>
In the frontline of resistance to this crackdown were members of the
Association of Independent Journalists (AJI). In October 1994 AJI became a
member organisation of the IFJ. In setting up their independent organisation,
the independent journalists protested strongly at the government crackdown on
media and rejected "all kinds of interference, intimidation, censorship and
media bans which deny freedom of speech and open access to information".<p>
In retribution the Ministry of Information encouraged victimisation by
newspaper editors. On October 31, Andreas Harsono, a prominent member of the
AJI working on the English-language Jakarta Post, was sacked on vague charges
of misconduct.<p>
The official PWI (Indonesian Journalists Association) has assisted the
authorities in their opposition to the independent journalists' movement and an
attempt to re-open DeTik under a new title was stopped after one day of
publication, in part on the grounds that journalists who were not members of
the PWI were involved its publication.<p>
Indonesia remains deeply sensitive to discussion over East Timor and has
pressured its neighbours Malaysia, Philippines and Thailand to undermine
activities which highlight the problem. In one case reported by Human Rights
Watch the Indonesian Government succeeded in having foreigners banned from a
conference being held in Manila on East Timor by cancelling joint venture
contracts between the two countries.<p>
The AJI issued a statement of protest on December 7, 1994 over the invasion of
the offices of the newspaper Suara Timor Timur by a gang of youths who
destroyed electronic equipment. They were looking for journalist Jacob Herin
because of a report he had written. They traced him to a hotel where he was
working and beat him up. [See article in this issue of Reportage on IFJ mission
to  Indonesia.]<p>
<p>
<B>MALAYSIA</B><p>
The Malaysian government's sensitivity to the publication of information which
it doesn't like was starkly revealed in a remarkable confrontation with British
media over reportage of the so-called Pergau Dam scandal. The Malaysian
Government cancelled contracts with British companies over the affair in which
allegations of corruption were made against the Government. Various threats
were made to foreign journalists as the affair developed, but eventually the
trade ban was lifted in September.<p>
In April a Filipino journalist Leah Makabenta was expelled for writing a "very
negative" article on migrant labour. In the same month a report by the BBC on
labour unrest in Indonesia was censored by the state broadcasting system. The
BBC said the item must be broadcast without cuts. The program was dropped
completely from Malaysian television on May 1.<p>
<B>SINGAPORE</B><p>
Political repression and strict curbs on media freedom remain in Singapore,
despite the country's exceptional economic growth. The editor of Business Times
was convicted and fined for "communicating and receiving government data". He
was charged under the country's Official Secrets Act for printing preliminary
estimates on quarterly economic growth in 1992.<p>
The International Herald Tribune, despite the appearance of its editor in court
to explain himself, was fined over an article it carried which was allegedly in
contempt of court. The opinion piece had criticised intolerant regimes in the
region.<p>
<p>
<B>VIETNAM</B><p>
In contrast with the situation in China press coverage of sensitive issues,
such as official corruption has been possible although criticism of the party
or the leadership remained impossible in a media which remains
state-controlled. Human Rights Watch reported that a week-long seminar
organised in March for foreign journalists to provide training for Vietnamese
journalists was cancelled, apparently by security officials who had launched a
campaign against peaceful evolution in the press at that time.	<p>


<HR WIDTH=100%>

<A NAME="compiled">This report has been compiled by the IFJ from information gathered through the
International Freedom of Expression exchange, the IFJ Journalists' Safety
Service, and Human Rights Watch.</A><p>
