<head><title>Mission to free Indonesia's media</title></head>
<H1>Mission to free Indonesia's media</H1>
<p>
<p>
<B>An <A HREF="R5IFJ_Safety.html">International Federation of Journalists</A> mission to Indonesia in April has
found that official interference in the press has created a climate of
insecurity and fear.</B>
<hr>
<p>
The recent International Federation of Journalists' (IFJ) mission to Indonesia
found individual journalists are being victimised and threatened with the loss
of their livelihood, and that journalists and other media professionals are
inhibited from speaking openly about press freedom and democ-racy.<p>
Improper self-censorship has become the norm throughout Indonesian media, and the role of media in serving society is profoundly compromised particularly in a period of political uncertainty.<p>
The mission, which included Christopher Warren, Federal Secretary of the
Australian Journalists Association section of the Media Entertainment and Arts
Alliance, found that constant threats that publishing licences will be revoked
undermine professional solidarity and imperil freedom of expression.<p>
The mission met with editors, journalists, human rights groups, trade unionists
and media experts to consider the current difficulties for press freedom and
recent actions against members of the Alliance of Independent Journalists
(AJI). <p>
The mission found universal recognition within media that the conditions for
press freedom have deteriorated rapidly since the closure in June 1994 of
Editor, DeTik and Tempo. [Note: The Tempo closure was overturned in May by an
Indonesian court.] The IFJ mission recommended:<p>
* The abolition of the SIUPP system of issuing and revoking licences to
publications.<p>
* An end to the banning of independent publications and to the harassment of
individual journalists.<p>
* An end to the ministerial decree by which media policy is held hostage to the
political process.<p>
* That journalists Ahmad Taufik and Eko Maryadi and mediaworker Danang,
arrested on March 17 1995, should be released from custody immediately.<p>
* The introduction of a new legal framework for freedom of the press which
honours the practice of freedom of expression set out in the Indonesian
constitution.<p>
* The development and implementation of professional and trade union
co-operation and assistance programmes to enhance the quality of ethical and
independent journalism in Indonesia.<p>
* That further international missions and visits should be carried out.<p>
* That the IFJ and the Journalists Safety Service should continue to monitor
developments in Indonesia through the IFJ Asia-Pacific Regional Office in Kuala
Lumpur, and<p>
* That the IFJ and the international trade union movement should promote
regional and international solidarity with AJI and all independent
journalists.<p>
The mission was carried out by Aidan White, General Secretary of the IFJ, Ching
Chabo of the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions, Judit Neurink of
the Netherlands Association of Journalists, and Christopher Warren, of the
MEAA. 
<p>
<hr>
