<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><HEAD><title>Reportage 5 Editorial</title></HEAD>
<IMG  WIDTH=240  Align=Center SRC="/images/reportage.gif" align=bottom><!-- Graphic Tag -->
<IMG HSPACE=20  SRC="../resources/dot_clear.gif"><FONT SIZE=6>Editorial</FONT><p>
<h1>Sex, drugs and journalism</h1><p>
<p>
The competition between magazines in Australia is hot, and a good cover can
make the difference between pretty ordinary sales and a best-seller. The
difference that a cover can make has been illustrated by the Sydney Morning
Herald's Stay in Touch column's look at what sells and what flops. Comparison
of recent covers of New Scientist magazine found that bare bodies sell and
worthy stories don't - at least that's one conclusion that can be made.<p>
Talking this over with colleagues in the magazine industry brings varying
responses. Known personalities sell, upcoming ones don't; sex sells, starving
children don't; trim bodies sell, aging flab doesn't; illicit drugs sell,
Aborigines don't.<p>
It is grim to consider that two magazine editors told me that their lowest
selling covers featured Aborigines; but even grimmer to hear that they won't
ever use Aborigines on their front covers again. But shouldn't they be
reflecting society, which includes Aborigines? "We're in business, and we'll
run what sells," sums up the responses.<p>
So where does this leave Reportage, trying to sell magazines through
newsagents? Does this mean we should do puff pieces on the life styles of
`hairdo' journalists, and carry less of the negative side of our media's
propaganda?<p>
Course not! We'll continue to examine journalism and the media as has become
our fashion. We'll look at the good, the bad, and the ugly and try to point to
a path to better things. <p>
And we want to do a deal with our readers. The deal is this: we'll continue
putting out Reportage four times a year, and in return you can help us to
increase our readership. So, tell your friends about us; get your workplace to
subscribe; get your local bookshop to stock it; get your local library to
subscribe; ask for it in every newsagent you see; give gift subscriptions to
your friends; take out an ad in the magazine; and subscribe yourself. If you
are a journalist, ring and interview us about stories in each issue; use our
articles as free research material but give us appropriate credit in your
program or article. That's all we ask.<p>
As we go to press, legal sanctions on the media's reporting of the activities
of ASIS seem to be only a matter of time if the recommendations of the Samuels
Commission of Inquiry into ASIS are followed. <p>
The Inquiry final report recommended that the recommendations of the 1991 Gibbs
Report be implemented. The Gibbs Committee which conducted a review of
Commonwealth Criminal Law had concluded that there is an offence "where there
is publication by a third party recipient of information in certain specified
circumstances". So not only government officers who leak to the media, but also
journalists who report the information, could be subject to prison terms of up
to seven years.<p>
In the meantime we have reviewed in this issue the transcripts of the media
representatives who appeared before the ASIS Inquiry, and find that attitudes
to `the public's right to know' are varied.<p>
Our Special Report this issue is on the lack of analytical reporting on
Aboriginal deaths in custody. A Royal Commission was indeed held, but the
recommendatiions were made in 1991, and few of them have so far been
implemented. Wendy Bacon and Bonita Mason ask why this is a dead issue.<p>
The debate over the future of Australia's old growth forests reached new levels
when Canberra was blockaded by loggers earlier this year. Such highly
structured media events are sure to continue, writes Sarah Ford.<p>
Sharon Davis spoke at the Centre for Investigative Journalism's Hidden Stories
seminar about how journalists' enthusiasm for the South African elections waned
quickly when bloodshed didn't break out.<p>
Recently in Australia, Noam Chomsky spoke to Reportage and gave his thoughts on
how journalists can still manage to break the hidden stories when the
structures of journalism and the media mitigate such efforts.<p>
Alan Knight sees that Thailand's media is becoming the leader of the region,
and finds that `Asian sensibilities' are a cover for repression. Aidan White of
the International Federation of Journalists says that journalists must face the
issue of human rights head on. We also bring you the IFJ's latest country
profiles on media freedom in countries in our region.<p>
 Well-known journalist, Brian Toohey, shows us some of the rubbish written by
some business and economics journalists during the height of the
entrepreneurial 80s. Amazing reading this makes. We review two books this
issue. Linda Kaucher reviews Alex Carey's Taking the Risk out of Democracy, and
we also review a media guide for Aboriginal organisations. And there's lots
more - just take a look. In the next issue we'll bring that examination of the
High Court's implied free speech decision we mentioned last issue.<p>
Just a quick note on getting your copy of Reportage. Obviously subscribing is
the best way to guarantee you don't miss a copy. Many newsagents get just a few
copies which may sell really fast. If you want to know which newsagents in your
area sell Reportage, phone us and we'll let you know. Sales have been
spectacularly good; so good in fact we are increasing the number of copies
going to newsagents.<p>
Also some newsagents, it seems, return the copies of Reportage they get to the
distributor without having put them on the news-stand. One in inner-suburban
Leichhardt in Sydney, to whom Reportage spoke said he'd only display
established titles. "Like those Soldier of Fortunes over there?" "Yes," he
said.<p>
Media theorists examining why small publications face an uphill battle in
Australia can now add another restriction on freedom of speech to their list.<p>
<p>
<cite>Peter Cronau</cite><p>
