<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<head><title>Guest Opinion</title></head><p>
<H1>Guest Opinion: When good news is bad news</H1><p>
<p>
In the cut-and-thrust of news and current affairs production, some stories
remain hidden because of a misery overload in the public, and some are hidden
because journalists think the story lies elsewhere. In an address to the ACIJ's
Hidden Stories seminar, Sharon Davis takes a tough look at how journalists
themselves can leave important stories untold.<p>
<p>
Early last year I was sent by the ABC to cover the elections in South Africa
for Background Briefing. It was an historic event that would end over 300 years
of white domination in that country and literally the eyes of the world were
watching. <p>
And when I say literally, I mean that there were over 2,000 journalists
covering that event in South Africa. Media conferences were like a football
scrum.<p>
I should have been able to guess the kind of news reporting that would follow.
Many news organisations unfortunately instead of sending their Africa
specialists, had sent their seasoned war correspondents. Talk in the bar at
night was of dodging bullets and which brand of flak jacket you were wearing.<p>
Not surprisingly because of this, when the great moment arrived - the election
- it was so peaceful, that these seasoned war correspondents very quickly
became bored. They came for a war, a blood bath between black and white, and
they didn't get it.  <p>
So by day two of the election, journalists in South Africa were around the bar
again talking about how boring this was. Just how many pictures could they send
back home of people standing in long queues voting? <p>
They were talking about where they were going to pack off and head to next.
Fortunately there was a war that had become rather bloody just up the road in
Rwanda. So they were all talking about heading off to Rwanda. <p>
That in itself was ironic because only three weeks before that, a journalist in
Australia, Tony Wright, had written a terrific column in the Sydney Morning
Herald about how difficult it was to get coverage of Rwanda in Australian
newspapers.<p>
A colleague of mine who had some interest in African affairs, when the fighting
actually started in Rwanda walked into his organisation and they said, "I
suppose you want to do a story on Rwanda.". Three weeks later with 500 bodies
floating down the river, suddenly Rwanda was in the news and all of these
people were packing off their stuff and heading off for it.<p>
The unfortunate thing was that while the voting in South Africa was the end of
one story, it was the beginning of another one, and a very important story as I
saw it. The majority party in the new parliament, the African National
Congress, had promised a number of things to the electorate that they would try
and redress the legacy of the past. <p>
That meant a new constitution. It meant compensation and restitution of land.
It meant housing, hospitals, education, roads, electricity, development. These
were all promised and, if successful, this program would literally turn South
Africa on its head and would have repercussions in the rest of the region as
well. <p>
The world's poorest country Mozambique sat only next door and South Africa's
social and economic transformation could have lessons for it, as well as
providing jobs in industry for the rest of the region - a region I might say
that we're used to seeing reported as an economic basket case.<p>
We're most familiar with the images of starving children, but what we're not
familiar with is the endeavours that people take in that region to actually get
the region operating economically.<p>
Now since the election as well, the government has been having a major problem
with the banks getting behind their reconstruction program. So, not only is
this reconstruction program being developed in this period but it's also had
all of these problems. But there's been almost no coverage of these events
since the election.<p>
Why not? Almost every news organisation around the world has either full-time
correspondents or journalists or stringers in South Africa, so it's not a
question of money. <p>
Many of these people file stories almost daily, so what it becomes is a
question of priorities and competing for world news space, and at the moment it
doesn't compete very well with things like the O J Simpson trial,
unfortunately.<p>
The competition particularly in world news terms, the competition for space, is
very driven by television. If there are good pictures coming from a region
around the world - and by that I mean pictures involving some form of conflict
- then television crews rush there. The radio and the newspapers don't want to
be left behind, so this kind of herd mentality goes on and that, I think,
drives the whole reporting.<p>
On the domestic front, in late 1993 I was approached by the Council for
Intellectual Disabilities to do a story on boarding houses. Even though the
Human Rights Commission had just delivered its report into human rights and
mental illness, the Council for Intellectual Disabilities were having trouble
getting politicians to face up to the problems that people with psychiatric
illnesses faced, and also people with intellectual disabilities, and they were
also having trouble getting any media reporting.<p>
Now as a result of that in early 1994, I spent a great deal of time with people
who live in a boarding house in Stanmore. I was shocked by their level of
disadvantage and powerlessness. They literally have no rights. They live in
appalling conditions. Their pension is taken from them. The management of the
boarding house controls their visitors and they don't even have a say as to who
shares their room.<p>
In this particular boarding house the management also had a series of
punishments. Any infringements of the rules could result in a loss of your
tobacco ration or your holiday, which is supplied by St Vincent de Paul. And
these rules seemed pretty arbitrary. <p>
The people in the boarding house lost their tobacco ration if they gave any of
their cigarettes away. Now we've all seen the occasional horror hostel story,
but what disturbed me about this and other boarding houses, is it's symptomatic
of the situation all over Australia. It's the system that allows these places
to continue and flourish that should be being reported on and isn't.<p>
At the same time, since the Human Rights Commission report, the government both
Federal and State have said they have taken a range of measures to address some
of these conditions, task forces and the like. But these are also lacking. <p>
In New South Wales for instance, the governments rely on people who have no
rights to report on their abusers and then risk homelessness. These things are
also not being reported. <p>
Perhaps it's because it's a down story. Perhaps it's because it a story where
you have to think creatively about how to report it again. In some ways stories
like this and unemployment, need journalists to think a bit more creatively
about how to report it. <p>
<p>
<p>
Sharon Davis has been responsible for revealing many previously hidden stories
on subjects as diverse as the Hilton Bombing case, police informers, boarding
house squalor, and democracy in South Africa. <p>
She has won the Walkley Award in 1993 and 1991 for Best Investigative Report on
radio. <p>
She has also won the United Nations Media Peace Prize in 1994 and 1991, the
1988 Human Rights Award for Best Radio Documentary, and was highly commended in
the 1991 Golden Quill Awards for Legal Reporting on radio. <p>
Sharon has been working on ABC's Radio Eye documentary program, and has worked
on Radio National's Background Briefing, Triple J's The Drum, and on 2SER's
Razor's Edge.<p>
She is presently in South Africa working on a training program for South
African journalists.
<p>
<hr>
