<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><html><head><title>Hidden Stories `94</title></head><p>
<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Hidden Stories `94</H1>
<p>
<B>In late 1994 some of Australia's most hidden news stories were exposed to a
wider public view. Peter Cronau introduces a new project of the ACIJ.</B><p>
<p>
Despite the deluge of news and information accessible through newspapers,
radio, TV, books, CD-ROMs, cable TV, and the Internet, some significant stories
are not getting wide coverage. In fact, they are effectively hidden from public
view. <p>
This theme was the subject of the Hidden Stories seminar held by the Australian
Centre for Independent Journalism in November at which numerous journalists and
others spoke of their experiences with stories that have been hidden.<p>
Most journalists know of stories that for a variety of reasons just fail to
break through. Sometimes reporters, editors and producers overlook good stories
in the rush to deadlines; sometimes the biases and preferences of reporters,
editors and producers see some stories ignored; sometimes a story stays
submerged until a "credible" source takes it up; sometimes a bigger event
displaces it from the news agenda.<p>
There is usually no conspiratorial cabal at work to keep a certain story out;
often it is a more subtle self-censoring and second-guessing how a story may be
received, that sees a story passed over. The commercial imperative that demands
the delivery of a certain audience profile to potential advertisers also plays
a part in eliminating some stories.<p>
No-one can say that stories about Aborigines, the unemployed, the environment,
the homeless, the disadvantaged, foreign aid abuses, failed diplomacy, human
rights violations, self-determination, political moral corruption,
scorched-earth economic policies and the like never get a run. But it's more a
matter of how those stories are portrayed, and how often.<p>
It was the lack of adequate coverage of these and other stories - but in
particular the scarcity of analytical coverage of Australia's role in events on
Bougainville - that in late 1993 suggested a role for the ACIJ in publicly
raising this "censorship", and in examining the reasons behind it. As
journalists ourselves, the idea of a Hidden Stories seminar seemed to offer the
chance to dig out the hidden stories and try to get them into the mainstream.
<p>
In the meantime the Centre received a visitor from Simon Fraser University in
Canada, Robert Hackett, who described a new project in Canada modelled on one
in the US, about stories that fail to get into the mainstream media. Project
Censored: Canada was launched in 1994.<p>
The original Project Censored in the US had been established in 1976 by Dr Carl
Jenson who is a professor of communication studies at Sonoma State University
in California.<p>
The US Project Censored has a team of qualified judges who sift through the 700
or so nominated censored stories each year to decide on the 25 top censored
stories.<p>
The visit to the ACIJ late last year of one of the judges of the US Project
Censored, Professor Jack Nelson, has given further impetus to the Hidden
Stories project idea.<p>
The first Hidden Stories seminar was held by the Centre in November in Sydney.
Over the next year the ACIJ will be developing the project and how it might
link in with both the US and Canada Projects Censored.<p>
In the meantime the Hidden Stories seminar verged on bursting at the seams as
the number of hidden stories nominated to the Centre expanded. Suggestions of
stories from journalists and others continued right up to the night and many
more were made during the course of the evening. <p>
One story raised by David Bowman was the lack of reporting on the poor and the
growing gap between rich and poor in this country. Very recently this has
attracted some media coverage.<p>
Contributions to the seminar came from a wide group including journalists,
environmentalist, researchers, academics, lobbyists, as well as the general
public. [See stories covered in Hidden Stories `94 in the box]<p>
The Hidden Stories project doesn't pretend to be able to take a comprehensive
look at the stories that are hidden from the public. We are working on a way of
doing that though.<p>
In the meantime the seminar provides a glimpse of some of the stories that are
being lived out largely under the noses of the Australian public and largely
without their knowledge. The publication here of some of those stories from the
seminar is a second step in the Centre's Hidden Stories project.<p>
Sharon Davis in the Guest Opinion piece for this issue describes how some
journalists treated the South African election and in our special report this
issue, Wendy Bacon and Bonita Mason look behind the lack of analytical
reporting on the rising rate of Aboriginal deaths in custody.	<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
What do you mean by "censorship"?<p>
"a suppression of information, whether purposeful or not, by any method
including bias, omission, under reporting or self censorship, which prevents
the public from knowing what's happening in its society."<p>
Source: Project Censored, US<p>
<p>
<p>
