<head><title>The Fourth Estate</title></head>
<h1>The Fourth Estate</h1><p>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag -->
<HR WIDTH=100%>

<h3>ABC introduces self-censorship guidelines</h3><p>
<p>
British offence at Australian reporting of the "Liz and Phil down by the lake"
sculpture has forced the ABC to introduce editorial guidelines for
self-censorship for its international services. Reportage presents here a
leaked ABC policy document on the new guidelines.<p>
<p>
<p>
<h3>International Broadcasting</h3><p>
<p>
Broadcasting to Britain by the ABC, through Radio Australia and Australia
Television, is often perceived to be a cultural intrusion and - as practised by
some existing services - may not mean a neutral exercise in information
delivery. This does not mean, however, that Australia Television and Radio
Australia should not be mindful of the concept of `cultural intrusion'. <p>
Values expressed by Australian programs may conflict with the beliefs, mores
and self-identities of the recipient society of Britain, and television may
represent a more potent cultural challenge than radio.<p>
The new Australia Television service to Britain aims to be a distinctive
Australian service directed to a country of cultural diversity. It will reflect
Australian values in information, entertainment, sport and the arts while
striving for relevance and accessibility to the British audience.<p>
It is not possible to prescribe guidelines to reflect in full the different
values of all people in Britain. The guidelines below are designed to assist
editors and producers in meeting the general needs and expectations of a new
and different overall audience for the ABC.<p>
<p>
<p>
<h3>Cultural Perspectives</h3><p>
<p>
Cultural sensitivities vary across Britain, both in nature and intensity, but
there are areas of common concern. In program selection and scheduling,
Australia Television and Radio Australia will be mindful of these concerns,
particularly in the area of entertainment programs such as drama and comedy.<p>
Examples of cultural sensitivity include:<p>
* Most Anglo societies, especially Britain, do not easily accept direct comment
or innuendo disparaging the authority, pride and self-respect of leaders and
their countries.<p>
* There may be a reluctance to reflect or have portrayed racial, ethnic or
religious differences or conflicts which may impinge on or threaten Britain's
national identity or sense of community.<p>
* Media in Britain may be reluctant to have depicted or reported events, even
in other and distant countries or societies, which may be seen as likely to
provoke agitation or communal tension - for example, demonstrations or conflict
for political, economic or religious motives.<p>
* Religious beliefs and practices vary widely and no absolute standards are
possible. However an awareness of, and respect for, the values of the region
will help to avoid unnecessary offence. For example, a cooking program which
showed the best way to prepare a rabbit dish, and which was broadcast during
the weekend of Easter, would clearly cause offence.<p>
* The deep respect in which Britain holds their Royal Family requires attention
to appropriate deference.<p>
* Media in the Britain tend not to report events as sensational.<p>
* Most societies, especially Britain, are sensitive in various degrees to the
nakedness of either gender in a sexual context. There is also particular
sensitivity to the public exposure of the female body, again in varying
degrees.<p>
* Satire and other forms of comedy casting disrespect may cause offence in
Britain.<p>
However the ABC recognises that the context of the material will determine its
usage and services will not distort or censor program material, particularly
information programs, in order to avoid the possibility of offence to one or
other part of the totality of its audience in Britain.<p>
It should be clearly stated that awareness of areas of sensitivity such as
those above will not mean that Australia Television or Radio Australia will be
restrained in any way from the full and accurate reporting and reflection of
events in the region, in the tradition of independence, authority and integrity
developed over 40 years by Radio Australia's news and information services.<p>
<p>
<p>
<h3>Guidelines for International Reportage</h3><p>
<p>
Fundamental to Radio Australia and Australia Television must be identification
with their target audience, projecting Australian values honestly but with
sensitivity to other values that exist throughout Britain.<p>
Important editorial and programming assumptions shall include:<p>
* Australia is an integral part of the British region; Radio Australia and
Australia Television will operate as British regional broadcasters rather than
as `foreigners'.<p>
* The world view of Australia Television and Radio Australia will be centred on
Britain, with global and Australian domestic affairs being seen in that
context. Australian domestic issues and interests have a natural and important
place on the information and entertainment agendas of Britain.<p>
* While recognising that news content will vary on a day-to-day basis according
to the relative importance of news events, news bulletins will be based on a
mix reflecting its regional priorities, ie. England region, important world
news, then other Australian news.<p>
* Some expressions of Australian culture may be inappropriate for distribution
within other cultures.<p>
The citizens of Britain within Australia Television's target area will have
some knowledge of Australian culture. However it would be unwise to think there
is uniformity of cultural familiarity among those audiences or to assume that
familiarity equates with acceptance.<p>
<p>
<p>
<h3>Editorial Perspectives</h3><p>
<p>
The political cultures of Britain periodically are offended or angered by the
portrayal and reportage of them by the Australian media. The ABC accepts that
to some extent this is inevitable and will stand by the authority, integrity
and independence of the news, current affairs and information services provided
by Australia Television and Radio Australia based on the accuracy and balance
of their reportage.<p>
As stated above, Australia Television and Radio Australia will not censor or
distort their news and information output to avoid the possibility of offence.
However editors and producers will be conscious of the need for care in style
and presentation--much may depend on how a message is expressed. Media in many
British societies do publish and broadcast critical material, although their
language may be more circumspect than that used in Australia.<p>
<p>
<p>
Note: These guidelines are in fact the ABC's "International Services Editorial
Guidelines" used for broadcasting to Asia and are taken from the ABC Editorial
Policies of June 1993 - the only changes Reportage has made are geographical
alterations and the Easter rabbit details.<p>
<hr>
