<head><title>Quick Grabs</title></head>
<H1>Quick Grabs</H1><p>
<CITE>By Peter Cronau</CITE>
<hr>
<p>
<H3>Oklahoma: rednecks rush in</H3><p>
<p>
In the immediate aftermath of the ghastly Oklahoma bombing many fools rushed in
to lay the blame at the feet of certain Muslims. One threatening phone call
reportedly received by an American muslim organisation was: "Killing children,
you filthy animals. God is going to punish you. You're nothing but a bunch of
stinking animals. Your religion is shit. Die." Such intolerance and readiness
to condemn sprang forth from many rednecks until a redneck was arrested over
the blast.<p>
While the words of a few individuals may not have much authority, the words of
the media have much more influence. Restraint was required from the media at a
time of uncertainty over the perpetrator and without the legal process having
been even commenced. <p>
As stories about the Muslim threat started to tumble from journalists' tongues,
the Fairfax chief executive, Stephen Mulholland, in Dallas USA at the time,
chose to write an agenda setting piece for one of his own papers. It was
published on April 22 in the Sydney Morning Herald, under the heading, "A
nation is shocked into resolve".<p>
In trying to say that the US would seek severe "vengeance" on the "intruder"
even involving "foreign strikes", something "the Germans and the Japanese
learnt ... in the last war", Mulholland had got it wrong, very wrong. With
unintended accuracy, he backed up his revenge scenario with a short quote from
D H Lawrence. The quote: "The essential American soul is stoic, hard, isolate,
a killer".<p>
How true those words may be if the clean-cut all-American boys arrested for the
bombing are tried and found guilty.<p>
<hr>
<H3>Info highway deadend</H3><p>
<p>
Another in our series "Why the information superhighway will not set you
free".<p>
The demonstration of Microsoft's Encarta '95 - the world's biggest selling
encyclopedia - began with the full bells and whistles approach. After opening
the program, the operator offered to look up the entry for "leopard" and with
no further prompting needed from the rapt audience of journalists at the
special demonstration, clicked on the button for video. The leopard bounding
along through the savanna grassland looked very impressive.<p>
The Encarta '95 CD ROM offers a multimedia pathway to over 26,000 articles
"compiled by a full-time dedicated editorial staff". These articles are linked
with 7,000 photos and illustrations, 800 maps, eight hours of sound recordings,
and more than 100 animations and video clips. But just where is this info
super-pathway taking us? Read on.<p>
Leaving leaping leopards aside for the moment, Reportage entered the search
facility and keyed in the word "genocide" just to see how a more serious side
of human existence was covered by Encarta.<p>
No genocidal generals bounding along through the corpses here. The unadorned
text stated:<p>
Although the UN adopted international laws against genocide in 1948 genocide is
not prevented. In 1975 the Khmer Rouge despotic regime took over Cambodia and
brutalised its people. Cambodia's urban populations were evicted from their
city homes, driven to rural areas, forced into hard labour, and treated so
inhumanely many did not survive. Educated middle classes were automatically
executed. In 1979 the Vietnamese overthrew the Khmer Rouge but as many as three
million people had already been killed.<p>
Despite many examples to choose from, Cambodia has seeped into the collective
conscious as the archetypal case of genocide post-1945. But while it was as
massive as it was monstrous, it is not the greatest genocide in terms of the
proportion of a country's population obliterated. That honour goes of course to
East Timor.<p>
Various estimates including from no less than a recent Governor of the
territory, state a figure of at least 200,000 or about one third of the
population at the time of the UN-condemned but Western-supported invasion by
Indonesia. <p>
So Reportage opened up the search facility of this, the world's top selling
encylopedia, and keyed in the words "East Timor". Result? - no listing.<p>
We did some more searches and finally found a mention of East Timor buried in a
listing titled "Timor" inside the entry for "Indonesia". It seems Microsoft has
accepted what the United Nations has refused to accept and has repeatedly
condemned, that is that East Timor is a part of the Republic of Indonesia. <p>
What it did say of the illegal invasion and one of the greatest massacres this
century though was instructive - not of East Timor, but of the biases of the
Encarta database:<p>
Portuguese Timor including the region of Dili in the east and a small area of
Oecusse in the north-west, were forceably annexed by Indonesia in late 1975.<p>
We looked further but that one sentence was it, and genocide was not mentioned:
"Is there any more on East Timor?" Reportage ventured. "That is the article on
Timor, um," said the operator, referring to the one sentence. <p>
Just like all media before, the new medium of the info superhighway gives
access to only what is put in, what is made most accessible, and what is
marketed the best.<p>
<hr>
<H3>Just doing our job</H3><p>
<p>
As you'll remember, in January, Queensland police impersonated an SBS
television crew to arrest a forest protester. The deception involved the use of
forged SBS TV labels on a TV camera borrowed from the land developer the
protestor had opposed.<p>
This won the praises of the Acting Police Commissioner, Bill Aldrich who came
clean saying: "Police every day and in every state assume other identifications
ranging from plumbers, to clergy, to school-teachers, to doctors and
journalists in undercover operations".<p>
Now imagine that. A police officer lying to you saying they are a doctor,
presumably to get information you only wished to tell a doctor. Or the plumber
allowed into your house actually being a police officer entering your house
without producing a search warrant. Or the temporary teacher in your child's
class actually being a police officer looking to bust kids. Or a police officer
posing as a member of the clergy hearing your confessions.<p>
Imagine a police officer posing as a journalist to get information on
government whistle-blowers. In a siege will journalists now attract gunfire
just in case they are really police in disguise?<p>
One could ask too, why police did not pose as a clerical worker to get access
to the internal decision-making of the company intending to clear the trees to
allow the controversial Skyrail project to go ahead, to ensure no illegalities
there. Instead the police were assisted by the developer, and with the use of
some SBS TV labels and by lying, an arrest was effected. The protester was not
even charged with trespass, the stated reason the arrest was initiated.<p>
<hr>
<H3>Union unhappy with police deception</H3><p>
Queensland State secretary of the Media Entertainment and Arts Alliance (MEAA),
Chris Perkins, wrote complaining of the impersonation to the Minister for
Police.  Perkins also met with the Police Media Liaison unit headed by Brian
Swift. <p>
Brian Swift says that following the meeting with Perkins, recommendations on
police posing as journalists would be furnished to the Police Commissioner. "We
are formulating a policy on potentially controversial trades," he says. <p>
According to Perkins and contrary to some published reports, the sometimes
heated meeting produced a result wholly unsatisfactory to the MEAA.<p>
Perkins says he did not agree to the content of the recommendations the Media
Liaison unit developed from the meeting, despite it being reported that he had.
In fact he unconditionally condemns the practice of police impersonating
journalists. "It should not happen," he says.<p>
Reportage gave Brian Swift the hypothetical example of a police officer posing
as a journalist to visit a school to get information from school kids on drug
use.<p>
"Yes, there may be occasions where police go under cover in schools," Swift
says.<p>
But as journalists? "That would be highly unlikely. We have to operate within
the law."<p>
Swift declined to let Reportage see a copy of the recommendations put to the
minister. However we understand those recommendations suggest that the tactic
of police posing as members of the media be used only in "exceptional
circumstances", but Swift refuses to define the word "exceptional". "We will
work that out as we go," he says. "There will be no pig headed approach by
us."<p>
<hr>
<H3>Excluding bystanders</H3><p>
<p>
The writer of a newsletter on the deaths of people in prison and police custody
[See article in this issue on the reporting of Aboriginal deaths in custody]
has received a commendation in the 1994 Media Awards of the WA Equal
Opportunity Commission.<p>
Jennifer Searcy won the award for her Death in Custody Newsletter which the
award citation describes as focusing "on raising awareness and working towards
equality of treatment for prisoners and detainees".<p>
In the newsletter, Searcy gives information about the circumstances of the
deaths of people in custody and jail. She also keeps statistics on the numbers
who die and details of their deaths. <p>
Searcy, by her extensive research work has become an acknowledged authority on
the subject. She is so up to date with the issue, she was able to publish in
July last year the 93/94 figures of deaths in custody, a full eight months
before their release in March this year by the Australian Institute of
Criminology.<p>
She found that in the 12 months to 30 June 1994 there were 85 deaths in prison
or police custody in Australia. Of these, 55 deaths were in prisons, 23 during
police operations (excluding bystanders), four in police lockups, and three in
juvenile institutions.<p>
Searcy can also give the longer term picture. From January 1990 to June 1995,
there were at least 231 deaths in custody, 37 of these being Aborigines.<p>
Searcy started researching the situation of deaths in custody and producing the
newsletter, following the death of her own son jailed over a minor traffic
accident. Her newsletter has a print run of 15,000 and is sent to journalists,
lawyers, judges, bureaucrats, politicians, and others.<p>
The bi-monthly newsletter is available from Jennifer Searcy, Campaign for
Prevention of Custodial Death, PO Box 847 Nedlands, WA 6009 (phone 09 386
4783). Donations are urgently needed to help keep the newsletter afloat. While
the newsletter is free to anyone who asks, Searcy would appreciate $10 pa to
help cover production costs.<p>
<hr>
<H3>Update on British broadcasting ban</H3><p>
<p>
Loyal readers may remember an item from the second issue of Reportage in
January 1994. It is now one year since the lifting of broadcasting restrictions
that meant Sinn Fein leaders appearing on Australian TV with dubbed in actors'
voices. A spokesperson for Sinn Fein, Rita O'Hare, says, "For Section 31 [of
the Irish Broadcasting Act] and the British broadcasting ban to go in the past
year has had huge significance for Sinn Fein, presenting us with terrific
opportunities after all these years to get to people through the main media of
communication. ... I think there is no place in a modern democracy for the
powers of censorship against a particular viewpoint."<p>
<hr>
<H3>Lost opportunities</H3><p>
<p>
"The media are powerful sources of information and our group is concerned that
the Philippines and Australia are missing out on a lot of business
opportunities because of unfair and unbalanced reporting." So was launched a
new group aimed at improving news coverage of the Philippines and Australia.<p>
The Filipino Journalists Alliance of Australia (FJAA) aims to be a
non-government resource for Australian media on things Philippines, and is
composed of Filipino journalists now living in Australia.<p>
"All we read, see or hear about the Philippines in Australian media are
scandals, natural disasters or the Marcoses as if these are the only things
readers are interested in, and as if these are the only things of importance
happening in the Philippines," says FJAA spokesperson Evelyn Opilas.<p>
"On the other hand, Australians victimising Filipinos get attention in
Philippine media as if Australian pedophiles, wife bashers and drunkards make
up the majority of Australia's population.<p>
"While we cannot deny the accuracy of most of those negative stories,
Australian readers will not get a fair picture of life in the Philippines if
this is all they read about."<p>
People wanting information about the Philippines or with enquiries about the
FJAA should be contact them at PO Box A846, Sydney South 2000; or by phone on
(02) 633 3494, (02) 787 3887, (02) 372 5234, or 015 70 6929.<p>
<hr>
<H3>New Pacific Journalism Review</H3><p>
<p>
Another advance for the South Pacific Centre for Communication and Information
in Development (SPCenCIID) at the University of Papua New Guinea is the launch
of a journal, the Pacific Journalism Review.  The journal examines Papua New
Guinea and Pacific regional journalism, news media, information and
communication issues. Contributors to the first issue just published include
news media practitioners, broadcasters, journalists, and researchers.<p>
Edited by UPNG journalism lecturer, David Robie, and senior UPNG journalism
student, Tande Temane, PJR contains a range of issues including censorship,
propaganda, women in the media, and ethical issues for journalism. The first
issue also examines Fiji PM Rabuka's relationship with the media, the role of
Christian media, and attacks on journalists.<p>
Pacific Journalism Review is distributed and sold on subscription throughout
the Pacific and other regions. It is a valuable resource for people in the
media, researchers and media students. The first Review is 98 pages and is
published in book form.<p>
Further information from: The Director, South Pacific Centre for Communication
and Information in Development (SPCenCIID), UPNG, Box 320, University PO,
National Capital District, Papua New Guinea. Tel/Fax: (675+) 267191. Email:
<A HREF="MAILTO:journupng@pactok. peg.apc.org">journupng@pactok. peg.apc.org</A>.<p>
Subscriptions are available; prices for Australia and Pacific: K10 pa. Make
cheques/drafts payable to Journalism UPNG. Send to: Journalism Publications,
SPA 1339, SPCenCIID, UPNG, Box 320, Uni PO, NCD, Papua New Guinea. <p>
Other publications are also available from SPCenCIID: the UPNG student-produced newspaper Uni Tavur: K15 pa, and Ita Diba, the quarterly Centre newsletter:
K10.<p>
<hr>
<H3>News media in the Pacific Island nations</H3><p>
<p>
The news media in the South Pacific may be small, but the region has a diverse
and vibrant mass communications industry. Ranging from the PNG Post-Courier
(circulation 41,000) and Fiji Times, to the fortnightly Tuvalu Echoes and
monthly Madang Watcher, from EMTV's national broadcasts via the Indonesian
Palapa satellite to Niue's tiny television unit, from PNG's National
Broadcasting Commission's Kalang and Karai services to Tokelau's traffic and
weather broadcasts: the media caters for an audience and readership scattered
over many islands and atolls. In French Polynesia, for example, the radio and
television stations broadcast to 160,000 people spread over an ocean territory
as large as Europe. Niue has a population of 2000; Papua New Guinea has more
than four million.<p>
The first comprehensive resource book on the South Pacific news media, Nius
Bilong Pasifik, was launched in January by the University of Papua New Guinea
Press, in association with SPCenCIID and the ACIJ. In the book, 18 prominent
Pacific journalists and media educators explore the nature and problems of the
region's mass communications industry. <p>
The book includes chapters on ownership and control in the Pacific, democracy
and the media in Tonga, the PNG Internal Security Act and crime, the greening
of the media, TV's clash of culture and content, New Caledonia's Radio Djiido,
bias and race tagging dilemmas, the lost plot in Fiji, regional organisations
and the media, and Australian media coverage of the Bougainville crisis.<p>
Edited by University of PNG journalism lecturer and author David Robie, this is
a unique book of value to all interested in the Pacific, as well as journalism
students, sociology and political science researchers and professional
journalists. The 280-page book has an extensive country profile section on each
Pacific nation with a map, social and political information and details of the
news media.<p>
The book is distributed in Australia by the ACIJ. For orders and inquiries
telephone (02) 330 2488. Price $19.95, plus $3 postage and packaging. See order
form at back of Reportage.<p>
<hr>
<H3>El Salvador media update</H3><p>
<p>
Apparently El Salvador's new independent weekly, Primera Plana (PP), has struck
a few problems. Angered by the competition media barons from the big dailies El
Diario de Hoy and La Prensa Grafica are making the newspaper's life difficult,
reports Vivien Altman, who wrote the article on El Salvador's post-war media
that appeared in Reportage Summer 1994/95.<p>
There are reports that PP is finding it hard to sell advertising copy and it
seems even some of their distributors are being harassed. "Boycotted," PP's
director Horacio Moya told Altman. "It's implicit, rather than explicit."<p>
PP is a new 24 page weekly describing itself as an "adventure, a responsibility
and a challenge in this new historical moment". "The paper wants to contribute
to the development of a democratic culture," stated an editorial. The paper has
taken a stand against the predominant machismo of Salvadoran society and
carries a regular column written by a feminist group.<p>
Launched last September, the paper is now selling more than 8,000 copies a
week, although circulation is considerably lower than hoped for. Moya told
Altman he is optimistic: "We've broken the back on advertising, pulling in more
money than we were."<p>
With El Salvador being an largely oral culture, finding a market for the paper
is not easy, says Altman. One medium term plan is to sell copy in the US where
a fifth of the Salvadoran population lives. But right now the biggest obstacle
is to capture a slice of the local Salvadoran market.<p>
<hr>
<H3>Psst, Bougainville</H3><p>
<p>
A dossier of reports of human rights abuses occurring on the island of
Bougainville was launched at the NSW Parliament House Theatrette on May 1.  The
document lists possibly hundreds of deaths and attacks on civilians on the
island since the conflict broke out into guerilla warfare in 1989. Titled,
Marilyn's List, the report was compiled by Marilyn Havini who lived on
Bougainville for 20 years and is married to a pro-independence Bougainville
Interim Government member.<p>
The reports are drawn from the now-shut Bougainville newspaper, Arawa Bulletin,
from PNG's Post Courier, the PNG Times, interviews with refugees, Amnesty
International, reports from relief agencies, as well as press releases from the
Bougainville Interim Government.<p>
The dossier, by putting on the record details of abuses, must be seen as a
challenge to those in the media and governments of PNG and Australia who deny
and downplay the reports. It would make sense if there was some way an
independent organisation could investigate and report on the claims, now that
fighting on the island has declined. At present in many of the instances
recorded, the media is faced with opposing truth claims by opposing sides of
the conflict. <p>
Now in terms of news events such a launch would normally expect to attract a
small group of reporters, prepared to ask hard questions of the author and to
perhaps later seek government responses to the document.<p>
But no, we are talking about Bougainville. The credibility of groups
campaigning for Bougainville in Australia seems at an all time low, partly due
to unfair attacks on them, partly due to their own actions. <p>
So how did the media treat the launch? With almost complete silence - the media
scrum at the launch consisted of one journalist. An organiser of the launch
said dozens of media outlets were invited, but that just a single journalist,
from community radio station Radio Skid Row, attended the launch.<p>
Reports did run on Radio 2SER and the ABC's Indian Pacific program, as well as
Radio Skid Row.<p>
Copies of the 30 page report are available free of cost to journalists and
interested others from Marilyn Havini, c/- PO Box 134, Erskinville NSW 2034.<p>
<hr>
<H3>Revising anniversaries</H3><p>
<p>
At a time of anniversaries as there have been lately, a great struggle often
takes place by historians and revisionists trying to establish their
interpretation of events as the true story, often spilling over into the media.
On April 29 celebrations greeted the 225th anniversary of the landing of
Captain James Cook at Kurnell in Sydney, and interestingly the local mayor used
the occasion to apologise to Aboriginal people for the effects of the British
invasion. <p>
A re-enactment with the new Endeavour showed the kids what a jolly chap was old
Cook. But the news reports and articles left out one uncomfortable fact:
Lieutenant Cook shot an Aborigine on the shore before he had even placed a foot
on the soil of the Great South Land. <p>
After a stone was thrown at his longboat, Cook shot at several gathered people,
with one man who was shot several times seen running away bleeding profusely.
Maybe this could be added to reports of the next anniversary.<p>
On April 28, as a part of its extensive Vietnam War End coverage, the Sydney
Morning Herald stated: "1964 - North Vietnam attacks US destroyer Maddox in
Gulf of Tonkin. US bombing of North Vietnam begins". This event had been the
pretext for the massive escalation of the US war effort, with the first US
combat troops being landed early the next year. Great, only thing is it never
happened quite that way. It is now generally accepted that the destroyer was in
fact within North Vietnamese territorial limits and had been shelling supply
bases within North Vietnam; there's even doubt as to whether the Maddox was
attacked at all. You'd think at a time of commemoration and admissions that
fighting the war was wrong, we could at least be told who started the war.<p>
But the biggest blooper was the effort of Army Magazine, the official magazine
of the Australian Army. They wrote that the Vietnam War ended on 27 January,
1972. Tell that to the Vietnamese, you may say. The war continued for three
years and three months after this date, with Saigon being captured by North
Vietnamese forces on April 30, 1975. The executive editor of Army Magazine,
Captain Eric Combe, says it was an error, though the date is uncannily close to
when the main part of the Australian force, the Australian Army Task Force,
departed Vietnam. So when did the war end for Australian troops?<p>
The SMH ran a piece revising several myths of the Vietnam War: "In fact all
Australian troops had been withdrawn from Vietnam by the end of 1971". But that
was wrong too. It was not until December 11, 1972, that the newly elected
Whitlam government announced that the Australian Army Assistance Group was to
be withdrawn within three weeks. Capt Combe says that the last Australian
troops to leave Vietnam were the Australian Logistics Support Group in January
1973. He also tells of the very last two Australian soldiers, members of the
Army PR unit, fighting on the gangway to be the last to leave.<p>
<p>
<hr>
