<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<head><title>BOOK REVIEWS</title></head>
<p>
<CENTER><H1>Going for Red Black and Gold:</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER><H2>The Indigenous Media Manual</H2></CENTER><p>
<p>
<B>Edited by Diana Plater<p>
Jumbunna Centre for Australian Indigenous Studies, Education and Research, 1994
74pp, $12<p>
ISBN 0 646 22855 2<p></B>
<CITE>Reviewed by Peter Cronau</CITE>
<hr>
<p>
The best thing about The Indigenous Media Manual is that this is no dry
textbook giving a mere academic view of how the media should cover Aboriginal
affairs. Its hands-on advice to Aboriginal people in their dealings with the
media is to take control, to ensure that they get their message across.<p>
Try this example of taking control from one of the people interviewed for the
book, Michael Mansell of the Tasmanian Aboriginal Legal Service: "If it is not
a live studio interview and you feel you did not go well, ask the interviewer
to repeat the question".<p>
Such simple but powerful advice comes from Mansell's years of experience in
dealing with a sometimes hostile media, and reflects his knowledge of how the
media works. He knows that at best just a short grab will appear, so an answer
repeated without bloopers will more likely be used.<p>
The Indigenous Media Manual aims to improve the ability of Aboriginal people to
provide the media with positive images of Aboriginal business. Rhoda Roberts,
an Aboriginal journalist on SBS's Vox Populi, writes in the Introduction to the
book that the positive image of sportsperson, Cathy Freeman, has shown that to
be Aboriginal is to be "original, talented and proud".<p>
"Her brilliantly conceived act changed the debate about Aboriginal affairs in
this nation. No longer are we, indigenous people, prepared to be seen as
victims, a threat or criminals. And we believe that positive images in the
media are the way to make people change their views," says Roberts.<p>
Put together by the Jumbunna Centre for Australian Indigenous Studies,
Education and Research, based at the University of Technology, Sydney, this
book will help empower Aborigines in their dealings with the media.<p>
To my knowledge it is the first generally available book of its type to address
Aboriginal people as its primary audience. A guide put together several years
ago by ATSIC in Perth titled Yarning With The Media, is no longer available.
Most previous books and guides have spoken to the general audience of mainly
non-Aboriginal journalists who are interested in writing on Aboriginal
issues.<p>
Among those titles, Signposts: A Guide For Journalists, published by the ACIJ
and co-edited by the editor of the present work, and Lester Bostock's, The
Greater Perspective: A Guideline For The Production Of Film And Television On
Aborigines And Torres Strait Islanders, a guide prepared for SBS TV, are the
most useful.<p>
Several Aboriginal communities have also developed their own media guides, such
as the Yuendumu-based Warlpiri Media Association's guidelines for media
covering Aboriginal issues in Central Australia.<p>
The team assembled by the Jumbunna Centre to put the manual together was led by
the editor, Dianna Plater, with co-editor Rhoda Roberts. The researchers on the
manual, Marnie Aquilina and Fiona Smith, are both Aboriginal students in BA
Communications at the UTS.<p>
The manual leads people through the process of presenting themselves to the
media, by first asking what it is people want from using the media. <p>
Once that is clear the manual describes who owns the media and how it works. It
tells what sort of stories get a run, and reveals the ethical obligations of
journalists. And it describes step-by-step hints on how to get on good terms
with journalists.<p>
There is a chapter on writing a press release and handling an interview. The
book even has a chapter on what to do when the news is bad, and how to make
conflict work for you.<p>
At the end is a guide to complaining about the media, just in case. There is
also a guide to the essential media outlets in the country together with fax
numbers, the ideal thing for an organisation wanting to get its message out.<p>
A criticism of the book could be its length, at just 74 pages. But in the real
world people working in Aboriginal organisations and in community organisations
don't often have the time to wade through anything much bigger.<p>
The advice provided in the present manual will prove useful to many normally
powerless groups and not just Aboriginal organisations. Every progressive
community-based organisation would benefit from using this book.<p>
George Negus, veteran journalist<p>
now with the ABC's Foreign Correspondent, says in the book the best advice on
dealing with a hostile media is to "either ignore them or answer in a
non-hostile way". He suggests Aboriginal groups trying to get balanced coverage
not be dissuaded by the negative reporting of some media outlets.<p>
"You will encounter some journalists and media that are biased, if not racist.
So it is good advice to not trust any journalist's judgement. Be aware - they
cannot always be trusted to have balanced reporting."<p>
Negus suggests to try to spread across many media outlets. "When you do find
journalists that support Aboriginal issues and are striking for balanced
reporting, exploit them. The media exploits you for their benefit, do the
same."<p>
And there are some tactics that Negus suggests can give an Aborigine being
interviewed the upper hand in an interview. "You will most likely know more
about the issue than the interviewer - this is especially true in Aboriginal
affairs. This is also a good psychological ploy. For example, if a journalist
asks you a question or makes a statement that you know is incorrect, say so."<p>
Sometimes though the media gets itself into a hunting frenzy in trying to cover
a bad news story about Aborigines. Cameron Forbes of The Australian believes,
however, it is possible to salvage an interview that is concentrating on a
negative side of a story. "If you have investigated the issue to be reported
and are honest in your interview - that is, honest about the good and bad
points - you can at least turn a negative story into a balanced one."<p>
That is what this book is mainly about - turning what has largely been a
negative story into a balanced one. Here's a selection of the sometimes
surprising advice that the book provides.<p>
Ray Martin of Channel Nine's Current Affair: "Make general comparisons with
whites. With any public money, there is always a risk of somebody ripping off
the system. If you are being accused of an alleged misuse of funds, remind the
interviewers of the Skases and the Bonds. Remember reporters are always looking
for scapegoats, so if the story is about single parents ripping off funds, say
it is only a handful, not all and there is a need to tighten the system."<p>
Marcia Langton of the Cape York Land Council: "Always work out first of all
whether what you are saying is `on the record' or `off the record'. Make it
very clear if you want what you are saying to be reported or not."<p>
Lester Bostock, media consultant: "Personal opinions are not wise. Always have
prepared statements. Be aware of not being pushed into making personal
comments. Say what you have to and leave. This applies to print, radio and
television media."<p>
Robert Tickner, Minister for Aboriginal Affairs: "Journalists' questions are
often based on wrong assumptions. If I am caught with those sorts of questions
I always return to basics in answering."<p>
Jack Waterford, deputy-editor at the Canberra Times: "Aboriginal people should
invite more people into their community. Be more proactive ... Let reporters
know what you believe is the future for Aboriginal affairs and what particular
concerns need to be addressed."<p>
Others whose advice is included in the manual are Paul Murphy (SBS TV), Paul
Lyneham (ABC TV), James Button (Time Australia), Barbara McCarthy (ABC TV),
Alan Knight (UTS), Debra Jopson (Sydney Morning Herald), Michael Shoreston
(Centralian Advocate), and Diana Simmonds (Bulletin).<p>
The advice they provide will help Aboriginal people get a more positive and
realistic picture across to the public through the media.<p>
But sometimes no amount of preparation can save the day, as Michael Mansell has
found out: "When doing an interview on Real Life, Stan Grant welcomed me in the
studio saying `G'day brother'. When we went to air the first question he threw
at me was an attack and I was not prepared for it as he had been quite friendly
and I thought he was on-side. But I guess Stan was just doing his job."<p>
<p>
(The Indigenous Media Manual is available for $12 plus $3 postage, from
Jumbunna Centre, UTS, PO Box 123, Broadway NSW 2007.)<p>
<p>
