<head><title>In safe hands</title></head>
<H1>In safe hands</H1><p>

<HR WIDTH=100%>

The IFJ Safety Fund has been established to aid journalists attacked for
telling the truth.<p>
<p>
The 1990s have been years of hope for democracy in Europe, of racial equality
in South Africa, and of renewed hope for peace in the Middle East. But they
have also been years of unprecedented violence against journalists.<p>
In response to the growing number of attacks the International Federation of
Journalists launched the "The IFJ Safety Fund" in 1992.<p>
This Fund provides humanitarian aid for journalists and their families. It
helps pay legal costs when journalists have to defend themselves. It gives
support and encouragement to journalists in all corners of the world, many of
whom feel isolated and defenceless.<p>
All member unions were asked to campaign for the fund, to prepare their own
material in the local languages and to collect donations, not only in the
framework of the union but, beyond that, by asking media organisations to give
their support.<p>
Journalists in need from all countries in Asia-Pacific, whether they are
members of the IFJ or not, can apply for assistance from the IFJ Safety Fund.
Further information from Marie-Anne Paquet at the IFJ: 266 rue Royale, 1260
Brussels. Telephone: 32 2 223 2265<p>
<p>
<p>
