<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: PNGJA</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>PNG journalists revive association</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW04: 11 November 1996
<P>
Title -- M53 MEDIA: PNG journos revive union
Date -- 11 November 1996
Byline -- Kevin Rale Pamba
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- The National (PNG), 11/11/96
Copyright -- The National
Status -- Unabridged</B>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
By Kevin Rale Pamba<BR>
PORT MORESBY: A meeting of journalists held at the Granville Motel here on Saturday decided to revive the Papua New Guinea Journalists Association (PNGJA).
<P>
An interim executive committee chosen on the occasion vowed to make the association a body that journalists can count on.
<P>
Post-Courier's chief political reporter Neville Togarewa was voted unanimously as interim president by the meeting.
<P>
He said the meeting was long overdue and journalists now, more than ever, needed to stand together to protect their profession.
<P>
Mr Togarewa and journalists from various news media organisations stressed the need to stand together against the challenges facing the profession.
<P>
The Independent's editor, Dominic Kakas, appealed to all working journalists to support the revived PNGJA as it was lack of support and interest that had it deregistered earlier.
<P>
Interim treasurer Ambie Bulum said lack of commitment by members was the reason that killed the former association.
<P>
The interim executive will look at various issues concerning journalists, including the Constitutional Review Commission-sponsored Media Accountability Bill that will be brought before Parliament which resumes session tomorrow.
<P>
Chief Ombudsman Simon Pentanu, who delivered the keynote address at the meeting, said: "You must revive the association and I wish you all the best.
<P>
"Let us be frank. There will always be opposition to press freedom all over the world. This opposition invariably comes from people and institutions who do not like truth being disclosed," he said.
<P>
"Truth will always hurt some people. But the truth is the lifeblood of any decent and honest society, which is the sort of place we should be trying to make Papua New Guinea," Mr Pentanu said.
<P>
"The truth is certainly something worth fighting for and maybe its even something to get 'savage' about. I wish the revived PNGJA all the best in its endeavours. You do have a fight on your hands. But I know that in the end truth will always prevail," Mr Pentanu said.
<P>
PNG Trade Union Congress General Secretary John Paska offered his support to the association and said unionism is about fairness and justice in bread and butter issues of an employee and professional issues.
<P>
He said the PNGJA will be an avenue for journalists to speak on these two areas.
<P>
Mr Paska gave suggestions on how to run the PNGJA and what can be done to make it strong.
<P>
The executive includes senior reporter of The Independent Abby Yadi (vice-president) and The National's business editor Cletus Ngaffkin (secretary).<BR>
+++pacmediawire
