<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: Baing</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Baing admits trying to stop EM TV program</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW05 The National (PNG): 2 October 1996
<P>
<HR>
<P>
In Parliament by Philip Kepson and Kevin Rale Pamba</B><BR>
PORT MORESBY: Forest Minister Andrew Baing yesterday admitted in Parliament that he had made four attempts to stop EM TV from broadcasting a program on Bougainville.
<P>
EM TV had broadcast an exclusive program involving an EM TV news crew interviewing rebel leader Sam Kauona last Sunday.
<P>
Mr Baing said he telephoned EM TV four times to try to stop the station from going ahead with the program because "it appeared to be promoting the rebel activities and was not suitable for public viewing".
<P>
Mr Baing made the admission when replying to a poser from Lae MP Bart Philemon during question time, to admit or deny that he had telephoned EM TV and interfered with its programming last Sunday.
<P>
"I rang up EM TV to stop the program because it appeared not to be in the interest of the people. Everything that appeared on the screen was all promotion of rebels' activities," said Mr Baing.
<P>
EM TV's news editor, Titi Gabi, said yesterday that Mr Baing had called four times whhile the program was on air, adding that the station had performed its normal duty as a media organisation.
<P>
"We played our duty and that was to try to inform the truyth about what was happening on Bougainville. However, it was not our role to promote any one party's interest on any subject or issue. And if anyone has taken us wrong about our Sunday's program, we owe no apology to anyone," said Ms Gabi.
<P>
She said a copy of the program had been given to Prime Minister's Department Secretary Noel Levi and his staff for viewing the previous Monday with the hope of getting their view on it before the broadcast on Sunday, but they had failed to turn up.
<P>
The program, entitled <B>The Ultimatium</B>, contained an interview with Kauona in which he threatened to execute five security force hostages unless troops are withdrawn from Bougainville and the island's independence is recognised.
<P>
Said Mr Baing: "As far as the government is concerned, the program must be in the interests of Papua New Guinea as a nation.
<P>
"And we do not allow press in this country to advocate and promote issues that are detrimental to the nation.
<P>
"The press of this country must have a responsibility to report and encourage unity in this country.
<P>
"It cannot go and put in the title of the program Sam Kauona gives an ultimatum to this government, it (program) encouraged that we should talk about disunity," Mr Baing said.
<P>
Meanwhile, the Media Council of PNG said it hoped that this was a one-off incident.
<P>
"This is frightening if politicians think they can pick up the phone and stop a television station or newspaper running a story," said Anna Solomon, council chairperson and editor-in-chief of The Independent newspaper.
<P>
Ms Solomon said the council would wait to hear from EM TV before considering lodging a formal complaint against Mr Baing.
<P>
<Font size=1>© 1996 The National and Pacific Media Watch.</FONT 1>
</table>
