<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: Cullen</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Press freedom and responsibility</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW06 The Independent (PNG): 11 October 1996
<P>
<HR>
<P>
Letter to the Editor, The Independent</B><BR>
I LIVED for ten years under President Banda's dictatorship in Malawi, southern Africa. Press freedom was virtually non-existent. So it was like a breath of fresh air coming to Papua New Guinea and seeing how much freedom the press enjoys here. But sometimes I feel it goes over the top.
<P>
To illustrate my point, I refer to two recent letters in the Post-Courier. The first, attempting to what I would call character assassination of Mr Peter Barter, the Provincial Affairs Minister.
<P>
While the writer (who hasn't the courage to reveal his true identity) is fully entitled to express his views about Mr Barter's figures on poker machines, he ends his letter: "It is no wonder that all provincial government claims of a lack of funds are prevalent and remain unresolved by Mr Barter as minister".
<P>
Apart from being both an illogical and unreasonable conclusion, such a wild generalisation comes extremely close to defamation. By adding: "God help our provinces and God help our people," Mr Trump boarders(sic) on the blasphemous. In certain countries, Mr Barter would be within his rights to sue for defamation.
<P>
As a journalist, I"m not in the business of promoting any particular politician. I let their record speak for itself.
<P>
As a politician, Mr Barter's, I think, is quite impressive. Look at the many social, health and educational care projects he promoted and sponsored in Madang. They would be the envy of many politicians and constituencies. It came as no surprise when he was asked to join the cabinet to bolster its image and calibre.
<P>
This brings me to the second letter (dated October 2), where Mr Public Servant blames Mr Barter for attempting to trim the public service. Again, everyone is entitled to share their opinion and feelings but when such views turn into a bare-faced personal vendetta, then press freedom is being used irresponsibly.
<P>
Mr Public Servant presumes Mr Barter created the present crisis. But look at the facts. He's only been in the caninet a few months. Sinvce then he's been on the road for a great deal of that time, travelling to most of the 19 provinces trying to sort out the mess.
<P>
Ending the letter with the comment, "but why when we pay you politicians many peanuts, do we get so much monkey business" is not only derogatory but tarnishes all politicians with the same degree or (sic) ineptitude. In my opinion, such remarks tilt dangerously towards possible libel.
<P>
Press freedom is an invaluable asset for any developing country. It should be fiercely protected. Debate and disagreements must be aired.
<P>
But a press that allows defamatory and spiteful attacks to go unchecked, whether they are against Mr Barter  or any other politician or public figure, does not help provide constructive and informed debate.
<P>
Fr Trevor Cullen<BR>
Head of Journalism<BR>
Divine Word Institute<BR>
Madang<BR> 
<P>
<Font size=1>© 1996 The Independent and Pacific Media Watch.</FONT 1>
</table>
<HR>
<A HREF="../index.html"><IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=30>  Return to Pacific Media Watch index</A></p>
</body>
