<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: Control</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>Media bills deferred for consultations</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW02: 13 November 1996
<P>
Title -- 335 MEDIA: "Control" Bills deferred
Date -- 13 November 1996
Byline -- Neville Togarewa
Origin -- Pacific Media Watch
Source -- Post-Courier (PNG), 13/11/96
Copyright -- Post-Courier
Status -- Unabridged</B> 
<P>
<HR>
<P>
By Neville Togarewa<BR>
The Constitutional Review Commission made an eleventh-hour decision to hold "intensive two-week consultative meetings" to discuss Bills relating to media accountability.
<P>
It took the decision after meeting at Parliament House on Monday and yesterday morning to consider and approve the Information and Communication Media Commission Bill.
<P>
Although the commission said in a statement that its decision was prompted by "goodwill", the Post-Courier was told last night that commission members had been told to expect a political backlash if the Bills were tabled in their present form.
<P>
The Information and Communication Authority Bill seeks to establish an
authority to "regulate" and "control" licensing of TV, radio, and newspaper
companies. The Media Commission Bill, if passed, would give the Government power to "register" journalists.
<P>
The implication is that only "registered" journalists would be allowed to work as reporters.
<P>
Commission members at yesterday's meeting  were warned about a political backlash from a public concerned about government tampering with freedom of expression and freedom of the press.
<P>
There was a strong possibility that media accountability would become an
election issue, they were told.
<P>
The commission released a statement saying chairman Ben Micah had received unanimous support from his commissioners for further consultations on the two Bills, and on proposed laws relating to freedom of information, copyright and defamation. 
<P>
A spokesman said that although the Bills had been prepared from
recommendations of the Commission's report on media accountability, "it
would be proper that interests groups from media and from telecommunication industry look at the draft laws and discuss with the CRC any areas of concern."
<P>
"What we may not see as restrictive could be viewed by others as restrictive," the spokesman said. "What we may see as an initiative to bring in more accountability could be viewed by others as control measures. That is why we must come to some understanding and compromise for the good of all concerned."
<P>
The commission appointed one of its members, PNG Trade Union Congress general secretary John Paska, to head a three-man committee to conduct the consultations.
<P>
The two members are Alotau MP Iairo Lasaro and Kiriwina-Goodenough MP Gerald Beona.
<P>
The Bills would be deferred and then submitted to Cabinet for approval before being presented in Parliament.<BR>
