<head><title> Pacific Media Watch: News Ltd</title></head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<HR>
<TD width=475 align=left>
<IMG SRC="../images/pmwlogo.gif" WIDTH=100> <Font size=6>Pacific Media Watch</Font 6>
<h1>News Ltd to stick to PNG commitment - chairman</h1>
<Font size=3><B>PMW03: 13 November 1996
<P>
Title -- 336 MEDIA: News Ltd 'committed to PNG'
Date -- 13 November 1996
Byline -- Oseah Philemon
Origin -- Niuswire
Source -- Post-Courier (PNG), 13/11/96
Copyright -- Post-Courier
Status -- Unabridged</B>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
By Oseah Philemon<BR>
Editor of the Post-Courier<BR>
The Post Courier Limited, publishers of the Post-Courier, yesterday declared its commitment in the future of Papua New Guinea.
<P>
Chairman Peter Chegwyn told the company's annual general meeting the board had a "very positive" view of PNG's future.
<P>
"Turning to politics briefly - and I must say reluctantly - we are often accused by politicians and others of being negative about PNG by highlighting issues such as law and order problems and political corruption.
<P>
"On the contrary, South Pacific Post has a very positive view of Papua New Guinea's future.
<P>
"We have demonstrated our confidence iin PNG over many years through our continuing investment in new technology and training - amounting to many millions of kina," Mr Chegwyn said.
<P>
Mr Chegwyn said: "The media plays a pivotal role in a democracy.
<P>
"Our challenge is three-fold: Firstly, to properly inform the people of Papua New Guinea; secondly, to accurately record the unfolding history of the nation; and thirdly , to stand up firmly when we believe the national interest is not being served.
<P>
"In meeting this challenge, we sometimes come into conflict with people in powerful positions.
<P>
"We are happy to accept constructive criticism of our role in PNG affairs, but we will not resile from our commitment to the People of Papua New Guinea.
<P>
"Turning to so-called foreign ownership, News Limited, the major shareholder in South Pacific Post, does not regard itself as a "foreigner" in PNG.
<P>
Mr Chegwyn said he was proud to say that of the 225 staff employed by South Pacific Post, 213 were Papua New Guinean men and women drawn from every province in the country.
<P>
Some were shareholders of the company, he said.
<P>
"We are very proud of our Papua New Guinean staff and we are committed to providing on-going training to ensure our people reach their full potential.
<P>
"News Limited - the world's leading communications company - has a strong, long-term commitment to its shareholders, staff, readers, advertisers and commercial printing clients in this country," he said.
<P>
As an example, Mr Chegwyn said the company had just spent K300,000 on upgrading its cybergraphic computer system, giving staff a state-of-the-art platform from which to move to full pagination of editorial and classified pages.
<P>
This investment put the company at the forefront of newspaper technology and
would result in lower overheads, fewer mistakes and better-looking newspapers
for our readers and advertisers, he said.
<P>
"We have budgeted to spend K250,000 this financial year on a major upgrade of the Goss newspaper press," Mr Chegwyn said.
<P>
"This will significantly improve our press's color printing capability, giving our advertisers the quality they demand in this increasingly color-conscious market.
<P>
"The company's recent investment of over K1 million in an advance color scanner
and a four-color computer-controller Komori press has been vindicated. Post Printing is now recognised as the number one quality color printing house in the South Pacific."
<P>
Mr Chegwyn said to maintain that commitment, large amounts of capital investment would be required in the coming years to enable the company to continue to bring the benefits of communications technology to the people of PNG.
<P>
"Sound investment decisions can only be made when the investor has a reasonable belief that the ground rules are not going to be changed midstream," Mr Chegwyn said.<BR>
