<HEAD><TITLE>Issue 2, Law</TITLE></HEAD> 
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=390 HEIGHT=80 ALT="Uni Tavur" ALIGN=TOP SRC="UniT_mast.gif"></CENTER>

<HR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
<TD width= 200></TD><td align =left> http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/UniT_296_Law.html</td><tr>
</table>
<hr>

<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
Lawyers back death penalty against critics.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Lawrence Fong</strong><p>

A University of Papua New Guinea academic has defended the country's reintroduction of the death penalty despite Amnesty International's latest strong condemnation.<P>

Yoli Tom'tavala, international law lecturer in the university+s law faculty, said yesterday that Amnesty International advocated what it was set up to support - protection and promotion of human rights.<P> 

But the organisation's condemnation could not stop PNG retaining the death penalty.<P>

"From PNG's point of view, there is no rule or law disallowing the practice of death penalty. It is perfectly okay and legal and conforms with our law," he said.<P>

Mr Tom'tavala was commenting on the London-based human rights organisation's new report, "Papua New Guinea: The death penalty - not the solution". The report condemns the Government over reintroduction of the death penalty. <P>

The report said an appeal against a death sentence was imminent, but this could not be confirmed with the Supreme Court registry. <P>

Charles Ombusu, a young man convicted of rape and wilful murder, was sentenced to death last year. His appeal is pending. <P>

The Amnesty report said PNG's decision to reintroduce the death penalty in 1991 was an "impulsive reaction" to public anger over violent crime. It added that the Government had not taken sufficient account of "strong and prominent opposition" within PNG to the death sentence. <P>

Mr Tom'tavala said: "PNG is not one of the countries which have adopted the international convention or agreement that outlaws the death penalty, therefore it is not bound by any international law to stop it." <P>

Mr Tom'tavala said even though people might have different moral views, PNG's position was clear on legal grounds. Section two of the Criminal Code Amendment Act "allows for a person who commits wilful murder to be liable to be sentenced to death".<P>

Tony Regan, another law lecturer, echoed Mr Tom'tavala's legal views, saying the death penalty was constitutional but it was up to the courts to decide whether it was appropriate.<P>

But he also said there was no link between the death penalty and reduced crime anywhere in the world. There had also been cases where innocent people had been executed.<P>







<HR><table border=0 width=100%>
<td width =49%>

