<HEAD><TITLE>Issue 2, Env</TITLE></HEAD> 
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=390 HEIGHT=80 ALT="Uni Tavur" ALIGN=TOP SRC="UniT_mast.gif"></CENTER>

<HR>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
<TD width= 200></TD><td align =left> http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/UniT_296_Env.html</td><tr>
</table>
<hr>

<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
Environment campaigner blasts media as 'too soft'.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Aiva Tamate and  Raphael Semel </strong><p>


<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475> <TD width= 475  align =left>


A grassroots speaker at last week's media freedom seminar has accused the news media of being "controlled" by Government and big business. 
</td></tr>
</table>

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475>
<td width =295 align left>

<br>Joseph Ka'au, a former Wantok editor and now campaigner for Greenpeace Pacific, said news media were too lenient on political leaders. <P>

He urged reporters to "hear the cries of your people" and cover resource development issues more rigorously.<P>

"I think the media have got more lenient today - they have got softer," he said.<P>

"I think they've got deeper into bed with Government and big business. They've forgotten the small people."<P>

He cited Porgera, Kutubu and Ok Tedi as examples of how the public should be asking questions about how the news media was performing.<P> 

"The media should be accountable to this country ... to the people of this country," he said.<P>

<td align=center> <IMG  alt= "Mr. Joseph Ka'au." SRC= "UT-Kaau.jpg"></td><tr>

</table>


<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475> <TD width= 475  align =left>

Last year, BHP had allegedly helped the Government of Papua New Guinea draw up legislation to "effectively stop our people from exercising their basic democratic right" to claim fair compensation for environmental damage, Mr Ka+au said.<P>

"In my view that legislation also effectively indicated that Papua New Guinean judges cannot be relied on to make fair and sound judgments on such claims. Now, it is a non issue."<P>

Last December, a national doctor had alleged on a television program that a person living along the Lagaip/Strickland River had died from possible chemical poisoning.<P>

"The program showed also that Porgera Joint Venture was probably discharging more heavy metals into the river system than allowed and that it had no compliance criteria for mercury -- a highly toxic chemical once in the food chain," he said.<P>

"What are we waiting for? Ten more people to die? One hundred more people to die? You tell me.<P>

"Two months later, zero media interest." <P>

Mr Ka'au recounted his experience as a journalist covering the temporary halt of the Kutubu oil pipeline construction by angry landowners in 1992. He claimed 
several stories of his were not published in the face of hostile industry pressure.<P>

"More problems are emerging now at Kutubu. Sosoro Hewago is rightfully asking for his share now," Mr Ka'au said.<P>

"I would suggest that he ask his cut -- maybe 10 per cent from Chevron and another 10 per cent from British Petroleum. The initial dissatisfaction was expressed back in 1992."<P>

Mr Ka'au claimed reporters needed to be from the streets or jungles of PNG to adequately report about the effect of policies on grassroots life. <P>

"How many of us from the media world can raise our hands and say, 'Yes, I used to collect bottles in Port Moresby to feed, cloth and educate myself?'" he asked.<P>

He also attacked the reliance by many PNG journalists on "fax and telephone journalism."<P>

Jessie Waibauru, president of the Journalism Students Society, criticised some media organisations for hiring unqualified staff in place of graduates or professional journalists.<P>

"This undermines our qualifications and the commitment by students to become ethical and professional journalists," she said. No organisations were identified, but it is understood some students are particularly concerned about a radio station.<P>


</td><tr>
</table>


