<HEAD><TITLE>Issue 6, Cover</TITLE></HEAD> 
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=390 HEIGHT=80 ALT="Uni Tavur" ALIGN=TOP SRC="UniT_mast.gif"></CENTER>

<hr>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
<TD width= 200></TD><td align =left> http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/UniT_696_Men.html</td><tr>
</table>
<hr>

<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
Menei defies court in  leadership feud.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Staff Reporters </strong><p>


<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475> <TD width= 475  align =left>

A national student leader at the centre of a bitter student politics feud
yesterday defied a summons to appear in court for alleged defamation.<P>

Leslie Menei, president of the Student Representive Council at the University
of Papua New Guinea, and also elected leader of one faction of the
controversial National Union of Students, was assaulted by students opposed to
his leadership on Monday.
</td><TR>
</TABLE>

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475>
<td width =270 align left>

<br>The next day he was served with the summons demanding that he appear in the
Boroko District Court.<P>

Mr Menei did not go. But he told Uni Tavur yesterday the differences over
leadership were 'on the verge of reconciliation'.<p>
  
His lawyer, Aloxy Donigi, appeared in court on his behalf.<P>

"Normally 14 days' notice is given to allow a defendant to prepare for the
case. I was only given two days - that isn't on," Mr Menei said.<P>

NUS president Mathew Parep, who served the summons, alleged that during a
debate at the campus forum on May 18 Mr Menei had branded him a "conman" and
his officials "conmen".<P>

He has also sought an injunction preventing Mr Menei using the NUS name. Mr
Menei denied any defamation. Mr Menei said, "I never implicated anyone, it was
a general statement."<P>

He appealed to student leaders not to stir up trouble as students prepare for
next month's examinations.<P>

</td>

<td align=center> <IMG  alt= "Mr. Oaeke." SRC= "UT-Menei.jpg"></td><tr>
</table>

<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=475> <TD width= 475  align =left>
On Monday, Vice-Chancellor Dr Rodney Hills intervened to break up a fight
between Chimbu and Engan students. <P>

He said it was only a small group of students who were unable to behave
themselves.  <P>

"They should be ashamed of themselves," Dr Hills said.<P>

"This is not the behavior of a university.  Students should not resort to
physical intimidation to solve problems."<P>

Mr Menei was attacked during the fight and his glasses were smashed.<P>

The fight broke out over a notice demanding Mr Menei's resignation on Monday.<P>

Earlier, on Saturday night, students broke into Mr Menei's room and ransacked
it. The SRC office was also broken into.<P>

The notice said: "Too may secret meetings with corrupted officials and
accepting bribery (sic). Moreover, students are losing confidence in his
leadership.<P>

"Leslie Menei should resign ... [he] must go."<P>

An Engan student ripped down the notice and Chimbu Students Society president
Aula Kobale demanded that it be put back. <P>

Another notice, signed by a Chimbu official, accused Mr Menei of victimising
Chimbu students in stories which had appeared in The National, Post-Courier and
Uni Tavur.<P>

</td><tr>

</table>
