<HEAD><TITLE>Issue4,Bougainville</TITLE></HEAD> 
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=390 HEIGHT=80 ALT="Uni Tavur" ALIGN=TOP SRC="UniT_mast.gif"></CENTER>


<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
<TD width= 200></TD><td align =left> http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/UniT_496_Boug.html</td><tr>
</table>
<hr>



<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif">
<Font size= 5>Greater autonomy 'the key' to Bougainville <font size= 3><p>

<strong>By JOSEPH MOROKANA</strong><p>
		Bougainvillean leaders have reaffirmed their stand in support of greater autonomy for the province to end the eight-year-old civil war. And a politics academic at the University of PNG has called for a federal system of government.<P>
		The Regional Member for Bougainville in the National Parliament, John Momis, and South Bougainville MP, Michael Laimo told Uni Tavur greater autonomy for Bougainville was the best solution to end the fighting. <p>
		They said that it was up to the National Government to negotiate with the people of Bougainville for a lasting solution to the fighting. <p>
		Their comments come in the wake of reports that Security Forces have been harassing villagers in "pacified" areas. <P>
		Mr Momis said: "There must be a constitutional guarantee to involve the people of Bougainville in the affairs of their province."<P>
		 He said there must be some form of decentralisation of power to the citizens of the country. He also condemned the provincial government reforms. <P>
		"The next round of peace talks can come after peace and reconciliation," Mr Momis said. <p>
		Mr Laimo called on Bougainville leaders in Government-controlled areas to continue peace dialogue for more autonomy. <P>
		He urged the leaders not to wait for the Bougainville Revolutionary Army to decide for them because "they"ll never do that while hiding in the bush". <P>
	Mr Laimo said he hoped the situation would be controlled without inflicting more deaths on civilians.<p>
	Dr Ray Anere, head of UPNG's politics department, told a seminar on Bougainville that the nation must change to a federal system. He said the present system had limited flexibility, had lost its "legitimacy" - because of military and restoration expenses - and was unable to maintain peace.<P>
	Dr Anere said that unless the Government considered changing to a federal system, it would face prolonged security operations and restricted basic citizens' rights.<P>




