<HEAD><TITLE>Issue 5,Camp</TITLE></HEAD> 
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=390 HEIGHT=80 ALT="Uni Tavur" ALIGN=TOP SRC="UniT_mast.gif"></CENTER>

<hr>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
<TD width= 200></TD><td align =left> http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/UniT_596_Camp.html</td><tr>
</table>
<hr>

<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
Campus repairs crisis hits uni.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Micheal Miise </strong><p>

	The University of Papua New Guinea is facing a crisis over maintenance of its facilities, including staff housing, student halls of residence, the library, lecture theatres, fire-fighting equipment and toilets on the Waigani campus. <P>
	Staff association spokespeople and other lecturers are critical and concerned about funding cuts for the university.<P>
	But a K16 million European Union aid program planned soon for UPNG is expected to improve facilities.<P>
	The university is currently operating on a K27 million budget this year - K12 million less than the budget asked for from the Government. Among maintenance problems on campus :
<UL><LI> Air conditioning in the Michael Somare Library has been crippled for more than six weeks, causing damage to books and microfilm records. 
<LI> Air conditioning problems have also hit the main lecture theatre and the arts lecture theatre has had power problems.
<LI>Housing repairs and maintenance are said to be a standstill. 
<LI> Routine repairs in classrooms have faced long delays. 
<LI> The journalism broadcast studio has been crippled by lack of repairs. 
<LI> Toilets are described as in a "shocking" state with little maintenance or cleaning.
<LI> The number of cleaning staff has been slashed from 41 cleaners to 20. 
<LI> Fire-fighting equipment around campus is missing or in a poor state of repair.
<LI> Maintenance in student dormitories is left undone - in one case no repairs or clean-up has been done two weeks after a fire damaged a room in the Dame Mary Kekedo hall.</UL><P>
	The European Union will soon sign a K16 million project to build and rehabilitate facilities at UPNG.<P>
	Head of delegation David MacRae said the project funds would be divided between the Goroka campus, medical faculty, creative arts faculty and the main Waigani campus.<P>
	Bursar Weusi Tafawa confirmed Fletcher Morobe would construct five buildings at the Waigani and Taurama campuses. Work would begin in June or July.<P>
	 Kametan Parkop, president of the National Non-Academic Staff Association, told Uni Tavur: "A lot of major maintenance needs to be done in the university and some houses need to be demolished, but the university has no money." <P>
	A law lecturer and past president of the University Overseas Staff Association, Ted Hill, said: "Some houses require maintenance, but resources must be allocated where they are most needed.<P>
	"Money should be spent on security rather than on housing." <P>
	Another academic, a resident of Tenth St, said: "I+m very disappointed - the key of my door was broken inside the lock in 1991 and I have made requests to maintenance but nothing has being done.<P>
	"We only lock the security door, we cannot lock the inside door because the broken key is still inside."<P>
	Buildings and estates head Whitney Kawage said repairs had already been started on staff houses.<P>
	"We have had maintenance requests for sbout 55 houses and we are trying our best to do repairs for all of them," he said. <P>
	"However, my boys cannot attend to all of the requests at the same time. I only have four groups of four men who are working."<P> 	He added that he had only taken up his position last October and funds had already been exhausted.<P>
	"This year our budget has been reduced so we cannot renovate all the houses to what they were like before - we'll only do small repairs." <P>
	The main lecture theatre has been without lights for about three weeks and its air conditioning has been out of order for six weeks. <P>
	The Michael Somare Library's air conditioning has also been out for six weeks. But small units have been installed.<P>





