<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
EDITORIAL : A free student  press and it's responsibility.<font size= 3><p>



Uni Tavur was founded in 1974 as a journalism training newspaper. Originally it was published by students under an autonomous journalism diploma program based at the University of PNG but funded by the New Zealand Government. <P>
	During the past 21 years, Uni Tavur has enjoyed a tradition of editorial independence which is appropriate for a journalism education newspaper. Its objective is to provide a training ground for our journalism students to apply their theoretical knowledge to "real life" news coverage, commentary and ethical dilemmas.<P>
	In the past there has been no attempt by any university administration to compromise this basic editorial independence, even at rare times when the administration hasn+t been happy. This is a newspaper, not a university administration PR publication.<P>
	Uni Tavur is also largely self-funded. No desktop publishing facilities have been provided by the university -- all have been given by outside donors. The printing bill at the Post-Courier is met by trust funds raised by the sale of advertising. Last year's petition to the administration by journalism students for help, particularly for broadcast equipment, went largely unheeded. <P>
	Four years ago, Uni Tavur was a simple A4 format newsletter produced with rusty typewriters. Today it is a professional tabloid with an electronic edition on the Internet. It has also won awards.<P>
	The International Federation of Journalists code of conduct supported by the PNG Journalists Association includes: The first duty of the journalist is respect for truth and for the right of the public to truth ... In pursuing this duty, the journalist shall at all times defend the principles of freedom of honest collection and publication of news, and of the right of fair comment and criticism ... The journalist shall observe professional secrecy regarding the source of information obtained in confidence.<P>
	 In recent weeks we have faced some pressure from the administration over our reporting of the Dr Topul Rali affair. Former chemistry head Dr Rali was a high-profile academic paid by the state; his alleged actions last December were a very public affair involving UPNG staff and property. Such a major incident should not be masked by secrecy. It is not a "private disciplinary matter". We reported the truth about the inquiry - and the subsequent University Council decision to dismiss Dr Rali - in accordance with journalistic ethics. The public has a right to know.<P>


And we wish to assure our readers that we will continue reporting news in the public interest without fear or favour.<P>



