<HEAD><TITLE>Issue 3, Moari</TITLE></HEAD> 
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=390 HEIGHT=80 ALT="Uni Tavur" ALIGN=TOP SRC="UniT_mast.gif"></CENTER>

<hr>
<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
<TD width= 200></TD><td align =left> http://acij.uts.edu.au/UniTavur/UniT_396_Maori.html</td><tr>
</table>
<hr>

<IMG alt=UniTavur Icon BORDER =0 ALIGN=BASELINE WIDTH=28 HEIGHT=30 SRC="Unit_slug.gif"><Font size= 5> 
Maori expert slams Hagahai 'outrage'.<font size= 3><p>

<strong> Staff Reporters </strong><p>

A Maori expert on indigenous intellectual, social and cultural property rights has challenged Papua New Guinea to press a case with the World Court over the "immoral and unethical" Hagahai cell line patent issue.<P>
	 Aroha Mead, deputy convenor of the Maori Congress in New Zealand, told Uni Tavur this week indigenous people in the Pacific were "outraged" over the Hagahai patent.<P>
	"We challenge the morality of Westerners extracting DNA samples from indigenous peoples without their full and informed consent," she said.<P>
	 PNG's High Commissioner to NZ, Damien Gamiandu, has been quoted saying PNG plans a protest against a US bid to enforce the worldwide patent. However, this has not been confirmed by the PNG Government. <p>
	The director of the PNG Institute of Medical Research, Dr Michael Alpers, defended the patent, saying it would safeguard Melanesian rights, not exploit them.<P>
	He said the institute would host a seminar on the issue at the University of PNG in August to raise public awareness and establish guidelines. 
	"The discovery came from the blood of the Hagahai individuals," he said. "The scientists involved did not exploit the people." <P>
	The Hagahai people had agreed to the research project before it began.<P>
	 Dr Alpers said the Hagahai patent had been turned into a global issue by Canadian non-government organisations which were concerned over life patenting.<P> 

	He said there was just a slight chance of commercial benefit from the patent. This would be shared between the Hagahai and the developer.<P>
	 Last month, Dr Alpers said in a Uni Tavur column it was better to have the Hagahai as part of the patent than to "have taken the ethical stance not to be involved and to have allowed all the rights to reside in the US." <P>
	The patent is for the PNG "human t-lymphotropic virus", or HTLV-I. In many countries, the metropolitan strain causes forms of cancer and paralysis and is spread through blood transfusions, but the Melanesian variant is disease-free.<P> 

	Ms Mead said this week: "Although many traditional cultures may not have the words for 'genetics' or 'DNA', most have strong customs protecting the sanctity of hair, blood, and saliva and mucus - the three sources of DNA most commonly tapped by Western researchers.<P>
	"The Hagahai patent is immoral and unethical but it is not unique - this is occuring all over the world."<P>
	Ms Mead said this was why the Hagahai patent was a global issue. <P>
	"Yesterday it was a Guaymi woman (from Panama). Today it is a Hagahai man from PNG. Tomorrow it will be a Solomon Islands man and other indigenous individuals," she said.<P>
	Ms Mead said the patent was not an issue of improved Hagahai health, or even PNG health - "it is about money, prestige for the 'inventors', racism, colonisation and greed."<P>
	She said the Canadian-based RAFI (Rural Advancement Foundation International) was preparing a case for the World Court to rule on the legality of human genetic patents.<P>
But a case needed to be brought by a Government and PNG was best placed to lodge a claim.<P>








