<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 1/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 1/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 1/2/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>25:52</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:02</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One - Coalition Media and Communications Policy</B>
<BR><BR>
Even before the Prime Minister announced March 2 as the Federal Election date, the Coalition was hitting the streets with its media and communications policies.  As a rapidly evolving sector in which reviews of cross-media ownership, telecommunications regualtions and the final free to air television channel are imminent, the election will have a lasting effect on media and communications in this country.  The coalition policy ha raised some hot issues - the hottest being its proposed sell-off of one third of Telstra.  In the case of Telstra, the coalition policy states that consumers will only receive maximum benefit with a signifiacnt private shareholding.  However the Consumers Telecommunications Network disagrees- saying that any sell-off will weaken Telstra's sense of social responsibility.  Michael Dwyer asked Shadow Minister for Communications and the Arts Senator Richard Alston, if the Consumers Telecommunications Network had it wrong...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well the fact is...	</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...anyone else in the sector."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>7:16</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Shadow Minister for Communications and the Arts, Senator Richard Alston</td>
 </table>
	<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two -	The Year Ahead With ...the Communications Law Centre</B>
<BR><BR>
Even without the  Federal Election, 1996 was going to be busy year in the media and communications sector.  Michael Dwyer spoke to Sue Ferguson, the Research and Policy Advisor at the Communications Law Centre ans asked her to provide an overview of 1996.  While much has been said about the Coalitions proposed sale of Telstra, this is just one part of a large policy package .  In her guide to 1996, Sue Ferguson begins by discussing some other important elements of the Coalition media and communications policy...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"The Coalition has already...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...something to say about."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>9:18</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Research and Policy Advisor at the Communications Law Centre, Sue Ferguson</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Three -	Community Television and the final free-to-air TV channel
</B>
<BR><BR>
Of great interest to the community broadcasting sector will be the review of the final free to air television channel.  Known as the sixth channel or channel 31, it has been used in recent years by community television.  A review of the use of this channel is now required by the Broadcasting Services Act - and community television is competing with several other potential uses for the channel.  To gain a quick picture of the year ahead for community television, Michael Dwyer  spoke to Television Vice-President at the Community Broadcasting Association of Australia, Mandy Grubb, and asked whether the priorities of the inquiry disadvantaged community television...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"It's been difficult...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...that we like."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>4:39</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Television Vice-President, Community Broadcasting Association of Australia, Mandy Grubb</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR><BR>

<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>
