<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 5/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 5/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 29/2/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:16</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:10</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One - Alternative Radio News From Around the World</B>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>Theme</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>Sting</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>around 4 minues</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Michael Jones - Newsreader</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two - LocalVision: Optus joins the Community Television Sector</B>
<BR><BR>
1996 is set to be a big year for community television with its future depending on a review into the permanent use of the sixth channel.  It's a sensitive period - so the appearance of a new community television model is causing some concern.  This is particularly the case as the model is being put forward by the communications giant - Optus.  Last week OptusVision lauched the first in a series of LocalVision cable community television stations.  Exusting community broadcasters have complained that the community access model used by Optus is flawed.  So what is LocalVision and is it really community television?  Michael Dwyer asked LocalVision Co-ordinator in Western Sydney, Judith Franz, what LocalVision could offer that existing community television models could not ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well it's not a case ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... to contact us."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>7:09</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>LocalVision Co-ordinator in Western Sydney - Judith Franz</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR>
<B>Iten Three - Jargon Jungle: AMARC</B>
<BR><BR>
Jargon Jungle is an occasional series which explains media and communications jargon.  This week, former President of the Community Broadcasting Association of Australia, Kaye Blackman, explains 'AMARC' ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>theme</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>theme</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>around 3:00</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Past President of the Community Broadcasting Association of Australia - Kaye Blackman</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR>
<B>Item Four - Film and Literature Censorship</B>
<BR><BR>
The Federal Government has recently introduced new legislation to streamline film and literature classification and censorship.  To mark the introduction of the legislation, a seminar was organised by the Australian Film Commission and the Office of Film and Literature Classification.  The keynote speaker was Richard Heffner - former Chair of the Film Regulation Board in the United States.  He spoke to Michael Dwyer about the current trends in regulation and censorship ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well I think ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... classification."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>around 5:00</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Former Chair of the Film Regulation Board in the United States - Richard Heffner</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR><BR>

<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>

