<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 4/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 4/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 22/2/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:40</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:20</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<H2>A program on film and television issues ...</H2>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Item One		Media Entertainment and Arts Alliance on the Federal Election</B><BR>
<BR>
In 1993 the Federal government received strong support from the arts - including the film and television production industry.  Come 1996, the Coalition has been careful to court the arts industry- with some major policy turnarounds since the last election.  In film and television this has meant a commitment to retain current funding levels for major bodies such as the Australian Film Commission.  The Media Entertainment and Arts Alliance (MEAA) represents many workers in film and television - Michael Dwyer asked Joint Federal Secretary Anne Britton, for her opinion of the Coalition policies . . .  
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well I suppose...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...recorded media industry."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>3:22 (includes voice link)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Joint Federal Secretary of the Media Entertainment and Arts Alliance - Anne Britton</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two		Jock Given on film, television and the Federal Election</B>
<BR><BR>
Jock Given is Director of the Communications Law Centre in Sydney and was formerly a Policy Advisor at the Australian Film Commission.  Having seen the film and television policies from both major parties, does he think there are significant differences between them...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well I think ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...film and tv industries."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>3:32 (includes voice link)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Director of the Communications Law Centre in Sydney and former Policy Advisor at the Australian Film Commission - Jock Given</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Three		Australian Television and International Mediascapes</B>
<BR><BR>
Over the past twenty years we've heard much about globalisation of the media.  Some critics have seen this globalisation as an exercise in cultural imperialism - with Western media products swamping local cultures.   Others see more subtle, differentiated or reflexive  movements between and within cultures.  "Australian Television and International Mediascapes" is the name of a new book on Australia's place within the global flow of television programs.  The book is co-authored by Professor of Communications at the University of Technology Sydney, Liz Jacka, and Associate Professor and Director of the Centre for Media Policy and Practice, at the Queensland University of Technology, Stuart Cunningham.  Michael Dwyer asked Professor Jacka where the book fits into globalisation debates…
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well I mean...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...compromised."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>15:18 (includes stab and voice link at about 8:00, so this interview could be split into two parts)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Professor of Communications at the University of Technology Sydney - Liz Jacka</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
