<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 3/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 3/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 15/2/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:10</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>26:44</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One -		CBAA Speaks on the Federal Election</B><BR>
<BR>
There are a  lot of issues and policies you could take into the voting booth on March 2. Maybe it's the economy, or health, or the environment that will sway you.  But since you're listening to community radio, you might be interested in the position of major community radio organisations. This week you'll hear from General Manager of the Community Broadcasting Association of Australia, Mike Thompson, and President of the National Ethnic and Multicultural Broadcasting Council, George Zangalis. While the Coalition has released a detailed media and communications policy including $4.5 million for community broadcasting, the Australian Labor Party is yet to put their position. Smaller parties especially the Democrats and the Greens have also been supportive of the sector and increased funding for community broadcasting. I asked Mike Thompson what he thought of the Coalition package ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well, it's the first time ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...as yet we haven't had a word from them."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>2:55</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>General Manager, Community Broadcasting Association of Australia, Mike Thompson</td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two -		NEMBC Speaks on the Federal Election</B><BR><BR>

Within the broader community broadcasting sector there are a number of smaller organisations who represent stations with more specific interests. Two influential organisations of this type are the National Indigenous Media Association of Australia - or NIMAA, and the National Ethnic and Multicultural Broadcasting Council. Next week we'll speak to Brett Leavy, Acting Executive Officer for NIMAA. They're still trying to get answers from the major parties - particularly the Coalition, who left the indigenous sector out of what was otherwise a comprehensive policy. The President of the NEMBC is George Zangalis. I asked him how he felt about the Coalition policies ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"We certainly welcome ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...definitely puts pressure on the government to do more."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>5:22 (includes voice link)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>President, National Ethnic and Multicultural Broadcasting Council, George Zangalis</td>
</table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Three -		Jargon Jungle: Australian Competition and Consumer Commission</B><BR><BR>

Jargon Jungle is a semi-regular segment in which we explain some jargon, a name or phrase that is doing the rounds.  The Australian Competition and Consumer Commission or ACCC is a new regulatory body with quite a lot of power and a big job to do.  
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>JJ theme ... then "If you've been ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...decision on the FOXTEL/Australis merger will be a good."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>3:31</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>voice report</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Four -		Report Released on Caller Number Display: Privacy Issues</B>
<BR><BR>
BEGINS WITH GRAB ( do not use)<BR>
<BR>
Our attention has been to privacy this week because of the release of a report on calling number display. The report was produced by the Privacy Advisory Committee at AUSTEL. Most simply, calling number display refers to technology which allows the phone number of someone calling your phone to be displayed as it rings. There are many benefits of this technology - for both callers, and those receiving calls. For example, for people receiving calls, it allows screening for nuisance and harassment callers. However, the technology also raises substantial privacy issues and these are recognised in the report. Before raising these issues I asked Sue Harlow - a member of AUSTEL, to explain the benefits of call number display in more detail ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"I must admit...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...of an opt-out situation."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>9:35 (includes voice links)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Member, AUSTEL, Sue Harlow<BR>     
Research and Policy Adviser, Communications Law Centre, Sue                            Ferguson</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR>

<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>

