<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 9/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 9/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 28/3/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>25:52</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:02</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One		Community Radio joins the Community Information Network</B>
<BR><BR>
The Community Information Network is a pilot project co-ordinated by the Department of Social Security.  Its aim is to provide access to the internet and computer information services for people who would otherwise muss out.  The information on the network is especially tailored to the concerns of people  on low incomes or with special needs.  Computers have been placed in many community centres - such as libraries - from where people can log into the information network.  Community Radio stations are about to join the list of community centres that provide computer access and information for the network.  It's a recognition of the role that community broadcasters play in the community.  Co-ordinating the project for the Community Broadcasting Association of Australia, is Matthew Arnison.  Michael Dwyer spoke to him about the information currently available on the Community Information Network...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well, um, there's been...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...comes to being implemented.</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>6:04</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>CBAA Community Information Network Co-ordinator - Matthew Arnison</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two		'From Sand to Celluloid' - New Indigenous Films Travelling Around Australia</B>
<BR><BR>
'From Sand to Celluloid' is a travelling collection of new indigenous films.  They were produced by first time directors as part of the Indigenous Drama Initiative.  This project was announced in the  1994 Creative Nation policy and has been supported by the Australian Film Commission, the SBS, the Australian Film Institute and several national and state film bodies.  Michael Dwyer spoke to some of the film-makers, and to the Manager of the Indigenous Branch of the Australian Film Commission, Wal Saunders.  He explained the ideas behind 'From Sand to Celluloid'...
<BR><BR>
Note: stations playing part program: this report contains its own introduction after the first grab.  The above introduction can be used if the report is played from the start of the interview with Wal Saunders ("It's about story-telling…) after the intro on the tape (duration from this point is 14:46)
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>(grab from film) FX then voice "How come you're always...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...they're successful, that's fine."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>15:08 (includes several voice links and grabs from the films)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Manager, Indigenous Branch, Australian Film Commission - Wal Saunders<BR>
		Director of "Fly Peewee, Fly" - Sally Riley<BR>
		Director of "Round Up" - Rima Tamou<BR>
		Producer of "Round Up" - Pauline Clague<BR></td>
 </table>

