<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 7/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 7/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 14/3/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:05</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:10</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One - CyberFringe at the Adelaide Fringe Festival</B>
<BR><BR>
The CyberFringe tried to create an electronic community of fringe-goers and internet surfers from around the world.  With information about fringe events, reviews of shows, and other fringey information, the CyberFringe allowed people to log in and share the fringe experience.  But is this use of the internet really pushing the boundaries?  Is the internet opening up new realms of human experience or is it mainly translating old media forms on to computers?  The CyberFringe was created by Virtual Artists - an Adelaide based internet arts company and was lauched by South Australian Premier dean Brown.  The launch called for Mr Brown to perform a virtual handshale with an internet surfer in California - but unfortunately the technology was not co-operating ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Welcome to the official launch ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... to nudge you off the computer."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>15:07 (including links)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Premier of South Australia - Dean Brown<BR>
Virtual Artist and CyberFringe Co-Producer - Jesse Reynolds</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two - Sound and Image in Cinema</B>
<table>
<BR><BR>
In mainstream cinema we are used to sound and image working seamlessly together to give a sense of being there.  But things haven't always been like this.  Early films were carried no sound of their own  - and over the years sound, music and voice were incorporated into cinema in a variety of ways.  The role of sound in cinema is not always obvious - and prior to the boom in selling movie soundtracks - the sound of a film wasn't always given much thought by audiences.  At this years Adelaide Festival, sound artist Pierre Henry explored the relationship between sound and image.  He showed silent films from the 1920's - for which he had composed soundscapes.  Pierre Henry was interviewed by Director of the Adelaide Festival, Barrie Kosky ...
<BR><BR>
<td>in</td><td>sound fx ..."At the time ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>sound fx</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>6:11</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Sound Artist performing at the Adelaide Festival - Pierre Henry</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR><BR>

