<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 21/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 21/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 20/6/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:18</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:28</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>

<H3>A Program on Film Censorship...</H3>

<BR><BR>
<B>Item One		Censorship and Film Festivals</B>
<BR><BR>
To this point the debate on censorship has been pushed by those who argue for more control on the portrayal of violence.  But at this years' Sydney Film Festival  calls were made for an organised anti-censorship movement.  Most vocal was David Stratton, Director of the Sydney Film Festival between 1966 and 1983.  In the Ian McPherson Lecture, Stratton gave a potted history of film censorship in Australia and the battles led by the Sydney Film Festival for more liberal censorship rules.  He ended the lecture by warning that vigilance against censorship was still needed in 1996.  Michael Dwyer talked to current Festival Director Paul Byrnes about film censorship and signs of a return to the bad old days ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well the bad old days ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... into our personal lounge rooms."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>6:38</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Sydney Film Festival Director - Paul Byrnes</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Two		Violence in Films - more than meets the eye?</B>
<BR><BR>

In recent debates about censorship the major concern has been the representation of violence.  But what is meant by the term ‘violence’ and has the current debate adequately considered the many reasons for representing violence in films?  A forum was held at the Sydney Film Festival with the aim of thinking more critically about the different ways that film-makers use violence.  One of the forum participants was Jane Mills - Head of Screen Studies at the Australian Film Television and Radio School.  She argued that current debate on violence is flawed ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"I think one of the major problems ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... can help us make sense of society."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>6:58</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Head of Screen Studies at the Australian film Television and Radio School - Jane Mills</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR>

<B>Item Three		Censorship and Creativity - rules are made to be broken</B>
<BR><BR>

The debate about censorship and the relationship between the world portrayed on the screen and the world on the streets is often repetitive.  The same arguments seems to be put and the same inconclusive results reached.  But in a seminar organised earlier this year by the Office of Film and Literature Classification, an interesting perspective was provided by John Morris - Chief Executive of the Australian Film Finance Corporation.  He spoke about the history of censorship and the creative solutions which film-makers have used to get around the restrictions.  He shared some of these stories with Michael Dwyer, but such are the times, John Morris was anxious not to be misunderstood as defending censorship ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"I do not believe that censorship ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... to certain elements in his film."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>8:30</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Chief Executive of the Australian Film Finance Corporation - John Morris</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR><BR>
<CENTER>
<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>
</CENTER>
<BR><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
