<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - PGM 13/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 13/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 25/4/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:52</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>28:10</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One		International Institute of Communications</B>
<BR><BR>

The  International Institute of Communications is a London-based  independent organisation in the media and communications sector.  The role of the IIC is to stimulate  discussion on the future of the sector - and its does this through a  variety of publications and conferences.  Membership is drawn from seventy countries - members primarily coming from industry and government agencies.  The IIC executive recently met in Australia - this meeting coincided with a forum on telecommunications.  Michael Dwyer spoke to Executive Director Vicki McCleod - herself an Australian seconded from Telstra - about the IIC and its activities...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well if I can go back...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...are in Australia."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>10:44</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>International Institute of Communications  Executive Director - Vicki McCleod</td>
</table>
<BR><BR>


<B>Item Two		Australian Broadcasting Authority criticises Internet Service Providers	</B>
<BR><BR>
The Australian Broadcasting Authority has told Internet Service Providers that they need better representation and that they need it now.  These comments were made by Chair of the ABA  Peter Webb  while speaking at the Online Services Regulation Forum.  Pressure is mounting on the Federal Government to regulate on-line services.  Some states have already decided to go it alone  and there is substantial community concern about internet -pornography.  The message to Internet Service Providers is that they risk being left out of the process - including the ABA 's current  inquiry into on-line services. Pete Manson spoke to ABA Chair Peter Webb, and asked about the pressures mounting on the federal government...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Traditional pressures..</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...to inflict harm on others."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>3:55</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Australian Broadcasting Authority Chair - Peter Webb</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Three		New media technologies and cultural institutions</B>

<BR><BR>
Stuffed animals and boxes of rocks were once part of the stereotype of museums as cold, slightly dull places. And while traditional exhibits still dominate cultural institutions, increasing use is being made of new media technologies.  Gary Warner is Creative Producer at the Museum of Sydney and he spoke at the Australian Film Commission Language of Interactivity Conference.  He has a distinguished career in the Australian film industry - being recognised with the 1993 Byron Kennedy Award.  Michael Dwyer spoke to Gary Warner about the use of mew media to inform and entertain....
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"I think that's probably...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...deems people should work."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>7:37</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Creative Producer at the Museum of Sydney - Gary Warner</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR><BR>

<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>
<BR>
