<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - PGM 17/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 17/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 23/5/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>27:10</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>28:04</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One		Committee of Ministers on the Portrayal of Violence</B>
<BR><BR>
Following the Port Arthur Massacre The Prime Minister, John Howard, announced that a committee of Government Ministers would examine the portrayal of violence in Australia.  In particular, they are to examine violence on television and videos and in video and computer games.  The Committee’s terms of reference have been released and public submissions have also been invited.  The terms of reference are quite broad and include a requirement to investigate  recent research on the relationship between representations of violence and violent behaviour.  Given the volume of research on this topic, Michael Dwyer asked Lecturer in Media Studies at the Queensland University of Technology, Terry Flew, whether we can expect the committee to make much progress...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well the first thing...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...some misleading responses."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>6:29</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Lecturer in Media Studies at the Queensland University of Technology, Terry Flew</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Two		Review of Commercial Television Codes of Practice	</B>
<BR><BR>
One of the terms of reference for the Ministerial Committee on the Portrayal of Violence (see previous story)
refers to the review of codes of practice governing the national and commercial television broadcasters.  In September this year the Commercial Television Code of Practice is due to be reviewed following the first three years of its operation.  However in a letter to the Minister for communications, the Federation of Australian Commercial Television Stations has suggested that the review be brought forward.  The Code of Practice is a requirement of the 1992 Broadcasting Services Act and covers issues including program classifications, material unsuitable for television and community complaints procedures.  Michael Dwyer spoke to General Managers of FACTS, Tony Branigan and asked him what the Federation was offering...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well er...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...complaints process."		</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>5:36</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>General Manager of the Federation of Australian Commercial Television Stations, Tony Branigan</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Three		Telecommunications Policy Forum - Part 2</B>
<BR><BR>

Last week on Media Magazine we broadcast part one of our forum on telecommunications policy.  Last week the program focused on competition policy and the changes to occur in 1997.  This week in part two, the focus is on the proposed privatisation of Telstra in the context of those changes.  The speakers are Gerard Goggin, Researcher at the Consumers Telecommunications Network, Helen Meredith a communications journalist with the Australian Financial Review, and John Quiggin Professor of Economics at James Cook University.  Helen Meredith begins the discussion, commenting on where the privatisation plans fit into the broader changes proposed for the telecommunications sector...

<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well I dare say...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...that it actually happens."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>9:21 </td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Gerard Goggin, Researcher at the Consumers Telecommunications Network<BR>
		Helen Meredith a communications journalist with the Australian Financial Review <BR>
		John Quiggin, Professor of Economics at James Cook University</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR><BR>
