<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 18/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 18/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 30/5/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:27</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:39</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One		World Round-up of Alternative Broadcasting News </B>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Being a journalist...	</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...Pegasus Network."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>3:11</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>read by Michael Jones</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Two		Community Television - is Sydney letting the side down?</B>
<BR><BR>

During 1996 the government will decide who will have permanent access to the final free to air television frequency around Australia.  Currently community television has been given the frequency on a trial basis that will end in mid 1997.  While community television is a frontrunner to get permanent access there are other strong candidates.  So in the meantime its important for community television to make the most of its trial period - something the other contenders have not received.  In this context the ongoing saga that is Community Television Sydney is not really what the sector needs.  After years of infighting and dubious commercial deals, CTS is now in the hands of administrators.  The Australian Broadcasting Authority has also been dragged into this tangled web - they are now reluctant to renew the CTS transmitter license.  Michael Dwyer spoke to Manager of Allocations and Renewals at the ABA, Nigel Ryan, about the licensing of Community Television Sydney and its implications for community television around Australia...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"In the present trial...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...will be reviewed."		</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>7:38</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Manager of Allocations and Renewals at the ABA, Nigel Ryan</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Three		Interactive Film Art</B>
<BR><BR>

Over the last few years we've heard plenty about interactive multimedia.  The darling of the former Labor governments 1994 Creative Nation statement, interactive multimedia was the brave new frontier.  Since then interactive multimedia has largely failed to deliver on the hype.  Chris Hales - a  film artist and lecturer at the University of the West of England is highly critical of much recent commercial multimedia development.  He sees his won work as interactive film art - a concept he explained to Michael Dwyer....
<BR><BR>

<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Interactive film art...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...inherent kind of democracy."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>7:35 </td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Film artist and lecturer at the University of the West of England, Chris Hale</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Three		Jargon Jungle - the LAP (License Area Planning) Process</B>
<BR><BR>

The Australian Broadcasting Authority - the ABA - is more than two years behind its License Area Planning (or LAP) Schedule.  The delays are causing major problems for aspirant broadcasters around the country - particularly aspirant community broadcasters.  So what is a LAP and why is the process taking so long?

<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>Theme  (begins with jungle atmos and drums)</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>Theme  (ends with lion roaring)	</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>2:19</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>voice piece</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR><BR>
