<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - PGM 11/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 11/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 11/4/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:52</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:57</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One		Independent Journalism on the Internet</B>
<BR><BR>

The Australian Centre for Independent Journalism has just launched a new website.  It's full of information for journalists and contains electronic versions of some of the centres own work in independent journalism.  Australian Centre for Independent Journalism Director Peter Cronau (PRON Crow-now) spoke to Michael Dwyer about the web-site...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"The ACIJ website...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...source material is accurate."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>7:08</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Australian Centre for Independent Journalism Director - Peter Cronau</td>
</table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item Two		Video-activism</B>
<BR><BR>

Media technology sometimes seems to be out of the reach of ordinary people - it costs lots of money and requires specialist training.  But this is not always the case, as people in community radio and television can tell you.  Another are in which technology is being used by ordinary people is video-activism.  While it's only just taking off in Australia, political activists have used video-activism to great effect in Britain and the United States.  Thomas Harding is a prominent British video-activist - he was recently in Australia and spoke to Jason Torrens...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Been a video-activist...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...to learn really."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>8:02</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>British video-activist - Thomas Harding</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>


<B>Item Three		New commercial radio stations - more trouble for community aspirants</B>
<BR><BR>

Some aspirant community radio stations have been trying to get a license for almost twenty four years.  The Australian Broadcasting Authority - the government body which gives out new radio licenses - is currently running several years behind schedule in its license allocation process.  Many community aspirant stations are getting very frustrated - and this hasn't been helped by a new government decision which gives priority to new commercial radio services in some regional areas.  The government has tried to fast track the provision of more services to some regional areas by giving existing commercial radio stations an extra FM license if there is only one existing commercial service in the area.  The effect has been that community radio services have again been overlooked.  In this report Michael Dwyer speaks to Cathleen Bruce - President of an aspirant radio group in Orange NSW - but first, Michele Dyne from the Australian Broadcasting Authority explains why the commercial stations are getting special treatment...

<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>Well at the moment...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...in the government department."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>5:56 (contains one link at 2:00)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Australian Broadcasting Authority - Michele Dyne <BR>
		President of the Orange Community Broadcasters - Cathleen Bruce</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR><BR>
<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=223 height=31 src="cueimage/mm.flat.
bottom.banner.jpg">
<a href=".../index.html"><img width=100 height=28 src="cueimages/button.flat.dir.home.jpg"></a>
<a href="#top"><img width=100 height=28 src="cueimage/button.flat.dir.top.jpg"></a>
