<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 23/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 23/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 4/7/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:41</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:38</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item One		Families and Electronic Entertainment</B>
<BR><BR>
Families and Electronic Entertainment  is the title of a new report from the Australian Broadcasting Authority and the Office of Film and Literature Classification.  The report examines the place of electronic entertainment in contemporary Australian families and how parents seek to regulate its use.  In the context of debates over censorship and classifications of television programs, videos, films and computer services this report is of particular interest.  Michael Dwyer spoke to Margaret Cupitt and Steven Nugent from the Australian Broadcasting Authority - they began by talking about the concerns that parents say they do have ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"We asked in this research ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... in their childrens' media consumption"</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>14:27 (includes one sting and voice link)</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Australian Broadcasting Authority Researchers - Margaret Cupitt and Steven Nugen</td>
 </table>

<BR>

NOTE FOR STATIONS PLAYING PART PROGRAM ONLY - PARTS ONE AND TWO OF ITEM ONE COULD BE PLAYED SEPARATELY. 
<BR><BR><BR>
<B>Item Two		The Media as an Anti-Educational Force</B>
<BR><BR>
The Centre for Popular Education at the University of Technology in Sydney has give media coverage of the Federal Election a poor report card.   Speaking at a recent conference on youth work, community work and popular education, Director of the Centre  - Professor Griff Foley argued that the media often has an anti-educational impact and that this was evident during and after the Federal election.  Michael Dwyer spoke to Professor Foley, who explained what it meant to make an educational critique of the media ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"What it's primarily aimed at ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... and how it could be supported more."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>7:31</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Director of the Centre for Popular Education - Professor Griff Foley</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR><BR>

<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>

