<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 31/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 31/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 29/8/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>27:15</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>28:17</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item One Senator Alston on Budget Outcomes for Community Broadcasting</B>
<BR><BR>
The Federal Coalition's 1996 Budget has delivered on most of the election promises made to the community broadcasting sector.  Overall, an additonal four point five  million dollars of funding will flow into the sector over the next three years.  Three million dollars has been allocated for support of ethnic radio programming.   A further one point five million will support three general community radio projects - the ComRadSat network, the Community Broadcasting Database and the Community Access Network (CAN).  While the sector has welcomed this additional funding, there have been some concerns expressed that the money allocated  - particularly for the CAN may not be enough to see it through.  Michael Dwyer spoke to Senator Alston about the budget outcomes for community broadcasting and whether there is room for further negotiation ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"We've delivered precisely ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... appropriate way of doing it."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>8:04</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Minister for Communications - Senator Richard Alston</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two		Community Broadcasting Association of Australia Response to Alston</B>
<BR><BR>
The Community Broadcasting Association of Australia has welcomed the additional funding.  Mike Thomson, General Manager of the CBAA responds to some of the views put by Senator Alston ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well it's the first time ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... hope that that continues."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>6:48</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>General Manager of the CBAA - Mike Thomson</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Three		The Manning-Clark Controversy</B>
<BR><BR>
The sometimes sedate state of Australian history was jolted last week by claims that eminent historian Manning-Clark had been awarded the Order of Lenin and was agent of influence for the Soviet Union.  The claims were made in the Brisbane Courier-Mail, the paper that earlier in 1996 blew the lid off the Darville/Demidenko hoax.  So is the Manning-Clark story a second major coup for the Courier-Mail or have they jumped the gun?  David McKnight, a Lecturer in Journalism at the University of Technology Sydney and author of a book on spies in Australia, took a torch behind the scenes for Media Magazine ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Manning-Clark was described ...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>... it may well be, that that's a good thing."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>6:46</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Lecturer in Journalism at the University of Technology, Sydney - David McKnight<td>
 </table>
<BR><BR><BR>
<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>

<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
