<TITLE>Media Magazine - Program 19/96</TITLE>
<A NAME="top"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<img width=115 align=left height=80 src="cueimage/mm.Australia.
6.gif"><BR>
<H2>MEDIA MAGAZINE CUE SHEET <BR>
Program 19/96 <BR>
ComRadSat TX 7/6/96</H2>
</center>
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>Program In</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Last Words At</td><td><B>26:27</B></td><tr>
<td>Program Out</td><td><B>theme</B></td><td>Total Duration</td><td><B>27:39</B></td>
</table>
<BR><BR>

<B>Item One		Internet Public Access Terminals</B>
<BR><BR>
The opening of cybercafes in Australia has received much publicity.  However despite having some success overseas, this has not been the case in Australia.  Some have closed and many others are on the borderline.  In this climate it may be surprising then that a company is proposing to places 3,500 internet access terminals in hotels, clubs and public spaces around Australia.  Managing Director of Internet Public Access Terminals, Daniel Albert believes that existing cybercafes have taken the wrong approach and that there is demand for public internet access...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"We believe that a great deal...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...too greatly on that."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>Managing Director of Internet Public Access Terminals Pty Ltd, Daniel Albert</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>5:58</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR>
<B>Item Two		Press Photography and Propaganda</B>
<BR><BR>

Many concerns were raised about the media coverage of the Pt Arthur massacre.  One of the more blatant breaches occurred in <I>The Australian</I>, when an altered photo of the alleged murderer was published on their front page.  But while digital technology makes image manipulation so much easier, a new book by Macquarie University academic Dr John Williams claims that this practice has a long history.  He spoke to Monica Clare...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"At the time...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...look like a fake."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>7:39</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>Visiting Fellow at the Department of Modern History, Macquarie University, Dr John Williams</td>
 </table>

<BR><BR>

<B>Item Three		Narrowcasting and the One Person Radio Station</B>
<BR><BR>

When people think of media they often imagine big buildings, hordes of people and megabucks.  But new digital technology has made it possible for one person to set up and run a arid station for around $10 000.  And if you can get your hands on a narrowcasting radio license then your all set to go.  One person who has done this is Geoff Harrison, General Manager of the Victorian Narrowcasting Network.  He spoke to Michael Dwyer about new technology, narrowcasting and new services ...
<BR><BR>
<table>
<td>in</td><td>"Well in the past...</td><tr>
<td>out</td><td>...community groups on their own level."</td><tr>
<td>duration</td><td>around 7'</td><tr>
<td>talent</td><td>General Manager of the Victorian Narrowcasting Network, Geoff Harrison</td>
 </table>
<BR><BR><BR><KBD></KBD>
<CENTER>
<B>APRA DETAILS AVAILABLE ON REQUEST</B>
</CENTER>
