<dd><H4><a HREF="http://www.finishing.com/">American Electroplaters and Surface Finishers Society</a>
<img src="giffiles/aesf.gif" border=0></b>
<dd>Aluminizing, anodizing, buffing, conversion coating, CVD, electroforming, 
<dd>electroplating, electroless plating, electropolishing, flame spraying, galvanizing, 
<dd>hot dipping, metal finishing, painting, phosphatizing, plating, polishing, powder 
<dd>coating, printed circuits, PVD, salt bath nitriding, and the surface finishing arts 
<dd>spoken here. </p>


<dd><H4><a HREF="http://www.finishing.com/IMF/index.html">The Institute of Metal Finishing</a><img src="giffiles/imf.gif" border=0></b>
<dd>Honorary Secretary General, Membership Director
<dd>Mrs. Jean Sturch, Education and Training Director
<dd>Exeter House
<dd>48 Holloway Head
<dd>Birmingham, BI 1NQ, England
<dd>Phone:  0121-622-7387
<dd>FAX:  0121-666-6316
<dd>Email:  <a href="mailto:ukfinishing@dial.pipex.com">ukfinishing@dial.pipex.com</a>
</p>

<dd><H4><a HREF="http://www.metal-finishing.com/mfsa/mfsa.htm">Metal Finishing Suppliers' Association Inc.</a><img src="giffiles/mfsa.gif" border=0></b>
<dd>Our members are in all aspects of the metal finishing industry and include manufacturers 
<dd>and distributors of metals, chemicals, and equipment for electroplating and other 
<dd>metal surface treatments and enhancements...for the minimization, removal, clean up, 
<dd>and disposal of spent chemicals and other industrial waste...and for pollution control 
<dd>and abatement. Consultants and other service companies to the metal finishing industry 
<dd>are also members of the Association.


</p>

<dd><b><a HREF="http://cai.eclipse.net/home2.htm">National Metal Finishing Resource Center</a>
<img src="giffiles/ncms.gif" border=0></b>
<dd>This is a subscription based service that will be available free until October 1996.
<dd>The Resource Center was established under a program jointly funded by the Commerce
<dd>Department's National Institute of Standards and Technology and the US Environmental
<dd>Protection Agency. Industry partners are the American Electroplaters and Surface
<dd>Finishers Society (AESF), the National Center for Manufacturing Sciences (NCMS), the
<dd>National Association of Metal Finishers (NAMF), and the Metal Finishing
<dd>Suppliers'Association (MFSA). The Pollution Prevention Roundtable is also a project
<dd>participant. 


<dd>  <b><a href="http://www.svc.org/"> The Society of Vacuum Coaters </a><img src="giffiles/svc.gif" border=0> </b>
<dd>The Society of Vacuum Coaters, a non-profit professional, trade and educational 
<dd>organization, is dedicated to the development of equipment and processes for 
<dd>high-volume production of coatings using vacuum-based processes. Its unique 
<dd>industrial focus targets the processing engineer and technician, end-user, equipment 
<dd>manufacturer, and the materials supplier. SVC seeks to disseminate knowledge, 
<dd>experience, and techniques to the vacuum coating industry through a variety of forums.

</p>

<img src="giffiles/bar2.gif">

<BR>


<h2><img src="giffiles/golden.gif" border=0  height=15 width =20 ><A NAME="print">Printing industry links</A></h2>
<br>
<p>

<dd><b><a href="http://www.dpia.org/">
Digital Printing & Imaging Association</a></b> <img src="giffiles/DPIMASTG.GIF" border=0>
<dd>The Digital Printing and Imaging Association (DPI) serves all segments of the 
<dd>graphics industry -- users, manufacturers and sellers -- who share a basic 
<dd>common denominator: the use of digital printing technology.

<p>
<dd><b><a href="http://www.fta-ffta.org/overview.html">
The Flexographic Technical Association</a></b><img src="giffiles/fta.gif" border=0>
<dd>Flexographic Technical Association is dedicated to assisting the flexo 
<dd>industry and your business.  Founded in 1958, the FTA is the only technical
<dd>society exclusively serving the needs of the flexographic printing industry.
<dd>FTA membership includes 1,770 (and counting) individuals representing over 
<dd>1,000 companies encompassing printers, suppliers, package buyers, consultants
<dd>and educational institutions.

<dd><H4><a HREF="http://www.gatf.lm.com/">
<dd>The Graphic Arts Technical Foundation</a><img src="giffiles/gatf.gif" border=0></b>
<dd>The Graphic Arts Technical Foundation is a member-supported, nonprofit, technical, and 
<DD>education organization serving the international graphic communications industries. Its 
<DD>mission statement reads "To serve the graphic communcations community as the leading 
<DD>resource for technical information and services through research and education." 


<dd><h4><a HREF="http://www.gaa.org">
<dd>The Gravure Association of America</a><img src="giffiles/gaa.gif" border=0></b>
<dd>The Gravure Association of American (GAA) is a trade association formed in January 
<dd>1987 as a result of the merger of the Gravure Technical Association, founded in 1948 
<dd> and the Gravure Research Institute, founded in 1947.  The mission of GAA is to 
<dd> promote and support the gravure process. GAA resources are dedicated to the collection 
<dd> and dissemination of information pertaining to gravure technology, marketing, 
<dd> environmental issues,government regulations, education, and training. 


<H4><a HREF="http://www.printing.org/">
<dd>Printing Industries of America, Inc.</a><img src="giffiles/pia.gif" border=0></b>
<DD>Printing Industries of America (PIA) is the world's largest graphic arts trade
<DD>association representing an industry with more than 990,000 employees and $116.3 
<dd>billion in sales annually. PIA promotes the interests of nearly 14,000 member 
<DD>companies, which become members by joining one of 33 regional affiliate 
<dd> organizations throughout the U.S.


<BR>
<H4><a HREF="http://www.inhs.uiuc.edu/pneac/pneac.html">
<dd>The Printer's National Environmental Assistance Center</a><img src="giffiles/pneac.gif" border=0></b>
<br>
<DD>The Printers' National Environmental Assistance Center (PNEAC) was established in 
<DD>1995 to provide environmental assistance to the printing industry. The essential 
<DD> approach used by the PNEAC to accomplish this objective is to improve 
<DD> communications and coordination among environmental technical assistance 
<DD>organizations and key printing industry associations.

<P>
<img src="giffiles/bar2.gif">
