<TITLE>NICKEL PLATE: ELECTROLYTIC</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Library">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Tom Teall">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<img src="giffiles/conthead.gif" border=0>
<h3>NICKEL PLATE:  ELECTROLYTIC (Steel Substrate)</h3>

<p><img src="giffiles/1018-g02.jpg" hspace=15 Align=left border=0>

The electrodeposition of nickel, or <a href="1070.htm">nickel plate</a>, is one of the
most widely used and versatile processes in the surface finishing
industry.  Nickel plate produces finishes with a variety of mechanical
and decorative characteristics .  Although a versatile process,
rigorous process control must be maintained to achieve the desired
performance attributes.
<P>
Nickel deposition is most commonly used as a surface preparation
and a bright undercoat for decorative chromium plating.   Brass,
gold, silver and other metals may also be plated<B> </B>over bright
nickel deposits for a variety of decorative applications.  Engineering
and electroforming applications are other common uses.   
<P>
Bright <a href="1070.htm">nickel plate</a> is most frequently used to give
decorative chromium deposits their smooth, mirror-like appearance<B>.</B>
 Organic addition agents, usually in a sulfate bath, are required
to obtain semi- and full-mirror bright nickel deposits.  These
agents modify the metal deposit during the plating process to
yield desired characteristics.
<P>
Another function of this nickel sub-layer is to provide a limited
degree of corrosion protection to a variety of substrates including
steel, brass, zinc and die castings.  Two developments have resulted
in significant increases in corrosion protection over earlier
decorative nickel-chromium deposits.
<P>
The first development is the use of double- and triple-layer nickel
coatings.  Double-layer nickel plate makes use of an initial layer
of semi-bright, sulfur-free nickel underneath a layer of fully
bright nickel.<B> </B> This initial layer is highly corrosion-resistant
and protects the substrate from  attack which 
begins at pore sites in the final chromium deposit.  Deposition
of a thin, highly reactive nickel layer between the two layers
further enhances this effect.  
<P>
A second change that has increased corrosion protection is the
introduction of chromium plating finishes that exhibit a high
degree of microporosity, or microcracking.  Microporosity causes
corrosive attack to be more uniformly dispersed over a large area,
thus delaying and reducing the pitting characteristic of failure
of the chrome layer at a relatively few sites as is the case with
conventional chromium plating.
<P>
<B>Electroforming</B> involves the deposition of nickel onto a
mandrel which is a form or a shape, producing an electroformed
object.  This object, which is the product itself, is then separated
from the mandrel.  The products formed in this manner usually
cannot be produced easily, or at all, by other means.  Molds,
dies, record stamping dies, textile printing screens and other
intricately shaped objects are among the items manufactured by
electroforming.  Electroforming is most commonly carried out in
a nickel sulfamate bath.  The high concentration of nickel in
this bath yields appreciably higher plating rates than a sulfate
bath.
<P>
 
<P>
Residual stress (tensile or compressive) in the nickel deposit
is an important factor to control due to its tendency to<B> </B>cause
warping or distortion of the electroformed product.  Residual
stress is a function of the concentration of chlorides and 
impurities in the plating solution.  Impurities may result from
breakdown of solution chemicals, trace contamination from the
anode, and drag-in from previous tanks.  Stress factors near zero
are obtained when chloride concentrations are as low as possible
and solutions are as pure as possible.
<P>
<B>Engineering nickel plate</B> is a matte finish used to alter
or enhance characteristics such as corrosion resistance, wear,
hardness and magnetic properties of the substrate.  Other applications
include repair, rebuilding, and salvage of various machine parts,
and heavy undercoatings for hard chrome plating.
<P>
Most engineering nickel plate applications are produced in a sulfate
or sulfamate bath.  Sulfamate is more commonly used because of
its high plating rate and production of stress-free deposits.
 Alternate bath formulations may be used to yield specific properties.
 An example of this is the use of an all-chloride bath to achieve
extremely hard, brittle deposits. <B>  </B>
<P>
<I>Lowenheim (1974)</I> provides a number of different solution
chemistries and discusses nickel plate applications in more detail.
<P>
<p><center><img src="giffiles/1018vsd1.gif" border=0><br>
<a href="1070.htm"><img src="giffiles/1018vsd2.gif" border=0></a></center>
<P>

(Reference for this article)
<P>
Lowenheim, Frederick A., <U>Modern Electroplating, Third Edition</U>,
John Wiley &amp; Sons, New York, NY, 1974.
<P>
<br>
