<TITLE>ION EXCHANGE</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Library">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Tom Teall">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<P>
<img src="giffiles/conthead.gif" border=0>
<h3>ION EXCHANGE</h3>

<p><img src="giffiles/1073-g02.jpg" hspace=15 Align=left border=0></p>

Ion exchange is a mature technology with a proven record of reducing
waste in the plating industry. 
<P>
 The technology is applicable to a variety of plating process
solutions including cyanide plating baths.  <I>Cushnie (1994)</I>
discusses a variety of applications for ion exchange based on
information gathered from industry and vendor surveys. 
<P>
Ion exchange is a chemical reaction in which an ion from in solution
is exchanged for a relatively benign, like charged ion attached
to a stationary medium (i.e., ion exchange resin).  This resin
is held in a column through which solution is passed, allowing
exchange to occur.  The reactions are predictable and the capacity
of the resins can be calculated.  When the resin capacity is reached,
the exchanged ions can be removed by displacement using a solution
containing the original ions.  This process is known as regeneration.
<P>
Resins are basically classified as either cationic or anionic.
 Cationic resins exchange hydrogen ions for positive ions such
as nickel, copper and zinc.  Anionic resins exchange hydroxyl
ions for negative ions such as chromates, sulfates, chlorides
and cyanide.  The regeneration step is generally carried out by
a strong mineral acid or base solution containing these ions.
<P>
Cationic resins are generally classified as strong or weak acid
types, and anionic resins as strong or weak base types.  An advantage
of the weak acid and weak base resins is that they require significantly
less reagent for regeneration than their strongly ionized counterparts.
 A number of general purpose and specialty ion exchange resins
are commercially available. 
<P>
The choice of resin for a particular application will depend on
the ion or ions to be removed and recovered, and the chemistry
of the process.  The resin is contained in a tank or container
equipped with valves, piping, retention screens and other components
necessary for proper operation. These containers are commonly
referred to as columns.
<P>
 
<P>
The basic operating cycle consists of: 
<ol><P><li><b>Service cycle</b>:  The solution to be treated  is passed
through the column until the resin is saturated.
<li><P><b>Backwash cycle</b>:  Water is flushed through the column
in reverse direction of the service cycle to redistribute the
resin.
<li><P><b>Regeneration cycle</b>:  A strong mineral acid or base solution
is passed through the exchanger to displace the exchanged ion,
restoring the resin to its original state.  The direction of flow
is generally in reverse of the service cycle.
<li><P><b>Rinse cycle</b>:  Water is passed through the exchanger
to remove excess regenerant.</ol>
<P>
Columns may be installed in parallel or in series.  In a parallel
arrangement, the input stream flows through one column while the
other is regenerated and held in reserve.  In a series configuration,
the input stream flows through both columns in sequence.  When
the first column is exhausted it is taken off line, regenerated
and returned to service as the second or trailing column.  In
both schemes, the roles of the two columns are continually interchanged.
 In most cases the feed solution will require particle and carbon
filtration to prevent solids from fouling the resin.
<P>
Various methods are used to determine the point at which regeneration
should take place.  These include the use of conductivity meters,
specific ion probes, analytical methods, cumulative elapsed time
or flow volume.
<P><a HREF="1078.htm">Drag-out recovery</a> 
or recovery rinsing is generally used
with ion exchange to return the majority of drag-out to the process
tank. This reduces the capacity and cost of equipment required
for ion exchange, and reduces the quantity of regenerant produced.
 Some installations use cation exchange only to remove metals.
 In these cases, the wastewater containing salts is discharged
directly to the POTW<B> - </B>if within discharge limits.  If
above discharge limits, on-site wastewater treatment is required
before discharge.  
<P>
The backwash solutions resulting from step 2 of the operating
cycle typically contain low levels of pollutants and are sent
to on-site wastewater treatment as well.  If zero discharge is
an ultimate goal, eliminating these waste streams becomes a priority.
 Some system designs reuse portions of the regenerant and backwash
streams to reduce total wastewater volume.<B> </B> The flow diagram
illustrates the choices available to handle the metal-rich regenerant
stream.
<P>
Modern ion exchange systems generally incorporate microprocessors
to control the complex switching of columns, through the service,
backwash, regeneration and rinse cycles.  Saturated columns are
either regenerated within the facility or off-site by an external
supplier.  The latter option eliminates the regenerant and backwash
streams along with the equipment and reagents they require.
<P>
<I>Cushnie (1994)</I> reports the following capital costs for
fully automatic equipment as a function of flow rate.  He notes
that pricing comparisons based solely on capacity can ignore factors
such as the degree of customization, level of automation, quality
of instrumentation, etc. 
<P>
<TABLE BORDER COLWIDTH="1,1">

<TR><TD>Flow rate (gpm) <TD>Ion exchange capital cost range ($ x 1000)

<TR><TD><center>10   <TD> <center>30 - 40
<TR><TD><center>20   <TD> <center>60 - 70
<TR><TD><center>30   <TD><center>85</center>
</TABLE>
<P>
Operating costs are dependent on labor requirements, regeneration
frequency and chemistry, energy requirements, and resin replacement.
 Labor requirements will vary depending on the degree of automation.
 Regeneration frequency will depend on the characteristics of
the input stream.  Resin life is also dependent on the input stream
and is usually measured in years.  These factors must be addressed
and determined in order to design, size and deliver an effective<B>
</B>system. The equipment supplier should be able to provide a
reasonably accurate estimate of operating costs using this data.
 A vendor may also be able to provide actual operating costs and
performance data on similar installations.  Design and installation
of an effective ion exchange system is highly dependent on the
vendor's competence.
<P>The flow diagram below represents a general ion exchange configuration
for metal recovery and deionized water recycle.  
<p><center><img src="giffiles/1073vsd1.gif" border=0><br>
<img src="giffiles/1073vsd2.gif" border=0></center></p>
