<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><img src="giffiles/conthead.gif" border=0></p>


<h2>DRAG OUT RECOVERY</h2>
<p>Drag-out recovery may also be called recovery rinsing, static rinsing, or return rinsing. It refers to the processing of  cleaning chemicals or plating solutions that have been removed from the process bath during the particular cleaning or plating process.  Drag-out recovery should be  distinguished from <a HREF="1060.htm">drag-out control/reduction</a> which seeks to reduce the quantity of material actually leaving the process tank. Drag-out control/reduction is treated as a separate topic and may be used as an alternative or complementary technique to drag-out recovery.

<p>Drag-out control, drag-out recovery and counterflow rinsing are all crucial factors in minimizing water usage and the quantity of chemicals which must be treated or recovered by other methods. For this reason they are the most influential factors in determining the size (and cost) of additional recovery systems which might be considered. 

<br><HR>
<br>

<h3>DRIP TANK</h3>
The most basic form of drag out recovery is a simple drip tank. Racks or barrels are allowed to hang or drain over an empty rinse. The accumulated process solution is periodically returned to the process tank. In some cases a drip tank may be the preferred configuration. However, in most cases a recovery rinse tank will be more efficient.

<br>
 <h3>RECOVERY RINSING</h3>
A single recovery rinse tank arrangement followed by a double counterflow rinse is illustrated below. The return volume in this system is equal to one-half the drag-out volume, yielding a  25% recovery. If return volume is equal to drag-out volume, a 50% recovery is realized and flow from the recovery rinse is eliminated. Additional increases in the return volume not only increase the recovery rate but allow decreased rinse flow to obtain the same rinsing levels. Higher temperature processes can recover more materials by replacing evaporation losses from the drag-out rinse. If the evaporation rate is twice the drag-out rate, the recovery rate increases to 66.7%. In such cases deionized water should be utilized to restore the drag out tank volume.

<p>It may be possible to achieve closed loop rinsing on relatively high temperature processes.  A second heated  tank may be employed to increase system evaporation and, hence, enable the  return of a larger drag-out volume.  Closed loop or high return systems will likely require some form of purification. Useful applications of this scheme include nickel plate, with carbon filtration and electrolytic purification prior to return or to alkaline cleaning, with oil separation and filtration prior to return. In the latter case, the heated recovery tank may be eliminated for high temperature cleaners. 
<div align=center><p><img src="giffiles/1078-g02.gif" border=0 ></center>

<br>
<h3>DRAG-IN / DRAG-OUT RECOVERY</h3>
The figure below illustrates a two tank drag-in / drag-out recovery configuration followed by a double counterflow rinse.  A well managed system of this type can reduce chemical losses up to 50 % on room temperature processes.  As noted above, higher temperature processes can recover more materials by replacing evaporation losses from the drag-out rinse and in such cases, deionized water should be used to restore the drag out tank volume.  Manually operated lines can employ a single tank to accomplish the same result by rinsing parts in the drag-out tank prior to processing.  One disadvantage of this arrangement is that work must be transported over the process tank to reach the rinse.  Additional concerns include the capital cost and floor space required to install additional tanks.  A pump may be necessary to equalize solution levels between the two tanks.
<div align=center><p><img src="giffiles/1078-g03.gif " border=0 ></center>

<p>These methods are generally applicable to any process including cleaners, acid pickles and others process solutions.  Many processes, however, are sensitive to high concentration rinses or the return of contaminants inherent in the process and simply cannot accommodate a large return volume.  Some type of recovery rinsing is usually employed to reduce drag-out volumes prior to  application of other recovery technologies such as evaporative recovery and ion exchange.
<p>
<a href="drag-out.htm">Drag Out Recovery Case Study</a>

