<h3>NICKEL PLATE:  ELECTROLYTIC (Sulfate/Sulfamate Bath)</h3>

<p><img src="giffiles/1070-g02.jpg" hspace=15 Align=left border=0>

The sulfate and sulfamate baths are the most widely used for nickel
plate general applications. <B> </B>Other nickel salt solutions
may be used for special purpose applications.  <I>Lowenheim (1974)</I><B>
</B>discusses a number of these special purpose applications.
 Knowledge of the specific chemistry for any particular nickel
plate application is essential for proper control of the process.
 The chemical composition and operating parameters for sulfate
and sulfamate baths shown below are representative of most nickel
plating baths.
<br>
<br>
<P>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>

<TABLE BORDER COLWIDTH="1,1,1">
<CAPTION><strong>CHEMICAL AND OPERATING PARAMETERS FOR SULFATE BATH:


<TR><TD><strong>Ingredient <TD><strong>Operating range <TD><strong>Function

<TR><TD>Nickel sulfate <TD>200 to 300 g/l  <TD>principle source of nickel ions
<P>
<TR><TD>Nickel chloride <TD>30 to 50 g/l <TD>improves conductivity and aids
anode corrosion

<TR><TD>Boric acid   <TD>30 to 45 g/l  <TD>promotes smoother, less brittle deposits 

<TR><TD>Wetting agents   <TD><center> *</center> <TD>reduce pitting

<TR><TD>Organic addition agents  <TD> <center> *</center> <TD>create the final, desired appearance
(from satinlike to full-mirror bright)

<TR><TD>Temperature    <TD>45 to 65  o C
<TR><TD>pH    <TD>3.0 to 4.2
</TABLE>
<P>
<br>

<TABLE BORDER COLWIDTH="1,1,1">
<CAPTION><strong>CHEMICAL AND OPERATING PARAMETERS FOR SULFAMATE BATH

<TR><TD><strong>Ingredient <TD><strong>Concentration (g/l) <TD><strong>Function

<TR><TD>Nickel sulfamate <TD>300 to 450 g/l <TD>principle source of nickel ions

<TR><TD>Nickel Chloride  <TD>5 to 15 g/l <TD>improves conductivity and aids anode corrosion

<TR><TD>Boric acid  <TD>30 to 45 g/l <TD>promotes smoother, less brittle deposits

<TR><TD>Wetting agents  <TD><center>*</center>  <TD>reduce pitting

<TR><TD>Organic addition agents  <TD><center>*</center>  <TD>create the final, desired appearance (from satinlike to full-mirror bright)

<TR><TD>Temperature <TD> 45 to 65 o C
<P>
<TR><TD>pH <TD>3.0 to 4.2
</TABLE>

<P>
* These agents are proprietary products and their use will generally
require adjustment of the process solution and operation to the
supplier's specifications.  In most cases, continuous or frequent
carbon filtration to remove particulates and impurities will be
necessary.
<P>
<br><center><a href="1070do.htm"><img src="giffiles/1070-g1a.gif"  border=0 ></a></center></p>

<P>
<P>
(Reference for this article)
<P>
Lowenheim, Frederick A., <U>Modern Electroplating, Third Edition</U>,
John Wiley &amp; Sons, New York, NY, 1974.

