<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Leonhardt Plating Company</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="#000000" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P><IMG SRC="giffiles/conthead.gif" HEIGHT=24 WIDTH=685></P>

<H2><B><FONT COLOR="#000000">Institute of Advanced Manufacturing Sciences,
Inc.</FONT></B>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></H2>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Case Study: Spray rinse tank for drag-out recovery </H2>

<TABLE ALIGN=LEFT hspace="15" >
<TR>
<TH colspan="2"><IMG SRC="file:///W|/htdocs/p2irisde/giffiles/dragout.jpg" <tr HEIGHT=240 WIDTH=320></TH>

<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM></TD>
</TR>

<CAPTION ALIGN=BOTTOM>
<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=-1>Spray recovery rinse following decorative <BR>
chrome plating operation</FONT></I></B> </P>
</CAPTION>
</TABLE>

<P>Based on recommendations from a waste reduction assessment conducted
by a the Institute of Advanced Manufacturing Sciences, a NIST Manufacturing
Extension Center, a simple spray rinse drag-out recovery tank was installed
on the decorative chrome plating line at the Leonhardt Plating Company
to reduce chromic acid drag-out losses. </P>

<P>Periodically, 10-15 gallons of deionized water is added to an empty
tank immediately following the chromic acid plating bath. The operator
uses a stream of rinse water generated by a recirculating pump to remove
most of the chromic acid drag-out from the work. </P>

<P>Notice the color difference between the rinsed and unrinsed parts in
the photo below. Over time, the chromic acid concentration of the drag-out
bath increases and enriched solution is returned as makeup to the plating
bath. If evaporation losses from the plating bath are sufficiently high,
significant savings in the cost of metal salt addition to the plating bath
can be achieved. It is important to charge the spray rinse tank with deionized
or reverse osmosis water to reduce contamination of the plating bath with
unwanted ion species. </P>

<TABLE ALIGN=LEFT hspace="15" >
<TR>
<TH colspan="2"><IMG SRC="file:///W|/htdocs/p2irisde/1078-go4.jpg" HEIGHT=240 WIDTH=320>
</TH>

<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=BOTTOM></TD>
</TR>

<CAPTION ALIGN=BOTTOM>
<P><B><I><FONT SIZE=-1>Detail of recovery spray rinse. Note viscous <BR>
yellow chromic acid on parts at left</FONT></I></B> </P>
</CAPTION>
</TABLE>

<P>Although drag-out reduction is an effective method of pollution prevention,
it may create its own set of problems. When drag-out is reduced, the buildup
of contaminants from the breakdown of bath chemicals and drag-in of minerals
tends to increase. Some method of maintaining or restoring bath chemistry
such as the use of <A HREF="1073.htm">ion exchange</A> for process water
may be necessary. In general, however, it is more cost effective to prevent
concentrated plating solutions from being diluted in subsequent processes
thus increasing the volume of solution that must be treated. </P>

<P>*</P>

<P>*</P>

<P>*</P>

<P>
<HR></P>

