<HEAD>

<TITLE>Technology Reinvestment Project</TITLE>


</HEAD><BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>

<H1>The Technology Reinvestment
Project</H1>
<h2>Dual-Use Innovation for a Stronger Defense</h2>

<CENTER><TABLE> 
<TR ALIGN=LEFT> <TD colspan=2><font size=4> Throughout this century, the United
States has become increasingly involved in world affairs, and, when necessary, conflicts.  At the same
time, we are using a more limited force to respond to more diverse
challenges.  In these circumstances, the United States must constantly
work to find new ways to minimize our casualties, multiply our power, and
protect our people and equipment.  Technology can provide solutions for
many of these concerns.
<P>
The Technology Reinvestment Project, under the management and sponsorship
of the Advanced Research Projects Agency, is ensuring that technology
development vital to current and future national security continues.  At
the same time, it is cooperating with and tapping into the resources of
the commercial sector, allowing Defense to maintain U.S. military
superiority by affordably producing the technology it needs.</font>
<td><IMG SRC="image/cover.gif">


<TR><TD><a href="cov_jet_lg.html"><IMG HEIGHT=130 ALT="Image of a Jet"
SRC="image/jet.gif" ALT="jet"></a>
<TD><a href="cov_ship_lg.html"><IMG HEIGHT=131 ALT="Battleship"
SRC="image/battleship.gif"></a>
<TD><a href="cov_tank_lg.html"><IMG HEIGHT=131 ALT="Tank" SRC="image/tank.gif">
</a>

</CENTER></TABLE>
<P>
<TABLE WIDTH=90% BORDER=5 cellpadding=6>
<TR><TD><BR><strong><I><font size=4>"[The TRP is] one of those
great deals for the military, and it's a great deal for the country."</font></I>
<p>General John M. Shalikashvili<BR>
Chairman, Joint Chiefs of Staff, 1995</strong>
</TABLE>
<br>
