<html><head><title>Fiscal Year 1995 Winners</title></head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>Affordable Advanced Controls Technologies</h1>
<p><A HREF="../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/cover_button.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/previous.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/toc.gif"></A>
<A HREF=bsmds.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/next.gif"></A>
<HR>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/focus.gif"><p>Military systems often depend on
sophisticated control systems in order to operate close to their performance limits.  New, more affordable
controls technology would reduce the costs of major military systems while
extending their useful life and reducing their maintenance requirements.
Because these same advantages are of interest to many commercial products and
systems, this creates an opportunity for R&amp;D projects in the mutual
interest of the DoD and the commercial sector.  This TRP focus area addresses a
broad spectrum of controls technologies such as standard components for "plug
and play" architectures, distributed high temperature controls, intelligent
sensor/actuator systems, and adaptive controls.  Introducing commercial
dynamism and economies of scale in the design and manufacture of control
systems important to the DoD will create a wider base of affordable controls
technologies for the military.<p>
<hr><p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>High Temperature Distributed Control Systems</h3><p>
<p>
<b>United Technologies Research Center</b>; AlliedSignal Aerospace;
AlliedSignal Aerospace Equipment Systems; Boeing Defense &amp; Space Group;
CALCE EPRC, University of Maryland; Hamilton Standard, Division of United
Technologies Corp.; Moog Inc.; Parker Hannifin Corp.; Rockwell International
Corporation, Science Center; Solid State Electronics Center/Honeywell Inc.;
Toranaga Technologies, Inc.; United Technologies Corp., Pratt &amp;
Whitney/GESP; United Technologies Microelectronics Center<p>
<p>
This project will develop and demonstrate affordable, reliable, distributed
control systems with electronic modules that operate at up to 200[[ring]] C.
Distributed control architectures offer better performance and reliability,
lower weight, and lower purchase and maintenance costs.  This project will
allow distributed architectures to be more widely used in both military and
commercial applications by improving the ability to place sensors and actuators
in hostile, high temperature environments.  In particular, this project will
demonstrate high temperature, distributed control components on a F119 jet
engine vane actuator and an automotive power steering system.<p>
<p>
* Estimated Total Project Cost: $19,418,717<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Industry Common Building Block Electronic Modules</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Lockheed Martin Control Systems</b>, AlliedSignal Aerospace Equipment
Systems, AlliedSignal Engines, General Electric Aircraft Engines, General
Electric Corporate R &amp; D, Lockheed Martin GES<p>
<p>
This team of control system users and a control system manufacturer will
develop Common Building Block Electronic Modules in order to significantly
lower the design, development, and manufacturing cost of digital controllers.
Such "black box" controllers are used in military and commercial jet engines,
automotive products, industrial automation, and many other applications.  The
electronic building blocks developed under this project would be used as
common, shared parts to create a wide variety of digital controllers at a lower
cost.  For example, it is estimated that this approach might lower the cost of
a typical jet engine controller by 20 to 40 percent.   The building blocks will
be developed by defining functions that can be shared and by constructing high
density electronic modules using new, low cost packaging technology.<p>
<p>
* Estimated Total Project Cost: $2,841,676<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>ISMIS, Intelligent Shock Mitigation and Isolation System, Through Applied
RSPM Technology</h3><p>
<p>
<b>ENIDINE INCORPORATED</b>; Hydro-Line, Inc.; Moog Controls Inc.; National
Center for Earthquake Engineering Research; Navy/Naval Surface Warfare Center;
University at Buffalo, State Univ. of New York<p>
<p>
This project will demonstrate intelligent shock mitigation and isolation system
(ISMIS) devices that could be integrated into the structural elements of
buildings and Navy ships.  These devices will reduce the effects of low
frequency, random vibrations on structures by using sophisticated
electromechanical components to intelligently absorb and redistribute the
vibrational energy.  In the case of Navy ships, these vibrations can stem from
underwater weapons and have a devastating effect on shipboard equipment.
Always a danger to ships, these shocks are an even more pressing problem as the
Navy uses more commercial-off-the-shelf equipment.  Earthquakes create a very
similar set of problems for buildings.  ISMIS is a possible solution to both
problems, creating an opportunity for the Navy to leverage the growing market
for seismic protection equipment.  If successful, this team will create a
commercial family of ISMIS products that the Navy could also use to meet its
needs.<p>
<p>
* Estimated Total Project Cost: $6,740,000<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Laser Wind and Hazard Profiler (LWiHP)</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Honeywell Technology Center</b>; Coherent Technologies, Inc.; Lightwave
Electronics Corporation; McDonnell Douglas Aerospace; McDonnell Douglas
Helicopter Systems<p>
<p>
Honeywell and its partners will design, fabricate, and flight test an eye-

safe
Laser Wind and Hazard Profiler.  This device will use recent advances in
solid-state lasers and light detection and ranging techniques to measure the
three dimensional wind velocity vector around aircraft.  This would give the
military improved weapons fire control accuracy for helicopters, as well as
high accuracy air data for the control of high performance aircraft.  The
commercial sector has an interest in this technology because it could help
detect wake vortices from nearby aircraft as well as turbulence in landing
areas.  This project will demonstrate both the performance and the
affordability of such a laser system, so that it will become attractive for
commercial and military customers.<p>
<p>
* Estimated Total Project Cost: $7,384,495<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Model Based Control and Diagnostics</h3><p>
<p>
<b>GE Aircraft Engines,</b> Ford Motor Company, General Electric Corporate R
&amp; D, Lockheed-Martin Control Systems<p>
<p>
GE and its partners will design, fabricate and test a prototype Model Based
Control and Diagnostics (MBCD) system.  MBCD uses a real-time model, embedded
in the digital controller, to enhance control and diagnostics.  This type of
adaptive control system has the potential to improve the thrust to weight
ratio, fuel consumption, reliability, weight, and cost of military jet engines.
Specific goals of this project are:  design a nonlinear, model based controller
and demonstrate its unique adaptive capabilities; implement the diagnostics
needed to detect, isolate, and accommodate faults; and demonstrate the ability
of the system to run efficiently with a reduced number of sensors. If
successful, MBCD will be introduced in several systems.  GE will use it on
military and commercial jet engines, Ford will insert this technology into
automobiles, and Lockheed-Martin will apply it to aircraft flight controls.<p>
<p>
* Estimated Total Project Cost: $3,686,563<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Vehicle Management System Integration Technology for Affordable Life Cycle
Cost (VITAL Program)</h3><p>
<p>
<b>McDonnell Douglas Aerospace</b>; Aircraft Braking Systems Corp.;
AlliedSignal Aerospace Equipment Systems; BF Goodrich; Electronic
Systems/Raytheon Company; Fotron, Inc.; Gec-Marconi Aerospace Inc.; Honeywell
Inc., Space and Aviation Control; HR Textron; Lear Astronics Corporation;
Litton Guidance and Control Systems Division; Lockheed Martin Control Systems;
McDonnell Douglas Aerospace; McDonnell Douglas Helicopter Systems; Moog Inc.;
Parker Hannifin Corp., Control Systems Division; Parker Hannifin Corp., Gull
Electronic Systems Division; Rosemount Aerospace Inc.; SCI Systems, Inc.;
Smiths Industries; Smiths Industries Defense Systems North America; United
Technologies Microelectronics Center, Inc.; United Technologies, Hamilton
Standard Division<p>
<p>
McDonnell Douglas and its partners will develop the components, interfaces,
practices, software, and tools needed for affordable vehicle management systems
(VMS) that can meet the requirements of both military and commercial aircraft
through an open, "plug and play" architecture.  This approach could be
integrated into current aircraft to extend their useful life and set the VMS
standard for the next generation of military and commercial aircraft.  By
developing components for a variety of dual use applications, the cost of VMS
systems can be reduced. For example, it is estimated that this approach could
reduce the life cycle cost of a fighter VMS by 23 percent over the current F-22
estimates, along with making improvements in weight and reliability.  The VITAL
project will culminate in flight-tests on military and commercial aircraft to
demonstrate its practicality and benefits.  This team, which includes many
major suppliers to the military and commercial aircraft markets, will be able
to sustain the technology and resource base necessary for this new VMS
paradigm.<p>
<p>
* Estimated Total Project Cost: $48,000,000<p>
Duration:  24 Months<p>
<p>
<HR align=left width=50%>
* The DoD will pay no more than 50% of the final total cost 

