</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Fiscal Year 1995 Winners</title></head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>Biological Sensors and Multiorgan Diagnostic Screening</h1><p>
<A HREF="../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/cover_button.gif"></A>
<A HREF=aact.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/previous.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/toc.gif"></A>
<A HREF=dwcns.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/next.gif"></A>
<HR>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/focus.gif"><p>Many soldiers wounded in combat must be diagnosed
and treated during the first hour after they are injured or their chances of recovery are
poor.  In fact, the percentage of wounded who survive this "Golden Hour" has
not changed since the Civil War, partly because it is so difficult to get good
diagnostic information on the battlefield.  This TRP focus area will improve
the quality and timeliness of diagnostic information available both on the
battlefield and in the field hospital by developing technologies that will
provide information about where shrapnel is located in the body, the extent and
nature of wounds, and internal bleeding. <p>
<p>
The civil trauma care community has a very similar set of problems, creating an
opportunity to work on technologies of interest to both the DoD and civil
sectors.  This will help ensure that emerging civil trauma care technology will
meet the military's requirements for "far forward" devices such as low power
consumption, portability, and ruggedness, and that the DoD will benefit from
the interoperability, technological dynamism, and cost reducing
economies-of-scale stemming from the civilian marketplace.  The five projects
in this focus area should lead to commercially viable, militarily useful
devices that will give corpsmen and physicians better diagnostic information
much less invasively, particularly through the use of ultrasound.<p>
<hr><p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Combat Surgical Ultrasound System &amp; Probes with Multi-Modality Image
Fusion, for Front Line Surgical Guidance &amp; Telesurgery</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Tetrad Corporation</b>, Materials Systems Inc., Medical Media Systems<p>
<p>
This project will develop a system that will allow field surgeons to use
internal, ultrasound probes to rapidly assess internal organ damage far less
invasively.  These small, rugged, autoclavable probes will be inserted through
wounds or other small holes.  The ultrasound data they produce will be fused
with other diagnostic data, such as MRIs or laproscopic video, in order to
produce a more usable and versatile image for the surgeon.  This project will
develop the probes, ultrasound system, and data fusion techniques needed to
integrate this system into a mobile surgery suite located near the front lines.
Civilian applications for minimally invasive surgery and trauma care closely
parallel the needs of the combat surgeon, creating an opportunity for this
technology to be sustained by a larger marketplace.  Eventually, these
capabilities could become one of the building blocks for the remote combat
surgery systems of the future.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $6,531,732<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Low-Power, High-Resolution, Portable Ultrasound Imaging System</h3>
<p>
<b>Teratech Corporation, </b>Parallel Design Inc., Tetrad Corporation<p>
<p>
In this project, Teratech and its partners will develop the technology
necessary for a battery-operated, high-resolution, portable ultrasound system.
Current ultrasound systems are ill-suited to the battlefield because they are
bulky, consume large amounts of power, and produce images that can be difficult
to interpret. This project will use innovative charge domain electronics for
the beamforming computation in order to dramatically reduce the power
consumption and size of these scanners and improve their field portability.
This team will also improve the image quality and diagnostic utility of the
ultrasound images by using adaptive beamforming techniques to correct the
aberrating effects of tissue.  Other enhancements to this system include a
technology that will allow physicians to see some internal functions, such as
blood flow, without surgery.  With survival rates highly dependent on treatment
speed, the portability and on-site diagnostic information  provided by this
system will improve the care of a wounded soldier on the battlefield or other
trauma victims.  <p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $2,834,680<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Portable 3-D Imaging Ultrasound Systems Based on 1.5-D and 1-D Integrated
Arrays</h3><p>
<p>
<b>GTS/Albatross Technologies, Inc.</b>; Alta Technology Corporation;
EndoSonics Corporation; Loral Infrared &amp; Imaging Systems; TechniScan,
Inc.<p>
<p>
This project will develop technology needed for the first portable, compact,
three dimensional (3-D) medical imaging ultrasound system.  Today, most
ultrasound images are two dimensional slices; this device would literally make
a new dimension in ultrasound diagnostics more commonly available.  This system
will feature mechanically scanned 1.5 D ultrasonic arrays (arrays fully
populated in one dimension, but with only a limited number of rows in the other
dimension) to form ultrasound images of a 3-D volume of tissue.  Additional
features of this project include beamforming electronics integrated with the
transducer arrays, unique interconnection technology, and a modular approach to
imaging software for ease of data transmission.  Compact, real time, 3-D
imaging systems represent a totally new product that will not only serve
existing clinical needs, but will open new diagnostic and monitoring
applications in combat casualty care, civilian emergency response, and general
radiology.  This dual-use development ensures that this exciting new capability
will meet the unique medical needs of the military on or near the front lines.
<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $4,715,177<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Portable Ultrasound Device for Battlefield Trauma</h3><p>
<p>
<b>University of Washington</b>; Advanced Technology Laboratories, Inc.;
Army/Madigan Army Hospital; Harborview Medical Center; Harris Semiconductor;
VLSI Technology, Inc.;<p>
<p>
This team will develop a lightweight, low-cost, real-time ultrasound imaging
system that could be used at forward echelon medical units on the battlefield
and in general medical practice.  Focused on reducing the size and cost of
ultrasound, this project will use advanced application specific integrated
circuits to create a hand-held, ultrasound imaging device with telemedicine
capability and an image quality comparable to the current top-of-the-line
conventional clinical systems, which are the size of refrigerators.  Madigan
Army Hospital is participating on the team to make sure that the device will be
suitable for the battlefield.  The portability of this instrument will enable
the diagnosis to be brought to the battlefield, rather than the casualty to the
hospital, thus improving combat casualty care.  In the civil sector, the
advantages of this device create the potential for reducing health care costs
while providing a longer range quality health care. <p>
<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $12,638,579<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Virtual Endoscopy</h3><p>
<p>
<b>General Electric Company</b>, Brigham and Women's Hospital, The Bowman Gray
School of Medicine<p>
<p>
This project will develop a virtual endoscope -- a safe, non-invasive, and more
cost-effective method of examining internal organs that will use virtual
reality technology to view large 3-D anatomy data sets produced by CAT scans,
ultrasound, or MRIs.   Essentially, this technology will allow physicians to
view this 3-D data as though they were looking through an endoscope, but
without the invasiveness and expense of an endoscopic procedure.  This will
improve the ability to diagnose and assess internal injuries on the far forward
battlefield by allowing a fast, contiguous, non-invasive examination of hollow
organs.  Moreover, data from a wounded soldier could be shown in a format
familiar to surgeons and endoscopists anywhere in the world, bringing their
radiological expertise to the physicians near the battlefield and wounded.  The
sophisticated image rendering of virtual endoscopy can be applied to other
current ARPA and TRP projects involving remote imaging on the battlefield, such
as handheld ultrasound and portable MRIs.  In the civilian realm, this
revolutionary radiological technology will have a wide variety of applications,
particularly for detecting colorectal cancer more comfortably and less
expensively through virtual colonoscopy.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $4,008,870<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<HR align=left width=50%>
* The DoD will pay no more than 50% of the final total cost 
<p><hr>
