<html><head><title>Fiscal Year 1995 Winners</title></head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>Digital Wireless Communications and Networking Systems</h1><p><A HREF="../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/cover_button.gif"></A>
<A HREF=bsmds.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/previous.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/toc.gif"></A>
<A HREF=mems.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/next.gif"></A>
<HR>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/focus.gif"><p>This focus area will accelerate the development
and military availability of innovative communications and networking products based on
configurable, modular, digital wireless technologies.  The military's need for
secure, high data rate, digital networks is well known; the Army's program to
"Digitize the Battlefield" is an excellent example of efforts in this area.  At
the same time, digital wireless communications is one of today's most active
commercial technology areas, with a great deal of research and new product
development occurring.  This situation creates an opportunity for the DoD to
leverage this commercial dynamism to ensure that emerging digital wireless
network technology will meet, at an affordable price, the DoD's special needs
such as security, rapid deployability, flexible topology, and dynamic bandwidth
allocation.  This focus area's six projects will help create the networks,
terminals, and components that can meet the needs of both military and
commercial digital wireless users.<p>
<hr><p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Advanced Communications Engine</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Hughes Communication Projects</b>, National Semiconductor Corporation<p>
<p>
The Advanced Communications Engine project led by Hughes Aircraft Company will
build a multi-band, multi-mode radio using a single path digital receiver that
will let both commercial and military users "program" the radio's
functionality.  This can be thought of as allowing the radio's specific
functions to be implemented through software instead of hardware.  Software can
be altered or updated much easier than hardware.  In addition, this approach
creates cost reducing economies of scale in the hardware.  This "communications
engine" will provide the capability to receive six simultaneous communications
channels across five  simultaneous bands. The project will also develop the
software needed to implement various military communications waveforms and an
encryption system.  These capabilities will mesh well with the Army's
initiative to "Digitize the Battlefield."  The wide variety of potential
commercial applications of this radio, including marine, law enforcement,
automobile, and cellular communications, will help keep down the cost of the
military radios.<p>
<p>
 *Estimated Total Project Cost: $14,650,165<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Defense Applications for a Multiple Path Beyond Line-Of-Site Communications
Network</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Orbital Sciences Corporation</b>, Torrey Science &amp; Technology
Corporation<p>
<p>
This project will design a prototype communications system for the Multiple
Path Beyond Line-of-Site Communications System (MUBLCOM) concept and
demonstrate it via an on-orbit satellite test.  If the concept proves feasible,
Orbital Sciences Corporation and Torrey Science Corporation plan to extend the
capability to a full satellite system, which could serve both commercial and
military customers.<p>
<p>
MUBLCOM would address many of DoD's needs for secure, mobile, interference
resistant, voice and data communications by providing digital voice and data
communications directly between small hand-held terminals that are rapidly
deployable, cost-effective, virtually terrain independent, all-weather,
beyond-line-of-sight capable, and secure. This capability would support combat
net radios and many special missions including long-range surveillance and fire
support teams.  In the commercial market, MUBLCOM could address the needs for
communications in remote areas, emergency/disaster response, remote sensor
monitoring, and container tracking. Overall, this project could lead to a
satellite-based communications system capable of meeting DoD's requirements,
but financed by private, instead of government capital -- a major saving to the
DoD.<p>
<p>
 *Estimated Total Project Cost: $15,036,811<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Digital Wireless Communications and Networking Systems Program</h3><p>
<p>
<b>ITT Aerospace</b>; Angeles Communications Design, Ericsson Inc.; Honeywell
Technology Center; Pacific Communication Sciences, Inc.; Techno-Sciences, Inc.;
UCLA - Electrical Engineering Department<p>
<p>
The Digital Wireless Communications and Networking Systems project led by ITT
will develop a small, rugged, modular, handheld multimedia terminal to securely
network voice, data, and high rate video.  By using advanced algorithms, signal
processing, and component technologies, these radios will operate autonomously
in a highly mobile, multi-hop environment over a wide geographic area without
base stations.  These types of capabilities are well aligned with the vision
behind the Army's initiative to Digitize the Battlefield. Waveform and
frequency flexibility will enable commercial applications, such as personal
communications systems and medical point of care, access to computer based
patient records. This dual-use development will ensure that this technology
emerges in a fashion commensurate with DoD's special needs.<p>
<p>
 *Estimated Total Project Cost: $6,858,506<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>High Speed Digital Wireless Battlefield Network</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Hughes Aircraft Company;</b> E-Systems, Inc.; Hughes Network Systems;
Stanford University<p>
<p>
Hughes Communications Products and its partners will demonstrate a
cost-effective High Speed Digital Wireless Battlefield Network that is rapidly
deployable, supports multimedia, and provides secure end-to-end networking --
the sort of network that could be crucial in the 21st Century battlefield. This
wideband wireless communications system will use code division multiple access
technology, smart antennas, intelligent network server software, and direct
broadcast satellites.  The team will leverage Hughes' investments in very small
aperture terminals and satellite-based video and data to broadcast high speed
data to the wireless network.  The project offers significant benefits to DoD
in the areas of intelligent networking, mobile base-stations, and secure/smart
antennas. These technologies also have important commercial applications in
areas like personal communications services and direct broadcast services,
providing leverage for the DoD.<p>
<p>
<p>
 *Estimated Total Project Cost: $8,833,812<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Miniature Filters For Wireless Networks</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Westinghouse Science and Technology Center</b>, TFR Technologies, Inc.<p>
<p>
The Miniature Filters for Wireless Networks project, led by Westinghouse
Science &amp; Technology Center, will develop fabrication procedures, packaging
techniques, and rapid computer design tools to reduce the size, weight, and
cost of miniature filters. These technologies will enable compact filters,
filterbanks, and oscillators to be built that will enhance DoD radar, low-cost
seekers, smart munitions, ESM receivers, and compact ID location transceivers
as well as improve commercial GPS and cellular communications products.  Three
different types of filters will be developed under this project, each having
specific military and commercial applications targeted for potential insertion.
Using these filters in high-volume commercial wireless applications will keep
them affordable and available to the DoD.<p>
<p>
 *Estimated Total Project Cost: $ 2,418,397<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Testbed for Digital Wireless Communications and Networking Systems</h3><p>
<p>
<b>AT&amp;T Corporation</b>, Army/CECOM RD&amp;E Center, Bell Communications
Research, David Sarnoff Research Center<p>
<p>
The Wireless Interworking Testbed Team, led by AT&amp;T and including the
Army's primary communications R&amp;D center (CECOM), will establish an
interoperable, end-to-end, mixed wireless and wireline testbed for
demonstrating and validating new technologies and standards. This will improve
the ability of both the DoD and the commercial sector to develop, integrate,
test, and buy new combinations of digital wireless products and technologies.
In particular, projects performed within the testbed will accelerate the
adaptation of commercial communications standards and products for military
uses.  Additionally, the testbed will lend itself towards the development of
large-scale commercial applications such as video-on-demand services which
could set the trend for the video distribution systems of the future.<p>
<p>
 *Estimated Total Project Cost: $2,870,000<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<HR align=left width=50%>
* The DoD will pay no more than 50% of the final total cost 
<hr>
