<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Fiscal Year 1995 Winners</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF>
<H1>Microelectromechanical Systems (MEMS) Applications</H1><P><A HREF="../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/cover_button.gif"></A>
<A HREF=dwcns.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/previous.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/toc.gif"></A>
<A HREF=ootw.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/next.gif"></A>
<HR>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/focus.gif"><p>Microelectromechanical systems (MEMS)
technology uses the materials and processes of semiconductor electronics to create integrated
electromechanical systems that merge computation, sensing, and actuation.  MEMS
technology will give existing and new weapons systems overwhelming sensing and
actuation abilities -- creating new ways to both <I>perceive</I>  and
<I>control  </I>the battlefield.  Embedding MEMS into weapons system, from
precision munitions to high-maneuverability aircraft, will bring the military
new levels of situational awareness and battlefield control.  MEMS is emerging
as one of the most important new technologies for both Defense and commercial
systems; it will make high-end performance affordable for low-end systems,
extend the lifetimes of existing systems, and create radically new
capabilities.<P>
<P>
The projects in this focus area will accelerate the affordability,
manufacturability, and insertion of MEMS devices into specific and mutually
supporting DoD and commercial applications. Starting from demonstrated MEMS
concepts, these projects focus on achievable, dual-use products requiring the
development of affordable manufacturing processes.<P>
<HR><P>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Automotive Micromachined Gyro and Derivative Applications</H3><P>
<P>
<B>Rockwell</B>; Alliant Tech Systems; Army/U.S. Army Research Laboratory;
Endevco; Ford Motor Company; Navy/Naval Surface Warfare Center; Rockwell Wabco
Vehicle Control Systems; The Charles Stark Draper Laboratory, Inc.; University
of California; Los Angeles (UCLA)<P>
<P>
The project will develop the manufacturing, testing, and device technology
necessary to make micromachined silicon gyroscopes and inertial sensor
assemblies available for only tens, instead of tens of thousands, of dollars
and weighing only tenths, instead of tens, of kilograms. Manufacturing these
MEMS devices cost effectively will make them viable for a variety of automotive
systems such as anti-lock braking systems (ABS), and for guidance applications
in a large class of DoD munitions, such as mortars, precision munitions, and
the Marine's Predator missile.<P>
<P>
This project takes advantage of the fact that the performance requirements for
gyroscopes in the Predator's guidance systems and the next generation ABS are
extremely similar.  By creating the manufacturing techniques and devices to
serve the growing, worldwide ABS market and DoD munitions, the development of a
MEMS-based gyro production capability will accelerate the availability of these
devices and reduce the DoD's acquisition costs for the Predator and related
guidance units. To help ensure that the project can serve both commercial and
military customers, its advisory group consists of the world's largest
manufacturer of conventional munitions and the world's number two auto maker.<P>
<P>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $12,184,914<P>
Duration:  24 months<P>
<P>
<P>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Self Monitoring Advanced Remote Technology System (SMARTS)</H3><P>
<P>
<B>Martin Marietta Technologies, Inc</B>.; Analog Devices, Inc., T &amp; IPD
Division; Auburn University, Remote Monitoring of America; System Excelerator,
Inc.; University of Florida; Weld Star Technology, Incorporated<P>
<P>
Martin Marietta and its partners will develop a wireless, tactical missile
readiness monitoring system by using MEMS devices, including latching
accelerometers and pressure sensors, to monitor the structural and
environmental integrity of missile housings.  The team will combine existing
and new MEMS technology, low power electronics, and wireless communications
into a unique sensor suite that will let DoD personnel remotely assess the
readiness of missile rounds in storage, transit, and the field.  SMARTS will
use two types of MEMS-based sensors to produce data to be transmitted via a
cellular phone or military data link to a modem anywhere in the world.
Compared to conventional, labor-intensive inspections, SMARTS will make rapid,
accurate, and timely readiness measurements possible for a broad range of
missile systems, improving weapon reliability, readiness, and effectiveness.<P>
<P>
SMARTS technology will also be used to remotely monitor the structural
integrity and traffic load on highway bridges and other structures.  Due to the
prohibitive costs of conventional data collection methods, highway structures
are monitored at intervals measured in years.  SMARTS will not only reduce
inspection costs but create new monitoring capabilities not possible today,
including continuous assessment for extreme weather or traffic conditions.
Using SMARTS for monitoring transportation structures will broaden the market
for integrated MEMS, low-power, and wireless technologies,  and ensure
affordable components and systems for the DoD use.  Civil and military users of
SMARTS will increase their systems' reliability, readiness, and safety with
order of magnitude reductions in maintenance time, labor, and costs.<P>
<P>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $4,000,000<P>
Duration:  24 months<P>
<P>
<HR align=left width=50%>
* The DoD will pay no more than 50% of the final total cost 
<P>
<hr>
