Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 11309
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Fiscal Year 1995 Winners</title></head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>Operations Other Than War/Law Enforcement</h1><p><A HREF="../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/cover_button.gif"></A>
<A HREF=mems.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/previous.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/toc.gif"></A>
<A HREF=spomt.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/next.gif"></A>
<HR>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/focus.gif"><p>Recently, there has been an increased emphasis
on military missions where the armed forces are used for purposes other than large scale combat.  Although
limited in scope, these missions --  termed operations other than war (OOTW) --
still present a hostile environment for the military forces performing them.
They also require a unique set of tools and strategies to accomplish the
mission while minimizing casualties to friendly forces and non-combatants.  For
example, these missions often require interacting with foreign civilian
populations or conducting military operations in urban areas.  The current
mission in Bosnia is a very visible example of this type of operation. <p>
<p>
While the development of technologies addressing these unique operations can
have a major, positive impact, the DoD cannot afford to support the entire cost
of sustaining the technology base for its limited use.  Fortunately, law
enforcement (LE) missions share many of the same operational and technical
requirements as DoD's OOTW mission.  Consequently, this general area has many
opportunities for creating common technologies that benefit both the OOTW and
civilian LE communities.  The benefits of these common technologies include the
sharing of front end conceptual design, engineering and prototype
demonstrations costs as well as providing a larger production base to reduce
unit costs.  Through this dual-use approach, DoD can have access to new
technologies for an important, but limited, operational requirement without the
need to support all of the required technology.<p>
<hr><p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Advanced CTP800 Turboprop for Surveillance Aircraft</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Light Helicopter Turbine Engine Company (Allison Engine Company and
AlliedSignal Engine)</b>, Ages Group, Army/Army Research Lab Program Office,
Chandler Evans<p>
<p>
This project will adapt and reconfigure the T800/CTS800 turboshaft engine
currently used in the US Army RAH-66 Commanche helicopter into a new 1350 shaft
horse power turboprop engine and demonstrate the new engine in aircraft
applicable to both military and commercial use. This will require redesigning
the gear box, flight controls, and various other mechanical aspects of the
engine.<p>
<p>
The performance of the T800 is significantly better than any other engine of
its class, but its cost is likely to remain high because of the limited size of
the helicopter market.  The turboprop market, on the other hand, offers a
larger number of opportunities for engine insertions and economies of scale.
By adapting the T800 engine for that use, its superior performance will be
available for a number of DoD applications. The first intended military
aircraft for the new engine is the Army's Airborne Reconnaissance Low
Surveillance platform, an asset used to support OOTW missions.  With a parallel
intended commercial platform (DeHavilland DHC-7), this new turboprop engine
would benefit both military and commercial aviation, including enhanced safety
and decreased operations, maintenance, and engine costs.  Many of these
improvements would, in turn, flow back to the Commanche engine from which the
new engine sprang, providing a benefit to that Army system as well.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $16,367,968 <p>
Duration:  30 months<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Affordable Language Education Software for Government and
CommercialCommerical Use</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Broderbund Software Inc</b>., Corona Corporation, SRI International<p>
<p>
This project will develop and demonstrate a prototype system for affordable,
portable foreign language training and maintenance.  It will develop software
to teach and maintain Spanish for native English speakers using personal
computers. The system will be designed so it can be used for other languages of
interest to the DoD. <p>
<p>
The availability of cost-effective, portable language training and maintenance
software will improve the efficiency of US operations.  Language proficiency is
extremely important in a variety of military situations, especially for the
Special Operations Forces.  Currently, DoD's language training and retraining
is done at centralized locations.  The world wide stationing of our forces on
land and sea makes it difficult and expensive to provide language proficiency.
Furthermore, language proficiency decreases without constant use or
maintenance; retraining is difficult when deployment can be at a moment's
notice. Spanish is an excellent demonstration language because a large number
of Special Operation Forces need this language. The similar needs within the
law enforcement community, counterdrug agencies, and the commercial business
sector will help ensure rapid acceptance and non-DoD funded enhancements of
this technology.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $9,343,771<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Diver Alert and Tracking System</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Sonetech Corporation;</b> Ocean Vision Technology; Perdix, Inc.; Sanders
Design International<p>
<p>
This project will develop and demonstrate a prototype Diver Alert and Tracking
System that will produce navigation accuracy  in the littoral, undersea
environment comparable to differential GPS. Although the need for military
divers to know their precise location is critical, current approaches to this
problem are rudimentary.  Because a GPS signal cannot be received underwater, a
different type of system, like this one, is needed by our military divers. For
example, this system would greatly enhance the mine location and clearance
capability of the Navy's Explosive Ordnance Disposal and Special Warfare
communities.  Because this navigation capability would also be of interest to
sports divers and commercial diving operations, it should be sustained and
enhanced by the non-DoD marketplace once this technology's feasibility is
demonstrated.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $1,017,632<p>
Duration:  12 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Electron Bombarded CCD Camera</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Intevac Advanced Technology Division</b>; EEV, Inc.; Federal Bureau of
Investigations,; Honeywell Inc.; The Charles Stark Draper Laboratory, Inc.;
University of Arizona<p>
<p>
This project will develop and prototype an Electron Bombarded Charged Coupled
Device (CCD) camera that will have two times better resolution at low light
levels, ten times greater sensitivity, half the package size, and a lower cost
than existing night vision CCD cameras.<p>
<p>
Low light vision is obviously of critical importance to the DoD; if this
project is successful, it will significantly improve that capability.  Possible
benefits include more accurate identification of personnel, vehicles, and
markings.  In addition, the smaller size and lower cost of this device will
allow it to be used in many more operational situations than current devices,
including as a subsystem in surveillance platforms.   The advantages of
improved low light vision at a lower cost and size also appeal to the law
enforcement and private security communities, providing a way for DoD to obtain
and sustain this technology at a lower cost.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $2,886,863<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Millimeter Wave Focal Plane Array Radar for Concealed Weapons
Detection</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Millitech Corporation,</b> Riverside Research Institute, Technology Service
Corporation<p>
<p>
This project will develop and demonstrate a millimeter wave focal plane array
radar for detecting weapons and other contraband materials concealed behind
walls, in packages, or under someone's clothing.  Millimeter wave radar is
ideal for this application because it can penetrate buildings or other
materials and clearly  show metal objects.  This project will develop a
brassboard system that can use both active and passive sensing modes.  <p>
<p>
In counterterrorism and hostage rescues, critical decisions must often be made
without fully knowing the number and location of an adversary's weapons.  The
consequences of being wrong can be disastrous.  This technology will be able to
improve the safety and success of military, particularly Special Forces, and
law enforcement missions by giving them significantly more knowledge about
previously unseen dangers. Other potential civil applications include weapons
detection systems similar to those currently used at airports and building
entrances.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $4,250,932<p>
Duration:  13 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Quick Reaction Spoken Language Translator (QRSLT)</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Language Systems Inc.</b>; Air Force/Rome Laboratory; Air Force/Wright
Laboratory; Eloquent Technology, Inc.; Entropic Research Laboratories, Inc.;
Motorola<p>
<p>
This proposal will develop a hand-held or body-mounted translator to assist
military or law enforcement officers communicate with people who speak a
foreign language.  The translator will take simple spoken English from its
operator, translate it into the foreign language, and generate an audible
output in that foreign language.  Conversely, the translator will also handle
spoken input in that foreign language, translate it into English, and generate
audible English output.  Both these translations will take place in very close
to real time.  Spanish will be the first language to be demonstrated, but other
languages, including Arabic, will be added as the system is expanded.<p>
<p>
Ineffective and misunderstood language or hand signals between the US military
and foreign populations can lead to serious, unfortunate consequences during
the confusion of a conflict.   For example, non-verbal offers to surrender are
often taken as just the opposite.  This technology will provide soldiers with
the ability to clearly and directly communicate with foreign populations --
dramatically reducing unnecessary casualties and making US forces more
effective. This capability will also be extremely useful for law enforcement
personnel communicating with people who have a very poor command of English.
The wide range of possible applications for this technology will create
incentives for future enhancement by the commercial sector and lead to lower
costs for the military.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $4,749,822<p>
Duration:  24 Months<p>
<p>
<HR align=left width=50%>
* The DoD will pay no more than 50% of the final total cost 
<p>
<hr>
<p><A HREF="../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/cover_button.gif">
<A HREF=mems.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/previous.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/toc.gif"></A>
