</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Fiscal Year 1995 Winners</title></head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>Small Precision Optics Manufacturing Technology</h1><p><A HREF="../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/cover_button.gif"></A>
<A HREF=ootw.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/previous.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/toc.gif"></A>
<A HREF=other.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/next.gif"></A>
<HR>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/focus.gif"><p>Optics are a critical component in over 350
current US military weapons systems ranging from relatively simple devices such as night vision optics to the most
complicated precision guided munitions, sensing, targeting, communications, and
reconnaissance systems.  Advances in precision optics in ultraviolet, visible
and infrared regions, will be increasingly important to next generation
advanced defense systems. The ability to fabricate the optics for these
advanced systems with improved performance and reduced manufacturing costs is a
critically important capability.  <p>
<p>
The projects in this focus area will develop technology to cost effectively
manufacture precision optical components to meet the needs of the DoD and a
broad spectrum of emerging commercial technologies  including optical
communications, optical data storage, microlithography, minimally invasive
laser surgery, environmental sensing, and surveillance systems.  These
technologies require high precision reflective and refractive optical elements
such as aspherics, toroids, cylinders, diffractive optical elements, and micro-

optics.
 Many consumer and business products such as copying machines, laser scanners,
laser printers, compact optical disks, and camcorders require low cost high
volume production of these same optics.  Demand for optics is projected to grow
geometrically in the next few decades.  These projects will help ensure that
the DoD can take advantage of the cost and capabilities that will result from
this growth.<p>
<hr><p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Cost Effective Manufacturing Technology for Fabricating Hybrid Diffractive
Optics</h3><p>
<p>
<b>AOtec, Inc.;</b> Army/Night Vision and Electronic Sensors Directorate;
Kaiser Electro-Optics; Kaiser Electronics; Loral Infrared and Imaging Systems<p>
<p>
This project will develop cost effective manufacturing technology for making
hybrid diffractive/refractive polymeric lenses -- lenses that integrate
diffraction and refraction within the same element.  Hybrid lenses allow the
number of optical elements in a design to be reduced, with a commensurate
reduction in cost, weight, and complexity.  In particular, this project will
develop processes for mass producing low cost, lightweight, compact,
shatter-resistant, precision plastic optics and an advanced automated optical
assembly station featuring real time, on-

line
testing, robotic systems, and image processing.<p>
<p>
Among the DoD systems that could be improved by low cost hybrid optics are
head-mounted displays for aviators, thermal imaging rifle sights, combat
vehicle vision enhancers, and simulators.  AOtec will develop the technology
working with end product developers in the defense area (Kaiser Electronics and
Loral Infrared and Imaging Systems) and the commercial area (Kaiser
Electro-Optics).  The performance improvements enabled by the project will be
demonstrated by the end-users.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost:<b> </b>$2,634,875<p>
Duration:  24 Months
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Deterministic Design, Manufacture and Assembly of Aspheric Optics</h3><p>
<p>
<b>University of Rochester, Center for Optics Manufacturing</b>; Apeiron; CNC
Systems; Eastman Kodak; Lockheed Martin; Moore Tool Company; Sinclair Optics
Inc.; Texas Instruments<p>
<p>
This project will develop and demonstrate cost effective, precision asphere
design, fabrication, and assembly technology.  A new machine tool will be
developed expressly for affordably producing these aspheric elements.  The
consortium will apply these new technologies (equipment and processes for
aspheric surface generation, deterministic microgrinding, magneto-rheological
finishing, and on-

line
metrology for in-situ dimensional measurements) to demonstrate improved system
size, weight, performance, and cost.  The technologies will be prototyped and
evaluated on selected military and commercial systems including:  the TADS/PNVS
(Target Acquisition and Designation Sight/Pilot Night Vision System) for the
Apache Helicopter; a digital micromirror device for high definition displays;
and advanced digital cameras.  In general, cost effective aspheric optics will
be needed for a variety of Defense applications such as the 21st Century Land
Warrior, pilot vision systems, and fire control.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost:  $ 6,838,000<p>
Duration:  24 Months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Diffractive Optics Technology for Battlefield Management Systems</h3><p>

<b>Rochester Photonics Corporation; </b>Army/ Weapons Sciences Directorate,
RD&amp;E Center; Eastman Kodak Co.; Hughes Aircraft Company, Research
Laboratories; Hughes Aircraft, Electro-Optical Systems; Hughes Training, Inc.;
NASA/Marshall Space Flight Center; Optivision,Inc.<p>
<p>
This team will develop low cost manufacturing techniques and processes for
fabricating precision, high performance, optical systems using diffractive
optics.  These performance improvements will be enabled by developing:  (1)
computer integrated manufacturing system for fabricating diffractive optics
master elements and molding tools, (2) low cost methods for replicating
visible, infrared optical elements, and (3) a model of stray-light effects in
diffractive optics.  Scatter and unwanted diffraction orders will be
characterized to improve the performance of sensors and displays.  During the
project, interactions between fabricators, system designers, and integrators
will accelerate technology development, evaluation, and insertion.<p>
<p>
Improvements in high-performance, low cost diffractive optics, and aspheric
optical elements will give system designers new degrees of freedom when
designing and optimizing optical systems -- leading to improved performance in
a significant number of Defense systems.  Specific Defense demonstrations in
this project include missile seeker systems, thermal weapons sights, advanced
head mounted displays, advanced electro-optic sensor systems, parallel optical
data intercon-nections, and optical encryption.  The commercial applications of
diffractive optics that would create cost-reducing economies of scale for the
DoD include: optical pick-up heads for data storage systems, consumer camera
lenses, and eye-pieces.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $14,278,602<p>
Duration: 30 Months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Integrated Small Precision Optics Manufacturing Technology</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Rockwell International Corporation;</b> Air Force/Wright Laboratory,
Materials Directorate; Focused Research, Inc.; Ford Motor Company; New
Interconnection and Packaging Technologies, Inc.; OCA Applied Optics; Polaroid
Corporation; Trustees of Boston University; University of California, San
Diego; University of Washington, Human Interface Technology Laboratory<p>
<p>
This experienced team of six companies, three universities, and a Defense
laboratory will create optical devices for beam scanning and spectral
discrimination by integrating low cost manufacturing technologies for
micro-optics, thin films, and micro-optoelectro-mechanics.  Successfully
demonstrating this technology will produce lower costs and increased
reliability for a variety of military applications.   Two specific
demonstrations will be emphasized -- an advanced missile launch warning sensor
and a very low cost helmet mounted display.  Additional military applications
for these devices include multi-wavelength imaging missile seekers, battlefield
chemical sensors, optical identification of friend or foe, and laser threat
warning receivers.  Product feasibility demonstrations will also be carried out
for these commercial products: automobile emission sensors, self contained auto
focus units, bar code scanners, and color sensors.   These commercial
applications will help sustain an affordable technology source for the DoD.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $4,358,232<p>
Duration: 24 Months<p>
<p>
<HR align=left width=50%>
* The DoD will pay no more than 50% of the final total cost 
