<html><head><title>Fiscal Year 1995 Winners</title></head>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff>
<h1>"Other" Technologies</h1><p>
<A HREF="../index.html"><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/cover_button.gif"></A>
<A HREF=spomt.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/previous.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/toc.gif"></A>
<A HREF=95desc.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/next.gif"></A>
<HR>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/focus.gif"><p>This area accepted proposals  
in technologies
other than the seven specific focus areas which were competed, allowing the 
TRP to take
advantage of other, unique opportunities of significant benefit to DoD.
Proposals in the five specific focus areas that were canceled prior to the
solicitation due to funding limitations were also submitted to this
area.<p>
<hr><p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Cryo-Electronics for Microwave Systems</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Superconductor Technologies Inc.</b>, Steinbrecher Corporation, Westinghouse
Electric Corporation<p>
<p>
This project will develop and refine processes and designs for High Temperature
Superconductor (HTS) microwave subsystems and transition these results into
improved military and commercial systems.   More specifically, it will improve
the technologies that most affect HTS subsystem cost and performance, including
HTS materials, packaging, cryo-coolers, switches, and filters, and will then
evaluate these new technologies in systems applications.<p>
<p>
For example, the performance of many DoD radar and communication systems are
limited by clutter and in-band interference.  Subsystems developed and tested
in this project would enable advanced radar systems to perform with 40 times
higher clutter than the standard technology for operations against small
targets in littoral and other high clutter areas.  HTS subsystems enabled by
this project would let electronic warfare systems fully operate in the presence
of complex signal interference and permit full bandwidth and sensitivity
operation of wireless communication systems.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $13,485,228<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Electric Variable Transmission</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Allison Transmission Division of General Motors Corporation</b>, Delphi
Energy &amp; Engine Management Systems, Electricore/NEMPC<p>
<p>
This project will develop and demonstrate a hybrid powertrain system for heavy
duty vehicles that combines the advantages of electrical and mechanical power.
Hybrid engine technology offers many potential advantages to military land
systems such as significant improvements in fuel economy (16 percent), reduced
exhaust emissions (10-20 percent), and a reduced IR signature.  This project's
parallel hybrid powertrain system will use mechanical (internal combustion
engine) and electrical (high voltage battery energy storage) input power in
parallel to deliver optimum performance to the wheels.  Keys to this system are
a variable transmission that will maintain  a constant engine speed, even as
the vehicle speed varies, and two highly efficient electrical machines that
will function either as a motor or generator depending on the vehicle's power
requirements.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $7,575,007<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Gas Generator Fire Suppression</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Kidde Technologies, Inc</b>., Atlantic Research Corporation<p>
<p>
Halons are ozone depleting substances that are being replaced with new,
environmentally friendly, fire extinguishing and gas generating technology.
This project will develop a fire suppressant delivery system that meets many of
the operational and physical configurations required by DoD for these new fire
fighting devices.  The project will identify extinguishment mechanisms using
innovative solid propellant gas generation technology, demonstrate the
feasibility of these techniques in specific military (dry bay) and related
commercial (industrial explosions) applications, and address residue,
toxicology, and inhabited area usage issues.  The initial demonstration will be
done in conjunction with the Air Force in an F-22 aircraft dry bay.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $2,881,778<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>Manufacturing Process Development for Thin Multi-Layer (Flat Panel)
Antennas</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Raytheon Co.</b>; Anaren Microwave, Inc.; Georgia Tech Research Institute;
Raytheon Advanced Device Center<p>
<p>
This project will develop a design and manufacturing process for small,
millimeter wave, flat panel, phased array antennas. This team of developers and
end-users will address the integration and affordability of high performance
components for DoD and commercial phased array applications. Its multilevel
packaging approach would reduce phased array antenna costs by a factor of 10
and create integrated/transponder assemblies that improve system performance.
The target cost for array unit cells is $30-$50 each.<p>
<p>
Phased array antennas offer significant performance and operational advantages
to the military.  The immediate military applications for thin, flat panel,
arrays include upgrades to airborne Milstar terminals, upgrades to shipboard
systems such as NESP, and satellite communication links for systems such as
J-STARS.  There is also considerable potential to use thin array technology for
multi-function apertures, including search and fire-control radars,
communications, interrogate friend or foe devices, and electronic counter
measures.  In the commercial realm, the application of low cost, thin, phased
array antennas for such things as direct broadcasting to commercial airliners
will help sustain an affordable technology base for the DoD to use.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $6,405,990<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<p>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="image/feature.gif"><h3>SiC Power Electronics for Affordable Next Generation Electric and Hybrid
Vehicles</h3><p>
<p>
<b>Westinghouse Science &amp; Technology Center</b>, Rutgers, The State
University of New Jersey, Silicon Power Corporation<p>
<p>
The project will develop a packaged 600V/100 ampere Silicon Carbide (SiC) Metal
Oxide Semiconductor  turn-off thyristor as a building block for solid-state
power controllers.  Military and commercial needs for power switching
components include aircraft, ships, and industrial power distribution.
Replacing conventional high power devices with semi-conductor technology will
allow a significant reduction in size and weight, a huge advantage for military
systems.<p>
<p>
However, because conventional semiconductors have limited temperature tolerance
and power density capabilities, cost-effective SiC based power-switching
devices are needed. SiC power switching devices are important for the Air
Force's More Electric Aircraft Program, the Navy's Power Electric Building
Block Program, and ARPA's Combat Hybrid Power program. The increased electric
breakdown strength, reduced size and cooling requirements, and increased
reliability of SiC devices will help replace hydraulic systems on aircraft with
wires and distributed motors, build more reliable shipboard power distribution
systems, and enable a hybrid power main battle tank with active armor and
electric guns. This project advances these goals by addressing critical
technical issues in making SiC devices such as packaging, high-temperature and
high power operation, and reduced manufacturing costs.<p>
<p>
*Estimated Total Project Cost: $6,509,576<p>
Duration:  24 months<p>
<p>
<HR align=left width=50%>
* The DoD will pay no more than 50% of the final total cost 
