<A HREF=proj_index.html><IMG ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="image/index.gif"></A>
<HR>

<H2><IMG SRC="image/blsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC2">Military Mobility and
Deployment</A></H2>
On the battlefield, in the sea, and in the air, the ability to mobilize,
deploy, and sustain military operations hinges on transportation and maneuvers.
The TRP recognizes these important requirements and is finding ways to apply
commercial technologies to military transport and vehicle needs. This effort is
making land vehicle technologies--such as electric and hybrid vehicles and
navigation and safety systems--more affordable. It is combining the expertise
of naval systems producers and commercial shipbuilders to manufacture naval
ships more efficiently. It is also looking toward advanced aeronautical
technologies that will contribute to air superiority well into the 21st century.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC3">Aeronautical/Aerospace
Technologies</A></H3>
The United States enjoys a dominant position in the world aircraft market
because of its aggressive research and development investment strategy,
especially in the Defense sector. However, this preeminence is being challenged
by both Europe and Asia. TRP projects in aeronautical technology--a classic
dual-use area--will provide significant Defense and commercial payoffs in
propulsion/engine technologies, flight sensors, aircraft controls, structures,
and design.
<P>

<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC4">Aircraft Surface Contamination
Detection Technology
Advancement</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Rosemount Aerospace, Inc. (Burnsville, MN)</I></LI>
<LI>FBS, Inc. (State College, PA)</LI>
<LI>McDonnell Douglas Corporation (Long Beach, CA)</LI>
<LI>Northwest Airlines, Inc. (St. Paul, MN)</LI></UL><P>    
This team is developing and demonstrating a commercially viable device to
efficiently remove ice from aircraft before takeoff. The device will increase
the reliability and safety of all-weather operations for DoD transport
aircraft, particularly from airstrips without effective deicing equipment.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC5"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap1.html#chap1-7">Autonomous Landing
Guidance</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Lear Astronics Corporation (Santa Monica, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Wright Laboratory (Wright-Patterson AFB, OH)</LI>
<LI>AlliedSignal, Air Transport Avionics Division (Fort Lauderdale, FL)</LI>
<LI>FLIR Systems, Inc. (Portland, OR)</LI>
<LI>Maryland Advanced Development Laboratory (Greenbelt, MD)</LI>
<LI>Northwest Airlines, Inc. (St. Paul, MN)</LI>
<LI>Norton Performance Plastics Corporation (Ravenna, OH)</LI>
<LI>United Airlines (Chicago, IL)</LI></UL><P>    
This partnership is developing an autonomous aircraft landing system that
allows commercial and military pilots to conduct "clear-day" flight operations
in inclement weather.  The DoD can use this system to plan and complete
military missions without concern for weather conditions. Also, operations
flown under the cover of clouds and fog will render enemy electro-optic systems
useless.
<P>

The system enables pilots to taxi, take off, roll out, and land in conditions
of extremely low visibility such as dense fog or in adverse weather during
combat. The consortium is integrating a Heads-Up Display with a Differential
Global Positioning System, Millimeter Wave Radar (MMWR), and Forward Looking
Infrared Radar. The Heads-Up Display presents sensor imagery and flight
guidance information on the cockpit windshield so that the pilot can compare
the sensor image with the real-world image. The MMWR provides sufficient
clarity to discern craters or obstacles on the runway. Forward-Looking Infrared
Radar complements the MMWR under certain atmospheric conditions.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC6">Completion of Technology
Development for the Face Gearing Concept</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>McDonnell Douglas Helicopter Company (Mesa, AZ)</I></LI>
<LI>Army/Vehicle Propulsion Directorate (Cleveland, OH)</LI>
<LI>Lucas Western (Park City, UT)</LI>
<LI>University of Illinois, Chicago (Chicago, IL)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is developing face-gear technology for aerospace and industrial
power transmission. Face gears can significantly improve weight, reliability,
and cost for both military and commercial transmission designers. In addition,
they reduce gearbox weight by <BR>40 percent, gearbox volume by more than 15
percent, noise by 10 decibels, and cost by <BR>10 percent. The DoD is
considering using face gears in the follow-on to the Apache Longbow helicopter.
Because these gears have their teeth on the faces rather than the edges, they
are more efficient, especially in transmission design. The focus of this effort
is on establishing and verifying gear design parameters and on developing
cost-effective manufacturing techniques.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC7">Dual-Use Sensor Technology for
Air Transportation System Capacity and Safety</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Martin Marietta Corporation (Moorestown, NJ)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Rome Laboratory (Griffiss AFB, NY)</LI>
<LI>Engineering Systems Design &amp; Analysis Company (Reston, VA)</LI>
<LI>General Electric Company (Schenectady, NY)</LI>
<LI>M/A COM, Inc. (Lowell, MA)</LI>
<LI>National Center for Atmospheric Research (Boulder, CO)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is accelerating the development of advanced, multipurpose, phased
array radar to detect and disseminate information on flight-hazardous weather
conditions while simultaneously monitoring local air traffic. This flexible
radar for airport terminal areas has electronically steerable beams. It will
allow national airspace transportation systems to operate more efficiently. It
will improve the safety of these systems by reducing air traffic separation,
enhancing precision control of airport traffic flow, and improving hazardous
weather detection and reporting.<P>
The DoD will benefit directly from this project, which will advance the
development of next-generation transmit/receive (T/R) modules. These modules
have extensive military applications. The project could significantly reduce
the cost of the modules.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC8">Electronically Controlled
Variable Displacement Vane Pump</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Coltec Industries, Chandler Evans Control Systems Division (West
Hartford,CT)</I></LI>
<LI>State of Connecticut, Department of Economic Development (Rocky Hill,
CT)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This partnership is developing a revolutionary fuel metering and pumping device
for commercial and military aircraft engines. The vane pump delivers the
precise amount of fuel to maximize aircraft engine performance. The team
projects a substantial worldwide market for fuel metering and pumping devices.
The DoD will benefit from the result--a lighter, less expensive, and more
precise fuel-monitoring pump that will allow the development of more
maneuverable tactical aircraft.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC9"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap1.html#chap1-6">Fly-by-Light Advanced Systems
Hardware Program</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>McDonnell Douglas Aerospace (St. Louis, MO)</I></LI>
<LI>AlliedSignal, Inc., Controls &amp; Accessories (South Bend, IN)</LI>
<LI>Berg Electronics (Whippany, NJ)</LI>
<LI>FORSS, Inc. (Naperville, IL)</LI>
<LI>Honeywell, Inc., Technology Center (Phoenix, AZ)</LI>
<LI>HR Textron, Inc. (Valencia, CA)</LI>
<LI>Lear Astronics Corporation (Santa Monica, CA)</LI>
<LI>Litton Systems, Inc., Guidance &amp; Control System (Woodland Hills, CA)</LI>
<LI>Martin Marietta Corporation, Martin Marietta Control Systems (Johnson City,
NY)</LI>
<LI>McDonnell Douglas Aerospace, Transport Aircraft Division (Long Beach,
CA)</LI>
<LI>McDonnell Douglas Helicopter Company (Mesa, AZ)</LI>
<LI>Moog, Inc., Aircraft Controls Division (East Aurora, NY)</LI>
<LI>NeuroDyne Inc. (Cambridge, MA)</LI>
<LI>Parker Bertea Aerospace (Irvine, CA)</LI>
<LI>Rosemount Aerospace, Inc. (Burnsville, MN)</LI>
<LI>Smiths Aerospace, Grand Rapids Division (Grand Rapids, MI)</LI>
</UL><P>    
These partners are developing components critical to making usable Fly-by-Light
technologies for DoD and commercial aircraft. Fly-by-Light will reduce the
weight of military aircraft by 6,000 pounds, make these planes immune to
electronic interference, and increase their reliability and maintainability by
10 percent. Fly-by-Light Advanced Systems Hardware (FLASH) technologies include
cost-effective and reliable fiber-optic cable plants, low-cost flight control
systems, and more reliable and maintainable actuators. The FLASH project will
directly stimulate the incorporation of fiber optics into the design of the
F-22, and both the F-22 and Joint Advanced Strike Technology (JAST) program
offices are cooperating to ensure direct and immediate transfer of the
technology. The team believes this technology can help the United States gain a
larger portion of the international aircraft market.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC10">Hybrid Technology Option
Project</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Lockheed Martin Corporation, Manned Space Systems Division (New
Orleans, LA)</I></LI>
<LI>Environmental Aerosciences Corporation (Miami, FL)</LI>
<LI>Lockheed Martin Corporation, Astronautics Division (Denver, CO)</LI>
<LI>Rockwell International Corporation, Rocketdyne Division (Canoga Park,
CA)</LI>
<LI>Thiokol Corporation, Science &amp; Engineering (Promontory, UT)</LI>
<LI>Thiokol Corporation, Space Operations (Promontory, UT)</LI>
<LI>United Technologies Corporation, Chemical Systems Division (San Jose,
CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is developing a 250,000-pound-thrust hybrid rocket motor that
integrates a solid synthetic rubber compound fuel with liquid oxygen. Hybrid
fuel performs better at half the cost of current solid boosters. The reduced
cost of boost propulsion for launch vehicles  makes Defense and commercial
launch systems more affordable.<P>
This technology is valuable to the DoD because hybrid rocket engines are
potentially safer and less expensive propulsion systems to operate than their
nonhybrid counterparts. This project has been restructured because one
participant has withdrawn.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC11"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap3.html#chap3-5">Passive Millimeter-Wave Camera</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>TRW, Inc., Space and Electronics Group (Redondo Beach, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Wright Laboratory (Wright-Patterson AFB, OH)</LI>
<LI>Army Research Laboratory (Fort Monmouth, NJ)</LI>
<LI>EPI/ETA Technologies (Colorado Springs, CO)</LI>
<LI>McDonnell Douglas Aerospace, Transport Aircraft Division (Long Beach,
CA)</LI>
<LI>NASA/Langley Research Center (Hampton, VA)</LI>
<LI>University of California, Los Angeles (Los Angeles, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
This TRP team is developing radar and infrared imaging system sensors that
produce TV-like images through fog, cloud, smoke, dust, and sandstorms. This
technology can be used for military aircraft landing and refueling, airborne
reconnaissance, and search and rescue, as well as for surveillance and vision
systems in tanks and other land vehicles.  Commercial applications include
all-weather vision systems for pilots.
<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC12">Military Land Vehicle Technologies</A></H3>
The DoD has one of the largest and most complex fleets of land vehicles in the
world. The TRP is improving electric and hybrid drive components, land
navigation, and safety systems and is making them more affordable by
encouraging the commercial sector to meet military needs with commercially
viable technology. Where military and commercial needs are similar, TRP funding
speeds the creation and deployment of the new military capability. More
frequently, special military requirements can be met by shaping commercial
technology goals to satisfy both sectors.
<P>
<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC13">$2,000 Electric
Powertrain</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Westinghouse Electric Corporation, Electric Systems Group (Baltimore,
MD)</I></LI>
<LI>Baltimore Gas &amp; Electric Company (Baltimore, MD)</LI>
<LI>Chrysler Corporation (Auburn Hills, MI)</LI>
<LI>Maryland Energy Administration (Annapolis, MD)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is developing a low-cost electric vehicle powertrain with the
power and smoothness of an internal combustion engine. The DoD will use this
technology to develop high-efficiency, low acoustic- and thermal-signature
combat vehicles, such as tanks, transports, and troop carriers. These vehicles
are part of the DoD's movement toward a family of combat vehicles propelled by
hybrid-electric or all-electric drivetrains.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC14">Automotive Collision
Avoidance
System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Hughes Aircraft Company (Malibu, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Delco Electronics Corporation (Kokomo, IN)</LI>
<LI>Delco Systems Operations (Goleta, CA)</LI>
<LI>Environmental Research Institute of Michigan (Ann Arbor, MI)</LI>
<LI>General Motors Corporation (Warren, MI)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Research Laboratories (Malibu, CA)</LI>
<LI>Systems Technology, Inc. (Hawthorne, CA)</LI>
<LI>University of California, Davis (Davis, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This partnership is designing a comprehensive collision avoidance system that
notifies drivers of threatening situations or hazards. The anticipated large
commercial market for this system will stimulate a direct and dramatic cost
reduction to the military for the system's sensors. It will also increase
private sector R&amp;D for technologies applicable to DoD missions, such as
Night Vision and Heads-Up Displays.<P>
Semiautomated systems that track vehicle positions and movements will provide
progressive intervention as a situation proceeds from a low probability to a
high probability of threat. The technologies incorporated in this system will
include Night Vision displays to provide drivers with a clearer view of the
vehicle ahead; Heads-Up Displays to present information in the forward visual
field so drivers do not have to divert their eyes from the road; intelligent
cruise control systems to integrate with antilock brakes and to sense
inadvertent lane changes and vehicle separation; and tire pressure monitoring
to optimize vehicle handling.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC15">Computer-Aided Earth Moving
With Digital Phase-Global Positioning System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Magnavox Electronic Systems Company (Torrance, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Army/Army Corps of Engineers (Vicksburg, MS)</LI>
<LI>Caterpillar, Inc. (Peoria, IL)</LI>
<LI>Spectra-Physics Laserplane, Inc. (Dayton, OH)</LI></UL><P>    
This team is adapting the Global Positioning System and laser guidance
technology from munitions systems to revolutionize "horizontal construction"
(e.g., highways, dams, landfills, airports). This technology will provide the
DoD with the ability to rapidly and accurately complete construction under
battlefield conditions. Moreover, the blade-control technology developed under
this project will feed directly into remotely controlled mine removal
equipment. With these technologies to control the position and orientation of
the blades of earth-moving equipment, any computer-designed path can be
sculpted to accuracies of a centimeter in real space, eliminating lengthy site
surveys and topographic analysis.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC16">Demonstration of Universal
Electric Transportation Subsystems</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Transportation Manufacturing Corporation (DUETS Consortium) (Roswell,
NM)</I></LI>
<LI>Alliance for Transportation Research (Albuquerque, NM)</LI>
<LI>Commonwealth of Massachusetts, Executive Office of Economic Affairs (Boston,
MA)</LI>
<LI>Davis Technologies International, Inc. (Dallas, TX)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Sandia National Laboratories (Albuquerque, NM)</LI>
<LI>Georgetown University (Washington, DC)</LI>
<LI>Honeywell, Inc. (Minneapolis, MN)</LI>
<LI>Kaman Electromagnetics Corporation (Hudson, MA)</LI>
<LI>Metropolitan Council of Transit Operations (Minneapolis, MN)</LI>
<LI>Minnesota Department of Transportation (St. Paul, MN)</LI>
<LI>Minnesota Technology, Inc. (Minneapolis, MN)</LI>
<LI>New Mexico Economic Development Department (Santa Fe, NM)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project will adapt military vehicle and aircraft subsystem technologies
for Defense and commercial applications. Through it, the DoD will gain
hybrid-electric and all-electric vehicles for combat. The project will lower
the cost and improve the performance of subsystems associated with large
vehicles, such as military tanks and buses for commercial mass transit.<P>
Specific subsystem technologies include an integrated electric drivetrain;
alternate-fuel generators; compressible suspension systems; and a fiber-optic,
fault-tolerant control system immune to electrical interference. These
technologies will also enable low-emission mass transit vehicles to interact
with the Intelligent Vehicle Highway System. They will reduce transportation
costs by 50 percent and damage to roadbeds by 20 percent.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC17">Electric Actuation and
Control
System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Rockwell International Corporation, North American Aircraft
Division(Los Angeles, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Wright Laboratory (Wright-Patterson Air Force Base, OH)</LI>
<LI>Caterpillar, Inc. (Peoria, IL)</LI>
<LI>Moog, Inc. (East Aurora, NY)</LI>
<LI>Rockwell International Corporation, Highway Product Division (Troy, MI)</LI>
<LI>Rockwell International Corporation, North American Aircraft Division (Seal
Beach, CA)</LI>
<LI>Rockwell International Corporation, Science Center (Thousand Oaks, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    

This TRP team is designing, developing, and fabricating affordable
electromechanical actuators, electrohydrostatic actuators, and direct drive
valves. Targeted applications include military aircraft that are less
expensive--thanks to a simultaneous commercial market for these actuators--and
direct drive valves in commercial equipment such as heavy construction
hydraulic systems and automotive and diesel engines.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC18">PowerPak Mobile Electric
Power
System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Martin Marietta Corporation, Armament Systems (Burlington,
VT)</I></LI>
<LI>Army/Belvoir RD&amp;E Center (Fort Belvoir, VA)</LI>
<LI>DoD/Joint Project Office Cruise Missiles &amp; Unmanned Aerial Vehicles,
Program Executive Office (Washington, DC)</LI>
<LI>Kaman Electromagnetics Corporation (Hudson, MA)</LI>
<LI>Rotary Power International (Woodbridge, NJ)</LI>
<LI>State of Vermont, Agency of Development &amp; Community Affairs (Montpelier,
VT)</LI>
<LI>University of Vermont (Burlington, VT)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is developing two prototype mobile electric power generation
systems called PowerPak that will provide the DoD with a lightweight,
fuel-efficient, mobile power source to use in military environments where there
is the risk of fire or explosion.
<P>
Mobile electric power systems use low-volatility, heavy fuels rather than
conventional gasoline. These fuels are readily available in many parts of the
world and are the preferred fuel in military inventories. Thus, this program
will reduce logistical problems, and the systems will exploit emerging engine
and generator technologies to reduce equipment size and weight by 50 percent
over traditional generators. PowerPak will enable emergency crews to use
rugged, lightweight equipment rather than gasoline-fueled generators.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC19"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap1.html#chap1-4">Turboalternator for Electric
Hybrid Vehicles</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>CALSTART (Burbank, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>AlliedSignal Aerospace, Aerospace Systems &amp; Equipment (Torrance, CA)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Aircraft Company, Power Control Systems Division (Torrance,
CA)</LI></UL><P>    
A turboalternator is being developed for automotive hybrid vehicles, which are
powered by electricity and fossil fuels. The DoD will use the product in its
hybrid vehicles and as an Auxiliary Power Unit (APU) for the Army's M1A1 tank.
Instead of running the tank's large turbine engine, the APU will provide quiet,
efficient, and low infrared (IR) signature power for electronic systems. Team
leaders have to make the turboalternator affordable and available enough for
use in other military vehicles, such as the Bradley Fighting Vehicle.<P>
Turboalternators are gas turbines that drive electric generators. This
technology will permit vehicles to operate on fossil fuels during acceleration
and on batteries during cruising mode. The new turbine will be faster and will
use innovative air bearings that magnetically float. In addition to the M1A1
tank, the TRP team will demonstrate the technology on a commercial mass transit
vehicle.<p>

<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC20">Shipbuilding
Technologies</A></H3>
International shipbuilding is currently strong, yet the nation's shipbuilding
industry is on the verge of collapse. For many years, the U.S. shipbuilding
industry has been sustained by large DoD contracts, but current and projected
Navy ship construction is insufficient to maintain the shipbuilding capacity
required for military mobilization. These TRP projects will help U.S. shipyards
become more competitive in international markets, while preserving and
improving the shipbuilding capability needed by the U.S. Navy. The projects
address innovative vessel design and construction processes, repair and
maintenance, and on-board technologies such as propulsion.
<p>
<hr>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC21">Center for Advanced Ship
Repair and Maintenance</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>CASRM, Inc. (Norfolk, VA)</I></LI>
<LI>City of Norfolk, Office of Economic Development (Norfolk, VA)</LI>
<LI>Old Dominion University (Norfolk, VA)</LI>
<LI>Virginia Center for Innovative Technology (Herndon, VA)</LI></UL><P>    
This consortium is developing best manufacturing practices for globally
competitive shipyards in order to advance shipyard repair and maintenance
practices and procedures. The center will focus on reducing high-cost
operations and activities that have an adverse environmental impact and on
solving other significant ship repair problems. It will provide the DoD with
new and improved strategies for lengthening the life of existing combat vessels
and for easing future procurement requirements.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC22"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap1.html#chap1-5">Commercial Shipbuilding
Focused Development Project</A></H3>

<UL><LI><I>Bath Iron Works Corporation (Bath, ME)</I></LI>
<LI>American Automar, Inc. (Washington, DC)</LI>
<LI>Great American Lines, Inc. (Roseland, NJ)</LI>
<LI>Kvaerner Masa Marine, Inc. (Vancouver, B.C., Canada)</LI>
<LI>Mitsui Engineering &amp; Shipbuilding Co., Ltd. (Tokyo, Japan)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This partnership plans to consolidate management and production technologies to
create a globally competitive shipyard. The DoD will thereby gain an
affordable, on-shore source for Navy shipbuilding and repair without supporting
a disintegrating, Defense-only shipyard industry.<P>
Specific technologies include computer-aided design and process simulation;
advanced automated fabrication processes; flexible automation/robotics;
real-time measurement systems for process control, production planning,
material control, and estimating; and pollution abatement. These technologies
directly improve the production of both U.S. Navy warships and commercial
vessels.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC23">Demonstration and Spin-Off of
the Integral Motor/Propeller Propulsion System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Westinghouse Electric Corporation, Electro-Mechanical Division
(Cheswick,
PA)</I></LI>
<LI>Ben Franklin Technology Center of Western Pennsylvania (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>Edison Chouest Offshore, Inc. (Galliano, LA)</LI>
<LI>Navy/Naval Surface Warfare Center (Bethesda, MD)</LI>
<LI>Pennsylvania State University, Applied Research Laboratory (State College,
PA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is taking the Integral Motor/Propeller system, developed for the
Navy's Seawolf submarine, and is producing a prototype for commercial
applications. Establishing a commercial market for this technology will lower
the cost and increase the availability and performance of this secondary
submarine propulsion system, even as sales to the military decline. These
systems can also be incorporated into future U.S. Navy all-electric ships. The
propulsion system can have a significant impact on the U.S. shipbuilding
industry by providing advanced propulsion technology to compete against
European and Japanese motors.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC24">Development of the Submerged
Electric Drive Cargo Pumping System</A></H3>

<UL><LI><I>Westinghouse Electric Corporation, Electro-Mechanical Division
(Cheswick,
PA)</I></LI>
<LI>Avondale Industries, Inc. (New Orleans, LA)</LI>
<LI>Ben Franklin Technology Center of Western Pennsylvania (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>IMA Associates (Washington, DC)</LI>
<LI>Navy/Naval Surface Warfare Center (Bethesda, MD)</LI>
<LI>Pennsylvania State University, Applied Research Laboratory (State College,
PA)</LI>
<LI>Seaworthy Electrical Systems (New York, NY)</LI></UL><P>    
This TRP project is applying submersible electric drive cargo pump technology
to commercial marine applications. The pumping system was originally developed
for U.S. Navy nuclear platforms. Establishing a commercial market for this
technology will give the Navy a new, low-cost, efficient pump for hazardous
fluids. The system is environmentally safe and could establish U.S. dominance
in liquid cargo handling.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC25">Portable Shipbuilding
Robotics</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Cybo Robots, Inc. (Indianapolis, IN)</I></LI>
<LI>ARM Automation, Inc. (Austin, TX)</LI>
<LI>Bath Iron Works Corporation (Bath, ME)</LI>
<LI>Carnegie Mellon University (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>Edison Welding Institute (Columbus, OH)</LI>
<LI>Ingalls Shipbuilding, Inc. (Pascagoula, MS)</LI>
<LI>K2T, Inc. (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>National Institute of Standards &amp; Technology (Boulder, CO)</LI>
<LI>National Steel &amp; Shipbuilding Company (San Diego, CA)</LI>
<LI>Navy/Naval Surface Warfare Center (Bethesda, MD)</LI>
<LI>Trellis Software &amp; Controls, Inc. (Rochester Hills, MI)</LI>
<LI>Trinity Marine Group (Brownsville, PA)</LI>
<LI>University of Texas, Austin (Austin, TX)</LI>
</UL><P>    

This project is creating a dual-use, portable robotic welding system to greatly
improve the productivity of the U.S. shipbuilding industry. These welding
robots will improve quality and reduce welding costs by 25 to 50 percent. They
will also reduce the need for inspection  and reworking by 50 to 80 percent.<P>
While the use of machines for welding is not new, robotics are currently most
effective on assembly lines, where there is a great deal of repetition.
Shipbuilding requires one-of-a-kind, complicated construction. This project
will integrate technical advances in personal computers, robotic design, 3-D
vision, and weld sensors to provide a portable robotic welding system
especially for the shipbuilding industry. These robots will be highly mobile
and programmable for specific vessel designs. Program operators estimate a 50
percent reduction in the cost of welding robots as a result of the project,
which means that U.S. manufacturers could purchase robots for less than
$25,000. These robots could automate up to 75 percent of ship welding, which
would quickly reduce the cost of shipbuilding.
<P>

<HR>

<H2><IMG SRC="image/blsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC26">Command, Control,
Communications, Computers, and Intelligence (C4I)</A></H2>
In this post-Cold War era, even the most primitive country may have forces
armed with powerful and sophisticated weapons. Small conflicts can quickly
escalate into large-scale battles. U.S. troops are usually deployed in
unfamiliar territories and cultures, and they may have difficulty operating
under such circumstances.<P>
These situations place great stress on command, control, communications,
computers, and intelligence (C4I) systems, which are designed to
help the military efficiently strategize and activate plans under any
circumstances. C4I systems allow troops to quickly set up and
operate by gathering, verifying, sorting, and analyzing information to
construct appropriate strategies. Decision makers can then disseminate the
processed information and orders and coordinate resulting tactical
components.
<P>
The TRP is addressing some of the military's most pervasive C4I
needs. Because the best advances in communications, information systems, and
computers are generally being developed in the commercial sector, the military
must work with industry to achieve its goals efficiently and affordably.
Therefore, the TRP is sponsoring collaborative efforts that will give the
military a reliable source of low-cost technology and ensure that future
C<SUP>4</SUP>I systems are simple and inexpensive to update. The following
section describes the TRP's efforts to improve C<SUP>4</SUP>I systems using
communications technology, computer hardware, and computer software.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC27">Communications
Technologies</A></H3>
The Joint Chiefs of Staff identified "maintaining near perfect real-time
knowledge of the enemy and communicating that to all forces in near real time"
as the first of five future joint warfighting capabilities most needed by the
United States. Near real-time communications requires very high bandwidth
networks. The DoD forecasts that by the year 2000, C<SUP>4</SUP>I functions
will need to handle hundreds of terabytes of data per day. While the military's
need for secure, digital, high-data-rate, upgradable networks is well known, it
is no longer feasible for the armed services to develop and maintain special
military communications equipment. It simply costs too much, and technological
momentum in the Defense R&amp;D community is low. Demands for frequent upgrades
leave little choice but to consider commercial systems. However, without the
DoD involvement, the commercial sector will not meet the military's
requirements for bandwidth, robust moving networks, electromagnetic
interference and jamming resistance, rapid mixed deployment, and security. The
TRP keeps the DoD's hand in this incredibly dynamic sector of the commercial
world.
<P>
<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC28">Advanced Automatic Train
Control System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART)/Hughes Morrison Knudsen (HMK) Alliance
(Oakland, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Hughes Aircraft Company (Fullerton, CA)</LI>
<LI>Morrison Knudsen Corporation (Boise, ID)</LI>
<LI>San Francisco Bay Area Rapid Transit (Oakland, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
This partnership is using the Army's Enhanced Position Location Reporting
System (EPLRS) technology to develop a position location system for commercial
vehicles. The military uses this technology to determine the precise location
of friendly combat vehicles on front lines and to report that information to
tactical commanders. Commercially, it will precisely locate subway trains, even
in tunnels, and allow passenger trains on the BART system to be run at closer
intervals. This technology will eliminate the need for a second tunnel under
the San Francisco Bay.<P>
For the DoD, the project means a less expensive EPLRS for military use. The
Army has spent considerable effort in developing this system, and has no
alternative with the same capabilities--even less capable systems will not be
available for years. However, the EPLRS is prohibitively expensive. This
project should lower the Army's EPLRS costs by 40 percent in 2 years by
incorporating less expensive commercial components, more efficient design
techniques, and economies of scale.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC29">Advanced Power Conversion
Based on the Aerocapacitor</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Power-One, Inc. (Camarillo, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Aerojet (General Corporation) (Rancho Cordova, CA)</LI>
<LI>California Trade &amp; Commerce Agency (Pasadena, CA)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (Livermore, CA)</LI>
<LI>Polystor Corporation (San Jose, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
This program is developing an affordable manufacturing process for
aerocapacitors, a type of inexpensive supercapacitor that offers a tenfold
increase in energy density over current capacitors. Higher energy density
allows more power to be stored in less space. The DoD will be able to use the
lower weight and increased performance in portable power applications, but the
technology could be scaled to larger applications such as military vehicles.
These supercapacitors are creating new opportunities for energy storage devices
in both the Defense and commercial sectors, ranging from semiconductors to
power supplies and electric vehicles.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC30">Beam-Agile Active-Transmit
Phased Array System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Space Systems/Loral (Palo Alto, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Rome Laboratory (Griffiss AFB, NY)</LI>
<LI>Syracuse Research Corporation (Syracuse, NY)</LI>
</UL><P>    
These partners are developing, fabricating, and implementing an active K-band,
satellite- borne antenna system. The DoD will use this system in military
operations that require directing multiple signals simultaneously, in real
time, to any position within the antenna's field of view. The system's ability
to simultaneously direct multiple signals to multiple positions reduces antenna
weight by 50 percent and increases radiated power by 500 percent. This weight
reduction and power increase will provide more affordable and considerably
superior satellite-borne communications capabilities to Defense and commercial
users alike.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC31">Commercialization of the DoD
Image Understanding Architecture Vision Computer: An Enabling Technology for
Computer-Aided Design-Directed, Vision-Guided Robotics for Flexible Manufacturing
</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Amerinex Artificial Intelligence, Inc. (Amherst, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>ACSIOM, Inc. (Amherst, MA)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Research Laboratories (Malibu, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This consortium is creating critical components for interpreting and
understanding visual images, which for the DoD means improved image analysis
capabilities at a lower cost. For commercial markets, it means improved medical
imagery, security and surveillance, intelligent character recognition, and
robotics. In the long run, the DoD will see improvements in areas such as
target acquisition, reconnaissance, unmanned aircraft and ground vehicles. The
commercial sector will see robots able to understand objects on the
manufacturing floor, recognize license plates at toll booths for intelligent
highways, and distinguish tumors from normal tissue in medical images.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC32"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap2.html#chap2-1">Developing Speech Recognition
for Future Digital Signal Processing in Handheld Computers</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Dragon Systems, Inc. (Newton, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Analog Devices, Inc. (Norwood, MA)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is developing a voice recognition system to replace tiny keyboards
on handheld computers. The DoD will benefit from this technology in such areas
as inventory applications, intelligence, data access and query, command and
control, portable battlefield information systems, and translation for
multilingual Defense forces.
<P>
The device can cope with small, specialized, technical vocabularies as well as
large vocabularies for general dictation. The speech recognition software can
be modified to fit available memory and thus adapted to multiple machines. This
technology can give U.S. manufacturers a global competitive edge in business,
education, and military applications.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC33">Development and Application
of Advanced Dual-Use Microwave Technologies for Wireless Communications and
Sensors
for Intelligent Vehicle Highway System Vehicles</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>M/A COM, Inc. (Lowell, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Northrop Corporation, Electronics Systems Division (Rolling Meadows,
IL)</LI>
</UL><P>    
These TRP partners are applying process-oriented manufacturing techniques for
Microwave and Millimeter Wave Integrated Circuits (MMICs) to commercial sensors
and electronics.  The effort will provide the DoD with new radio frequency
models and products that have improved size, operating voltages, and
efficiency.
<P>
Targeted applications include the Intelligent Vehicle Highway System, personal
communications systems and networks, and cellular wireless communications.
Previous DoD investments in the MMIC, which reduced overall chip size by 75
percent, will help make these commercial applications globally competitive.
Commercial viability will, in turn, lower the cost and increase the
capabilities of these devices for the DoD.

<H3> <A NAME="RTFToC34"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap2.html#chap2-2">Experimental SONET Optical
Carrier-192 and Asynchronous Transfer Mode Self-Healing Ring</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Bellcore (Morristown, NJ)</I></LI>
<LI>AT&amp;T Bell Laboratories (Breinigsville, PA)</LI>
<LI>Rockwell International Corporation, Microelectronics Technology Center
(Newbury Park, CA)</LI>
<LI>Southwestern Bell, Inc. (St. Louis, MO)</LI>
<LI>Tektronix, Inc., Tektronix Laboratories (Beaverton, OR)</LI>
<LI>Washington University, St. Louis (St. Louis, MO)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is developing and testing a 10 gigabit-per-second (Gb/s)
self-healing fiber-optic transmission system called the Synchronous Optical
Network. The project addresses current and long-term surge requirements of
Defense communication, providing significant benefits to the DoD's Global Grid
concept. The 10 Gb/s bandwidth and other DoD requirements (such as security)
were unlikely to be addressed in a timely manner without DoD involvement.<P>
The proposed system reduces network complexity and cost, increases network
efficiency, and permits high-capacity data throughput. A self-healing ring
network can survive network node failures or optical fiber cuts, permitting
computer networks to automatically operate around a failed network node, which
is critical for Defense requirements.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC35"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap2.html#chap2-3">High-Capacity, Solid Polymer
Battery Development</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Lockheed Missiles &amp; Space Company, Inc. (Sunnyvale, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Ultralife Batteries, Inc. (Newark, NJ)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is designed to develop lithium ion batteries with a polymeric
matrix to replace current technology with long-life, rechargeable batteries.
These batteries conform to the installation space available, and thus provide
immense packaging flexibility. This technology will enable the DoD to reduce
its field units' logistical resupply requirements, carrying weight, and
operation and maintenance costs--major issues, especially for the Army.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC36"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A>  <A
HREF="chap2.html#chap2-3">Lithium Ion Rechargeable
Battery Development and Deployment</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Saft America, Inc. (Valdese, NC)</I></LI>
<LI>Apple Computer, Inc. (Cupertino, CA)</LI>
<LI>Army Research Laboratory (Fort Monmouth, NJ)</LI>
<LI>FMC Corporation (Gastonia, NC)</LI>
<LI>North Carolina A&amp;T State University (Greensboro, NC)</LI>
<LI>State of North Carolina (Raleigh, NC)</LI>
<LI>Western Piedmont College (Morganton, NC)</LI></UL><P>    
This project will create production capacity for rechargeable,
high-energy-density lithium batteries. As in the project above, this technology
will help the DoD's field units by reducing resupply, carrying weight, and
operation and maintenance costs.<P>
In the past, lithium batteries have not met stringent power and longevity
requirements for Defense or commercial applications. This TRP approach is based
on lithium ion technology that produces rechargeable batteries at low cost over
their life cycles. Commercial uses for such batteries include portable
telephones and laptop computers.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC37">Millennium: 21st Century
Broadband Digital Telecommunication Technology</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Raytheon Company, Electromagnetic Systems Division (Goleta,
CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Honeywell, Inc., Systems and Research Center (Bloomington, MN)</LI>
<LI>NASA/Lewis Research Center (Cleveland, OH)</LI>
<LI>TRW, Inc., Electronics &amp; Technology Division (Redondo Beach,
CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This team is developing multichannel digital multiplexers and demodulators for
multimedia signal processing. These products fill the DoD's critical need for
high-performance  electronic warfare systems that are reconfigurable and
reliable. Using this technology, single platforms can serve multiple functions
and greatly reduce procurement and operating costs. Applications include
Defense and commercial satellites, multimedia cable television studios,
integrated avionics, and digital electronic warfare receivers.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC38">Spatial Division Multiple Access Wireless Communication
Systems</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>ArrayComm, Inc. (Santa Clara, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Spectrian, Inc. (Mountain View, CA)</LI>
<LI>Watkins-Johnson Company (Gaithersburg, MD)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is developing a prototype Spatial Division Multiple Access (SDMA)
base station or transmitter for next-generation wireless communications. The
DoD will use this technology to improve capability and cost savings for
co-channel interference reduction in signal intelligence, quick-reaction
telecommunications, and direction-finding capabilities.<P>
The SDMA is expected to increase the efficiency of radio signal transmissions
by up to <BR>35 percent. At the core of the technology is the ability to
estimate signal parameters accurately and efficiently from measurements made
with an array of sensors. One important parameter is the direction of the
signal. Knowing the spatial direction of a signal will allow developers to
increase system efficiency, capacity, and service quality and reduce the system
infrastructure cost per subscriber. Other Defense uses for this technology
include array digital signal processing, precision antenna arrays, and
special-purpose wireless communication Application-Specific Integrated Circuits.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC39">Wire-Com Engine for
Communication Products</A></H3>

<UL><LI><I>Rockwell International Corporation, Microelectronics Technology Center
(Newbury Park, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>BEL-Tronics, Ltd. (Covington, GA)</LI>
<LI>Georgia Institute of Technology (Atlanta, GA)</LI></UL><P>    
This team is developing a prototype of a single-module optoelectronic device
capable of meeting a large number of wireless system requirements. The project
will significantly reduce the cost of radio frequency modules used in analog
and digital communications. It will also bring price and performance benefits
to the DoD in areas such as secure communications and will enable quick and
economic modifications to military components. Commercial applications include
secure communications, wireless local area networks, cordless telephones,
wireless security systems, personal communication networks, home entertainment
systems, and automotive security products.
<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC40">National Information Infrastructure
Interoperability</A></H3>
Because rapid, effective information transfer affects almost every Defense
operation, the DoD has traditionally been the leader in information technology.
The National Information Infrastructure (NII), begun by the DoD as ARPANET in
the 1960s, is expanding rapidly but is paced by commercial growth. The DoD can
no longer control the direction of the NII, so it must instead leverage
emerging commercial capabilities. This leveraging will only be possible if
those capabilities can work within the DoD--in other words, if there is a set
of consistent, useful standards. The pervasiveness of military information
systems, coupled with a requirement to use commercial capabilities, demands
Defense involvement in developing NII interoperability protocols.<P>
TRP projects in NII interoperability will ensure the creation of open
interoperability standards in a number of areas important to the DoD. These
projects were chosen because they are critical to Defense and are expected to
be commercially viable. If successful, they will expand the NII's commercial
capabilities into airborne and terrestrial communications, health care,
training, and maintenance--all in a way that is helpful to Defense. Without the
TRP, these systems would likely be developed in a proprietary fashion,
drastically reducing the interoperability required by Defense.
<P>
<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC41">Asynchronous Transfer Mode
Interoperability Testbed for the National Information Infrastructure</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Bellcore (Morristown, NJ)</I></LI>
<LI>DoD/Joint Interoperability Test Center (Fort Huachuca, AZ)</LI>
<LI>Planar Systems, Inc. (Beaverton, OR)</LI>
<LI>Trustees of the University of Pennsylvania (Philadelphia, PA)</LI></UL><P>   

These TRP partners are implementing an Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM)
interoperability system to develop tools, procedures, and standards that
promote interoperability among ATM products. The effort will focus on signaling
interoperability, traffic management, and upper layer protocol interoperability
over the ATM. The Joint Interoperability Test Center's involvement ensures that
this project will influence DoD network architectures. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC42">HyperEducation
Consortium</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Worcester Polytechnic Institute, Center for High Performance Computing
(Marlborough, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>AimTech Corporation (Nashua, NH)</LI>
<LI>Digital Equipment Corporation (Stow, MA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
Project participants are developing tools that will allow educators to easily
create interactive learning materials, lessons, applications, courses, and
curricula targeted for access through the National Information Infrastructure
(NII). This project will open the education and training market to a large
number of electronic providers. It has the potential to revolutionize the way
people learn and teach, allowing lesson materials to be quickly created,
adapted, and accessed via the NII. These capabilities are essential to DoD's
dynamic training environment. They will significantly reduce the time and costs
involved in developing training materials. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC43">Interoperability Testbed for
Diagnostic and Prognostic Maintenance of Equipment and Processes</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Pennsylvania State University, Applied Research Laboratory (State
College, PA)</I></LI>
<LI>Bogan Inc. (Eddystone, PA)</LI>
<LI>EPRI (Electric Power Research Institute) (Eddystone, PA)</LI>
<LI>Pennsylvania State University (State College, PA)</LI></UL><P>    
This team is developing methods for providing monitoring and diagnostic
services via the National Information Infrastructure (NII) that will reduce the
need for constant preventive maintenance of complex equipment. This capability
will significantly lower the life-cycle costs of expensive machinery used for
DoD operations.
<P>
The physical testbed will integrate EPRI's utility network and Penn State's
network technology, thus incorporating intelligent information retrieval
mechanisms. As a result, interoperability standards and conformance testing
tools will emerge to support remote monitoring and diagnostic services via the
NII. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC44">National Information
Infrastructure Interoperability Testbed for Mobile Applications</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Boeing Defense &amp; Space Group (Kent, WA)</I></LI>
<LI>Claircom Communications, L.P. (Seattle, WA)</LI>
<LI>GTE Government Systems Corporation, Communication Systems Division (Needham
Heights, MA)</LI>
<LI>Jet Propulsion Laboratory (Pasadena, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
The participants in this project are extending the National Information
Infrastructure (NII) to aircraft in flight by developing open interface
standards that will permit the NII's mobile and ground-based components to
interoperate. Successful development of such standards will allow easy
adaptation of commercial inflight communication systems for a variety of DoD
applications, including airborne command and control. Participants will create
information infrastructure products for the airborne environment; create and
document standards to allow these products to interoperate; and validate the
interoperation through the use of ground- and air-based testbeds. (Selected in
1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC45">National Industrial
Information Infrastructure Protocols</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>IBM Corporation (Stamford, CT)</I></LI>
<LI>CAD Framework Initiative (Austin, TX)</LI>
<LI>Digital Equipment Corporation (Nashua, NH)</LI>
<LI>Enterprise Integration Technologies Corporation (Palo Alto, CA)</LI>
<LI>General Dynamics, Electric Boat Division (Gratin, CT)</LI>
<LI>IBM Corporation, Microelectronics (Poughkeepsie, NY)</LI>
<LI>IBM Corporation, Networking Software Division (Endicott, NY)</LI>
<LI>IBM Corporation, Software Solutions Division (Somers, NY)</LI>
<LI>International TechneGroup, Inc. (Milford, OH)</LI>
<LI>Lockheed Aeronautical (Marietta, GA)</LI>
<LI>Magnavox Electronic Systems (Fort Wayne, IN)</LI>
<LI>National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) (Gaithersburg, MD)</LI>
<LI>Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute (Troy, NY)</LI>
<LI>StepTools, Inc. (Troy, NY)</LI>
<LI>Taligent, Inc. (Cupertino, CA)</LI>
<LI>Texas Instruments, Inc. (Dallas, TX)</LI>
<LI>UES, Inc. (Dublin, OH)</LI>
<LI>University of Florida (Gainesville, FL)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is creating open industry software standards that will integrate
computing environments across the U.S. manufacturing industrial base. As a
result, geographically separated organizations will be able to electronically
link into "virtual enterprises" to access, share, and communicate manufacturing
design solutions. The DoD benefits will be twofold: First, development of
common software standards will apply directly to military systems, allowing
them to "cross-talk" with civilian systems as needed. Second, the increased
efficiency of U.S. manufacturing that will result from this project will create
tremendous cost savings for military procurement.
<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC46">Software Development</A></H3>

The DoD is an enormous developer and user of software. An estimated 85 percent
of the installed software base for Defense is customized with all components
written especially for that software package. This situation involves a great
deal of duplication that is both costly and time-consuming. An alternative,
called "Object-Oriented Software," allows reusable software components, or
objects, to function as building blocks in creating new programs or in updating
existing ones. This alternative requires that both the program and the object
be created according to a common set of standards.<P>
The TRP's software projects are aimed at reusing software components to
radically reduce the effort required to field new software applications.
Building on emerging industry standards for software object technologies, these
projects will significantly accelerate the development of tools to help build
the infrastructure for component ware, create a pool of developers experienced
in applying the new tools, and deliver a series of demonstration applications
with both Defense and commercial  relevance. In addition to advancing specific
demonstrations of interest to the DoD, these efforts will keep object-based
software from becoming compartmentalized--as might happen under strictly
proprietary development-- and will prevent the DoD from relying on a single
vendor or software approach.
<P>
<HR>
<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC47">East/West Consortium: Next
Generation Authoring Tools and Instructional Applications
</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Apple Computer, Inc. (Cupertino, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Carnegie Mellon University (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>Houghton Mifflin Publishing Company (Boston, MA)</LI>
<LI>PWS Publishing Company (Boston, MA)</LI>
<LI>Stanford University Medical School (Stanford, CA)</LI>
<LI>University of Colorado (Boulder, CO)</LI>
<LI>University of Massachusetts (Amherst, MA)</LI></UL><P>    
This partnership is accelerating the development of new authoring tools that
educators and trainers who are not computer experts can use to generate
instructional materials in one-tenth of the time currently required. These
tools follow standards established by the Apple-IBM joint ventures Taligent,
Inc., and Kaleida. In 1990, the Armed Services spent $9.6 billion on training
materials. The products from this project will greatly reduce that cost while
increasing the effectiveness of DoD training.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC48">LEGOS: Object-Based Software
Components for Mission-Critical Systems</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>I-Kinetics, Inc. (Cambridge, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Heuristicrats Research, Inc. (Berkeley, CA)</LI>
<LI>Iona Technologies, Ltd. (Dublin, Ireland)</LI>
<LI>Netlinks Technology, Inc. (Nashua, NH)</LI>
<LI>SunSoft (Mountain View, CA)</LI>
<LI>United Technologies Corporation, Pratt &amp; Whitney (Jupiter,
FL)</LI></UL><P>    
These TRP partners are developing reusable software components and services
that adhere to the Object Management Group's emerging technology standards. The
DoD can use this technology for such applications as logistics planning and
management systems for ship maintenance. Key innovations include the capacity
for software component composition and synthesis, tools for collaborating with
existing software, object management services for fault-tolerant systems, and
team-based work-flow automation. The project will demonstrate full work-flow
integration for the executive program management information systems of NAVSEA.
The commercial demonstration also has potentially important applications for
military acquisition. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC49">Object Technology for Rapid
Software Development and Delivery</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Andersen Consulting (Chicago, IL)</I></LI>
<LI>CoGenTex, Inc. (Ithaca, NY)</LI>
<LI>Expersoft Corporation (San Diego, CA)</LI>
<LI>Raytheon Company, Missile Systems Division (Tewksbury, MA)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is developing reusable software components and services that
adhere to the Object Management Group's emerging technology standards. Key
innovations include support for reusable components and the capability to
specify new components via high-level languages and integrated graphical
interfaces. These components and services will be used to create one
demonstration system for battle management and another for factory work-center
management. During the course of these 2-year demonstrations, the technologies
from this project will be integrated and tested for interoperability with the
technologies produced by the other two Object Technology consortia.<P>
Battlefield management is one of the most difficult software challenges in the
military. The project's demonstration of this capacity is particularly
important because battlefield management demands the flexibility, rapid growth,
and modularity that will be a key feature of object-based software techniques.
Future battlefield management codes will be constructed in this manner.
(Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC50">Object Technology for Rapid
Software Development and Delivery</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Template Software, Inc. (Herndon, VA)</I></LI>
<LI>Honeywell, Inc., Technology Center (Minneapolis, MN)</LI>
<LI>IBM Corporation (Austin, TX)</LI>
<LI>ISX Corporation (Westlake Village, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
The partners in this project are developing reusable software components and
services that adhere to the Object Management Group's emerging technology
standards. An integrated visual development environment for distributed,
object-based software systems is one key innovation. This environment will
support management of concurrent user-centered system integration and
development.
<P>
The components and services produced in this project will be used to create two
demonstration applications: an air campaign planner and a manufacturing
scheduler. During the course of the 2-year project, these technologies will be
integrated and demonstrated with the technologies produced by the other two
Object Technology consortia. ISX will implement the Defense demonstration
application for Air Campaign Planning. (Selected in 1994)
<P>
<HR>

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC51">Computers,Data Storage, and Displays</A></H3>
While high-density data storage is undergoing rapid commercial advances, the
military's requirements for size and ruggedness still push the state of the
art. The DoD must leverage commercial developments to ensure that those
advances will meet its needs. Commercial developments in flat-panel displays
are primarily foreign and unresponsive to Defense requirements. Only a robust,
commercially viable U.S. technology base can meet these Defense needs
affordably. Thus, the DoD must leverage emerging U.S. commercial technology to
meet its requirements for both flat-panel and head-mounted displays.
<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC52"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap2.html#chap2-7">Customer-Driven Field
Emission Display Manufacturing Partnership</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Silicon Video Corporation (Cupertino, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Accufab Systems, Inc. (Corvallis, OR)</LI>
<LI>Advanced Technology Materials, Inc. (Danbury, CT)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (Livermore, CA)</LI>
<LI>Planar Systems, Inc. (Beaverton, OR)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is developing technology for low-cost manufacturing of
medium-sized field emission displays based on Silicon Video's technology. Field
emission technology is valuable to the DoD because it offers considerable
promise for displays that will ultimately be brighter, more power efficient,
and less expensive to manufacture than active-matrix liquid crystal displays.
Planar is the DoD's largest supplier of color cathode ray tubes. The project
will offer field emission displays for enhanced performance and significantly
greater reliability in military applications. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC53">High-Density Magnetic Disk
Storage for Portable Information Systems
</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Micropolis Corporation (Chatsworth, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Adaptec, Inc. (Milpitas, CA)</LI>
<LI>Intevac Vacuum Systems Division (Santa Clara, CA)</LI>
<LI>Read-Rite Corporation (Milpitas, CA)</LI>
<LI>Silicon Systems, Inc. (Tustin, CA)</LI>
<LI>Tulip Memory Systems, Inc. (Fremont, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
This project was to develop breakthrough technology for high-density, portable
magnetic disk information systems with area densities 12 times greater than
current systems. However, negotiations for this effort were unsuccessful.
(Selected in 1994)

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC54"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap2.html#chap2-7">Next-Generation
High-Resolution and Color Thin-Film Electroluminescent Display</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Planar Systems, Inc. (Beaverton, OR)</I></LI>
<LI>Advanced Technology Materials, Inc. (Danbury, CT)</LI>
<LI>AlliedSignal Aerospace, Microelectronics &amp; Technology Center (Columbia,
MD)</LI>
<LI>ASM Epitaxy (Phoenix, AZ)</LI>
<LI>Boeing Defense and Space Group, Electronic Systems Division (Seattle,
WA)</LI>
<LI>Carnegie Mellon University (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>Computing Devices Canada Ltd. (Nepean, Ontario, Canada)</LI>
<LI>David Sarnoff Research Center, Inc. (Princeton, NJ)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (Livermore, CA)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Los Alamos National Laboratory (Los Alamos, NM)</LI>
<LI>Georgia Institute of Technology (Atlanta, GA)</LI>
<LI>Hewlett-Packard Company (Palo Alto, CA)</LI>
<LI>Honeywell, Inc., Military Avionics Division (St. Louis Park, MN)</LI>
<LI>Intervision Systems Incorporated (Raleigh, NC)</LI>
<LI>Oregon Graduate Institute of Science &amp; Technology (Beaverton, OR)</LI>
<LI>University of Florida (Gainesville, FL)</LI>
<LI>Virtual Vision, Inc. (Redmond, WA)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is improving the efficiency and power consumption of thin-film
electroluminescent (EL) displays while expanding the partners' production
capacity to develop and manufacture an active-matrix EL display suitable for
head-mounted and miniature applications. The DoD uses more EL displays than any
other type of flat-panel display because of their inherent rugged nature,
wide-viewing angle range, and wide temperature operating range. DoD demand for
head-mounted displays is expected to grow significantly. The DoD will benefit
from production economies driven by new industrial and consumer applications.
(Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC55">Short-Wavelength Optical
Storage
</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>3M Disk Technology Lab (St. Paul, MN)</I></LI>
<LI>Carnegie Mellon University (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>IBM Corporation, Almaden Research Center (San Jose, CA)</LI>
<LI>Philips Electronics, Netherlands (Eindhoven, Netherlands)</LI>
<LI>Philips Electronics North America Corporation (Briarcliff Manor, NY)</LI>
<LI>University of Arizona (Tucson, AZ)</LI></UL><P>    
Partners in this project are developing a rewritable optical storage system
that will store up to 10 gigabytes on a single 5.25-inch optical disk. The
technology will be used in future portable systems, and the DoD is expected to
use it in its portable field systems. This effort should increase storage
capacity five- to tenfold over today's state-of-the-art commercial systems. The
high-density storage system project will develop the drive head and
mass-producible, low-cost plastic media. Other major advancements will be
throughput increases from about 6 megabytes per second (Mbps) to more than 40
Mbps and reduction in access time to less than 25 milliseconds. The initial
impact of this technology will be in the information server market, with an
immediate effect on Defense needs. (Selected in 1994)<P>

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC56"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap2.html#chap2-7">TI/Raytheon "Leap-Ahead"
Approach to U.S. Flat-Panel Display Competitiveness</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Texas Instruments, Inc. (Dallas, TX)</I></LI>
<LI>EG&amp;G Power Systems (Covina, CA)</LI>
<LI>Georgia Institute of Technology (Atlanta, GA)</LI>
<LI>Lockheed Sanders, Inc. (Nashua, NH)</LI>
<LI>MRS Technology, Inc. (Chelmsford, MA)</LI>
<LI>Raytheon Company (Tewksbury, MA)</LI></UL><P>    
This team is improving field emission display technology using a low-voltage
phosphor approach licensed from Pixel, International. The project seeks to
reduce the manufacturing costs, improve packaging technology, and increase the
power efficiency required to bring this technology to the market. Texas
Instruments will pursue conventional brightness displays for consumer use and
small-sized displays for DoD applications. Raytheon will develop a
high-brightness version appropriate for DoD and commercial aircraft markets and
high-end commercial applications that require full-sunlight readability, high
brightness, and wide viewing angle. (Selected in 1994)
<P>
<HR>
<H2><IMG SRC="image/blsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC57">Battlefield Sensors</A></H2>
Night vision, surveillance, and chemical agent detection are just a few of the
uses for military sensors in which advanced technology can give U.S. troops a
big advantage in battle. The armed forces have recognized the benefits of
advanced sensors for years, but the commercial sector is just beginning to see
broad uses for civilian purposes. Now, as military procurement for sensor
R&amp;D diminishes, the commercial market has begun to grow rapidly. The TRP is
trying to tap into this new commercial R&amp;D so that the military can access
state-of-the-art sensors at a reduced cost. This strategy will allow the
military to learn about and apply technological advances that are occurring in
the commercial marketplace and tailor them to Defense needs.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC58">Uncooled Infrared Sensors</A></H3>

The U.S. military has "owned the night" because of generations of cryogenically
cooled infrared (IR) sensors. These sensors were a major reason for America's
ground victory in Desert Storm. Unfortunately, the high cost of cooled sensors
has prevented their wide distribution to combat troops. Uncooled IR sensors are
a lower cost alternative for a wide range of applications and a high priority
for military users, but they still require more development for both
performance and affordability. While military procurement is low, the potential
civilian market--more than 100,000 units per year--is attracting industrial
investment. The TRP's strategy is to leverage this investment and improve
performance and affordability by adding special military requirements to an
emerging industry.
<P>
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC59"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap3.html#chap3-3">Uncooled Infrared
Microbolometer Sensor Cost Reduction Program</A></H3>

<UL><LI><I>Loral Infrared &amp; Imaging Systems (Lexington, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Agema Infrared Systems (Secaucus, NJ)</LI>
<LI>Econolite Control Products, Inc. (Anaheim, CA)</LI>
<LI>Honeywell, Inc., Military Avionics Division (St. Louis Park, MN)</LI>
<LI>Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Lincoln Laboratory (Lexington,
MA)</LI>
<LI>Optimax Systems, Inc. (Ontario, NY)</LI>
<LI>Space Instruments, Inc. (Encinitas, CA)</LI>
<LI>SSG, Inc. (Waltham, MA)</LI></UL><P>    

This TRP team is committed to broadly disseminating uncooled infrared products
based on the monolithic microbolometer infrared sensor. The DoD benefits from
incorporating low-cost infrared sensor products lie in submunitions and
man-portable systems.
<P>
A microbolometer is a sensitive resistance thermometer used to detect and
measure thermal radiation. It has several advantages over current sensors,
including a monolithic structure that improves productivity. The TRP team will
develop high-sensitivity infrared sensors; innovative manufacturing techniques
for low-cost, reflective optics; and modularized electronics common to families
of uncooled infrared sensors. Target application areas include process
monitoring, energy conservation, hazardous material handling, preventive
maintenance, traffic monitoring, and environmental safety. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC60"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap3.html#chap3-3">Uncooled Infrared Sensors</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Texas Instruments, Inc. (Dallas, TX)</I></LI>
<LI>Delco Electronics Corporation (Kokomo, IN)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Aircraft Company/ Hughes Industrial Electronics Company (Torrance,
CA)</LI>
<LI>Marlow Industries, Inc. (Dallas, TX)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project will reduce the cost of infrared technology and provide products
for an expanded military and commercial market. Applications will include
drivers' aid for commercial and DoD cars, trucks, tanks, and ships; covert
surveillance and weapon sights for military and law enforcement agencies; and
physical security for commercial and military compounds, buildings, ports,
airports, and prisons. The team's prototypes are based on common component
technology that can be used in multiple configurations. The basic components
include low-cost optics, modular electronics, packaging, and the Barium
Strontium Titanate ferroelectric infrared detector. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC61"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap3.html#chap3-3">Uncooled Low-Cost Technology
Reinvestment Alliance (ULTRA)</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Inframetrics Inc. (North Billerica, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Coherent, Inc. (Auburn, CA)</LI>
<LI>General Motors Corporation (Warren, MI)</LI>
<LI>Honeywell, Inc. (Minneapolis, MN)</LI>
<LI>Navy/Naval Surface Warfare Center (Crane, IN)</LI>
<LI>New Jersey Institute of Technology (Newark, NJ)</LI>
<LI>Pacific Gas &amp; Electric Company (San Francisco, CA)</LI>
<LI>Rockwell International Corporation, Autonetics Electronics Systems Division
(Anaheim, CA)</LI>
<LI>Telic OPTICS, Inc. (Marlborough, MA)</LI>
<LI>Wayne State University (Detroit, MI)</LI>
</UL><P>    
ULTRA is developing an uncooled infrared sensor based on the monolithic
microbolometer developed by the Honeywell Technology Center. The DoD will use
the sensor in missile seekers and missile warning receivers, and for such dual
uses as predictive and preventive maintenance, process control, nondestructive
testing, fire fighting, and surveillance.
<P>
A microbolometer is a sensitive resistance thermometer used for the detection
and measurement of thermal radiation. It has several advantages over current
sensors, including its monolithic structure, which improves productivity. ULTRA
will provide a low-cost infrared sensor that will include the microbolometer
infrared detector, read-out electronics, and a unique detector package. These
components will be integrated into an established commercial camera design.
(Selected in 1994)
<P>
<HR>
<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC61B">Nuclear, Biological, and
Chemical Protection Technologies</A></H3>
These TRP efforts will benefit Defense in at least three important ways. First,
a natural extension of the commercial interest in environmental cleanup will
allow more effective identification and monitoring of harmful chemicals and
biological organisms at military bases--reducing the cost of cleanup at the
many contaminated Defense sites around the world. Second, the projects will
enhance the ability to remotely detect biological and chemical warfare agents
during combat. Nearly every military engagement (including peacekeeping) during
the past 20 years has been conducted under the threat of these agents. Third,
advanced environmental sensors are vital for chemical warfare treaty
verification. Military requirements, which would not be met by purely
commercial developments, include ruggedness, portability, reliability, and low
false alarm rates.
<P>

<HR>
<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC62">Advanced "Zero Emissions"
Control Valve Development</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Target Rock Corporation (East Farmingdale, NY)</I></LI>
<LI>MPR Associates, Inc. (Alexandria, VA)</LI>
<LI>Peerless Instrument Co., Inc. (Elmhurst, NY)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is developing a zero-emission control valve that is hermetically
sealed to prevent leakage of hazardous material. The technology was initially
developed to meet zero-emissions requirements for the U.S. Navy. The DoD will
benefit from the 40 percent reduction in the valve's cost.<P>
These valves will also help manufacturing industries meet current Environmental
Protection Agency and Occupational Safety and Health Administration regulations
as well as emission requirements established in the 1990 amendments to the
Clean Air Act. Industries that can benefit from the technology include
hydrocarbon processing, chemical processing, and pulp and paper.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC63">Air Quality Monitoring System
Using a Neural Network-Based Fourier Transform Infrared Spectrometer </A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>AIL Systems, Inc. (Deer Park, NY)</I></LI>
<LI>MIDAC Corporation (Irvine, CA)</LI>
<LI>New York State Department of Economic Development (Plainview,
NY)</LI></UL><P>    
This TRP team is developing and testing an air quality monitor that promises a
major breakthrough in mapping and examining battlefield and industrial sites
for hazardous waste. The detection sensitivity of this system is increased by a
ratio of 50:1 over currently available systems. The DoD will be able to use the
system for chemical weapons treaty verification and for remote detection of
chemical weapons on the battlefield. Other applications include fence-line
monitoring of landfills and hazardous waste sites, in-plant air quality
control, detection of contaminants in waste water, in-situ inspection of
automobile emissions, and mapping of airborne pollutants.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC64">E-SMART System for In-Situ
Detection of Environmental Contaminants</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>General Atomics (San Diego, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Armstrong Laboratory (Tyndall AFB, FL)</LI>
<LI>Georgia Tech Research Institute (Atlanta, GA)</LI>
<LI>Isco, Inc. (Lincoln, NE)</LI>
<LI>Photonic Sensor Systems, Inc. (Atlanta, GA)</LI>
<LI>Science &amp; Engineering Analysis Corporation (San Diego, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
These partners are developing a comprehensive, fully integrated system for the
in-situ, real-time detection and monitoring of groundwater contaminants using
optical interferometry. The system will be able to detect spilled fuel,
chlorinated solvents, and heavy metals--contaminants of critical importance to
the DoD. The system will be compatible with the Environmental Systems
Management Analysis and Reporting Network (E-SMART). These environmental
monitoring system standards are being developed for the DoD in order to
facilitate the operation and commercialization of new sensor technologies. The
system will also include the measurement of temperature, pH, and hydrology and
automated error correction to enhance accuracy. This comprehensive team will
build an integrated system that includes data handling, networking, and 3-D
visualization software for complete site mapping. It will be tested against
standard laboratory techniques to ensure regulatory acceptance. (Selected in1994)

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC65"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap3.html#3-5">EcoScan--A Tunable Infrared
Laser Remote Sensing System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Rockwell International Corporation, Rocketdyne Division (Canoga Park,
CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Wright Laboratories, WL/MLPO (Wright-Patterson AFB, OH)</LI>
<LI>Army/Center for Night Vision &amp; Electro-Optics (Fort Belvoir, VA)</LI>
<LI>Army/Edgewood RD&amp;E Center (Aberdeen Proving Ground, MD)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Oak Ridge National Laboratory (Oak Ridge, TN)</LI>
<LI>NASA/John C. Stennis Space Center (Stennis Space Center, MS)</LI>
<LI>South Coast Air Quality Management District (Diamond Bar, CA)</LI>
<LI>WAHLCO, Inc. (Santa Ana, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is designing and developing a portable environmental monitor that
can remotely identify low concentrations of hazardous chemicals detectable in
the infrared spectrum. The system permits rapid response teams to determine the
seriousness of toxic spills, assess auto emissions for compliance with the
Clean Air Act, and remotely sense chemical warfare agents on the battlefield.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC66">Field-Deployable, Continuous
Monitoring Mass Spectrometer</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Teledyne Electronic Technologies (Mountain View, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>DOE/Oak Ridge National Laboratory (Oak Ridge, TN)</LI>
<LI>Monsanto Company (St. Louis, MO)</LI>
<LI>Phillips Petroleum Company (Bartlesville, OK)</LI>
<LI>Scientific Instrument Services, Inc. (Ringoes, NJ)</LI>
<LI>Synergist, Inc. (Blakely, PA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This team is designing, developing, testing, and demonstrating a rugged,
field-deployable, continuous monitoring system. The system will help the DoD
detect volatile organic compounds, polychlorinated biphenyls, heavy metals, and
explosives in subsurface soil and water, surface water, solid waste piles, and
in liquid- and solid-phase industrial processes. It will employ a patented
direct-injection sampler coupled with a commercial, affordable, and highly
sensitive ion trap mass spectrometer. Military uses include treaty verification
and battlefield monitoring for both chemical and biological warfare agents.<P>
A strong interdisciplinary team will rapidly take this unique combination of
innovative technologies from the laboratory to the field. The team will
accelerate regulatory acceptance of the spectrometer by conducting
demonstrations and assessing it with proven laboratory methods. (Selected in
1994)

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC67"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A>  <A
HREF="chap3.html#chap3-6">Gamma Ray Imaging System for
Nuclear Environment Monitor</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>AIL Systems, Inc. (Deer Park, NY)</I></LI>
<LI>Consolidated Edison Company of New York (Buchanan, NY)</LI>
<LI>Industrial Quality, Inc. (Gaithersburg, MD)</LI>
<LI>PMX, Inc. (Northport, NY)</LI></UL><P>    
This team is developing a 2-D gamma ray imaging system that allows sources
emitting gamma rays to be viewed on TV-like monitors to precisely determine
their location, size, and intensity. The DoD will use this device for military
nuclear surveillance applications, including the detection of concealed nuclear
materials in smuggling operations.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC68">IMAS: An Intelligent
Modular-Array System for the Monitoring of Volatile Organic Compounds in the
Environment
</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Sawtek, Inc. (Apopka, FL)</I></LI>
<LI>DOE/Pacific Northwest Laboratories, Battelle (Richland, WA)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Sandia National Laboratories (Albuquerque, NM)</LI>
<LI>Tektronix, Inc. (Beaverton, OR)</LI></UL><P>    
This consortium is developing a system for fast, on-site monitoring of volatile
organic compounds in air, water, and soil. The DoD will use this technology for
such applications as base monitoring and the detection of chemical warfare
agents. The project builds on the team's previous successes in surface acoustic
wave devices and smart monitoring instruments. The Intelligent Modular-Array
System will contain multi-element arrays to detect mixtures of contaminants, as
well as on-board calibration and diagnostics to ensure accurate measurements.
The team will tackle complete system integration--from sampling to
network-level status reporting. This low-cost, versatile, integrated sensor
system will be used for rapid site characterization, worker safety enhancement,
and process monitoring. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC69">Miniaturized Environmental
Monitoring Instrumentation Based Upon the Mass Spectrograph Chip</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Westinghouse Electric Corporation, Space Division (Baltimore,
MD)</I></LI>
<LI>Bechdon Company, Inc. (Upper Marlboro, MD)</LI>
<LI>Microsensor Technology, Inc. (Fremont, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is developing the mass spectrograph chip and microvacuum pump for
a battery-operated, handheld, gas-sensing system to detect any gas--including
battlefield chemicals, automobile emissions, ozone precursors, and hazardous
air pollutants. The DoD will use this technology for chemical agent detection
on the battlefield, as well as for enclosed space monitoring in submarines,
tanks, and similar environments.<P>
The system will be sensitive enough to detect gas at a level of 1 part per
billion and will be smaller and less expensive than existing equipment.
Potential applications include drug interdiction, treaty verification, waste
site remediation, Clean Air Act monitoring, and office environment monitoring.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC70">Rapid Optical Screening Tool
(ROST)</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Unisys Corporation (St. Paul, MN)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Armstrong Laboratory (Tyndall AFB, FL)</LI>
<LI>Dakota Technologies, Inc. (Fargo, ND)</LI>
<LI>North Dakota State University (Fargo, ND)</LI></UL><P>    
This partnership is developing an automated system to detect petroleum
contaminants in soil, which will provide the DoD with both cost savings and
enhanced efficiencies for characterizing, monitoring, and remediating hazardous
waste sites and military base cleanups. The effort will expand on previous work
by automating data collection and mapping of data, ruggedizing and
miniaturizing current hardware components, and developing a user-friendly
interface for environmental technicians.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC71">Ultraviolet Differential
Absorption Light Detection and Ranging (UV DIAL Lidar)</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>OCA Applied Optics (Garden Grove, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Los Alamos Science (Los Alamos, NM)</LI></UL><P>    
The consortium is designing a cost-effective, highly sensitive system to
remotely monitor emissions controlled by the Clean Air Act, such as nitrogen
oxides, sulfur oxides, and hydrocarbons from multiple smokestacks or vehicles.
The DoD will use the system to detect chemical and biological warfare hazards
on the battlefield. The system will permit rapid response teams to determine
the seriousness of toxic spills, assess auto emissions for compliance with the
Clean Air Act, and sense chemical warfare agents on the battlefield from remote
locations--thereby saving soldiers and equipment from contamination.<P>
The system employs ultraviolet (UV) differential absorption light detection and
ranging (Lidar). Known as UV DIAL Lidar, it is similar in concept to
conventional radar but uses ultraviolet light to chemically map suspended
aerosols in the atmosphere. The innovative construction scheme, which involves
a solid-state UV laser, will lead to the production of a compact, rugged system
rather than a collection of individual components that require constant
calibration. The proposed system would function day or night and in all weather
conditions. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC72">Volatile Organic Compound
Sensors, Communications, Processing, and Display</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Hughes Aircraft Company, Undersea Systems Division (Fullerton,
CA)</I></LI>
<LI>AAI-ABTECH (Yardley, PA)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Research Laboratories (Malibu, CA)</LI>
<LI>University of Pennsylvania (Philadelphia, PA)</LI></UL><P>    
This consortium is developing a system of remotely locatable sensors that are
low cost, low power, and compact. They will be able to detect trace amounts of
volatile organic compounds in real time. This system's high sensitivity is
critical to the DoD's ability to detect chemical and biological warfare agents.
It is also important for process control and for detecting fugitive
emissions.
<P>
The system is based on an innovative sensor concept that will be able to
measure small changes in resistance caused by adsorption of a monolayer of
contaminant molecules. The team will ensure that the system is completely
integrated--combining low-cost sensor technology with signal handling,
telemetry, and both remote and centralized control capabilities. Strong ties to
a diversified user group will ensure rapid industrial and regulatory
acceptance. (Selected in 1994)
<P>
<HR>
<H3><IMG SRC="image/blsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC73">Electronics Design and
Manufacturing</A></H3>
The global market has created a demand for electronic components and subsystems
that are generally more advanced and less expensive than those used in Defense
products. Yet, as crucial as electronics are to Defense, the military market is
rapidly dwindling as the commercial market grows. For example, the military
annually buys more than $1 billion worth of integrated circuits--a small and
still-shrinking fraction of the total market. This declining use of electronic
products has reduced the military's influence on their manufacture and thus
their ability to meet Defense specifications. To remedy this problem, the TRP
is leveraging the commercial electronics market to obtain affordable
leading-edge technology for military missions. It is cofunding industrial
development efforts that can serve both the military and the commercial sector.

<P>
<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC74">Analog Optoelectronic Module
Development</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Hughes Research Laboratories (Malibu, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Amoco Laser Company (Naperville, IL)</LI>
<LI>Boeing Defense Company, Boeing Defense and Space Group (Seattle, WA)</LI>
<LI>GTE Laboratories, Inc. (Waltham, MA)</LI>
<LI>Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Lincoln Laboratory (Lexington,
MA)</LI>
<LI>Navy/Naval Command, Control, and Ocean Surveillance Center (San Diego,
CA)</LI>
<LI>Ortel Corporation (Alhambra, CA)</LI>
<LI>United Technologies Photonics, Inc. (Bloomfield, CT)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This TRP team is developing cost-effective analog modules that complement
digital communications systems. These modules will be critical components for a
number of DoD systems, including antenna remoting; wideband phased-array
antennas with agile beams; electronic warfare; and advanced electronics for
aircraft, missiles, and space platforms.
<P>
Wideband analog transport of digital signals using optoelectronics is far more
cost-effective than its alternatives for a number of emerging opportunities,
such as interactive networks, wireless communications, cellular/mobile phone
systems, electronic warfare, and advanced aircraft avionics. This project will
accelerate the pace of inserting optoelectronics into analog systems, which has
been rather slow, despite the large market potential and recognized Defense
payoffs.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC75">Competitive Low-Cost
Packaging for Wireless Communications in a Global Market</A></H3>

<UL><LI><I>Hughes Aircraft Company, Microelectronics Division (Newport Beach,
CA)</I></LI>
<LI>H-E Microwave (Tucson, AZ)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Network Systems (San Diego, CA)</LI>
<LI>National Semiconductor Corporation (Santa Clara, CA)</LI>
<LI>Pennsylvania State University (State College, PA)</LI>
<LI>University of California, Irvine (Irvine, CA)</LI></UL><P>    

This project is designed to create a new ceramic packaging technology for
low-cost wireless applications. This technology will cut costs for many DoD
radio frequency (RF) electronics applications by reducing component count and
assembly costs.
<P>
The team is developing a low-temperature, cofired ceramic substrate technology
that incorporates both wiring and passive components, low-cost encapsulation
for sensitive devices, high-volume assembly and test techniques, active RF
components, and a number of dual-use application demonstrations. (Selected in
1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC76">Extrapolation of Adaptive
Optics Technology to the Manufacture of Electronics and Next Generation
Information Display Systems</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>AOI International (Lowell, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Optical Research Associates (Framingham, MA)</LI></UL><P>    
This TRP team is developing real-time, adaptive, wavefront-sensing optics
technology. The DoD will benefit from the resulting increased availability,
affordability, and performance of ultrafine-line circuit boards that are
critical to both current and future military systems. This technology can be
used for high-speed process control and for inspecting circuit boards and
flat-panel displays.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC77">In-Situ Process Control for
Growth of InP-Based Heterostructure Materials forGigahertz Circuits</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Hughes Research Laboratories (Malibu, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Emcore Corporation (Somerset, NJ)</LI>
<LI>J.A. Woollam Co. (Lincoln, NE)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This TRP group will develop and apply in-situ process sensors and controls for
low-pressure metal-organic chemical vapor deposition growth of heterostructure
materials based on indium phosphide (InP). The DoD will benefit from the
improved performance of materials, which will be available in larger volumes,
at higher yields, and at lower cost. This technology will enhance military
electronics capabilities in electronic warfare, guided missiles, spacecraft,
communications, command, and control.
<P>
The goal of the project is the simultaneous sensing and control of both doping
and composition in the production of electronic circuits. The effort will
enable competitive organizations to acquire modest quantities of leading-edge
InP-based custom electronic components at affordable prices by increasing the
availability and reducing the costs of heterostructure substrates. In addition,
it will support a technology critical to Defense needs and enhance U.S.
capability in compound semiconductor growth equipment, materials, and devices.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC78"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap5.html#chap5-3">Integrated Optoelectronic
Modules</A></H3>

<UL><LI><I>AlliedSignal Aerospace, Guidance &amp; Control Systems (Teterboro,
NJ)</I></LI>
<LI>AlliedSignal Aerospace, Microelectronics &amp; Technology Center (MTC)
(Columbia, MD)</LI>
<LI>AlliedSignal, Research &amp; Technology (Morris Township, NJ)</LI>
<LI>AT&amp;T Bell Laboratories (Murray Hill, NJ)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is creating a wide array of reliable optoelectronic components on
a common substrate, which will mean lower weight and volume as well as reduced
cost for critical military subsystems. These components will be more rugged and
thus will facilitate such DoD applications as high-speed telecommunications
switches and gyroscopes for precise navigation of aircraft, missiles, and
"smart" munitions.
<P>
The components under development include switches, multiplexers, beam
splitters, amplifiers, and waveguides. Commercial applications for these
modules include navigation for automobiles and optical computer networks for
offices and the National Information Infrastructure.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC79">Low-Cost Electronic Packaging
Through Systems Approach to Ball Grid Array Package Assembly</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Ultra Clean International Corporation (Woburn, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>IC Optometrology, Inc. (Scottsdale, AZ)</LI>
<LI>Indy Electronics, Inc. (Manteca, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
This program is developing a less expensive and more environmentally friendly
approach to assembling Ball Grid Array (BGA) packages. BGA packages are
expected to become the predominant form factor for high pin-count devices used
in both DoD and commercial applications. The team will optimize the materials,
processes, and equipment used to assemble these packages. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC80">Low-Cost Flip-Chip</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>National Semiconductor Corporation (Santa Clara, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Communications (Santa Clara, CA)</LI>
<LI>APTOS Corporation (Milpitas, CA)</LI>
<LI>Delco Electronics Corporation (Kokomo, IN)</LI>
<LI>Dril-Tron, Inc., DBA/Litronic Industries (Costa Mesa, CA)</LI>
<LI>Hewlett-Packard Company (Palo Alto, CA)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Aircraft Company, Missile Systems (Tucson, AZ)</LI>
<LI>Jabil Circuit, Inc. (San Jose, CA)</LI>
<LI>Sheldahl Inc. (Northfield, MN)</LI>
<LI>SunDisk Corporation (Santa Clara, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
This team is developing technologies and capabilities needed to produce
low-cost flip-chip assemblies. The team includes both suppliers and end users
and will produce a number of DoD and dual-use application demonstrations, such
as portable wireless communications, Personal Computer Memory Card
International Association (PCMCIA) storage cards, missile guidance electronics,
and modems for satellite communications.
<P>
Flip-chip assembly is projected to replace wire banding as the predominant
method of connecting to high-performance, high-pin-count integrated circuits.
The team will develop solder bumping capability, testing and handling processes
and hardware, substrates optimized for flip-chip interconnections,
surface-mount-compatible board assembly processes, and industry standard design
rules for area-array and peripheral bumped chips. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC81">Low-Cost, High-Density,
Sequential Build Printed Wiring Board Manufacturing</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Shipley Co. (Marlborough, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Advance Circuits, Inc. (Minnetonka, MN)</LI>
<LI>AlliedSignal Aerospace (Kansas City, MO)</LI>
<LI>Delco Electronics Corporation (Kokomo, IN)</LI>
<LI>E.I. DuPont de Nemours &amp; Co., Inc. (Research Triangle Park, NC)</LI>
<LI>Interconnection Technology Research Institute (Austin, TX)</LI>
<LI>Zycon Corporation (Santa Clara, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is developing a high-volume manufacturing process for high-density
Printed Wiring Boards (PWBs), which could cut production costs by 50 percent
compared with current processes for comparable boards. This savings will
benefit both the DoD and the commercial sector. The process will be compatible
with existing PWB manufacturing equipment, enabling small and medium-sized
fabricators to enhance their capability without significant capital
investments. The additive process also produces significantly less hazardous
waste than competing additive or subtractive metallization processes. The
benefits of the technology will be demonstrated on several military and
commercial applications. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC82">Low-Cost Packaging Based on
Area Bonding Adhesives with X, Y, and Z Axis
Conductivity
</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Merix Corporation (Needham Heights, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Alpha Metals, Inc. (Jersey City, NJ)</LI>
<LI>Auburn University, Space Power Institute (Auburn, AL)</LI></UL><P>    
This TRP team is developing several new low-cost packaging approaches using
conductive epoxy adhesives and preforms. The DoD and commercial applications
include direct chip attachments, ball grid and pad array packages, and simple
multichip modules. Working with military and commercial semiconductor
manufacturers, the team will develop prototypes of several package styles for
electrical and thermal evaluation. The conductive epoxy-based packages are less
expensive and solder free. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC83">Low-Cost Packaging Technology
for Automotive Electronics</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Chrysler Corporation (Huntsville, AL)</I></LI>
<LI>AlliedSignal Controls &amp; Accessories (Tucson, AZ)</LI>
<LI>AMP AKZO, Carolina Circuits (Greenville, SC)</LI>
<LI>Auburn University (Auburn, AL)</LI>
<LI>Avex Electronics (Huntsville, AL)</LI>
<LI>Delco Electronics Corporation (Kokomo, IN)</LI></UL><P>    
This group is developing compact, reliable, low-cost packaging to meet the
harsh environmental requirements of military and aerospace applications and
under-the-hood automotive electronics. The DoD will benefit from the
commercially driven technology's dramatic cost reduction as compared with
current military packaging approaches.<P>
The team will develop low-cost, high-density laminate substrates; fine-pitch
wire bonding; and low-cost flip-chip assembly to support low-cost ball grid
array multichip modules. The team will also develop electromagnetic
interference modeling tools, test strategies, and cost models and develop and
qualify several military and commercial product emulators. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC84">Low-Cost Plastic
Packaging</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>National Semiconductor Corporation (Sunnyvale, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Amoco Corporation (Naperville, IL)</LI>
<LI>AT&amp;T Microelectronics (Allentown, PA)</LI>
<LI>Composidie, Leading Technologies Division (Apollo, PA)</LI>
<LI>Delco Electronics Corporation (Kokomo, IN)</LI>
<LI>Dexter Electronic Materials (Olean, NY)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Sandia National Laboratories (Albuquerque, NM)</LI>
<LI>Integrated Packaging Assembly Corporation (San Jose, CA)</LI>
<LI>Olin Metals Research Labs (New Haven, CT)</LI>
<LI>Plaskon Electronic Materials, Inc. (Spring House, PA)</LI>
<LI>Sheldahl Inc. (Northfield, MN)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is refining plastic packaging technology to reduce its cost and
increase its density, performance, and reliability. This technology will allow
a number of high-performance military and commercial integrated circuits to
shift to plastic packaging at a substantial cost reduction. The newly developed
materials and processes will be demonstrated on a number of single-chip and
multichip modules with dual-use applicability. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC85"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap5.html#chap5-4">MCM Consortium--The Path to a
Globally Competitive MCM Industry in the United States</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Hughes Electronics, Microelectronics Division (Newport Beach,
CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Boeing Company (Kent, WA)</LI>
<LI>Micromodule Systems (Cupertino, CA)</LI>
<LI>nChip (San Jose, CA)</LI>
<LI>Texas Instruments, Inc. (Dallas, TX)</LI></UL><P>    
Multiple chip module (MCM) technology, a new method of interconnecting
integrated circuits on a common substrate, has become the key to increasing
performance and reducing size and cost in the microelectronics industry. In
this project, the TRP team is lowering equipment manufacturing costs by making
all needed technology advances simultaneously. MCM technology will enable the
DoD to reduce the size and increase the performance of electronic equipment,
such as electronic circuit boards used in computers and radar.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC86">Pad Printer</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>MultiLythics (Pittsburgh, PA)</I></LI>
<LI>Lambrecht and Long, Inc. (Greenville, SC)</LI>
<LI>MRA Laboratories, Inc. (North Adams, MA)</LI></UL>
<P>    
This team is developing a dramatically improved printing technology for the
production of thick-film hybrids and multilayer ceramic packages. The
technology, which has long been used to produce fine dinnerware, can deposit
finer conductive lines and smaller passive components than current
screen-printing approaches. The process allows thick-film hybrids and ceramic
multichip modules, which are widely used in Defense, telecommunications, and
automotive applications, to be significantly reduced in size and produced at a
lower cost. Size reduction is particularly important for military applications,
so more capability can be designed into ever-smaller weapons systems. (Selected
in 1994)

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC87"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap5.html#chap5-2">Power Electronic Building
Blocks for Affordable High Performance of Electric Power</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Electric Power Research Institute (Palo Alto, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Harris Semiconductor (Melbourne, FL)</LI></UL>
<P>    
This project is designed to create highly efficient Power Electronic Building
Blocks that will convert, control, and condition electricity to meet U.S.
commercial electric requirements. Military applications for this technology
range from low-power devices in electric aircraft  systems to extremely
high-power devices in ships and submarines. The benefits to the DoD include
affordability, survivability, and mission reliability through the expanded use
of electric power. The program should enable American companies to dominate the
market for power electronics devices and the systems that incorporate them. The
team has already demonstrated the feasibility of substantially reducing the
size of these devices.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC88">Regional Technology Alliance
for High Aspect Ratio MEMS Technology Development</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>North Carolina State University (Raleigh, NC)</I></LI>
<LI>DOE/Oak Ridge National Laboratory (Oak Ridge, TN)</LI>
<LI>IBM Corporation (Yorktown Heights, NY)</LI>
<LI>IEP Group, Inc. (Raleigh, NC)</LI>
<LI>Louisiana State University (Baton Rouge, LA)</LI>
<LI>Microelectronics Center of North Carolina (Research Triangle Park, NC)</LI>
<LI>North Carolina A&amp;T State University (Greensboro, NC)</LI>
<LI>TVJ Electroforming (Chicago, IL)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is developing manufacturing approaches for microelectromechanical
systems (MEMS) to integrate electronic, mechanical, and optical
microcomponents. The DoD will be able to use this technology for many military
applications, including inertial navigation systems, multiplex/demultiplex
units, high-density electrical connectors, miniature read/write heads for
magnetic storage media, and feedback control pressure/flow regulators. This
project will ensure cost-effective access to a wide array of militarily
relevant components through a commercially viable U.S. technology base.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC89">Technology and Productization
Acceleration of Low-Cost, Aluminum Nitride Electronic Packaging</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Carborundum Company, Microelectronics Division (Phoenix, AZ)</I></LI>
<LI>DOE/Sandia National Laboratories (Livermore, CA)</LI>
<LI>Dow Chemical Company (Midland, MI)</LI>
<LI>Evans Company (Santa Barbara, CA)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Aircraft Company (El Segundo, CA)</LI>
<LI>IBM Corporation, Microelectronics Division (Hopewell Junction, NY)</LI>
<LI>Massachusetts Institute of Technology (Cambridge, MA)</LI></UL><P>    
This TRP partnership is enabling the high-volume production of aluminum
nitride-based packages at a cost that is competitive with existing lower
performance ceramic packages. The team will develop the low-cost processes and
equipment for powder synthesis, sintering, and plating according to the needs
of both the DoD and commercial users.
<P>
Many DoD applications require the high thermal conductivity of ceramic
packaging. Aluminum nitride has 10 times the thermal conductivity of alumina,
the material currently used for most ceramic packages, and a coefficient of
thermal expansion that is well matched to silicon chips. These properties will
enable the production of low-cost ceramic packages to support the very large,
high-power, high-pin-count, area-array chips the semiconductor industry
anticipates using in leading-edge microprocessor and application specific
integrated circuits. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC90">Technology to Produce
High-Performance, Low-Cost Interconnections for Flip-Chip Attach</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>IBM Corporation (Endicott, NY)</I></LI>
<LI>IBM Corporation, T.J. Watson Research Center (Yorktown Heights, NY)</LI>
<LI>Universal Instruments (Binghamton, NY)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This team is creating isotropically electrically conductive adhesives to form
high-performance interconnections on flip-chip attachments. The technology will
produce an order-of-magnitude improvement in manufacturing labor hours over
current solder-based systems, for both the DoD and civilian electronics
assembly operations. Specific objectives include lower-cost, higher-volume
manufacturing, environmentally safe materials (e.g., lead free), and higher
density assemblies.

<P>
<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/blsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC91">Casualty Treatment</A></H3>
Soldiers are the mainstay of a strong and effective military system. If they
are wounded, the nation owes them the best treatment possible. The TRP is
advancing medical technologies that will help soldiers survive the "golden
hour"--the first hour after injury, when many die. Studies show that a large
percentage of combat zone casualties must be diagnosed and treated during this
hour or the chance of recovery is poor. This low survival rate, unchanged since
the Civil War, is largely due to lack of information and access. It has
historically been difficult to extract diagnostic information and obtain expert
medical advice under battlefield conditions.

<P>
<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC92">Advanced Picture Archiving
and Communications System (PACS)</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Loral Western Development Labs (San Jose, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Georgetown University Medical Center (Washington, DC)</LI>
<LI>Loral Aerosys (Irvine, CA)</LI>
<LI>University of California, Irvine (Irvine, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
The partners on this TRP team are developing an all-digital radiology PACS for
Defense and commercial hospitals. This project will reduce the cost and improve
the quality of the DoD's Medical Diagnostic Imaging System (MDIS) by providing
filmless radiology capabilities with improved architectures and interfaces. The
open architecture system will integrate digital medical images with the MDIS.
Computer-assisted diagnostics will facilitate early diagnosis from radiological
images. Radiology reports will be generated in minutes rather than days,
enabling rapid transcription and generation of hospital reports.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC93">An Amorphous Silicon Medical
Imager</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Ginzton Research Center (Palo Alto, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (Palo Alto, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
In this project, the TRP partners are developing an electronic replacement for
x-ray film using amorphous silicon technology. The system will permit immediate
transmission of radiographic images to other sites--essential for remote
treatment of combat casualties. Mobile units equipped with digital x-ray
transmitting equipment will allow remotely located, rear echelon experts to
assist in battlefield diagnoses.
<P>
The proposed medical imager will have the same image quality as standard chest
x-ray film. Unlike film, this equipment will capture and display real-time
images at geographically distant locations. The imager will produce electronic
pictures at one-eighth the cost of standard x-ray film. This technology will
significantly affect other imaging systems, such as photocopiers and cameras.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC94">Digital X-Ray System for
Trauma and Battlefield Applications (feature on page 66)</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>General Electric Company, Corporate Research &amp; Development
(Schenectady, NY)</I></LI>
<LI>EG&amp;G (Boxborough, MA)</LI></UL><P>    
This project will develop a digital, filmless x-ray imaging system for mobile
trauma care units in battlefield and civilian hospitals. The project will
enable the DoD to have digital x-ray transmitting equipment on mobile
units--thus allowing rear echelon experts to review  and diagnose an injury via
teleradiometry.
<P>
The digital images will cost one-eighth as much as current x-ray technology.
General Electric's approach is based on a solid state x-ray imaging panel that
uses amorphous silicon technology.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC95">Microfabrication of
Ophthalmic Surgical Knives--Process Development and Mechanical Design</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Johns Hopkins Hospital (Baltimore, MD)</I></LI>
<LI>Storz Ophthalmic Instrument Company (St. Louis, MO)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project will create innovative processes to manufacture low-cost sapphire
surgical scalpels for use in eye surgery. In ophthalmic surgery, a dull scalpel
can damage the underlying retina. Sapphire scalpels are sharp and long lasting.
Initial project estimates suggest that these scalpels can be produced for less
than $50. Thus, for the DoD, the project means direct savings, improved health
care, and insight into etching geometrically complex shapes for advanced
targeting and acquisition sensors such as accelerometers and pressure sensors
on fighter aircraft.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC96">National Academic Medical
Center Information Collaborative
</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Science Applications International Corporation (Falls Church,
VA)</I></LI>
<LI>Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center (New York, NY)</LI>
<LI>Duke University Medical Center (Durham, NC)</LI>
<LI>Georgetown University Medical Center (Washington, DC)</LI>
<LI>Medical University of South Carolina (Charleston, SC)</LI>
<LI>Navy/National Medical Naval Center (Bethesda, MD)</LI>
<LI>Stanford University Medical Center (Stanford, CA)</LI>
<LI>Sun Microsystems, Inc. (Santa Clara, CA)</LI>
<LI>University of Chicago Hospitals (Chicago, IL)</LI>
<LI>University of Massachusetts Medical Center (Worcester, MA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is demonstrating the feasibility of allowing the databases in one
medical facility to be directly accessed by other medical facilities. Such a
system will permit the efficient sharing of data critical to the DoD's
treatment of mobile military forces on the battlefield.
<P>
Individual medical facilities throughout the United States collect and process
large amounts of up-to-date, detailed clinical data. The data reside online
only at that facility and are not readily available to other institutions.
Thus, medical testing is duplicated and procedures are performed without the
benefit of the very latest clinical results. By developing better software and
new standards for databases, the TRP project will enable one medical facility
to examine and use the data of another facility as if the data were locally
stored. If successful, this effort will turn individual and collaborative
research efforts into "data banks" available to all facilities and health care
providers.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC97">National Information
Infrastructure-Health Information Network (NII-HIN)</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Rockwell International Corporation, North American Aircraft Division
(Seal Beach, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>AT&amp;T Strategic Software Projects (Naperville, IL)</LI>
<LI>AT&amp;T Global Information Solutions (Atlanta, GA)</LI>
<LI>Carnegie Mellon University (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>Connecticut Hospital Research &amp; Education Foundation (Hartford, CT)</LI>
<LI>ISX Corporation (Westlake Village, CA)</LI>
<LI>Ohio Corporation for Health Information (Columbus, OH)</LI>
<LI>Oracle Corporation (Chicago, IL)</LI>
<LI>Preferred Emergency Physicians, S.C. (SC)</LI>
<LI>Rockwell International Corporation, Communications Systems Division (Seal
Beach, CA)</LI>
<LI>University of Texas, Arlington (Arlington, TX)</LI>
<LI>Wisconsin Health Information Network (Brookfield, WI)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This partnership is developing a wide-area information infrastructure to
support interoperability among health care organizations. Mobility is important
for military personnel during both peacetime and conflict. Standardized,
commercially available NII-based health care systems that allow direct access
to treatment records from the battlefield would be valuable to the DoD. This
project focuses on the emergency health care community and the transfer and
management of patient care data in crises. The project testbed will be used to
develop and validate additional services based on the technologies created by
the participants. (Selected in 1994)

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC98">Solid-State Oxygen
Generator</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Litton Systems, Inc. (Davenport, IA)</I></LI>
<LI>CeramPhysics, Inc. (Westerville, OH)</LI>
<LI>Innovative Materials Technologies (Worthington, OH)</LI>
<LI>Triox Technologies, Inc. (Murray, UT)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is creating a prototype ceramic honeycomb system that will
separate oxygen from air and deliver the oxygen under pressure without pumps or
moving parts. The system will enhance such DoD operations as military airborne
MEDEVAC, military field medical hospitals, and military aviation aircrew.<P>
When perfected, the technology will be far more reliable than current systems
and will be inexpensive to mass produce. The initial application will be for
home health care patients. The partners estimate that the unit cost of
oxygen-generating equipment can be reduced from $1,000 to less than $100. Other
applications include generating oxygen for metal-cutting and welding equipment,
airborne ambulances and oxygen scrubbing for manufacturing.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC99"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap4.html#chap4-3">Surgical Simulation for Limb
Trauma Management</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>MusculoGraphics, Inc. (Evanston, IL)</I></LI>
<LI>Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center (Lebanon, NH)</LI>
<LI>Limb Rehabilitation Institute of Chicago (Chicago, IL)</LI>
<LI>Medical Media Systems, Inc. (Hanover, NH)</LI>
</UL>
<P>    
This project is developing the first anatomically correct, 3-D computer visual
model of a human limb for high-fidelity surgical training. The DoD can use the
technology for surgical training on simulations of limb trauma typically
encountered in battlefield scenarios. And for telesurgery, which is especially
critical in remote battlefield situations, these simulation techniques will
permit patient-specific anatomical geometries to be extracted directly from
medical image data.
<P>
The project will significantly reduce surgical training costs and the use of
animal subjects. The tools will be independent of the particular computer
platform or user interface. The modeling techniques will be generalized to
serve as a framework for a dynamic computational model of the entire body.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC100"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap4.html#chap4-4>System for Noninvasive
Arterial Blood Gas Measurement</A></H3>

<UL><LI><I>Rio Grande Medical Technologies, Inc. (Albuquerque, NM)</I></LI>
<LI>DOE/Sandia National Laboratories (Albuquerque, NM)</LI>
<LI>University of New Mexico (Albuquerque, NM)</LI></UL><P>    
A noninvasive, low-cost arterial gas measurement device is being developed to
continually measure arterial blood gases without risk of infection. Noninvasive
monitors are critical to the DoD when soldiers are at risk of contamination by
chemical warfare agents. The monitors will eliminate the need to draw arterial
blood (a much more difficult procedure than drawing venous blood) from the
wounded at or near the battlefield, which will reduce cost and waste as well as
limit the incidence of infection from blood-borne pathogens. Continuous
monitoring, as opposed to traditional periodic sampling, is a superior method
of tracking the wounded soldier's health during the first critical hour.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC101"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap4.html#chap4-5">Trauma Care Information
Management System</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Rockwell International Corporation, Command and Control Systems
Division (Richardson, TX)</I></LI>
<LI>AT&amp;T Bell Laboratories (Naperville, IL)</LI>
<LI>ISX Corporation (Westlake Village, CA)</LI>
<LI>Medical College of Georgia Research Institute, Inc. (Augusta, GA)</LI>
<LI>NCR Corporation (Atlanta, GA)</LI>
<LI>Rockwell International Corporation, Rockwell Science Center (Thousand Oaks,
CA)</LI>
<LI>Science Applications International Corporation (San Diego, CA)</LI>
<LI>Texas Instruments, Inc. (Dallas, TX)</LI>
<LI>Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences (Bethesda, MD)</LI>
<LI>University of Southern California (Los Angeles, CA)</LI>
<LI>University of Texas, Arlington (Arlington, TX)</LI>
</UL>
<P>    
This partnership is developing a Trauma Care Information Management System to
aid information flow and patient processing decisions in civilian and
battlefield trauma care. The DoD will benefit from advances in triage and
treatment of combat troops in battlefield situations. Remote medical treatment
and remote consultation with specialists will limit the numbers of and dangers
to medical personnel in battle zones. The new system will monitor patient
medical status remotely, track diagnoses and treatments, and maintain
information about patient location. It will notify medical personnel about
which patients or combat troops need immediate medical attention.<P>
Initial estimates indicate that 20 percent of U.S. health care costs are
consumed in activities directly related to information handling. The Trauma
Care Information Management System will reduce such costs, thereby increasing
the efficiency and effectiveness of medical staff.
<P>
<HR>
<H3><IMG SRC="image/blsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC102">Mechanical Systems and
Materials</A></H3>

Mechanical systems and materials are vital to virtually all major operations in
both the Defense and commercial arenas. How these systems are produced and what
materials are used affect their performance, ultimately dictating their
lifetimes, operating costs, and maintenance requirements.<P>
The TRP is sponsoring several activities to develop enabling technologies that
are the bedrock of modern manufacturing capabilities for Defense. The program
is building on emerging commercial technologies and initiating new commercial
markets for Defense technologies. In especially critical areas, such as
composite materials, the TRP is funding innovative efforts for Defense-related
materials that will benefit both military and commercial sectors far into the
21st century. By leveraging commercial activities and markets in areas critical
to the DoD, the TRP's efforts will ensure that key technologies are both
available and affordable to the military.

<P>
<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC103">Advanced Composites for
Bridge Infrastructure Renewal </A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>University of California, San Diego (San Diego, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Amoco Performance Products, Inc. (Alpharetta, GA)</LI>
<LI>Hercules, Inc. (Magna, UT)</LI>
<LI>J. Muller International, Inc. (San Diego, CA)</LI>
<LI>Trans-Science Corporation (La Jolla, CA)</LI>
<LI>University of Delaware (Newark, DE)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This program is adapting polymer matrix composite materials for use in bridge
construction and rehabilitation,which will enable the DoD to make mobile,
lightweight bridges for use by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers in combat
situations or after natural disasters.
<P>
Durable, lightweight composites were originally developed for military aircraft
and missile systems. Composite bridge structures offer several advantages: (1)
rapid modular erection procedures, which reduce construction time and cost; (2)
higher strength-to-weight ratios, which permit smaller and lighter foundations,
abutments, and piers; and (3) superior corrosion resistance, which reduces
maintenance and extends service life. Composite materials can be used to
replace cracked bridge decks, resurface roads, and reinforce crumbling bridge
columns. Developing a robust commercial market for high-performance polymer
composites will also lower costs and help preserve this critical technology for
the DoD.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC104"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap6.html#chap6-5">Affordable Composites for
Propulsion</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>United Technologies Corporation, Pratt &amp; Whitney (West Palm Beach,
FL)</I></LI>
<LI>Boeing Company, Commercial Airplane Group (Renton, WA)</LI>
<LI>Dow-United Technologies, Composite Products, Inc. (Wallingford, CT)</LI>
<LI>E. I. DuPont (Wilmington, DE)</LI>
<LI>Hercules, Inc. (Magna, UT)</LI>
<LI>United Technologies Corporation, Hamilton Standard (Windsor Locks, CT)</LI>
<LI>Vought Aircraft (Dallas, TX)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is focused on overcoming the barriers to the widespread
application of composite materials. The program will provide affordable
composites through new manufacturing technology and automated processing
techniques. Costs can be reduced through economies of scale associated with
integrating military and commercial industrial bases. The program will also
facilitate large-scale use of polymer matrix composites in aircraft propulsion
systems.
<P>
Advanced engine designs being considered for future production have the
potential to increase performance and fuel efficiency of both military and
commercial aircraft. However, this potential can be realized only if much of
the metal engine structure is replaced with affordable polymer composites. If
successful, this effort will enhance U.S. competitiveness in aircraft
production and preserve a critical capability for DoD weapons systems.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC105">Dual-Use Hydrostatic Bearing
Program</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>United Technologies Corporation, Pratt &amp; Whitney (West Palm Beach,
FL)</I></LI>
<LI>Air Force/Phillips Laboratory (Edwards AFB, CA)</LI>
<LI>Carrier Corporation (Syracuse, NY)</LI></UL><P>    
This TRP team is developing hydrostatic support systems for rocket engines and
commercial air-conditioning systems. Current bearing systems limit the life,
reliability, and performance of rocket engine pumps; commercial activities will
ensure the availability to the DoD of low-cost hydrostatic technology.<P>
This technology enables the development of more efficient direct-drive systems
by improving their aerodynamic design and eliminating numerous gears. Unlike
conventional rolling element bearings, hydrostatic bearings use a
non-ozone-depleting refrigerant as the lubricant. This approach lowers
maintenance costs and increases the life expectancy of the bearings.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC106"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></a> <A
HREF="chap6.html#chap6-2">Just-in-Time Maintenance</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Grumman Data Systems (Bethpage, NY)</I></LI>
<LI>Long Island Lighting Company (Hicksville, NY)</LI>
<LI>Texas A&amp;M University (College Station, TX)</LI></UL><P>    
These partners are building and testing a prototype system to detect faults in
rotating machinery before the equipment fails. Such failure can be catastrophic
in critical applications--in helicopter rotors or cooling pumps in nuclear
reactors, for example. As a result of the project, the DoD should realize lower
operating costs and longer lifetimes for its operation of military helicopters.
Faulty components will be replaced just before it is necessary, rather than on
a prearranged maintenance schedule. When this project is completed, the
technology will be licensed to other companies for incorporation into Defense
and commercial applications.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC107">Low-Cost, High-Performance
Tooling by 3-D Printing</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>United Technologies Corporation (East Hartford, CT)</I></LI>
<LI>3M Company (St. Paul, MN)</LI>
<LI>Ashland Chemical Corporation (Columbus, OH)</LI>
<LI>Hasbro, Inc. (Pawtucket, RI)</LI>
<LI>Johnson &amp; Johnson Corporation (New Brunswick, NJ)</LI>
<LI>Massachusetts Institute of Technology (Cambridge, MA)</LI>
<LI>Procter &amp; Gamble Corporation (Cincinnati, OH)</LI>
<LI>Soligen, Inc. (Northridge, CA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is based on a new tool manufacturing approach that uses injection
molding to reduce the time from design to production from the current 2 to 6
months to 1 week. It will reduce the cost of low-rate production lines that are
typical of military manufacturing. The DoD is a large consumer of parts
fabricated from injection molding, such as turbine blades and vehicle parts.
Thus, it will reap great benefits from lower costs and shorter procurement
times for critical, small-volume purchase components.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC108"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></a> <A
HREF="chap6.html#chap6-3">Precision Laser Machining</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>TRW, Inc., Space and Electronics Group (Redondo Beach, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>Boeing Company (Kent, WA)</LI>
<LI>Caterpillar, Inc. (Mossville, IL)</LI>
<LI>Chrysler Corporation (Madison Heights, MI)</LI>
<LI>Cummins Engine Company, Inc. (Columbus, IN)</LI>
<LI>Edison Welding Institute (Columbus, OH)</LI>
<LI>Fibertek, Inc. (Herndon, VA)</LI>
<LI>Ford Motor Company (Livonia, MI)</LI>
<LI>General Electric Aircraft Engines (Cincinnati, OH)</LI>
<LI>General Electric Company, Corporate Research &amp; Development (Schenectady,
NY)</LI>
<LI>General Motors Technical Center (Warren, MI)</LI>
<LI>Hughes Aircraft Company (Malibu, CA)</LI>
<LI>Newport News Shipbuilding (Newport News, VA)</LI>
<LI>Northrop Corporation, Electronics Systems Division (Hawthorne, CA)</LI>
<LI>Pennsylvania State University (State College, PA)</LI>
<LI>Process Equipment Company (Tipp City, OH)</LI>
<LI>SDL (San Jose, CA)</LI>
<LI>TRW, Inc., VSSI (Mesa, AZ)</LI>
<LI>United Technologies Corporation, Applied Physics (East Hartford, CT)</LI>
<LI>University of Illinois (Urbana, IL)</LI>
<LI>Utilase Systems, Inc. (Detroit, MI)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This team is developing precision laser machine tools for drilling, cutting,
welding, and heat-treating a variety of metallic and composite parts on
manufacturing assembly lines. The laser machine tools will also be used to join
advanced high-strength metals and composite materials less expensively than
conventional methods. These tools will improve the DoD's manufacturing and
machining processes. The project promises to improve military aircraft
component performance and fuel efficiency and to reduce life-cycle costs. In
addition, it will improve laser capabilities for battlefield applications such
as optical guidance of munitions; infrared countermeasures against heat-seeking
missiles; remote detection of chemical and biological agents; detection of
underwater mines; target identification, location, and tracking; and remote
disposal of mines and other munitions.
<P>
This technology will improve precision and tooling speeds. For example, it will
allow the drilling of ultrafine, uniformly spaced cooling holes for jet
engines, which will double the life of engine parts and improve engine
performance. This process should replace some chemical machining
methods--thereby eliminating hazardous chemical discharge--and will permit the
use of lighter-weight plastics, which will increase fuel efficiency in both
automobiles and jet fighters.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC109"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap2.html#chap2-6">Wearable Computer Systems
With Transparent, Head-Mounted Displays for Manufacturing, Maintenance, and
Training Applications</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Boeing Computer Services (Bellevue, WA)</I></LI>
<LI>Carnegie Mellon University (Pittsburgh, PA)</LI>
<LI>Honeywell, Inc., Military Avionics Division (St. Louis Park, MN)</LI>
<LI>Virtual Vision, Inc. (Redmond, WA)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is creating a portable, head-mounted display with a
position-sensing system. One version of the system will superimpose images
directly on the surface of objects, while a second version will project text
and images onto the operator's protective face shield. Users will have
hands-free access to information for manufacturing, assembly, maintenance, or
training operations to improve productivity and accuracy. Of special
significance to the military is the prospect of performing maintenance and
repair on military equipment with  the aid of hands-free, interactive drawings,
photographs, and text that are projected directly into the soldier's view.

<HR>
<H2><IMG SRC="image/blsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC110">Weapons, Survivability, and
Other</A></H2>
The TRP's focus on weapons and survivability addresses dual-use technologies
that can directly enhance the military's ability to fight. Harnessing
commercial technology to improve or develop battlefield systems seems a less
likely endeavor than, for example, using this technology to improve military
communications or mobility. However, there are areas in which the military and
commercial sectors can work together. With mass production, systems in these
areas will be cheaper and easier for the military to access. With the
commercial sector setting the pace, the military will be able to move from
prototype to usable system much faster than if Defense developed it alone.
<P>
<HR>

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC111">Commercialization
Demonstration of Mid-Sized Superconducting Magnetic Energy Storage Technology for
Electric Utility Applications</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Babcock &amp; Wilcox, Naval Nuclear Fuel Division (Lynchburg,
VA)</I></LI>
<LI>Anchorage Municipal Light &amp; Power (Anchorage, AK)</LI>
<LI>DOE/Argonne National Laboratory (Argonne, IL)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This team is designing and demonstrating a superconducting magnetic energy
storage system to store energy for public utilities during nonpeak times for
use during later periods of high demand. The project is expected to develop the
capability to provide 1800 megajoules of energy in a burst mode, which will
improve such DoD applications as electromagnetic launchers and directed-energy
weapons. The project will demonstrate that such a system can be
cost-effectively built and safely operated. It will eventually be taken over by
the Navy.

<H3><A NAME="RTFToC112"><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"></A> <A
HREF="chap7.html#chap7-2">Development of Monolithic
Motion-Detecting Components Made With Microelectromechanical Systems (MEMS)
Technology</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Analog Devices, Inc. (Wilmington, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Delco Systems Operations (Brighton, MI)</LI>
<LI>GM Chassis Systems (Overland Park, KS)</LI>
<LI>Martin Marietta Corporation, Electronics and Missiles (Orlando, FL)</LI>
</UL><P>    
This project is developing designs and production processes for extremely
small, very accurate, and reliable motion sensors known as
microelectromechanical systems (MEMS). For the DoD, the effort will mean a new,
low-cost approach to safe-and-arm devices for projectiles and missiles--an
alternative that has self-test capabilities and is much smaller and less
expensive than current systems. The Army tested the TRP prototype from Analog
Devices, Inc., in 1994. The gun-launched MEMS device functioned perfectly after
experiencing acceleration of 30,000 g's.
<P>
The automotive industry's need for highly reliable, low-cost deceleration
sensors for air bags has driven this technology. A key feature of the program
is the built-in, self-test feature that minimizes ongoing maintenance costs by
signaling potential sensor failure.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC113">High-Power, High-Temperature
Superconductor Technology Development</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>COM DEV, Ltd. (Ontario, Canada)</I></LI>
<LI>DuPont (Wilmington, DE)</LI></UL><P>    
This project is integrating low- and high-power high-temperature superconductor
(HTS) microwave components for commercial and Defense satellites. The DoD will
benefit from this technology's ability to significantly reduce military
satellite weight by a factor of 10, to enhance performance, and to cut power
requirements in half.
<P>
The mass, volume, and power consumption of electronic payload equipment are
major contributors to the overall cost of satellites. HTS technology offers a
tenfold reduction in size and a twofold reduction in power consumption, thus
creating longer-lasting communications and weather satellites. The TRP team
estimates that these improvements will save $40 million per satellite.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC114">Pyrotechnic-Actuated Vehicle
Rescue Equipment</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Hi-Shear Technology Corporation (Torrance, CA)</I></LI>
<LI>City of Torrance Fire Department (Torrance, CA)</LI></UL><P>    
Normal rescue equipment uses expensive, gasoline-powered hydraulic pumps,
hoses, and cutters. This now-completed project adapted existing Defense
pyrotechnic technology to create a new generation of portable emergency rescue
equipment. The project preserved and improved current Defense pyrotechnics. It
eliminated electrical and umbilical connections by utilizing pyrotechnic
cartridges, which reduced the weight of rescue equipment by 50 percent and the
cost by 70 percent. This new generation of rescue equipment will be
cost-effective for small fire departments and rescue squads and portable enough
for military search and rescue helicopters. In fact, the pyrotechnic-driven
cutters were used effectively in rescue operations after the bombing of the
Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City. This project has helped preserve an
important DoD industry while applying its technology to commercial products.

<H3><IMG SRC="image/smrdsq.gif"> <A NAME="RTFToC115">Use of Buried
Land-Mine-Detection Acoustic/Seismic Technology for the
Measurement of Soil Compaction for Civilian Construction Projects
</A></H3>
<UL><LI><I>Bolt Beranek and Newman, Inc. (Cambridge, MA)</I></LI>
<LI>Charles Nelson Associates, Inc. (Minneapolis, MN)</LI>
<LI>MTS Systems Corporation (Minneapolis, MN)</LI></UL><P>    
This TRP team is developing handheld and "measure-while-in-motion"
instrumentation to accurately measure soil compaction. Soil is the foundation
for roads, pipelines, and other structures. It is compacted by heavy vibrating
equipment to increase its load-carrying and distribution capacity. Present
methods for testing soil compaction in the field are slow, labor intensive, and
often inaccurate. Current precautions to ensure soil compactness significantly
increase the cost and construction time of transportation projects.<P>
The technology for this handheld device is an outgrowth of the seismic
technology developed to detect buried land mines. It is applicable to the
seismic sensing of time-critical targets such as mobile missile launchers.
Developing civilian construction applications will advance this technology and
reduce the costs of the underlying sensing and processing systems, thus making
the approach more affordable for the military. This technology can be used by
the Army Corps of Engineers and combat construction personnel to build
roadways, airstrips, and other operational constructions.
